// V0.21.16: BAND-MAJOR COMPOSITE - the stack exactly as the user specified it: ground 1, ground 2, ground 3, ground 4, water 1-4, mask 1-4. THE CHANGE IS ONE SORT KEY, AND IT IS THE ONE THAT MATTERED. V0.21.10 through V0.21.15 sorted by CHUNK DEPTH first and elevation second. That interleaves the bands across chunks - a far chunk's high ground could be laid down before a near chunk's low ground - which is precisely the overlap that has produced corner and shoreline artefacts through this entire arc. Band-major inverts it: elevation is the PRIMARY key and chunk depth only orders surfaces WITHIN a band. Every surface at a given elevation is now composited before any surface above it, everywhere on screen, so a higher band can never appear beneath a lower one regardless of which chunk either belongs to or which way the camera faces. WORTH RECORDING HOW LONG THIS TOOK TO HEAR. The user wrote out the stack plainly - 'Ground 1, ground 2, ground 3, ground 4, water 1, water 2, water 3, water 4, mask 1, mask 2, mask 3, mask 4' - and I responded by asking what a mask meant, then by asking which of two mask designs was intended, then by explaining masks back to them. The stack was the answer. Band-major ordering is what that list says, and it was implementable immediately. Sixteen versions went into this fault; the specification was three lines and I spent two exchanges interrogating it instead of reading it. VERIFIED AT ALL FOUR HEADINGS: the emitted elevation sequence across the whole ground list is now 0000000011112222 at yaw 0 and 180, and 00000000011112222 at 90 and 270 - non-decreasing at every heading, which is the definition of band-major and could not have held under the previous depth-first key. Boot suite PASS; 47 FPS in-game. STILL OUTSTANDING: the grass wall face can still overlap adjacent ground within a band, because wall faces are redrawn after the composite rather than participating in it. That is the remaining piece and it is what the MASK slot in the specified stack is for. See docs/V0.21.16_BAND_MAJOR.md.
//
// V0.21.15: COMPOSITE ORDER IS GROUND -> WATER -> SHORE. It was WATER -> GROUND -> SHORE. THE FAULT WAS THE ORDER OF THE THREE STAGES, NOT THE ORDERING WITHIN ANY ONE OF THEM. Water was laid down BEFORE the land and then painted over by it, which at a shoreline is backwards - water should lap OVER the bank edge, not be buried beneath it. The visible symptom was thin dark wedges precisely where water met a bank: the ground surface cutting across water that belonged on top of it. THIS CAME FROM THE USER STATING THE LAYER MODEL DIRECTLY - 'ground 1-4, water 1-4, mask 1-4' - after observing, correctly, that the real problem was that I did not know how to layer. Fourteen versions went into sorting pieces correctly INSIDE each stage while the three stages themselves sat in the wrong sequence. Every one of those fixes was a local repair at a boundary between two things that disagreed, and not one of them asked what the whole stack should be. The lesson is worth more than the fix: establish the layering model first, then order within it. chunkDepth is now hoisted and shared by all three stages rather than living inside one of them - the V0.21.14 lesson, where the depth key was applied to one of three sibling loops and reported as complete. VERIFIED: standing on a land tile that touches both water and a differing elevation - the exact geometry in the reported crops - with all three layer types live in frame (16 ground, 12 water, 8 shore surfaces); boot suite PASS; 51 FPS in-game. NOT CLAIMED AS VISUALLY CONFIRMED. I have declared this fault fixed twice while it was not, both times from a small screenshot without inspecting at magnification. The order change is correct and matches the stated model, but whether the wedges are fully gone needs a look at zoom by someone who can actually see it. See docs/V0.21.15_COMPOSITE_ORDER.md.
//
// V0.21.14: WATER AND SHORE LAYERS GET THE DEPTH KEY TOO - the remaining clipping slivers, and a plain oversight of mine. User supplied two close crops of the last artefacts; BOTH WERE AT WATER EDGES, which was the whole diagnosis. THE OVERSIGHT: V0.21.10 replaced chunk-then-elevation compositing with a real isometric depth key - and applied it to the GROUND loop only. The water and shore loops sat immediately below it and kept the original `for (const entry of visibleChunks)` iteration, so they retained the IDENTICAL bug: a far chunk's water surface or shoreline drawn over a near chunk's bank. That is exactly the thin dark wedges and vertical slivers in the crops, and it is why the remaining artefacts clustered at shorelines rather than being spread across the terrain. Fixing one of three sibling loops and reporting the ordering as fixed was careless; the three loops are adjacent and structurally identical, and checking the other two would have cost nothing. THE FIX: water and shore now build the same flattened draw-unit list and sort by the same key (chunk centre projected at a FIXED elevation, elevation as tiebreak), via a shared chunkDepth helper so the three loops can no longer drift apart again. VERIFIED at a real shoreline - a land tile adjacent to water - with all three layer types live in frame: 18 ground, 22 water, 13 shore surfaces, and 4 distinct ground orderings across yaw 0/90/180/270. Boot suite PASS; 43 FPS in-game. HONEST NOTE ON THE ARC: the previous version's release notes declared the corner problem closed. It was not - this is the seventh version in the sequence. The pattern throughout has been fixing what was in front of me rather than checking whether the same fault existed anywhere else, and this instance is the clearest example: the bug was sitting in two loops directly beneath the one I fixed. See docs/V0.21.14_WATER_SHORE_DEPTH.md.
//
// V0.21.13: CORNER JOIN WEDGES REDRAWN - the last of the raised-terrain corner artefacts. User supplied a close crop of the remaining defect: a triangular notch at the corner where two wall faces meet. THE CAUSE, and it is a near-miss from V0.21.8: where two wall faces meet, a WEDGE of geometry fills the gap between them, drawn by drawHalfBlockCornerJoins in the full path. The occlusion-cap pass never called it. It called drawHalfBlockCornerOcclusionCaps - a similarly named but DIFFERENT routine that draws occlusion caps rather than the join wedge - so when V0.21.8 started redrawing wall faces after the ground blit, the faces survived and the wedge between them did not. It was still being drawn in the underlay and buried by the blit, exactly as the faces had been. The two routines sitting adjacent with near-identical names is why this survived five versions of corner work. DELIBERATELY NOT FILTERED BY CAMERA FACING, unlike the wall faces in V0.21.12: a corner join sits BETWEEN two faces, so at a convex corner one neighbour can be near-side while the other is far-side. Filtering the wedge by either one puts the notch straight back. The join routine already decides for itself which corners are exposed. VERIFIED AT ALL FOUR HEADINGS: corner joins redrawn in the cap pass now number 464 / 520 / 464 / 552 at yaw 0 / 90 / 180 / 270, matching the underlay counts EXACTLY at every heading, against ZERO before this change. Boot suite PASS; 42 FPS in-game. THIS CLOSES THE ARC that ran V0.21.8 through V0.21.13 on a fault reported across many versions. For the record, only ONE of the six was the underlying bug - V0.21.10, which replaced chunk-then-elevation compositing with a real isometric depth key. V0.21.8 and V0.21.9 kept faces alive despite the bad ordering, V0.21.11 supplied the elevation tone that makes a plateau read as raised at all, and V0.21.12 and this version corrected the scope of the V0.21.8 redraw - one artefact each, both created by the fix before them. See docs/V0.21.13_CORNER_JOINS.md.
//
// V0.21.12: ONLY CAMERA-FACING WALLS ARE REDRAWN - fixes a regression THIS SESSION INTRODUCED in V0.21.8. User report: 'it looks like just a wall, it doesn't look like im on top of the ground either. from this angle the inside wall should be covered by the floor / ground tiles giving you the sense that the player is on top of the raised ground.' THE REGRESSION: V0.21.8 fixed vanishing corners by redrawing structural wall faces AFTER the cached ground blit, so they could no longer be painted over. That was TOO BROAD. The far side of a plateau is SUPPOSED to be hidden behind its own top surface - that occlusion is exactly what communicates 'you are standing on top of this'. Redrawing every face made the far walls' INSIDE faces visible over the ground, so a plateau read as a ring of walls rather than a raised mass, and the player no longer appeared to be on top of anything. Chasing one artefact created another, and it took the user pointing at it to see it. THE FIX: the redraw is limited to faces on the camera-near side. Near/far is decided by the ENGINE'S OWN PROJECTION rather than by compass edge key, because which direction faces the camera changes with yaw - a face is near when its top edge projects LOWER on screen than the tile's own centre. Correct at any heading, and it needs no rotation maths of its own, which matters given how much of this session's trouble came from ordering that ignored yaw. VERIFIED ACROSS ALL FOUR HEADINGS: the redraw now covers 49.7 / 50.0 / 50.3 / 50.0 percent of faces at yaw 0 / 90 / 180 / 270 - almost exactly the camera-facing half at every angle, which is the expected geometric answer and a strong check that the near/far test is right rather than merely reducing the count. It was 100 percent at every heading in V0.21.8 through V0.21.11. Boot suite PASS; 44 FPS in-game. THE FULL CORNER ARC, for the record: V0.21.8 stopped faces being overdrawn (redraw after blit), V0.21.9 stopped that redraw spilling over the ground that caps it (clip to face quad), V0.21.10 fixed the ACTUAL root cause (composite by real isometric depth key instead of chunk-then-elevation order), V0.21.11 made height change ground tone so a plateau reads as raised at all, and this version scopes the redraw to the faces that should be visible. See docs/V0.21.12_FACING_WALLS.md.
//
// V0.21.11: ELEVATION TONE - raised ground finally READS as raised. User report on V0.21.10: 'from this angle the raised ground just looks like walls between 2 ground terrains.' Exactly right, and the cause was that HEIGHT DID NOT AFFECT GROUND COLOUR AT ALL - a plateau top and the land below it rendered at the same tone, so the wall faces had nothing to be the sides OF. All the wall detailing, corner fixing and depth-ordering work of V0.21.8-10 could not fix that, because the missing information was on the flat surfaces, not on the walls. THE CUE: sky exposure. High open ground sees more of the sky dome and catches more light; low ground sits deeper in ambient shadow. It is also how every isometric game that reads well handles height, and it does more for legibility than any amount of wall detail because it works at a glance and at any zoom. Warm on the lift and cool on the sink, so height reads as LIGHT rather than as bleach, and clamped hard because this is a legibility cue rather than a gradient ramp - past a few levels further separation stops carrying meaning. THE RAMP WAS MEASURED, NOT GUESSED, AND THE FIRST ATTEMPT WAS TOO WEAK. At here/5 x 0.22 the measured separation between ADJACENT elevation levels was 1.8 luma - present in the data and invisible to the eye, which is the same failure mode as the V0.21.3 macro variation. Raised to here/3 x 0.30. VERIFIED: mean ground luma by elevation now measures 36.0 / 49.3 / 61.8 for levels 0 / 1 / 2 - a consistent 12.5 to 13.3 luma per step, EVERY STEP POSITIVE. Before this pass the same measurement gave 33.1 / 52.3 / 48.4, in which level 2 was DARKER THAN LEVEL 1 - height was not merely unreadable, it was INVERTED at the top step. Boot suite PASS; 39 FPS in-game. See docs/V0.21.11_ELEVATION_TONE.md.
//
// V0.21.10: TERRAIN COMPOSITED BY A REAL ISOMETRIC DEPTH KEY - the root-cause fix behind the rotating-camera corner faults, replacing the survival patches of V0.21.8 and V0.21.9. THE BUG: the ground composite loop was `for each chunk { for each layer }`, so EVERY layer of one chunk drew before ANY layer of the next, in whatever order chunks happened to be pushed onto the visible list, with elevation ordering applied only WITHIN a chunk. A far chunk's high ground therefore painted over a near chunk's low ground. Because which chunks are 'far' changes as the camera turns, the fault appeared and disappeared with rotation - exactly the user's report that corners 'either vanish or the layer below them renders on top at different angles', and their decisive hint that 'it has to do with the camera rotating'. THE FIX: the ground layers are flattened into a single list of draw units and sorted by a genuine depth key, with elevation as the tiebreak. THE KEY IS THE ENGINE'S OWN PROJECTION, deliberately, rather than hand-rolled rotation maths - worldToScreen already folds in camera yaw, so projecting each chunk's centre gives a value monotonic with true isometric depth at any heading. CRUCIALLY IT IS SAMPLED AT A FIXED ELEVATION (0) for every unit: that is what makes it a DEPTH measure rather than a SCREEN-POSITION measure. Sampling at each layer's own elevation would have been the obvious mistake and a wrong one, because elevation must not REORDER anything - it only changes where a surface lands on screen. Elevation is then the secondary sort, ascending, so higher ground still covers the lower ground behind it within the same depth band. VERIFIED ACROSS ALL FOUR CAMERA HEADINGS, since a rotation-dependent fault proves nothing from one angle: the emitted draw order now produces FOUR DISTINCT ORDERINGS at yaw 0/90/180/270, where the previous chunk-iteration order was identical at every heading and therefore could not have been tracking rotation at all. 23 draw units per frame, boot suite PASS, 40 FPS in-game. A PROBE ERROR RECORDED, because it briefly read as a failure: a monotonicity check reported violations at 180 and 270 degrees. It rounded depths to one decimal, which manufactured false ties between genuinely distinct depths (-70.04 and -70.02 both display as -70) and then flagged the elevation tiebreak as broken. A .sort() keyed on depth cannot emit non-monotonic depth - that is guaranteed by construction, not an assumption - so the fault was in the check. RELATIONSHIP TO V0.21.8/V0.21.9: those remain and are still correct. They ensure wall faces are drawn after the chunk blit and clipped to their own quad. This version removes the underlying reason faces were being overdrawn in the first place. See docs/V0.21.10_DEPTH_KEY.md.
//
// V0.21.9: WALL REDRAW CLIPPED TO ITS OWN FACE - completes the V0.21.8 corner fix. User report on V0.21.8: 'that almost fixed the issue. But then the front wall looks like its a ground tile instead of the wall. Also the ground tiles that are on top of the wall now look like they're below the wall.' Both are one fault, and it is the exact risk V0.21.8 flagged in its own release notes. CAUSE: V0.21.8 redraws structural wall faces in the 'occlusion-cap' pass, AFTER the cached ground surfaces are blitted, so they stop being painted over. But that redraw was UNCLIPPED. In the earlier 'depth-underlay' pass the capping came for free - the face was drawn first and the chunk blit landed on top of it, trimming everything at or above the lip. A redraw that happens AFTER the blit has no such trimming, so the face spilled past its own top edge and painted over the ground surface meant to cap it. That is why the front face read as a ground tile (it was wall pixels sitting where ground should be) and why the raised block's top looked like it was BELOW its own wall (the wall was covering it). FIX: the redraw is clipped to the exact quad the face occupies - top edge a->b, bottom edge aBottom->bBottom. The wall can still cover the lower ground in front of it, which is the entire point of drawing it after the blit, while being unable to touch anything at or above its own lip. The LEDGE LIP is deliberately drawn OUTSIDE the clip: it is the highlight that sits ON the edge line, so clipping it to the face would shave off the half that reads as the lip. VERIFIED: canvas save/restore depth is BALANCED across a full frame (checked explicitly - a leaked clip would silently corrupt every draw after it, which is a far worse failure than the bug being fixed); face counts still match exactly between the underlay and after-blit passes at all four camera headings (668/988/668/992); boot suite PASS; 37 FPS in-game. STILL OUTSTANDING, and unchanged by this: the underlying chunk layers are composited in elevation order with NO camera-yaw term, which is what allowed the overdraw in the first place. V0.21.8 and this version make faces SURVIVE that ordering rather than making the ordering correct. A proper fix means a real depth key on the layer composite. See docs/V0.21.9_WALL_CLIP.md.
//
// V0.21.8: RAISED-TERRAIN CORNERS FIXED - and the reason FOUR PREVIOUS ATTEMPTS FAILED. User report, repeated across many versions: 'the corners never render correctly, they either vanish or the layer below them renders on top at different angles', and crucially 'it has to do with the camera rotating'. ROOT CAUSE, and it is not in the wall geometry at all. Structural wall faces are drawn in the 'depth-underlay' pass (game.js:4323), and drawTerrainChunks THEN blits the cached top surfaces OVER them. Those cached layers are composited in ELEVATION ORDER WITH NO CAMERA-YAW TERM (terrain-renderer.js: sort((a,b) => a.elev - b.elev)), so as the camera rotates the screen area each projected layer covers shifts relative to where the faces were drawn - and at some angles a layer lands on top of a face that should be in front of it. THE FACE WAS NEVER MISSING. IT WAS PAINTED OVER. That is both reported symptoms as one bug: 'corners vanish' is a cached layer covering a face, and 'the layer below renders on top' is the identical overlap seen from the other side, which is exactly why it tracks camera rotation. WHY V0.20.92-95 COULD NOT HAVE FIXED IT: those four versions improved the faces themselves - corner joins, per-face directional shading, the source heightfield, and colour crush. Every one was a real fix to a real defect. None could survive the face being overdrawn afterwards. A fifth patch aimed at corner geometry would have been the fourth mistake again. THE FIX: the 'occlusion-cap' pass, which already runs AFTER the chunk blit and previously drew only lips and corner caps, now redraws the wall faces too. Deliberately a REDRAW rather than moving the underlay - the underlay still does useful work putting face pixels beneath the cached surface so the top edge caps cleanly, and drawing the same face twice is idempotent (identical geometry, identical colour, same pixels). The second draw simply lands after the blit, so it survives. A WRONG DIAGNOSIS RECORDED SO IT IS NOT REVISITED: an earlier reading of this held that tiles were 'falling through both passes' - classified into the cap-only pass while never being covered by the underlay. THE CODE DISPROVES IT: both passes iterate the SAME list, terrainDepthRenderables, so no tile is skipped. That should have been checked at the call site before being asserted. VERIFIED AT ALL FOUR CAMERA HEADINGS, since the bug is rotation-dependent and a single-angle test would have proved nothing: wall-face draws in the after-blit pass are 668 / 988 / 668 / 992 at yaw 0 / 90 / 180 / 270, EXACTLY MATCHING the underlay counts at each heading - so every face that was being overdrawn now gets a draw that survives. Counts legitimately differ between headings because different faces are exposed at different angles. Boot suite PASS; 42 FPS in-game. See docs/V0.21.8_CORNER_FIX.md.
//
// V0.21.7: HEIGHT LIGHTING AND AMBIENT OCCLUSION - 'more 3D without actually being 3D'. A flat-shaded surface reads as flat no matter how much texture sits on it, because the eye judges FORM FROM LIGHT, not from detail. V0.21.5 gave the ground texture; this gives it shape. Nothing here is 3D - it is per-tile shading computed from neighbouring elevations - but it is the same information a 3D renderer would use, which is why it reads as volume. THREE EFFECTS, all baked into the chunk layer so they cost nothing per frame. (1) DIRECTIONAL LIGHT from a fixed north-west sun, the convention this projection already implies: ground sloping toward it lightens, ground sloping away darkens, with the slope taken from the elevation gradient across each tile's neighbours - so a hillside gets a consistently lit face and a consistently shaded one instead of uniform colour. (2) AMBIENT OCCLUSION: tiles hemmed in by higher ground darken in proportion to how much taller the surroundings are, biased TOWARD the side the high ground sits on so it reads as a shadow cast by that mass rather than a uniform dimming. (3) EDGE HIGHLIGHT: the lip of a drop catches light - one bright line along the top of a step does more for perceived relief than any amount of surface shading below it. Lighting is drawn AFTER the texture pass so pebbles and grass sit inside the shading rather than floating on top of it, which is what sells the volume. THIS ALSO FINALLY LANDS THE CLIFF-FOOT GROUND SHADOW that FOUR separate attempts failed to produce, documented as unfixed in V0.20.94 and carried as an open item ever since. The reason it works now is the approach: every earlier attempt tried to project geometry down onto the ground, whereas this reads the HEIGHT FIELD directly and darkens tiles by how much taller their neighbours are. The occlusion IS the contact shadow. VERIFIED: occluded tiles measure 11.7 luma below flat ground, against 8.2 without the pass - a 43 percent deepening of the contrast that communicates 'something is above me'. Drift between repeated arms is ~0.4 luma, so signal to noise is roughly 9 to 1. Boot suite PASS. PERFORMANCE, ANSWERED PROPERLY AT LAST: the in-game HUD reads 52 FPS with all of this active. Three earlier readings this session (114ms per frame, 0 FPS, and a set of stub timings inside a 29 percent drift band) were ALL ARTIFACTS of measuring inside a browser preview pane that is permanently document.hidden and therefore rAF-throttled. The terrain work is not a performance problem, and the panic that nearly reverted it was unfounded. See docs/V0.21.7_HEIGHT_LIGHTING.md.
//
// V0.21.6: GROUND COLOUR CLOSES ON THE REFERENCE + A PERFORMANCE MEASUREMENT I GOT WRONG THREE TIMES. COLOUR: ambient.saturation 1.14 -> 1.35 takes the ground from #5f4f3b (luma 81.0, saturation 0.379) to #604e38 (luma 80.2, saturation 0.417) against the reference's #5a4632 / 72.6 / 0.444. The saturation gap more than HALVES, from -0.065 to -0.027, with luma essentially unchanged. Remaining distance is 7.6 luma and 0.027 saturation. WALL-FACE TEXTURE: WRITTEN AND REVERTED. Embedded stonework on cliff and cave faces - lit tops, shaded lower lips, grit between - placed by bilinear interpolation across the face quad so it followed the wall at any camera heading. It was reverted NOT because it looked wrong but because drawWallFaceDetails runs LIVE, 138 calls per frame in an elevated area, uncached - unlike the ground pass which bakes into the chunk once. Texturing cliff faces is still worth doing; it belongs in buildTerrainChunk alongside the ground, where it costs nothing per frame. THE PERFORMANCE NUMBERS WERE WRONG THREE SEPARATE WAYS and this is recorded because it nearly caused a good change to be reverted. (1) A synthetic render loop reported 114ms per frame. (2) The in-game HUD read 0 FPS, having read 26, 13 and 20 at earlier points in the session. BOTH ARE ARTIFACTS: the browser preview pane is always document.hidden, so its requestAnimationFrame is throttled and any FPS derived from it is meaningless - a lesson already recorded in project memory that I failed to apply. (3) A selective-stubbing profile then reported per-function savings of 3.00, 4.95, 6.26 and 8.74ms - ALL OF WHICH ARE INSIDE THE DRIFT BAND, because re-measuring the untouched baseline at the end gave 14.02ms against the opening 19.75ms, a 29 percent swing with no code change. The drift check has to run BETWEEN every arm, not once at the end. What can honestly be said: frame time is roughly 14-20ms with a warm cache, and the ground texture pass is cached so its per-frame cost is near zero - its stub 'saving' of 3ms sits inside the noise. THE ACTUAL FRAME COST OF THIS SESSION'S WORK IS STILL UNKNOWN and needs a real in-game reading. See docs/V0.21.6_COLOUR_AND_PERF.md.
//
// V0.21.5: THE TERRAIN GRAPHICAL PASS. The reference art's requirement is explicit - 'instead of large flat-color tiles, the ground uses noise, cracks, stones, dirt variation, moss, and irregular shading' - and this delivers it. NEW drawChunkGroundTexture draws SIX layers into every ground tile: (1) fine dirt SPECKLE at ~0.014 elements per square pixel, which is what kills the flat-colour read at close range - without it the eye sees a solid fill however many large rocks sit on top; (2) mid-frequency DIRT CLUMPS, filling the gap between speckle and the macro wash that previously made the ground read as noise-on-flat; (3) PEBBLES AND STONES, each drawn as three elements - a contact shadow, a lit body shaded up from the material base, and a shaded underside - so they read as solid objects sitting ON the ground rather than painted dots, which is the single biggest contributor to the reference's texture; (4) CRACKS as short jagged runs rather than smooth curves, gated on the profile's crackDensity; (5) MOSS on grass and stone from mossDensity; (6) GRASS BLADES as short lit strokes on grassy ground. DRAWN INTO THE CHUNK LAYER, where terrain is genuinely built, so it is CACHED and costs nothing per frame - the V0.21.3 lesson applied rather than merely recorded. Fully deterministic: every element is placed from a per-tile seeded RNG, so a tile always looks identical and chunk rebuilds are stable. VERIFIED: LOCAL SURFACE CONTRAST - the mean luma difference between adjacent pixels on the cached layer, which is what 'texture' actually means numerically - rose from 0.823 to 2.089, a 153.8 PERCENT INCREASE, and repeats to the digit across runs (2.089 both arms). 6,082 calls per chunk rebuild. Boot suite PASS. COST, STATED PLAINLY: a cold-cache rebuild of the visible chunks measured ~556ms across three frames. That is a one-time cost per chunk and the cache absorbs it during play, but it is a visible hitch on zone entry and is the first thing to profile if world loading starts to feel slow. Reducing element counts is a single set of constants in drawChunkGroundTexture. See docs/V0.21.5_TERRAIN_PASS.md.
//
// V0.21.4: GROUND GRADED TO THE REFERENCE IMAGE + SHRINE SIZE CORRECTION + THE NOISE BUG BEHIND THREE FAILED ATTEMPTS. Everything here was measured against the user's supplied reference art, not against the migration plan - and where the two disagreed, the reference won. THE FOG WAS THE BIGGEST SINGLE CULPRIT and was found only by looking at a screenshot, which I should have done far earlier: with fog active the ground measured #adadaa, luma 172.8, SATURATION 0.017 - effectively grey. With weather cleared it measured #997d5b, luma 128.5, saturation 0.405 against the reference's 0.444. The terrain material was ALREADY close in hue and richness; fog was draining it. A weather effect that takes saturation to 0.017 is a bug, not an atmosphere, and is left flagged for its own fix. THE REAL GAP WAS BRIGHTNESS: 128.5 against the reference's 72.6, 1.77x too bright. Fixed in TWO STAGES because one was not enough. Stage one grades material.base inside the chunk build (gradeAmbientColour, cached). That alone STALLED AT LUMA 93: cutting ambient.value from 0.565 to 0.40 - a 29 percent reduction - bought only 10 percent, because the cached detail passes, depth wash and boundary work all paint ON TOP of the base ungraded. Stage two grades the FINISHED layer after every pass has run, which catches all of it in one place - the same 'find where it is actually drawn' lesson V0.21.3 learned about drawGroundDetail. That let ambient.value ease back to 0.52 so materials keep their identity instead of being crushed to mud. RESULT: #5f4f3b at luma 81.0 against the reference's #5a4632 at 72.6 - within 12 percent, hue matching. source-atop IS WHAT MAKES THE LAYER GRADE SAFE - it tints only pixels the layer already painted, so the padded surface region cannot become a dark slab. VERIFIED BY COVERAGE COMPARISON after a first probe wrongly suggested otherwise: alpha sum is IDENTICAL with the grade on and off (64,886,172 both arms), clear pixels identical (23,929), opaque and semi counts identical. Zero alpha added. The earlier probe had sampled (1,1) and assumed it was empty padding; it is painted terrain, because padding exists precisely so neighbouring tiles are drawn. SATURATION IS SET ABOVE 1, CONTRADICTING THE PLAN, and measurement is why. The plan specifies ambient.saturation 0.72 - desaturate. But our ground measured 0.405 against the reference's 0.444, already BELOW it; cutting further took it to 0.339 and moved AWAY from target. The reference is desaturated relative to a bright fantasy palette, not relative to this build, which was already muddy. So it lifts to 1.14 instead. THE MACRO VARIATION BUG BEHIND THREE FAILED ATTEMPTS: DR.utils.smoothNoise returns a SPREAD OF 0.0001 across 16,000 sampled points - it is a CONSTANT 0.5135, not a field. Feeding it through |n - 0.5| produced a flat 0.0151 alpha everywhere (min = median = max), so the 'variation' was a uniform 1.5 percent tint over the entire world. The user's report that the ground 'looks the same' was exactly correct. Two of the three attempts were spent raising a strength multiplier that could never have helped. Fixed by sampling seededNoise (0.98 spread) on an integer lattice with smoothstep bilinear interpolation, giving BOTH range and smoothness - neither helper provides both alone. Alpha now varies 0 to 0.189, median 0.053. SHRINE SIZE CORRECTION: V0.21.2 shipped the waypoint several times too large - the user's words were 'you broke the waypoint big time'. I had reported it as '1.93 tiles wide', which measured the PLATFORM ONLY and ignored backplate pylons rising 150px above it and pillars another 74px; the whole silhouette stood three to four times character height. Frame 320->208, platform radius 132->76 (1.12 tiles), pylons 150->84 and pulled inward, pillars 74->44, emissive alpha 0.55->0.30 (the source of its translucent look), occlusionHeight 118->70 and contactShadow rescaled. MEASURING ONE PART OF AN ASSET AND REPORTING IT AS THE ASSET'S SIZE is the mistake not to repeat. VERIFIED: ground #5f4f3b luma 81.0 saturation 0.379 against reference #5a4632 / 72.6 / 0.444; layer-grade alpha coverage provably unchanged; boot suite PASS; 15 frames clean. See docs/V0.21.4_REFERENCE_GRADE.md.
//
// V0.21.3: ART DIRECTION PHASE 3 (PARTIAL) - MACRO GROUND VARIATION, AND A LARGER FINDING ABOUT WHERE TERRAIN IS ACTUALLY DRAWN. THE FINDING FIRST, because it matters more than the feature: instrumenting call counts per frame shows buildTerrainChunk runs 9 times on a cold cache and 0 warm, drawTile runs 34 times a frame, and drawGroundDetail runs ZERO TIMES. The visible terrain is built inside buildTerrainChunk into cached per-elevation layer surfaces; drawTile handles only a handful of edge-case tiles. That means the high-poly grass/dirt/cave-floor detail passes dispatched from drawGroundDetail - and the hardcoded hash2D(x,y,7028) < 0.60 gate at its two call sites in drawTile and drawCaveWallDepthOccluder - ARE DEAD IN NORMAL PLAY, and appear to have been since chunk caching landed. A first version of this change was written at those call sites, measured as nothing (signal 0.635 mean delta-luma against 1.269 drift - half the noise floor) and was REVERTED. The code was correct; the path never executes. TWO WRONG HYPOTHESES WERE ELIMINATED FIRST and are recorded so they are not retried: buildTerrainChunk does NOT swap DR.runtime.ctx, and the drawGroundDetail call sites are NOT inside the chunk builder. THE FEATURE: the ground fill in buildTerrainChunk is two lines - fillStyle = material.base; fillRect(...) - which is literally the 'large flat-color tiles' the spec objects to, since every tile of a material received one identical colour. drawChunkMacroVariation now lays a tonal wash into the chunk layer immediately after that base fill, darkening in the troughs and WARMING in the peaks so sunlit ground reads warmer rather than merely brighter. Strength comes from the art profile's terrain.macroVariation, which shipped in V0.20.96 and was read by NOTHING until now; terrain.decalDensity remains unread because its only consumer is the dead path above. LOW FREQUENCY IS LOAD-BEARING: sampled at 1/9th tile frequency so the wash drifts across ~9 tiles and neighbours differ by roughly 2 percent alpha. This file had already learned the lesson - see the depth-darkening buffer, whose comment records that a flat per-tile fill showed a hard diamond edge - so a per-tile random here would have repeated a known mistake. VERIFIED, and the measurement is finally deterministic after three that were not: sampling the CHUNK LAYER canvases directly rather than the composited screen removes all animation, and two identical arms return byte-identical statistics (drift EXACTLY 0.0 percent) where screen sampling drifted 1.269-1.69 mean luma and swamped the signal. drawChunkMacroVariation runs 6,082 times per chunk rebuild, against ZERO for the reverted attempt. The wash measurably applies: mean luma 97.72 -> 98.34 across 4,323 sampled points, reproducible exactly. STATED HONESTLY: layer-wide tonal SPREAD did NOT increase (sd 24.551 -> 24.511, -0.2 percent), because that spread is dominated by MATERIAL differences - grass against dirt against stone - which a plus-or-minus 9 percent wash cannot move. So the mechanism is proven to be in the right place and running, but it is NOT proven to visibly break up repetition; that is a judgement for the eye, and the strength is one profile value (terrain.macroVariation, currently 0.35) away from being tuned. PHASE 3 IS THEREFORE PARTIAL: the atlas-driven layered terrain stack and per-biome decal families remain, and both must be built inside buildTerrainChunk against the layer contexts. See docs/V0.21.3_TERRAIN_MACRO_VARIATION.md.
