// V0.21.2: ART DIRECTION PHASE 2 - THE WAYPOINT VERTICAL SLICE. The spec is explicit that the waypoint 'must be rendered as one authored shrine asset, not a small procedural circle with generic glow', and lists what it must contain: raised circular stone platform, concentric rune rings, weathered masonry, 2-4 ritual pillars, cold blue flames, bright centre core, vertical beam, drifting particles, grounded shadowing, optional ruined backplate. All of it is now present. HOW THIS IS 'AUTHORED' WITHOUT A PNG FROM AN ARTIST, stated plainly: NEW systems/waypoint-shrine-asset.js draws the shrine ONCE at high detail into an offscreen canvas and registers it through the authored-atlas pipeline built in V0.20.97, with real anchor / occlusionHeight / contactShadow / emissive / light metadata. That is how pre-rendered 2.5D assets genuinely work - a source is rendered down to a sprite - and it means the RUNTIME PATH IS THE AUTHORED PATH, not procedural redrawing every frame. When a hand-painted PNG eventually replaces the bake, only the page source changes; every consumer already reads it as an atlas frame. It is also the FIRST REAL ASSET through the Phase 10 pipeline, which is the only way to learn whether that pipeline actually works - it does, registering with 0 errors and 0 warnings. WHAT IS BAKED VS WHAT STAYS LIVE, following the spec's own module separation: BAKED (static, object-renderer) is the raised platform, 26 fitted masonry blocks with individual tone/mortar/chipping, 20 radial paving wedges, concentric joint rings, 90 grime and moss patches, 12 crack paths, 4 ritual pillars with courses and capitals, and a ruined backplate arch - plus a matching EMISSIVE page carrying two segmented rune rings, 16 radial glyph ticks and a central sigil, composited additively so the runes read as light rather than paint. LIVE (animated, effects-renderer) stays the cold blue flames, bright centre core, vertical beam and drifting motes, because baking those would freeze the part that sells the effect. The bake is DETERMINISTIC (seeded), so every build produces the identical asset. SIZED IN TILE UNITS so it survives a tile-metric change: a 320px frame spanning ~2.35 tiles at 136x68, measured in-world at 1.93 tiles wide and 203px tall against the old dais's 58px radius. The spec's complaint about 'a small glowing puddle' was fair and is answered. A DOUBLE SHADOW RETIRED ON THE WAY THROUGH: drawWaypoint drew its own contact shadow INLINE while 'waypoint' is also in the shadowSize table added in V0.20.99, so every attuned waypoint has been standing on two stacked shadows since that version. The V0.20.99 probe counted drawPropContactShadow calls and structurally COULD NOT SEE an inline one - a blind spot in the measurement, not in the reasoning. The procedural block is now gated behind the authored path, which retires it. THE PROCEDURAL DAIS IS KEPT AS A COMPLETE FALLBACK rather than deleted, so if the bake or its atlas registration ever fails the waypoint degrades to the previous look instead of to bare ground. MEASUREMENT NOTE WORTH RECORDING, because it cost a full diagnostic cycle and nearly produced a false bug report: object-renderer.js destructures `ctx` ONCE AT INSTALL TIME, so swapping DR.runtime.ctx to a recording canvas does NOT redirect it. A probe built that way saw the shrine blit (which reads DR.runtime.ctx live) but NOT the procedural dais, and reported the fallback as broken at 385 pixels. It was never broken - the dais was drawing to the real canvas the whole time. Re-measured on the real canvas, both paths draw substantially with blue light present in every run. A separate shadow-shape classifier also had to be discarded after it reported 26 props with doubled shadows including ones never touched - it was counting drawPropContactShadow's OWN ellipse as a second shadow, i.e. measuring itself. VERIFIED: atlas registers with 0 errors / 0 warnings; colour page 36,366 painted pixels (35.5 percent coverage) and emissive page 3,082; frame metadata carries anchor (160,268), occlusionHeight 118, contactShadow and light; rendered in isolation at 33,647 pixels and 1.93 tiles wide; both authored and fallback paths draw with light on the real canvas across four alternating runs; boot suite PASS with stat-pipeline 15/15, items 397/397, authoredAtlases 1 atlas / 1 frame, 0 atlas errors; 20 frames render clean; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.21.2_WAYPOINT_SHRINE.md.
