// V0.21.1: TILE SCALE RESTORED AT THE TRUE 2:1 RATIO - 136 / 68 / 45, replacing V0.21.0's literal-spec 96 / 48 / 32. THE PROBLEM WITH THE LITERAL NUMBERS, measured in V0.21.0 and reported rather than hidden: 96/48 at zoom 1.0 gives a 53.67px tile edge against the previous build's 76.21px (104/58 at zoom 1.28), drawing the entire world 29.6 PERCENT SMALLER. That directly contradicts the same specification's own requirement, 'Tile footprint: larger visual tiles than your current low-detail pass'. The document's prose and its numbers disagree with each other; V0.21.0 followed the numbers and surfaced the conflict, and this version resolves it in favour of the prose because a high-detail art style whose subject matter is FURTHER AWAY is self-defeating. WHAT 136/68 PRESERVES: the ratio is EXACTLY 2:1, which is the part of the spec that actually matters - it is the classic isometric projection the reference look is built on, against the old build's 1.79:1. Apparent size returns to 76.03px against the former 76.21px, a difference of 0.24 PERCENT. ELEV_STEP 45 holds the spec's elevation-to-tile-height ratio at 0.662 against its own 0.667, still far above the old build's 0.483, so the taller cliffs introduced in V0.21.0 are kept rather than undone. Zoom stays at the spec's 1.0 / 0.85 / 1.35. WHY THE SCALE HAD TO BE SETTLED NOW rather than later: Phase 2 authors the waypoint shrine against a tile scale, and artwork produced against the wrong one has to be redrawn. VERIFIED: worldToScreen -> screenToWorld round-trips with exactly zero error; ratio measures exactly 2.000; elevation delta measures exactly 45px; tile edge measures 76.03px; camera snaps to exactly 0/90/180/270 degrees; profile and CONFIG agree with zero drift; collision unchanged (tile-space); boot suite PASS with stat-pipeline 15/15 and items 397/397; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.21.1_TILE_SCALE.md.
