// V0.21.0: ART DIRECTION PHASE 1, DONE TO SPECIFICATION. V0.20.96 claimed this phase but deviated on its two hardest requirements; this version implements them and CORRECTS THE REASONING I GAVE FOR SKIPPING THEM. THE CORRECTION FIRST, because the false claim was repeated in the patch notes, VERSION.txt, README and a docs report: V0.20.96 refused to change TILE_W/TILE_H/ELEV_STEP on the grounds that they were 'load-bearing for collision, prop anchors, every authored landmark coordinate and every saved world'. THAT WAS WRONG. Auditing every read site found 28, and ALL of them are projection or presentation - worldToScreen/screenToWorld in game.js, the isometric basis vectors in terrain-renderer.js and render-backend-system.js, a jump-lift offset in entity-renderer.js, and a cosmetic fishing-line clamp in fishing-system.js. NOTHING in collision, NOTHING in the save system, NOTHING in stored coordinates. The world grid is in TILE space; these constants only decide how that grid projects to pixels. The migration was safe all along. METRICS NOW 96 / 48 / 32 (from 104 / 58 / 28). 96:48 is EXACTLY 2:1, the classic isometric ratio the reference look is built on, against the shipped 1.79:1. Elevation steps 32px instead of 28, so cliffs read taller. Zoom defaults tightened to the spec's 1.0 / 0.85 / 1.35 (from 1.28 / 0.72 / 1.9). CAMERA IS NOW snap-isometric-4. The spec's first choice is a fixed camera, naming 'snap-isometric-4' as the fallback 'if Q/E rotation must stay'. Rotation is an established feature here - four versions of terrain corner work went into making walls read at every angle - so the sanctioned fallback ships. V0.20.96's EIGHT angles were not on the spec's list at all. SNAP_ANGLES = 1 makes it fully fixed. applyArtDirectionProfile() IS NOW ACTUALLY CALLED, from game.js at boot. It never was: the profile shipped in V0.20.96 and NOTHING invoked it, so the camera mode and snap count were never applied and CONFIG/profile agreement was never checked. It also no longer tries to WRITE the metrics the way the migration plan's sample code does - DR.CONFIG is frozen, so `this.CONFIG.TILE_W = p.tileWidth` would have been silently discarded, leaving profile and projection disagreeing with no symptom. core/config.js is the single source of truth and the profile now VERIFIES against it, warning loudly on drift. HONEST CONSEQUENCE, MEASURED: the spec's own numbers make the world about 30 percent SMALLER on screen. Effective tile edge falls from 76.2px (104/58 at zoom 1.28) to 53.67px (96/48 at zoom 1.0), a 29.6 percent reduction. This CONTRADICTS the spec's own stated intent of 'larger visual tiles than your current low-detail pass', which is an internal inconsistency in the document, not an implementation error - its literal numbers are what shipped. Restoring the previous apparent size at a true 2:1 ratio needs either TILE_W 136 / TILE_H 68 at zoom 1.0, or zoom 1.42 which exceeds the spec's own 1.35 ceiling. Awaiting a call on which. VERIFIED, and gameplay preservation is the phase's own requirement: worldToScreen -> screenToWorld round-trips with EXACTLY ZERO error at four fractional world points; tile ratio measures exactly 2.000; elevation delta measures exactly 32px; foot-anchor depth ordering preserved; collision identical (tile-space, 49/49 walkable in a 7x7 around spawn); profile drift empty so CONFIG and profile agree; camera reports mode snap-isometric-4 with snapAngles 4; 20 frames render clean; boot suite PASS with stat-pipeline 15/15 and items 397/397; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.21.0_ART_DIRECTION_PHASE1_SPEC.md.
