// V0.20.99: ART DIRECTION PHASE 19 - PROP GROUNDING. The user's words four versions ago were "they look like they're floating", and while that complaint was about terrain, the same fault ran through the props: a contact shadow is what stops an object reading as pasted onto the map. MEASURED, NOT GUESSED, AND THE MEASUREMENT MATTERED. Reading the source suggested 118 of 141 prop types had no shadow, because only 24 appear in the shadowSize table in drawObjectShape. That number was WRONG: many props call drawPropContactShadow directly inside their own draw function and never appear in the table. Instrumenting the helper and invoking drawObject once per dispatch type gave the real figure - of 105 types that draw anything, 66 were ALREADY grounded and 39 genuinely were not. Guessing from the table alone would have double-shadowed dozens of props. OF THOSE 39, TWENTY-SEVEN ARE NOW GROUNDED and TWELVE ARE DELIBERATELY LEFT ALONE with the reason recorded at the table: cave/caveExit/caveStairsDown/caveStairsUp/dungeonStairs are OPENINGS IN THE FLOOR and a shadow cast over a hole reads as a lid on it; stalactiteCluster/flowstoneDrapery/heavyWebCurtain hang from the CEILING and never touch the ground (stalagmiteCluster, which does, IS grounded); miningVein is embedded in a rock face; fire is a LIGHT SOURCE and darkness directly beneath a flame is backwards; grassTuft and flower are small enough that a shadow only muddies the grass. THE LANDMARKS ARE THE POINT: townHouse, shop, well, campStall, ruinWall, ruinPillar and the WAYPOINT SHRINE - the prop this project rebuilt by hand two versions of work ago - were all sitting on the ground with nothing under them at all. SEPARATE PRE-EXISTING BUG FOUND BY THE SAME PROBE AND FIXED AT ROOT: 'barrel' was listed in the shadowSize table AND drawBarrel called drawPropContactShadow itself with the IDENTICAL (16, 7, 0.24), so every barrel in the game drew its shadow TWICE, stacking to an effective alpha near 0.42 against an authored 0.24 - over half again as dark as intended. The table entry was the duplicate, so the table entry is what was removed. Barrel now measures exactly 1 shadow call. STILL OUTSTANDING AND REPORTED RATHER THAN CHANGED: giantWebLair draws 4 contact shadows; it is a composite lair of several mounds so that is plausibly deliberate, and I could not confirm the intent. ART PROFILE, ANOTHER DEAD BLOCK MADE LIVE: drawPropContactShadow now honours PROFILE.shadows.groundedProps and contactRadiusScale. Both hold their existing values (true, 1) so this is a NO-OP BY VALUE today and nothing changes appearance - it converts a dead block into a real knob, continuing the V0.20.98 finding that five of the profile's blocks were read by nothing. Note the profile is frozen, so groundedProps is an edit-the-profile switch rather than a runtime toggle. VERIFIED: grounded prop types 66 -> 93 of 105; the 12 remaining are ALL on the intentional list with ZERO unexpected; barrel double-shadow 2 -> 1. Pixel-proven rather than call-proven, because a call is not evidence of visible output - drawn over a flat grey field with an identity transform, all 14 sampled grounded props darken the ground beneath them (peak 8-39 luma, 42-2743 darkened pixels; ruinWall is weakest at peak 8 because the wall body covers most of its own shadow, which is correct for a wall flush to the ground), while all four negative controls - flower, caveExit, fire, stalactiteCluster - stay at EXACTLY 0 darkened pixels. 20 frames render clean, boot suite PASS, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.99_PROP_GROUNDING.md.
//
// V0.20.98: ART DIRECTION PHASE 16 - SPELL/COMBAT VFX, AND THE PHASE 1 PROFILE FINALLY GETS A CONSUMER. FIRST, A FINDING WORTH RECORDING: an audit of who actually READ the V0.20.96 art profile returned exactly ONE caller - applyCameraYawSnap at game.js:3546. applyArtDirectionProfile() was NEVER CALLED, and the ambient/terrain/shadows/lighting/vfx blocks were read by NOTHING. Phase 1 shipped a file that was ~90 percent dead - precisely the 'computed in one place, consumed in another' failure that file's own header says it exists to prevent. Phase 16 therefore starts by making the vfx block authoritative rather than decorative. THE CHANGE: additive spell VFX ('lighter'/'screen' passes) now draw brighter by PROFILE.vfx.additiveBoost (1.35 nominal), so localized magic reads as the only real light source in a dark world. Structural source-over drawing is deliberately untouched - boosting that washes out silhouettes instead of glow. WHY A CONTEXT INTERCEPT AND NOT A RENDERER EDIT: canvas globalAlpha is ABSOLUTE, not multiplicative, so a wrapper that merely sets alpha before calling through is overwritten by the first of ~200 branches and does nothing. Editing 200 call sites is the cascade-patch the golden rules forbid and would leave every FUTURE effect needing the same edit. Shadowing the ctx globalAlpha accessor for the duration of one drawEffect call is ONE place that every branch respects, including ones not yet written. Verified BEFORE writing it: the shadow intercepts correctly, save/restore behaves through it, delete restores the native accessor exactly, and it costs ~0.05us per assignment (200k assignments: 4.3ms native vs 14.6ms shadowed), so 2000 per frame is ~0.1ms. Restoration is in a finally block - a leaked shadow would boost the entire rest of the frame including terrain, entities and UI. INSTALLED AS A SEPARATE installVfxPass(Game) CALLED AFTER EffectsRenderer.install at game.js:4594, not from the systems block at 4553, because drawEffect does not exist yet at 4553 and the wrapper would have been silently overwritten - the same class of fault this version opens by reporting. MEASUREMENT, INCLUDING TWO METHODS I THREW AWAY: whole-scene pixel diffing was ABANDONED as unsound - a repeat of arm 1 drifted 20 percent, the same magnitude as the effect being claimed, and per-arm baselines still left a within-arm spread of 188 percent because these renderers animate off this.time so no two frames match. Switched to the deterministic op-recording method this project used in V0.20.0: hand the real drawEffect an instrumented context and record the alpha actually in force at each drawing operation. RESULT, fully deterministic and repeatable: wizardElement 1.21x additive light over 12 ops, bolt 1.18x over 5, casterMotif 1.10x over 17. Effective gain is BELOW the nominal 1.35 because clamping to 1 absorbs the remainder. STATED PLAINLY: 'ring' gains NOTHING (1.00x) - it emits a single additive op already at full alpha, and it is likely the most common effect in the game given 99 spawnRing call sites. So this is not a uniform brightening and must not be described as one. Across all sampled types 71.4 percent of additive ops had headroom, median alpha 0.343. CONTROLS ALL PASS: source-over alpha byte-identical in every arm; additive alpha never exceeds 1; the lighting.boostExempt list (coreBloom/beamRoot/flameCore - the V0.20.89 clip-to-white elements) is honored and its arm is byte-identical; uiPrefs.hdVfx=false restores original behaviour exactly; the context is handed back with zero own properties. PERF: +1.1ms (1.8 percent) with 120 SIMULTANEOUS effects, arms overlapping (off 60.4-63.2ms, on 60.9-65.0ms) so it is within noise at a load far above normal. Boot suite PASS, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.98_VFX_PHASE16.md.
//
// V0.20.97: ART DIRECTION PHASE 10 - THE AUTHORED ASSET PIPELINE. The contract an artist exports against, plus the loader, validator and missing-frame diagnostics that consume it, shipped BEFORE the art so that commissioned work drops in rather than needing a second migration. NEW systems/authored-atlas-system.js defines schema 'blackroot-authored-atlas-v1' (pages, frames with rect/anchor/occlusionHeight/contactShadow/emissive/light, and actor animation groups), and exposes registerAuthoredAtlas / loadAuthoredAtlas / authoredFrame / hasAuthoredArt / authoredAtlasReport. DELIBERATELY SEPARATE from systems/sprite-atlas-system.js: that indexes sprites BAKED FROM OUR OWN PROCEDURAL RENDERERS ('dream-realms-entity-atlas'), which has no anchors, no emissive masks, no occlusion height and no animation grouping because a bake of our own output needs none of them - authored art needs all of them. Confirmed while doing this that assets/atlases/entities.json is an empty placeholder ("pages": [], "frames": {}) with the real V0.20.53 bake preserved alongside it as entities.baked-v0.20.53.manifest.js. THE VALIDATOR IS THE POINT, because every one of these failures is otherwise SILENT: an anchor that is not the FOOT makes props float exactly like the terrain did before V0.20.94 (warned, since a centre anchor is almost always an export mistake rather than intent); an anchor outside its frame rect draws the prop offset with no error at all (hard error); a rect outside its page samples garbage (hard error); and a missing animation frame in one of eight directions is INVISIBLE until a player happens to face that way (hard error, and the missing keys are named). Page dimensions above 2048 warn CITING THE V0.20.53/54 REVERT - 4096-square pages blit ~6.6x slower and cost 1.28GB of texture - so that lesson is enforced rather than remembered. Registration REFUSES an invalid atlas outright rather than half-loading it, because a partially valid atlas produces missing sprites at runtime with no explanation. WIRED into runValidationSuite as an `authoredAtlas` section so a bad atlas fails at BOOT, where the reason is still visible, instead of at render time; with none registered it reports 'no authored atlases registered - procedural rendering in use', which is not a failure. NOTHING HERE INVENTS ART: no atlas exists yet, hasAuthoredArt() returns false, every path degrades to 'not available' and THE GAME RENDERS EXACTLY AS IT DID. NEW docs/ASSET_EXPORT_SPEC.md is the artist-facing document - projection (104x58 tiles, 28px elevation step, 8 directions indexed from south clockwise), anchors, emissive masks, contact shadows, occlusion height, required animation groups, folder layout and a delivery checklist. VERIFIED BY NEGATIVE CONTROL, since a validator that passes everything is worthless: a valid manifest is accepted with zero errors, and each of centre-anchor (warn), oversized page (warn), anchor outside frame, rect outside page, missing animation frames, wrong schema and no pages is caught with a specific message; warnings are non-fatal while errors block registration; registerAuthoredAtlas returns true for the good manifest and false for the bad one. node --check clean; validate.sh PASS. See docs/V0.20.97_AUTHORED_ASSET_PIPELINE.md.
//
// V0.20.96: ART DIRECTION PHASE 1 - centralized style profile + 8-angle camera snap. First step of the requested migration to a high-detail dark-fantasy isometric presentation. TWO THINGS SHIPPED. (1) systems/art-direction-system.js is now the ONE source of truth for presentation style. Style constants were previously scattered - shade values in terrain-renderer, glow alphas in object-renderer, particle densities in effects-renderer - which is exactly how the V0.20.93 shading regression happened: a value computed in one place, consumed in another, with nothing tying them together. The profile carries ambient/terrain/shadow/lighting/actor/vfx knobs plus artProfileValue() for safe lookup, and records the V0.20.89 night-boost exemption list so the elements that clip to white are named rather than rediscovered. (2) The camera now eases onto one of EIGHT authored headings once rotation settles, chosen over a hard fixed-isometric lock so rotation survives as a feature while still permitting per-angle art later. It deliberately does nothing while |yawVel| > 0.06, so turning feels continuous while the key is held instead of notching. TILE METRICS DELIBERATELY NOT CHANGED, against the migration plan's proposal of 96/48/32 versus the shipped 104/58/28: those three numbers are load-bearing for collision, camera framing, prop anchors, every authored landmark coordinate and every saved world. Changing them is its own measured migration, not a line in a style profile - so the profile MIRRORS them read-only and records the target under `proposed` with status 'not applied'. SCOPE STATED HONESTLY IN THE FILE ITSELF: this defines the target style and the knobs; it cannot invent art. Authored sprite sheets, monster atlases, terrain tile families and UI art are asset production and must come from an artist or a render pipeline. Two facts in the migration plan were already contradicted by this codebase and are recorded: 99MB of baked entity atlas sits on disk from V0.20.53, REVERTED in V0.20.54 for being 5-6x SLOWER (4096-square pages blit 6.6x slower than small ones), so 'move to atlases' is not straightforwardly correct here; and the plan's fixed-camera requirement conflicts with the four versions of terrain corner work just completed for free rotation. VERIFIED: profile installs and resolves; camera snaps to grid from 0.37 and 2.9 rad; leaves yaw untouched while turning; CONFIG tile metrics unchanged before AND after applyArtDirectionProfile(); 20 frames render clean. See docs/V0.20.96_ART_DIRECTION_PHASE1.md.
//
// V0.20.95: GRASS CLIFF FACES NO LONGER CRUSH TO BLACK - a regression I introduced in V0.20.93, reported as black patches in the terrain. They were NOT holes: they were wall faces rendered at exactly rgb(0,0,0), which on a cleared canvas is indistinguishable from a hole. MEASURED PER MATERIAL: DEEP_GRASS, DARK_GRASS, FOREST_FLOOR and UNDERBRUSH all produced rgb(0,0,0) on their WEST face bottoms. Their side colours are very dark (luma 33-40), so the PRE-EXISTING -42 bottom stop already sat at luma 2-5, and V0.20.93's directional offset of -13.6 on the west face took the remainder. Stone, ruin, camp and dirt were never affected (28, 25, 23, 9). FIX: negative shading is now scaled by the material's HEADROOM, luma/70 clamped to [0.42, 1]. Stone, ruin and camp compute headroom 1.0 and are byte-identical to before; the dark materials get proportionally less darkening and lift clear of black. This fixes my regression AND the long-standing near-black bottom on grass walls, which had been at luma 2-5 since long before any of this work. VERIFIED: no material bottoms out below luma 6 (was 0), stone headroom confirmed 1.0 so its look is unchanged, and perpendicular-face contrast is preserved at 13-29 points so V0.20.93's directional lighting still reads. LIVE: black pixel area across four grass-cliff locations at three camera yaws each fell 24,958 -> 15,697, a 37% reduction, measured by A/B against the unscaled version. HONEST NOTE: the remaining black is genuine deep shadow at the foot of tall grass walls, not zeroed pixels - and the missing ground contact shadow (four failed attempts, V0.20.94) would do more for how grounded this reads than any further shade tuning. See docs/V0.20.95_GRASS_WALL_BLACK_CRUSH.md.
//
// V0.20.94: ASHEN VALLEY TERRAIN FORMS PLATEAUS, NOT A STAIRCASE - and the floating look was MY GENERATOR, not the renderer. Two screenshots settled it: one showed a hairline zigzag with isolated blocks at its corners across nearly flat ground, the other showed a real cliff into water rendering perfectly. The renderer was never at fault. MEASURED: one elevation unit is 28px against a 59.5px tile - nearly half a tile, so every step is a full-height wall - and Ashen Valley carried 107 elevation edges per 1,000 tiles against Dark Woods' 2. A FIFTY-THREE times denser field of full-height steps, which is exactly the endless hairline staircase reported as floating slabs. ROOT CAUSE: the generator floored `basin * 2.6 + n2 * 1.7 + n3 * 0.7`, where n2 is noise at scale 14 and n3 at scale 7 - high-frequency terms, so the floor flipped by one every couple of tiles. FIX IN TWO PARTS, because the first was not enough and the measurement said so: (1) elevation now comes from low-frequency relief only, plus three box-blur passes over the CONTINUOUS height before it is floored - blurring before flooring is what produces broad flat ground with occasional real cliffs rather than a step wherever noise crosses an integer. That took it 107 -> 67. (2) The ridge term keyed off TILE TYPE, and type is chosen from the same n1/n2/n3 noise just removed from elevation, so `type === STONE ? 1.35 : 0` reintroduced per-tile churn through the back door; highland mass is now its own smooth field. 67 -> 52. n2/n3 still drive tile TYPE, where per-tile variation is exactly what is wanted. ON THE REMAINING NUMBER, HONESTLY: 52 edges per 1,000 is still well above Dark Woods' 2, but that target was worthless - Dark Woods scores 2 because it is 99.5% FLAT (31,533 of 31,684 sampled tiles at elevation zero) and has no relief to speak of. The meaningful measure is the length of unbroken flat ground between steps: 18.3 tiles, roughly 1,000 pixels, which is a plateau rather than a staircase. One-unit steps fell from 4,602 to 2,038. VERIFIED the zone is unharmed: city plate still flat and walkable, all nine subregion anchors reachable within 8 tiles, roads level, waypoint and road crossing both in place, renders clean at four camera yaws across four locations, highlands 5.71ms. NOT FIXED, and I am not claiming otherwise: nothing casts a shadow onto the ground at the foot of a cliff. Four attempts at adding one all failed - see docs/V0.20.94_ASHEN_VALLEY_TERRAIN_PLATEAUS.md for what each proved. See that report.
//
// V0.20.93: CLIFF FACES ARE LIT BY DIRECTION - the actual cause of 'corners don't render correctly at every angle'. A zoomed screenshot settled it: nothing was missing or misplaced, every wall face of a raised block was simply drawn in the SAME flat shade, so two perpendicular walls meeting at a corner had ZERO contrast between them and a stepped stone cliff read as folded paper. ROOT CAUSE: each face already carried a per-direction shade (n -28, e -20, s -32, w -38, set in terrainEdgeDefinitionsForTile) and tallFaces faithfully propagated it - but drawLayeredWallFace never took it as an argument and built one identical gradient from def.side for all four sides. The value was computed, carried, and thrown away. It IS used at one other site (an outline stroke), which is why it looked wired up. FIX: the shade is passed in and applied RELATIVE to its set's midpoint rather than absolutely - applying it raw would have darkened every cliff in the game by 20-38 points - and widened x1.6 so the distinction survives the vertical gradient layered on top. Both call sites updated, overworld and cave wall. VERIFIED: perpendicular face pairs now differ by 10-19 luminance points where they previously differed by ZERO (e 115, n 102, s 96, w 86 - a coherent directional light); 20-21 distinct stone shades visible in the live scene at every 90 degrees of camera yaw; no perf cost (highlands 5.65ms and 7.18ms on a repeat arm) and no errors across all zones at four yaws. THREE WRONG HYPOTHESES BEFORE THIS ONE, all measured and discarded rather than shipped: yaw-fixed screen corners (corner tops proved exact to 0.00px at every yaw), per-tile jitter separating shared edges (drawLayeredWallFace uses the passed corner points untouched), and 'thin dark seams' varying with angle (those are the intentional contact-darkening and ambient-occlusion strokes drawn along every face bottom). I asked for a zoomed screenshot rather than guess a fourth time, and it took one look to see. See docs/V0.20.93_DIRECTIONAL_CLIFF_SHADING.md.
//
// V0.20.92: CORNER WALLS ON RAISED TERRAIN. Reported from a screenshot of the Ashen highlands: notches along the cliff edges where a slope steps diagonally. ROOT CAUSE, one line: resolveHalfBlockExposure opened its corner loop with `if (!sideFaces.length) continue`, which drops any corner exposed ONLY diagonally. That is the common staircase case - a tile level with BOTH cardinal neighbours but higher than the diagonal one has no side faces at all, so nobody drew its corner column. MEASURED, not eyeballed: 433 of 1,579 interior exposed corners in the highlands (27.4%) had zero owners. PRE-EXISTING, NOT AN ASHEN VALLEY BUG - Dark Woods measured 34.6% by the same audit and simply never showed it, because it has almost no raised ground; Ashen Valley's elevation is what made a years-old fault visible. TWO MEASUREMENT ERRORS OF MY OWN ON THE WAY, both caught before they became conclusions: (1) a first audit sampling every 3rd tile reported a 50% orphan rate, which was an artifact - a corner is shared by four tiles and I was excluding three of them by construction; (2) the contiguous rescan still counted corners on the boundary of the scan window whose owners lay outside it, and every one of my first six 'orphan' samples turned out to sit on that boundary row. Only corners with all four sharers inside the window are counted now. THE FIX is scoped to a genuine ELEVATION drop. I first allowed any diagonal exposure and measured the consequence: orphans went to zero but double-drawn corners rose 8 -> 16, because isLowerTerrainExposure is also true for water and cave-wall adjacency, so both diagonal pairs around a corner could claim it. Restricting to tileElev > diagonalElev returns Dark Woods to its baseline of 4 doubles and leaves water corners to the shore pass that already owns them. HONEST RESIDUAL: the Ashen highlands still carry 8 double-drawn corners more than baseline, 0.5% of 1,579 - a slightly darker seam, against 433 corners that previously had no wall at all. The rendering consumer needed no change: it already treats a join with fewer than two side faces as the lighter single column, which is exactly right for a diagonal notch. VERIFIED: elevation corners 0 orphaned in Ashen highlands, Ashen basin and Dark Woods; no perf cost - the highlands measure 6.06ms and 6.02ms on a repeat arm (165 FPS) with 433 extra corner columns; no render errors across highlands, riverlands and Dark Woods. See docs/V0.20.92_TERRAIN_CORNER_WALLS.md.
//
// V0.20.91: ASHEN VALLEY WAS BURNING 35ms A FRAME ON AN EMPTY ZONE - found by the 'measure before building the city' decision, and it justified that decision immediately. BASELINE FIRST, as agreed: Dark Woods camp 3,691 draw calls at ~14ms; the EMPTY Ashenfall plate 738 draw calls - five times FEWER - at ~38ms. A zone drawing almost nothing and running three times slower is not draw-call bound, so building a city on it would have been pointless. Splitting update from render located it precisely: Ashenfall update 34.88ms / render 1.31ms against Dark Woods update 1.44ms / render 4.26ms, reproduced on a repeat arm (35.71 / 1.36). Stubbing each external system in turn: FISHING, 32.84ms of a 34.06ms update - 96%. TWO COMPOUNDING FAULTS, both the same hardcoded-single-overworld assumption that broke the map label and fog key in V0.20.83. (1) zoneKey() returned 'dark_woods' for ANY overworld, so Ashen Valley inherited Dark Woods' ambient fish, whose stored coordinates are dry land here - every fish re-targeted every frame. It now returns the active overworld zone, and activeMap/activeObjects treat any zone without a parentZone as an overworld instead of testing `zone !== 'dark_woods'`, which had been sending Ashen Valley down the CAVE branch. (2) findWaterCandidate clamped its search to CONFIG.MAP_SIZE - a constant of 200 that predates both the Dark Woods 360 expansion and this zone - so on a 450x450 map it searched only the top-left 200x200 corner. Ashen Valley's river lies entirely east of x=280, so that corner holds NO water: every fish failed, fell through to a full grid sweep, and repeated it the next frame. Dark Woods survived the identical bug purely because its creek happens to sit inside its first 200x200 - the constant has been wrong there for many versions and never showed. The real map size is used now, and a failed search sets a 4-second per-zone backoff so a waterless region can never re-sweep sixty times a second again - that guard is for the zones not yet built, not for this one. VERIFIED: Ashenfall update 34.88ms -> 1.93ms (18x), whole frame 38ms -> 3.69ms; Ashen wilderness 43.31 -> 11.1ms; riverlands 9.92ms; Dark Woods unchanged within drift. Fishing still works in BOTH zones (both go active on cast), and each zone now keeps its own fish - 34 in Dark Woods, 10 in Ashen Valley. NOTED FOR THE CONTENT PHASE: Ashen Valley has no fish table of its own yet and falls back to Dark Woods' fish; the spec asks for 6 new ones. See docs/V0.20.91_ASHEN_VALLEY_UPDATE_STALL.md.
//
// V0.20.90: WAYPOINT TRAVEL MENU (spec 5.6). Requested: interacting with a waypoint should open a menu listing every waypoint you know, like Diablo 2. Until now interacting only ATTUNED the waypoint - travelTargets()/travelTo() existed as API from V0.20.80 with no interface on top, so fast travel was reachable only from the console. BEHAVIOUR: the interact key attunes on first touch (discovery must still be earned by standing there - spec 5.5 forbids remote unlock) and then opens the list; an already-attuned waypoint goes straight to it, which is the Diablo behaviour. Escape closes, matching every other panel. THE LIST follows spec 5.6: grouped by region (Diablo groups by act, and it is the structure the zone list needs anyway as regions are added); discovered entries show name, region and level range and are clickable; UNDISCOVERED entries are shown but masked as ??? and disabled, so the player knows something exists there without being told what or being able to reach it; the waypoint you are standing on is highlighted and reads 'You are here'. Every disabled button CARRIES ITS REASON as its own label - in combat it reads 'You cannot travel while in combat.' rather than silently refusing, which is spec 5.7's 'blocked travel must provide a specific reason' put where the player is actually looking. Built as a `panel gameWindow` section filled by innerHTML, the same idiom the mount and skills panels use - no new UI framework, and it inherits the existing window styling. VERIFIED BY DRIVING THE REAL UI, not the API beneath it: pressing the interact key on a waypoint opens the panel and attunes it in one action; the list renders two zone headings and masks both undiscovered entries as ???; CLICKING the Ashenfall button travels to ashen_valley, lands at 226,233 and closes the panel; reopening there marks Ashenfall as 'You are here' and re-enables the other two; setting combat disables all travel buttons with the reason as the label; and clicking back returns to Dark Woods. Escape closes. See docs/V0.20.90_WAYPOINT_TRAVEL_MENU.md.
//
// V0.20.89: THE OLD WAYPOINT AURA REMOVED FROM ON TOP OF THE NEW WAYPOINT. Reported with a screenshot: a pale blue blob sitting on the centre of the new dais. It was not the new art - it was the 'waypointAura' EFFECT added in V0.17.51 to give the old flat grey disc a pulsing glow, ring and motes. Effects render AFTER world objects, so it drew straight over the rebuilt stonework. The V0.20.88 waypoint already draws its own core, pool, rings, beam and motes, making the aura pure duplication. REMOVED IN FULL: the spawner in waypoint-system, the dispatch branch and drawWaypointAuraEffect in effects-renderer (3.2KB). The system now PURGES any waypointAura still present rather than creating them - those effects carry life: 1e9 and would otherwise never expire, so a session already running (or any world carrying one) would have kept an orphan forever; the purge runs on init and on the same ~1s cadence the old refresh used. ONE BEHAVIOUR WAS WORTH KEEPING and would have been silently lost: V0.17.56 item 3 scaled the aura at night so a waypoint reads as a beacon in the dark. That moved into drawWaypoint, off the same world-light nightStrength everything else uses. GETTING THAT RIGHT TOOK THREE MEASURED ATTEMPTS, each corrected by pixels rather than by eye: (1) scaling `pulse` did NOTHING measurable (2225 vs 2223 blue px) because pulse already peaks at 1, so scaling it can only lift troughs - the old aura scaled ALPHAS, so now so does this, via an L() helper on 13 light alphas; (2) that worked (+22.7% blue) but brought the blob BACK at full night, the saturated centre run going 10px -> 25px, because boosting an already-bright core additively clips it - the core bloom and the beam ROOT are therefore exempt from the boost, which is exactly the 'capped so it never blows out' note V0.17.56 wrote about its own aura; (3) still 16px, and locating the runs by POSITION showed all 7 were at the dais centre, not the flames - so the core disc's alpha is now divided by nightBoost, compensating for the boosted pool and rings beneath it. FINAL: +33.9% brighter at night, widest saturated centre run 8px by day and 12px at midnight, no aura effects after 330 frames, an injected legacy aura is purged, and the renderer no longer knows the type at all. See docs/V0.20.89_WAYPOINT_AURA_REMOVED.md.
//
// V0.20.88: WAYPOINT REBUILT AGAIN, PROPERLY. Reported: 'Thats not even close to the waypoint image i gave you' - and that was right. HOW I GOT IT WRONG: V0.20.86 was verified with a coarse 58x32 ASCII map that confirmed dais/braziers/ring/core/beam were all PRESENT, and I reported presence as resemblance. Structure existing is not the same as looking like the reference, and a 58x32 map cannot show proportion, saturation or surface detail - the three things that were wrong. MEASURED THE ACTUAL FAULTS instead of guessing: (1) total footprint 75px wide against a ~150px-tall player sprite, roughly half the size it should read at; (2) the centre saturated to pure 255,255,255 across a 12px band, because the core used SOURCE-OVER rgba(238,250,255,0.95) - that is white PAINT, not light, and it flattened everything under it into the reported blob; (3) no readable masonry, the rim was a single flat grey; (4) no thickness, a flat disc rather than a stone platform. FIXES: radius 34 -> 58 (footprint 75 -> 129px wide, 171 tall); the dais now has a real SIDE WALL with vertical joints, so it is a platform rather than a disc; the rim is 20 alternating fitted block faces with mortar (16 distinct shades measured around the arc, up from a flat one); three engraved courses cut into the inner floor; 16 rune segments; and EVERY light element is additive with capped alpha, so the glow blooms over the stone instead of erasing it. The core is now a 4px disc with a 20px bloom - measured, the widest fully-saturated run through the centre is 8px, down from a 12px band, so it reads as a highlight rather than a smear. VERIFIED AGAINST THE FOUR NAMED FAULTS, not against 'is it present': footprint >=110px wide PASS; no blown-out blob PASS; masonry readable (16 shades) PASS; real thickness (15 rows of side wall) PASS. The remaining saturated pixels are 138 in the two brazier flame cores and 17 at the beam base, which is where a hot core belongs. See docs/V0.20.88_WAYPOINT_REBUILD.md.
//
// V0.20.87: DEAD LANTERN CAMP WAYPOINT, plus the same-zone travel this exposed. Requested: add a waypoint to Dead Lantern Camp. Placed at 106,105 - just off the south-east road out of camp, 7.1 tiles from the spawn point - rather than inside the hub, because the camp already carries 60 props in a 26x26 box and a waypoint needs clear ground to read as a landmark and to be a gathering spot (spec 5.3). Named per the spec's own example list (5.11). DARK WOODS IS NOW THE FIRST ZONE WITH TWO WAYPOINTS, which broke an assumption I had baked in: travel was refused whenever the destination's zone matched the player's current zone ('You are already in that region'), so Dead Lantern and Stone Hedge could never reach each other. The refusal is now per WAYPOINT, not per zone - you are refused only if you are standing at the one you picked - and travelToOverworldZone takes an allowSameZone option so intra-zone arrival runs through the same safety path as any other travel (walkable landing, transition cooldown, cancelled fishing/gathering). The arrival log is suppressed for same-zone hops, since 'You arrive in Dark Woods' reads wrong when you never left. TWO PLACEMENT FAULTS, BOTH SILENT, BOTH FOUND BY CHECKING THE WORLD RATHER THAN THE CODE: (1) the ensure ran inside generateMap BEFORE storeOverworldZone, and since it targets the dark_woods SLOT by name (the V0.20.81 lesson) it wrote into the grid the store was about to replace - it ran, returned success, and the object was not in the world. (2) Moving it after the store still failed, because ensureStartingCampRevamp runs later from game.js and CLEARS EVERY OBJECT INSIDE THE CAMP ELLIPSE (clearAndSet nulls them); 106,105 sits at 0.76 of that radius, so the waypoint was placed and then wiped on every boot. It is now called from game.js immediately AFTER the camp revamp, and the redundant earlier calls were removed rather than left as decoration. THE PATTERN IS WORTH NAMING: three versions running, a prop has been placed into a grid that something later discarded, and each time the function reported success. 'Placed' is not 'present' - verify by reading the world back at boot. VERIFIED: both Dark Woods waypoints exist at a clean boot AND survive character creation (the revamp runs again there); the camp one is 7.1 tiles from spawn, detected and attunable; travel camp -> Stone Hedge -> camp both succeed and stay in Dark Woods; standing on one refuses only itself. Suite ok, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.87_DEAD_LANTERN_WAYPOINT.md.
//
// V0.20.86: WAYPOINT VISUAL REBUILT from a supplied reference image. The old drawWaypoint was a ~24px grey disc with three scratched lines - unreadable as a landmark, and nothing like the 'large circular stone platform, engraved runes, rotating inner ring, particle wisps, faint vertical beam, activated rune segments' the Ashen Valley spec section 5.4 asks for. NEW STRUCTURE, back to front: ground shadow, two-tier stone dais built from 16 radial blocks with mortar lines (which is what makes it read as masonry rather than a flat disc), engraved rune ring, 12 rune segments that light in a running sequence, two counter-rotating glyph rings, radial core glow, vertical beam, rising motes, then the two flanking braziers LAST so they occlude the beam correctly. Radius went 24 -> 34 so it reads as a landmark. THE SPEC'S THREE STATES are honoured: dormant keeps the full stonework and cut runes but has no beam, no lit segments and no flame - still obviously a waypoint, which section 5.4 explicitly requires - while attuned lights all of it. THE BEAM IS ADDITIVE ('lighter'), and that was a measured correction rather than a preference: source-over blue at 0.2-0.3 alpha over the brown ground resolved to roughly (123,119,112), which is visually grey - it classified as STONE in the pixel check, not as glow. Additive keeps it blue over any ground, which matters because this same object stands on dirt in Dark Woods and on paved ground in Ashenfall; verified on both, 392 and 1176 blue pixels in the beam column respectively. A STATE BUG WAS FIXED ALONGSIDE IT, and the new art is what exposed it: obj.attuned is baked when the world is generated - when there may be no player yet - and tryAttuneWaypoint does not re-set it on the 'already attuned' path, so a waypoint you HAD attuned rendered dormant after every reload. Attunement is now read from player.unlockedWaypoints, the single source of truth (Item 9), with obj.attuned kept only as a fallback for objects with no id. Every ellipse radius is clamped at draw time - a negative radius throws and takes the whole frame with it, which is the failure that produced a black screen during the silk-critter work. VERIFIED BY RENDERING AND READING THE PIXELS, not by inspecting the code: attuned draws 4360px vs the dormant 2655px, 1278 blue vs 125, 365 bright vs 0, and stands 121px tall vs 43px because of the beam; an ASCII render of the output confirms dais, both braziers, rune ring, core and beam are all present and correctly stacked. Suite ok, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.86_WAYPOINT_VISUAL.md.
//
// V0.20.85: MINI-MAP FIX - a regression I introduced in V0.20.80 and did not catch for five versions. Reported: 'Mini Map doesn't work anymore.' ROOT CAUSE: setActiveOverworldZone set `this.staticMinimap = null` to force a redraw at the new zone's size - but NOTHING ever rebuilt it, and drawMinimap early-returns on a null staticMinimap. So the mini-map went permanently black. Worse than a travel-only bug: resetCharacterOwnedState calls setActiveOverworldZone, so this fired for EVERY NEW CHARACTER with no travel required, which is exactly the screenshot. FIX: rebuild it rather than null it - `this.staticMinimap = this.buildStaticMinimap?.() || this.staticMinimap` - which is the exact idiom portal-system.js already uses, with the fallback keeping the previous image if a rebuild fails rather than blanking the HUD. HOW THIS SHOULD HAVE BEEN CAUGHT: every OTHER map-swapping path in the codebase (portal-system, combat-system, save-system, world-serializer) rebuilds the static minimap right where it swaps the map. Mine was the only one that did not. When adding a new code path that does what four existing paths already do, the correct check is to diff against those paths - not to reason from first principles about what the new path needs. That diff would have taken a minute and saved five versions. VERIFIED BY PIXELS, not by the field merely being non-null: the on-screen mini-map canvas is 98.3% non-black in BOTH zones, and the static image rebuilds at the correct per-zone size (360 for Dark Woods, 450 for Ashen Valley) across start, travel out, and travel back. Suite ok, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.85_MINIMAP_REGRESSION.md.
//
// V0.20.84: THE HUD ZONE LINE WAS STATIC HTML THAT NOTHING EVER UPDATED. Screenshot showed the mini-map panel reading 'Blackroot / Dark Woods - 200x200'. Two faults in one string: the SIZE had been wrong since Dark Woods was resized from 200 to 360 (V0.17.4x), and the ZONE NAME could not follow the player because #minimapZoneLine is literal markup in the HTML with NO JavaScript writing to it anywhere - confirmed by grepping every JS file for the id and finding zero references. It had simply been decorative text that happened to be true when it was written. FIX: syncMinimapZoneLine() derives the text from the live zone - product name, the same mapZoneLabel() the zone-map panel uses (so the two can never disagree), and the actual map dimensions. WHERE IT IS CALLED FROM MATTERS, and the first attempt was wrong: hooking drawMinimap left the label showing the PREVIOUS zone, because drawMinimap ran ZERO times across 10 render() calls - it only fires on certain HUD events, not per frame. Measured rather than assumed. It is now driven from setActiveOverworldZone, which is the only thing that can change the text, making it both correct and free. The write is still guarded by a cached string so nothing touches the DOM when the text is unchanged. NOTE: the label deliberately uses the literal 'Blackroot' rather than DR.DEFAULT_WORLD.worldName, which still reads 'Dream Realms' because it is part of the persisted save schema - using it would have regressed the HUD branding to the old name. VERIFIED: at boot it corrects itself from the stale '200x200' markup to 'Blackroot / Dark Woods - 360x360'; travelling shows 'Blackroot / Ashen Valley - 450x450' immediately with no render needed; walking back through the road returns it; and 30 identical frames produce ZERO DOM writes. Suite ok, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.84_HUD_ZONE_LINE.md.
//
// V0.20.83: EDGE CROSSINGS, CORRECT ZONE NAMING, AND A SAVE-CORRUPTING BUG CAUSED BY THE V0.20.80 ACCESSORS. Reported: the warp should be at the edge of the map in both zones, and the zone map should not always say Dark Woods. (1) EDGES: crossings moved to Dark Woods x=357 of 360 (2 tiles from the edge) and Ashen Valley x=3 of 450, so the transition happens where the world visibly ends rather than a short walk inside it. Arrivals stay ~11-12 tiles from the opposite crossing, preserving the V0.20.82 anti-bounce offset. (2) ZONE NAME: minimap-renderer's mapZoneLabel() returned a HARDCODED 'Dark Woods' for any overworld, so the whole map panel was mislabelled in the new zone; it now reads the active zone's authored name. (3) FOG, which is the same bug one level deeper: fogZoneKey() also returned a hardcoded 'dark_woods', so Ashen Valley wrote into DARK WOODS' exploration memory - and at Dark Woods' 360 size against a 450 map. That is exactly why the new zone opened as 'Dark Woods - Explored 0.2%' with one tiny revealed circle: it was reading another zone's fog buffer, sized wrong. Exploration is now per overworld zone. (4) THE SERIOUS ONE, AND IT IS A DIRECT CONSEQUENCE OF THE V0.20.80 ACCESSOR DESIGN: world-serializer's getOverworldMap/getOverworldObjects read game.overworldMap, which since V0.20.80 means THE ACTIVE ZONE rather than Dark Woods. The world save schema stores exactly one overworld under the key dark_woods - so an autosave that fired while the player stood in Ashen Valley serialised its 450x450 terrain into the save's dark_woods slot, PERMANENTLY REPLACING THE STARTING ZONE. Confirmed by a clean boot loading a 'Dark Woods' that was 450 wide, with the Dark Woods and Ashen Valley slots holding the SAME ARRAY OBJECT. This is precisely the risk the accessor approach carries: existing code that said 'overworldMap' meant Dark Woods and now means whatever zone is active. Both readers now take the dark_woods slot BY NAME. (5) And because the damage lives in the SAVE rather than in memory, it survives every reboot, so apply() now REJECTS a saved overworld whose dimensions are not Dark Woods' and falls back to procedural generation - losing editor decoration but keeping the world correct, which is the right trade because a wrong Dark Woods is unrecoverable and a regenerated one is not. VERIFIED: the guard rejected the actually-corrupted 12MB local save with a specific reason and regenerated Dark Woods at 360 with the crossing intact; serialising WHILE STANDING IN ASHEN VALLEY now writes Dark Woods' 360x360; the zone map reads 'Ashen Valley' there and 'Dark Woods' at home; fog keys are separate and the Ashen Valley buffer is sized 450. Suite ok, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.83_EDGE_CROSSINGS_AND_SAVE_CORRUPTION.md.
//
// V0.20.82: THE ROAD CUTS THROUGH THE TREELINE, AND WALKING IT TRAVELS. Reported: there needs to be a path that EXITS the Dark Woods into Ashenfall, with the new zone lying beyond the dense tree border. ROOT CAUSE: ensureDarkWoodsTreeWallBoundary rings the entire 360x360 map in impassable boundary trees - every tile within 4 of the edge is blocked, elevated and given a boundaryTreeWall object. The V0.20.81 crossing sat at x=344, FIFTEEN tiles inside that wall, so it read as a signpost standing in the woods with the treeline unbroken behind it. There was no visible or physical way out; the crossing was a teleport pad in the forest, not an exit. FIX: the road is now carved from inside the forest THROUGH the boundary wall to the map edge (x=326 to x=359 at y=249-251), clearing both the blocked tiles and the boundaryTreeWall OBJECTS - leaving the objects would have kept the gap impassable no matter what the tiles said. The gate is 3 tiles tall, a track rather than a boulevard, and the wall above and below it is verified still intact so the map is not simply opened up. A pair of standing stones frames the gate mouth so it reads as a deliberate opening. Ordering is safe because this function runs late in generateMap and again on world load, so it cuts into a wall that already exists rather than racing it. WALKING NOW TRAVELS: a zone border you must press a key at reads as a signpost, not a way out, so zone-link-system gained an update() that triggers on proximity. Two guards against the corridor loop the spec's validation list calls out: zoneTransitionCooldown (already ticked by game.js, and used by the cave system for exactly this), and ARRIVAL POINTS MOVED ~10 TILES SHORT of the opposite crossing - previously each link's arrival was the other link's exact tile, which with walk-through triggering would have bounced the player between zones forever. The E interaction is kept as well. ONE BUG FOUND IN TESTING: the gate markers silently placed nothing, because the guard only allowed replacing empty ground or boundary trees, and a flower and a mushroom happened to occupy those two tiles; decor now yields, authored props do not. VERIFIED: the road is continuous and unblocked from x=330 to the map edge at x=359, with the boundary wall intact 4 tiles above and below; a character walking EAST with no key presses crosses at (44.5, 300.5) into Valley Farmland; standing still after arrival does not bounce back; walking further inland does not re-trigger; walking WEST returns to Gloamroot Depths at (340.5, 250.5) on walkable ground; and idling there does not bounce again. Suite ok, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.82_TREELINE_GATE.md.
//
// V0.20.81: ASHEN VALLEY WAS UNREACHABLE - a ROAD now connects it. Asked directly whether Ashenfall was connected to Dark Woods; it was not, and worse, it was DEADLOCKED. Fast travel to a waypoint requires that waypoint be DISCOVERED, discovery requires standing beside it, and standing beside it required already being in Ashen Valley. Measured on a fresh character: REACHABLE_BY_NORMAL_PLAY false, legitimateRoutes []. Nothing in Dark Woods referenced the zone - no border, no entrance, no neighbour data. Only debug.travelZone() got there, which means V0.20.80's claim that 'you can travel to it' was true for me and false for a player. I verified the travel MECHANISM and never asked whether a character could invoke it. FIX: DR.ZONE_LINKS in data/default-zones.js defines the walked routes between zones, systems/zone-link-system.js owns the interaction (mirroring the waypoint system's shape rather than inventing a second idiom), and the two world generators place the crossings. The Dark Woods side sits at the far east, ~157 tiles from the start point, which puts it inside GLOAMROOT DEPTHS (levels 7-10) - the right difficulty step into a level 10-20 region, not somewhere a level 3 character stumbles. The Ashen Valley side lands in VALLEY FARMLAND (levels 10-12), joined by road to the city. The waypoint is deliberately NOT gifted: the spec forbids remote unlock, so the player walks there and attunes it like any other. Symmetry is required and asserted - every link has a return leg, or a player can walk somewhere they cannot walk back from. THREE FURTHER BUGS, EACH FOUND ONLY BY WALKING A FRESH CHARACTER THROUGH IT: (1) the crossing was placed BEFORE normalizeOverworldCollisionAndDensity, which prunes objects - the road tiles were carved and the interactable silently removed; moved after it, where the herbs already sit for the same reason. (2) It still did nothing on any EXISTING save, because a saved world bypasses generateMap entirely; re-ensured on world load, exactly as the shipped catalogs are merged rather than replaced - without this every current player had no way in. (3) Even then it did nothing, because the function operated on this.map/this.objects, and during a world load the zone grids are populated BEFORE the live map is assigned - so it ran, found nothing, and returned 0. It now targets the dark_woods slot BY NAME. Same shape as the waypoint nearly placed in the wrong zone. (4) And the interaction system registered but was INERT: installExternalSystems only stores the returned runtime and never calls init(), so game.zoneLinkSystem was never assigned - no error, anywhere. waypoint-system.js calls its own runtime.init() at the end of install; this now does too. VERIFIED end to end on a fresh character with no waypoints and no debug: walks to the crossing in Gloamroot Depths, crosses to Valley Farmland on walkable ground, attunes Ashenfall (deadlock broken), walks the return road home to Dark Woods, and fast travel is then ALLOWED in both directions. The crossing is present on the existing 12MB world save, not just new worlds. Combat blocks the road with a reason. Suite ok, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.81_ROAD_TO_ASHEN_VALLEY.md.
//
// V0.20.80: ASHEN VALLEY PHASE 1 (Roadmap Item 26) - A SECOND OVERWORLD ZONE EXISTS. The game previously had exactly one overworld: game.overworldMap/overworldObjects/overworldEnemies were plain fields holding Dark Woods, and portal-system.js restores the overworld with a literal `this.map = this.overworldMap`. There was nowhere for a second region to live. ARCHITECTURE, AND WHY IT IS NOT A CASCADE PATCH: those three names have ~70 call sites across 20+ files, but only EIGHT are WRITES. Renaming them to a keyed collection would have meant editing all 70. Instead core/overworld-zone-registry.js turns them into PROTOTYPE ACCESSORS onto the active zone's slot - every existing read works unchanged, every existing write lands in the active zone, and switching zones is one assignment. Accessors are installed FIRST in game.js, before `new Game()`, because the constructor assigns all three and an assignment with no setter present would create own properties that permanently shadow them (the same shadowing trap that broke ctx patching during the V0.20.4x profiling work). NEW CONTENT: data/default-zones.js gains ashen_valley (450x450, levels 10-20) with NINE subregions - Ashenfall City, Valley Farmland, Ashen Riverlands, Ashwood Forest, Sunken Marsh, Old Ruins, Rocky Highlands, Abandoned Mine, Abandoned Cemetery. systems/ashen-valley-world-system.js generates the terrain (river spine, marsh, highlands, ruins, forest, flattened city plate, roads to every subregion) using the exact {type,elev,blocked,waterDepth} tile contract Dark Woods uses, so collision, pathfinding, swimming, fishing, minimap and the renderer all work on it with zero changes. Generation is LAZY - 202,500 tiles is not worth paying at boot for players who never travel; it costs 42ms on first entry. FAST TRAVEL: systems/waypoint-system.js's own header set the condition 'with exactly one waypoint in the game so far, a fast-travel menu would have nowhere meaningful to travel between yet'. A second waypoint now exists, so travel is implemented, with the spec's rules - discovery is per character and personal, an undiscovered destination is refused, and every refusal carries a specific reason. THREE BUGS FOUND BY TESTING, ALL MINE: (1) the Ashenfall waypoint was nearly placed in DARK WOODS, because Game.placeObject writes to `this.objects` - the ACTIVE zone - and Ashen Valley is generated while Dark Woods is still active; it is now written directly into the new zone's own array. (2) A NEW CHARACTER inherited the previous character's zone and would have begun in the level 10-20 region; fixed by a mirror in resetCharacterOwnedState, the same belongings-leak shape as the V0.20.2 mount bug. (3) That mirror initially set only the zone ID and not the live map, leaving a fresh character standing on Ashen Valley's 450x450 terrain while every readout said 'dark_woods' - nastier than the original bug because it looks correct from outside. (4) Subregions were authored LARGEST-FIRST, and because box regions are tested in array order with first-match-wins, Sunken Marsh was completely hidden behind Ashen Riverlands and Abandoned Mine behind Ashwood Forest - both regions could never resolve anywhere. Now ordered smallest-area-first. PERSISTENCE: activeOverworldZoneId is saved, restored and reset; saves written before this version have no such field and correctly default to Dark Woods, where every existing character is. VERIFIED: no accessor shadowing; Dark Woods unchanged through the accessors and unaffected by generating another zone; travel both ways with walkable arrival; all 9 subregions own real WALKABLE territory with zero occlusion (swept every 2nd tile of the whole 450x450 zone, not just anchors); new character resets to Dark Woods 360x360; an Ashen Valley save restores to 450x450; a legacy save with no zone field lands safely in Dark Woods. Suite ok, 397/397, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.80_ASHEN_VALLEY_PHASE1.md.
