// V0.20.51: ROOTS AT THE FEET - the real fix, and the reason I missed it twice. Reported repeatedly that snare roots wrap the waist instead of the ankles. I twice 'verified' a fix and was twice wrong, because I tested with a FIGHTER and the bug is CLASS-SPECIFIC. MECHANISM: ground-anchored VFX prefer target._lastGroundAnchor.groundY (V0.18.36) because a humanoid's model origin sits at the hips, ~33-44px above the rendered feet. The shared humanoid base renderer derives that foot line properly - groundY = y + max(legs.near.foot.y, legs.far.foot.y) - but the BESPOKE class models published `groundY: y`, the model ORIGIN, i.e. the hips. Any class routed through its own premium model therefore reported its waist as the ground. MEASURED ACROSS ALL 14 CLASSES: thirteen reported the foot line +33px BELOW the hip anchor; PALADIN reported -5px, i.e. ABOVE it - and the reporter's character is a Paladin. FIX: both bespoke publishers (drawPremiumPaladinModel and the fighter-bruiser variant) now derive groundY from their own leg/foot anchors exactly as the base renderer does. VERIFIED, this time end to end and not by proxy: all 14 classes now report a positive foot line (Paladin 44px, others 33px, zero broken); and applying a REAL root status to a live Paladin resolves the effect to drawY 682 against a true foot line of 682 - dead on the feet, 44px below the hips. LESSON: 'I verified it' is worthless if the sample cannot exhibit the bug. A per-class defect needs a per-class sweep, and the two earlier checks (anchor exists / Fighter draws correctly) were both true and both irrelevant. Suite ok, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.51_ROOTS_AT_FEET.md.
//
// V0.20.50: REVERT OF V0.20.49 - my humanoid sprite-cache optimisation made things WORSE (12 FPS -> 7) and broke the snare-root foot anchors. Both were my fault and both are undone. WHY IT FAILED: the runtime cache key correctly includes the animation bucket and moveBlend, so for an actor that is actually MOVING the key changes constantly. The cache has a per-frame miss budget (96), which real motion blows immediately - measured 2,514 budget skips in a sampled frame - so drawModel DECLINED nearly every call. But each declined call had already paid for an entity object spread, an equipment resolution and a long cache-key string build, and then the procedural draw ran anyway. I added pure overhead on top of the original work. WHY MY VERIFICATION MISSED IT: I benchmarked by calling render() in a loop on a FROZEN frame - no update(), so nothing moved, every key was stable and the cache reported a 92% hit rate. It did not survive contact with a moving world. A render-only benchmark is not a benchmark. THE ROOT BUG: humanoid feet draw ~38px below the body origin, so _rootVfxFootAnchor sits at the hips; the true foot line is published by the humanoid renderer as _lastGroundAnchor.groundY (V0.18.36), which the effects renderer prefers. On a cache HIT no draw ran, so _lastGroundAnchor was never published and roots fell back to the hip anchor - roots at the waist, exactly as reported. REVERTED: the humanoid branches call their procedural models directly again and the drawCachedHumanoid helper is deleted (no dead code). VERIFIED: 15/15 humanoids publish _lastGroundAnchor again, the player's foot line sits +33px below the hip anchor, 0 entities on the cache path, suite ok, 0 console errors. Item 21 is NOT abandoned, but the next attempt must be benchmarked with update() running so actors move. See docs/V0.20.50_REVERT_HUMANOID_CACHING.md.
//
// V0.20.49: HUMANOID RENDER CACHING - Roadmap Item 21, first slice, no content removed. Your FPS counter read 12, which matched my harness prediction and put the whole remaining gap in RENDER (~70ms of an ~83ms frame; update is ~11ms after V0.20.46). Profiled the render by counting canvas ops: 6,407 beginPath, 4,297 stroke, 3,135 fill per frame - and only 92 drawImage. Ablation attributed ~12ms and ~2,612 of those strokes to ENTITIES: 19 drawn actors were costing ~140 vector operations EACH because humanoid models were re-drawn limb-by-limb every frame. ROOT CAUSE, and it was not missing technology: tryDrawEntityAtlasFrame depends on a PRE-BAKED atlas (assets/atlases/entities.json) that loads its manifest but has ZERO pages and ZERO frames, so isReady() is always false and 100% of fallbacks report 'atlas_not_ready' - every actor dropped to the procedural path. The RUNTIME sprite cache, which bakes a procedural model to a bitmap on demand, was already healthy (95% hit rate) but was only wired into the NPC path. FIX: humanoid entities now route through that same runtime cache (drawCachedHumanoid). Two details make it safe - the draw methods render into the module-scoped window.ctx rather than a passed context, so the bake temporarily repoints window.ctx at the cache's offscreen canvas and restores it in a finally (the identical pattern this file already used for cached nameplates); and the cache re-applies _nameplateAnchor on every draw INCLUDING hits, so nameplates, health bars and rod/VFX anchors keep tracking. The procedural draw remains the fallback whenever the cache declines, so nothing can go unrendered. RESULT: render 31.4 -> 18.3ms in-harness (-42%), beginPath 6,407 -> 3,713 (-42%), stroke 4,297 -> 1,685 (-61%), 15 of 16 drawn entities cached, 0 bake failures, 0 evictions. CORRECTNESS verified rather than assumed: four facings produce four distinct cache entries (a shared key would have actors facing the wrong way), walk and idle differ, and BOTH player gear (which lives on game.equipment, not the entity) and bot gear invalidate and revert. That last one caught a regression I had introduced: resolveActorVisualEquipment returns an EMPTY OBJECT for bots, which is truthy, and assigning it to visualEquipment shadowed botEquipment in buildKey's fallback chain - a bot's gear change would have left a stale sprite. Now only assigned when a real gear map resolves. Suite ok, 0 console errors. Render is still the dominant half; world-object baking and effect gradients are the next slices. See docs/V0.20.49_HUMANOID_RENDER_CACHING.md.
//
// V0.20.48: THREE REPORTED ISSUES. (1) FPS COUNTER NOT VISIBLE - my V0.20.47 fix was wrong and my verification was wrong in the same way: I placed the box at a fixed top:232px 'below the mini-map' and then checked only that its computed display was not 'none'. The mini-map panel is actually 310px tall, so the counter sat BEHIND it; elementFromPoint at its centre returned worldClockTime. display!=='none' is not the same as visible. It is now a flex CHILD of #minimapWrap, so it always flows below whatever that panel contains at any height (the dungeon card shows/hides and changes it). Re-verified by occlusion, not by style: elementFromPoint at its centre returns fpsCounter itself, and driving the real updater renders '60 FPS' / '20 FPS'. (2) BOT SLIDING - bots have their own locomotion state and 13 of 14 set it correctly, but one was measured covering 1.09 tiles with moveBlend 0 and no velocity, so getEntityAtlasAction resolved 'idle' and it slid in a standing pose. Cause: a bot can be repositioned while its own update has already declared it stationary - the casting/busy branches zero moveBlend and return early - so a fix INSIDE the bot update was overwritten in the same frame. Moved it to a post-pass (Game.deriveBotLocomotion) that runs after every entity update, deriving the gait from ground actually covered. Per-frame measurement: sliding went from sustained to 1.6% of walking frames (single transition frames from the one-frame derivation lag). The first attempt traded one bug for another - it only ever RAISED moveBlend, so stationary bots animated in place (655 of 871 still frames); adding a decay brought that to the intended blend-out tail. (3) PARTY INVITE WINDOW - the markup and handlers existed but there was NO CSS for .partyInvitePopup anywhere, so an invite rendered as an unstyled block in document flow. Added a proper centred modal: fixed 50%/42%, z-index 60, framed card, class emblem, member line and styled Accept/Decline. Verified centred, on top and interactive. Suite ok, 396/396, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.48_FPS_BOTS_PARTY_INVITE.md.
