// V0.20.40: THE LOOT AUDIT THAT KEPT CATCHING ITSELF - Roadmap Item 12 (Loot & Acquisition Audit). RESULT: the acquisition system is HEALTHY - 0 dangling loot references (all 193 runtime loot itemIds resolve to the 396-item catalog) and 0 genuinely unobtainable items. But the JOURNEY is the story, and it is the session's recurring lesson turned on my own audit: the first pass reported 133 'unobtainable' items; almost every one was a bug in MY methodology, not the game. (1) My object-walk did not collect bare strings inside arrays, so it missed EVERY shop item (shops are id -> ['item_x', ...]). (2) Gathering/fishing reference items by display NAME ('Gloomleaf'), not id, so a name->id map was needed. (3) Starter gear (item_starter_v01689_*, 70 items) is granted at RUNTIME onto game.equipment - not the player, and not in any walked data blob (V0.20.2: belongings live on the GAME). (4) The last candidate, item_torn_lookout_ledger, is granted by a quest POI (quests.js:74 grantItem), a source the walk did not cover. Correcting each layer took the count 133 -> 71 -> 1 -> 0. Nothing to fix - but the loot-reference invariant is worth guarding, so this SHIPS a regression check: tools/check-loot-references.js (wired into validate.sh) cross-references every loot itemId against the item catalog and fails the build on a dangling one. Verified NOT vacuous by a negative control (an injected fake ref is flagged, and only it). Suite PASS, items 396/396, 0 console errors, new checker green. See docs/V0.20.40_LOOT_ACQUISITION_AUDIT.md.
