// V0.20.20: THE ROGUE HAD NO KNIFE - Roadmap Item 6 extended past the Fighter, and a correction of my own plan twice over. I RECOMMENDED THIS AS 'the engineering is done, the work is just craft - author vfxStyle across six classes'. THAT WAS FALSE, and checking before authoring is the only reason it did not become 100 lines of dead data: spell.vfxStyle was read in exactly ONE place (spell-system.js:1021, the Fighter's own resolver) out of THIRTEEN class resolvers. FIRST FIX - the mechanism, before any authoring: two other playAttackAnimation call sites hardcoded 'slash', both inside resolveClassSpell, the GENERIC fallback resolver every class without a bespoke path falls through to. That is precisely the `id === 'titan_chop' || id === 'perfect_masterstroke' ? 'slam' : 'slash'` bug V0.20.0 fixed for the Fighter, still alive one function away, making vfxStyle inert for everyone else. Both call sites (the melee branch and the charge/gap-closer branch - both, or a style would work on a class's normal swing and vanish on its charge) now read spell.vfxStyle. SECOND CORRECTION - the scope: only FOUR classes have melee/meleeDebuff spells at all (Fighter 10, Rogue 11, Paladin 4, Warden 3). The casters use spawnBolt/spawnRing - a different mechanism entirely - so 'six classes' was wrong; the Wizard's 10x spawnRing is the Assassin's pre-V0.18.29 problem and needs a build, not a field. THE REAL FIND: the ROGUE never called playAttackAnimation AT ALL. Eleven melee abilities - Backstab, Garrote, Silent Execution - spawned a ring on the ground and dealt damage with NO strike drawn. The only melee class in the game with no melee animation. Fixed in resolveRogueRevampSpell, placed before the damage so the strike reads as causing it. AUTHORED 10 styles using existing silhouettes (no new renderer work): backstab/perfect_counter -> thrust (a stab and a counter are not swings), sap/stonehand_strike -> crush (a blackjack and a stone fist are blunt), twin_fang -> claw (two daggers ARE the twin-arc), flurry_cut -> wild, killing_cut/silent_execution/divine_verdict -> execute, judgment -> slam. DELIBERATELY LEFT BASELINE: Quick Cut and Radiant Strike are the plain opening swing, and Bleeding Vein, Garrote, Deathdose, Briar Lash, Thornsnare and Holy Rebuke have NO honest silhouette in DR.SLASH_STYLES - a bleed, a wire and a poison are not shapes this renderer knows, and forcing one would be decoration rather than communication. VERIFIED BY WHAT REACHES THE RENDERER, not by what is in the file - and it caught me mid-flight: the first run showed all 7 Rogue styles as '(none)', because the Rogue resolver never animated, so I had authored dead data exactly as feared. I removed them, fixed the resolver, restored them, and re-tested: 12/12 now draw their authored style. One apparent failure - Killing Cut drawing nothing - was MY TEST: it is an execute and correctly refused a full-health dummy ('requires the target to be at or below 30% HP'); at 10% it draws its execute. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues (the unknown-vfx-style validator accepts all 19), warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.20_MELEE_SILHOUETTES.md.
// V0.20.19: YOU CAN TURN THE SHAKING OFF - Roadmap Item 20's first real accessibility feature (1 of 12), and the one with the strongest case: vestibular. Screen shake fires on melee swings (combat-system:1471), critical strikes (combat-system:1667) and portals (portal-system:278), and is decayed each frame by effects-system:276. It can now be turned off in a new ACCESSIBILITY section in Settings - its own section rather than filed under HUD, because it is not a HUD preference and someone looking for it will look for the word. GATED AT THE CONSUMER: shake is written from four places and READ in exactly ONE - getCameraProjectionCache (game.js) - so one line covers every source, plus any future one, instead of four edits and four chances to miss the fifth. That is the cascade-patch the golden rules forbid, avoided by finding the funnel. It zeroes the READ rather than camera.shake itself: the producers keep incrementing and effects-system keeps decaying precisely as before, so no other system can notice the setting exists, and toggling it back mid-session is instant with no state to reconcile. OFF BY DEFAULT (i.e. shake stays ON) - a default must never silently change how the game looks for a player who did not ask. It reuses the existing settingKey toggle path, so it persists through V0.20.18's uiPrefs save for free; this is the first feature that NEEDED that fix, and without it the toggle would have been forgotten on every reload - worse than never offering it. VERIFIED through the real code path, after a first probe that measured NOTHING because I guessed the function name wrong (it returned undefined for both states and I nearly read that as a working gate): with the pref off the view consumes 4; with it on the source still writes 4 and the view consumes 0; producers untouched. The row renders in its own section with an explanation, clicks through the panel's own handler, flips the pref and saves immediately. NOTE the toggle BUTTON TEXT stays stale after a synthetic click - but the shipped Show Minimap toggle behaves IDENTICALLY under the same test, and a re-render shows the correct state for both, so this is either a pre-existing quirk or an artifact of dispatching .click() rather than a real user click. It is NOT mine, my row is indistinguishable from the ones that shipped years of versions ago, and chasing it would be chasing a test artifact. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.19_SCREEN_SHAKE_TOGGLE.md.
// V0.20.18: THE SETTINGS REMEMBER YOU NOW - uiPrefs persist, which they never have. THE BUG: game.js assigned `this.uiPrefs = { showMinimap: true, showMercPanel: true, showPartyHud: true, largeChat: true }` fresh on every boot, and NOTHING saved or loaded it - verified empirically, not by reading: after toggling a pref, nothing in localStorage mentioned it, nothing in serializeCharacterState carried it, and typeof saveUiPrefs was 'undefined'. Toggle Show Minimap off, reload, it is back on. Three settings the game offers and then forgets. THE DETAIL THAT MAKES IT WORTH TELLING: that line sits directly above `this.keyBindings = this.loadKeyBindings()` - a persistence system that has worked correctly the whole time, one line away, never copied. THE FIX deliberately mirrors that neighbour rather than inventing a scheme: defaultUiPrefs/loadUiPrefs/saveUiPrefs with the same storage-key shape ('dream-realms.ui-prefs.v1'), the same defaults-then-overlay merge (so a pref added in a LATER version appears for an existing player instead of being missing - verified with an old blob containing only showMinimap: the old choice is kept AND the newer defaults fill in), and the same swallow-and-carry-on error handling (verified: corrupt JSON falls back to defaults rather than breaking boot). Saved at the ONE place a pref mutates - the settingKey branch of the settings-panel click handler, confirmed by grep to be the only assignment to uiPrefs[...] in the codebase - so there is exactly one save site, not a scattering. Per-BROWSER rather than per-character, like the keybindings it copies: whether the minimap is visible is a property of the person playing, not of their Fighter. WHY IT MATTERS BEYOND THE THREE TOGGLES: found while auditing Roadmap Item 20, which requires 'accessibility settings must persist per user'. This was the hard blocker underneath the whole item - a reduced-motion or screen-shake toggle built on uiPrefs today would be forgotten on every reload, and an accessibility setting the game forgets is WORSE than one it never offered. Item 20's audit also found: input support is largely DONE (full key remapping - setKeyBinding/saveKeyBindings/resetKeyBindings - plus Steam Deck support), while accessibility features are 0 of 12 (no UI/font scale, colourblind, reduced motion, particle density, shake toggle, high contrast, subtitles, dialogue speed, hold-vs-toggle); and screen shake is real (set on hits, crits and portals) with EXACTLY ONE consumer at game.js:3512, so a toggle is a one-line gate covering all four sources - now unblocked by this. VERIFIED BY A REAL PAGE RELOAD rather than a simulated one: showMinimap:false survived a genuine boot, and the minimap element computed to display:none, proving the pref reached the SCREEN and not just the object. Test state cleaned up afterwards. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.18_UI_PREFS_PERSISTENCE.md.
// V0.20.17: WHAT DYING COSTS YOU - Roadmap Item 24 (death, failure and recovery). Item 24's headline deliverable is 'a central failure-policy document [defining] which states are temporary, recoverable, permanent, or branch-specific', and it did not exist. docs/FAILURE_POLICY.md now does - and every rule in it was MEASURED against the running game rather than read out of the code: a character was killed and respawned repeatedly with food, potion and class buffs active. THE POLICY, IN ONE LINE: death costs you time and nothing else. Measured on death - food/potion/class buffs ALL SURVIVE; inventory untouched (5 -> 5); money untouched; player XP and level not lost; profession XP not lost; equipment untouched (and NO item in the game carries a durability field, so 'swimming deaths damage equipment' is unanswerable - nothing can be damaged); death location recorded (deathZone/deathDungeonId/deathDungeonFloor); 'You were slain' logged immediately. Measured on respawn - HP restored to FULL, buffs STILL survive, returns to the Dream Spirit near camp (100.5,91.5 vs camp 100,100), 'You return to the Dream Spirit' logged. THE KEY RESULT IS CONSISTENCY: buffs persist through BOTH death and respawn - one policy applied at both ends, with no seam where a buff survives dying and then vanishes on returning, which is exactly the inconsistency Item 24 exists to prevent. A HUNCH OF MINE WAS WRONG AND MEASURING KILLED IT: I flagged Item 24 as 'the sleeper' because a test character died in V0.20.10 and I did not notice for three debugging rounds - I assumed death was silent. It is not. It logs immediately; I was reading playerAlive rather than the log. Item 24's visibility rule was already met. NOTHING CHANGED IN THE GAME. The document describes what already happens, classifies it (temporary: death/HP/DPS meter; recoverable: position, via camp respawn or bot resurrection; PERMANENT: nothing at all; branch-specific: only the Rurik quest fork), and marks the rules Item 24 lists for systems that DO NOT EXIST - mount state, taming materials, equipment durability - as unanswerable rather than answering them with fiction, because a policy describing behaviour the code does not have is precisely the dead data this session has spent fifteen versions removing. Two consistency requirements are honestly marked UNVERIFIED: whether death state round-trips through serializeCharacterState, and quest recovery across zones. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/FAILURE_POLICY.md.
// V0.20.16: LOOK AT ME WHEN I'M TALKING TO YOU - Roadmap Item 16 ambient behaviour, and a dead call of MY OWN from one version ago. THE BUG I SHIPPED: V0.20.15's patrol ended with `npc.setFacingFromDelta?.(nx - npc.x, ny - npc.y)`. A placed NPC is a plain grid node, NOT an Entity - it has no setFacingFromDelta and no facingX/facingY at all (verified: the node has 29 keys and neither field is among them). The optional chain swallowed the call in perfect silence, so the Mossfang Scout and Road Warden Cael walked their new rounds for an entire version SLIDING, never turning to face their direction of travel. The `?.` that made the call safe is exactly what made it invisible: the same dead-call pattern as V0.20.9's findLootableCorpseNear (a guard calling a method that never existed), written by me ONE VERSION AFTER I documented the pattern in the dead-field map. THE FIX: new faceNodeToward(node, dx, dy) sets facingX/facingY DIRECTLY - those are the fields the renderer actually reads (entity-renderer standingDirectionProfile, V0.19.9) - normalised, and refusing a zero delta rather than writing facing (0,0), because V0.19.7 spent a whole version on what happens when a facing vector is quietly wrong and (0,0) is not a direction. WHAT FOUND IT: asking whether NPCs turn to face the PLAYER when spoken to. They never have - interactWithNpc went straight to openNpcWindow, so Road Warden Cael would tell you the road is safer than the trees while facing away from you down it. Item 16 asks for NPCs that react rather than stare, and this is the cheapest possible instance: no authored data needed, the player's position is right there. Now every NPC turns to whoever walks up, from any side. VERIFIED: the probe that exposed the dead call now shows facing going from {} (absent) to a properly normalised vector (length exactly 1.0000); NPCs face the player correctly from all four approaches (east -> 0 deg, west -> 180, south -> 90, north -> -90); and standing EXACTLY on top of an NPC keeps their previous facing (0,-1) rather than writing (0,0). Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.16_NPC_FACING.md.
// V0.20.15: ROADMAP ITEM 16 (NPC schedules and ambient behaviour) - TWO PEOPLE WHO ASKED TO WALK. Item 16's goal is 'make camps feel inhabited rather than static', and the data had already asked for it: every one of the 33 NPCs authors `patrol: { mode, radius, speed }`, and NOTHING has ever read it for behaviour. The two apparent reads are both false - editor-system.js:1758 merely COPIES the field, and dungeon-system.js reads `encounter.patrol`, a completely different object. That is also why tools/check-dead-fields.js never flagged it: the scan is NAME-based, not type-aware, so a field name read on ANY object counts as read everywhere - the same false negative found with maxRank (read on talent nodes, not professions) in V0.20.14. The scanner's candidate list is a floor, not a ceiling. THE FIELD IS TWO KINDS AT ONCE, which is new: 31 NPCs author mode 'stationary' - exactly what they already do, so EMPTY, describing the default - while TWO author 'short_loop' with a radius and a speed and have stood perfectly still since they were written, so BROKEN. Only the two that asked get movement: Mossfang Scout (lore, radius 3, speed 0.8) and Road Warden Cael (quest_giver, radius 2, speed 0.65). ITEM 16'S SAFETY RULES, each honoured explicitly and each verified rather than asserted: 'critical quest NPCs must never become inaccessible' - Cael carries SIX quests, and his authored radius of 2 means he orbits his own post and cannot leave it (verified: 0 strayed beyond radius; still found by findNearbyNpc from his home tile). 'NPCs must not overlap' + 'must respect collision' - a step onto an unwalkable tile, an occupied tile, or the player is REFUSED rather than forced (verified: 0 overlaps). 'must not block portals, exits, or narrow paths' - movement is bounded to the authored radius around HOME, captured once at first sight so the loop cannot drift off its post a little each lap; an NPC can never wander into a doorway it did not start in. 'dialogue interaction should pause or adapt movement safely' - the active NPC holds still while their window is open (verified: Cael moved 0.0000 across 120 ticks of being talked to, and resumed after). 'must recover if an NPC becomes stuck' - there is no stuck state to recover FROM: the angle is DERIVED from the clock, so a refused step is simply skipped and the next angle is tried. 'deterministic and save-compatible' - the angle is a pure function of Date.now() and a hash of the NPC's own id (so two patrollers never march in step); NO patrol state is stored, so there is nothing to save, migrate or desync, and a reload resumes mid-stride. A FIRST ATTEMPT MOVED NOBODY, and the reason is V0.20.4's lesson repeating: patrol is authored on the DRAFT, and allNpcs() returns raw placed NODES - only interactWithNpc merges the draft in. I read the runtime copy instead of the descriptor, exactly as the quest journal once did. Now resolved from DR.NPC_DRAFT_BY_ID and cached per node. Verified: 2 of 28 moved, at exactly their authored radii (3 and 2); 26 stayed still; 0 strayed; 0 overlaps. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.15_NPC_PATROLS.md.
// V0.20.14: THE THIRD KIND OF DEAD - no game change, deliberately. Triaging the next dead-field candidates found something that reframes the remaining list: allowedZone / allowedRegion / allowedBiome (8x each, data/resources.js) are unread ON PURPOSE, and the data file ITSELF documents it: 'declarative spawn-scope metadata (placement already enforces exclusivity physically via the dark_woods resource grid; a later phase can read these to hard-guard)'. The author knew, wrote down why, and the rule IS enforced - just physically, by ensureDarkWoodsOverworldHerbs only placing each herb in its own region, rather than declaratively. Retiring them would delete a documented plan; implementing them would duplicate an enforcement that already works. The correct action is NONE, and taking none is the finding. THAT IS A THIRD CATEGORY, and all three look IDENTICAL in a scanner list while wanting opposite treatment: BROKEN - claims something and never delivers (coneDegrees drew a circle; 33 NPC portraits never shown; interactLabel had a hardcoded twin) -> implement. EMPTY - true of everything, or duplicated by a field that IS read (requiresHeavyWeapon is on every Fighter attack including the lv1 basic; the loose footstep fields were copies of footstepProfile) -> retire (86 declarations across V0.20.12-13). DELIBERATE - documented metadata awaiting a phase -> LEAVE ALONE. tools/check-dead-fields.js now prints all three with their examples and ends with the only instruction that actually works: open the file, read the comments, ask what it would MEAN if it were read. This matters because the scan has now been wrong in every available direction - it missed quoted keys (V0.20.11), it reported a profile's own nested contents as dead tile fields (V0.20.13), my triage grep counted a default literal in code as a read (V0.20.13), and I myself called an empty flag a broken gate (V0.20.12). Four errors, four kinds. The tool's value is that it points; the judgement was always the human part, and the tool now says so in its own output. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. 24 candidates remain, each needing the file opened rather than the list trusted. See docs/V0.20.14_THIRD_KIND_OF_DEAD.md.
// V0.20.13: THE SAME WORDS, TWICE - continuing the dead-field retirement, with V0.20.12's lesson applied FIRST: ask what a field would MEAN if it were read, before touching it. THE DUPLICATION: every tile in data/tiles.js authored `terrainType: 'grass', footstepEffect: 'grass_blade_fx', footstepSound: 'grass_soft', footstepRateModifier: 1.0` loose on one line - and on the NEXT line a `footstepProfile: { terrainId, terrainName, particleEffect: 'grass_blade_fx', decalEffectOptional, soundSet: 'grass_soft', stepIntervalModifier: 1.0, ... }` carrying the same three values under different names, plus everything else. ONLY THE PROFILE IS READ: systems/terrain-footstep-system.js reads def.footstepProfile for particles, and systems/audio-system.js:535 reads profile.soundSet for the sound. So the three loose fields are exact duplicates of profile contents - 33 declarations removed, behaviour-neutral, and footsteps are unchanged (grass still sounds like grass because soundSet: 'grass_soft' inside the profile was always the one being played). WHAT WAS NOT CUT, AND WHY - this is the V0.20.12 lesson paying for itself: the scanner also flagged terrainName (10x) and decalEffectOptional (10x), and an earlier pass of mine called them dead. They have ZERO loose declarations. They exist ONLY INSIDE footstepProfile, which is read wholesale and whose shape terrainFallbackProfile deliberately mirrors - the scanner was reporting the profile's own contents as if they were tile fields. Cutting them would have been the heavy-weapon mistake again, in the opposite direction: acting on 'not read' without asking what it would mean. My own earlier triage ALSO mis-called terrainName, counting the fallback profile's literal in code as a read. Two wrong answers about the same field, from two different tools, before looking at the actual structure. VERIFIED: footstepEffect/footstepSound/footstepRateModifier 11 -> 0 each; terrainType (which IS read by terrainFallbackProfile) untouched at 11; all 11 footstepProfile declarations intact; at runtime 10 of 11 tile defs carry a truthy profile and the 11th is Cave Wall with a DELIBERATE null - you cannot walk on a wall, and terrain-footstep-system:84 checks `=== null` for exactly that case, so it is not a gap; the grass profile still carries soundSet/particleEffect/stepIntervalModifier. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. Dead-field candidates now 27 -> 24. See docs/V0.20.13_TILE_FOOTSTEP_DUPLICATES.md.
// V0.20.12: I WAS WRONG ABOUT THE HEAVY WEAPON - retiring 53 dead field declarations, and correcting V0.20.11's own recommendation. V0.20.11's new scanner found requiresHeavyWeapon (authored 13x in data/spells.js, 0 reads) and I reported it as 'the coneDegrees pattern exactly: an authored gameplay gate that never gates', recommending implement-or-retire with a balance decision. INVESTIGATING IT KILLED THAT FRAMING. The flag is on 13 of the Fighter's 20 spells - and the other 7 are all buffs and a dashStrike, i.e. every spell that does NOT swing a weapon. So it is true of every Fighter attack that uses a weapon, INCLUDING Heavy Swing at level 1, the class's basic attack. Meanwhile only 7 of the game's 42 weapons carry twoHanded, one of them the Blackroot Staff (a caster weapon). Enforcing the gate would have locked a Fighter's ENTIRE kit - basic attack included - behind a handful of weapons they may not even own: that is not a bug fix, that is a broken class. The field discriminates NOTHING; it says 'the Fighter's weapon attacks use the Fighter's weapon'. A flag that is true of every member of a set carries no information - the same fault as the 'Required' marker refused in V0.20.5 (no task is optional, so the word would never vary). classMechanic is the same shape and equally uninformative: 20/20 Shaman spells say 'primal_schools', 20/20 Summoner spells say 'planar_summons' - one value per class, stamped onto every spell of that class. It is a CLASS-level fact copied 40 times; it belongs on the class, not the spell. BOTH RETIRED (the poisonResist decision, on the retire branch): 53 declarations deleted from data/spells.js - 40 classMechanic + 13 requiresHeavyWeapon. Behaviour-neutral BY CONSTRUCTION, since nothing read them, and verified rather than assumed: 280 spells still compile, Fighter/Shaman/Summoner still 20 each, 0 compiler errors, Heavy Swing keeps its real fields (power, weaponDamageMultiplier), suite PASS, 0 console errors. The scanner's own candidate list drops 29 -> 27, which closes the loop it opened. THE LESSON, and it is the session's own lesson turned back on me: 'authored and never read' identifies a SUSPECT, not a crime. Six times it meant something was broken; twice now it has meant the field was always meaningless. Reporting 'a gate that never gates' before checking WHAT it gates was the same failure as trusting a green check without asking what it proved. Remaining candidates (27) are unchanged and still need triage - the tiles' footstepSound/footstepEffect/terrainName/decalEffectOptional are already triaged as superseded legacy (the footstep system reads footstepProfile, which all 11 tiles author and which carries the same information) and are the obvious next retirement. See docs/V0.20.12_RETIRING_DEAD_FIELDS.md.
// V0.20.11: A MAP OF WHAT NOBODY READS - tooling for the bug class this whole session kept finding by accident. SIX dead fields turned up one at a time: coneDegrees (V0.19.6, authored on a spell that calls itself a cone, read for one hardcoded id), the 'east'/'west' poses (V0.19.9, unreachable because `0 || 1` is 1), slam/crush/cast (V0.20.0, styles passed and never drawn), portrait (V0.20.6, authored on ALL 33 NPCs and read by NOTHING), interactLabel (V0.20.10, authored on 4 objects, hidden behind a hardcoded twin and a missing panel), plus one I wrote myself (V0.20.9's findLootableCorpseNear, a guard calling a method that never existed). Each was somebody's care that never reached a player, and each was found by tripping over it. NEW tools/check-dead-fields.js: collects every field name authored in data/*.js and cross-checks for ANY read outside data/ - `.field`, ['field'], destructuring, or the name as a lookup string. FINDINGS: 29 candidates at a 3+-use threshold, of which TWO are CONFIRMED by targeted grep and are real: classMechanic (authored 40x in data/spells.js, 0 reads anywhere in systems/render/core/entities/game.js) and requiresHeavyWeapon (authored 13x, 0 reads - THIRTEEN abilities declare they need a heavy weapon, and the only heavy-weapon logic in the codebase is inventory-system's equip check, so they can all be cast with a dagger: the coneDegrees pattern exactly, an authored gameplay gate that never gates). Also triaged: the tiles' footstepSound / footstepEffect / footstepRateModifier / terrainName / decalEffectOptional are dead but NOT a broken feature - systems/terrain-footstep-system.js reads `footstepProfile`, which all 11 tiles also author and which carries the same information, so those five are superseded LEGACY duplicates and the honest fix is retirement, not implementation (the poisonResist decision, on the retire branch). DELIBERATELY ADVISORY and NOT wired into validate.sh as a build failure, because it is a heuristic and a checker that cries wolf gets ignored: dynamic obj[key] access reads a field without naming it, and a field can exist purely to round-trip through save/load. Both limitations are real and both bit during development - the tool initially missed QUOTED keys ("classMechanic": is not classMechanic:), and my own triage grep counted WRITES in code (a default profile literal declaring terrainName) as reads, giving confident wrong answers in opposite directions. The two confirmed findings above were verified by hand after both tools disagreed. Capitalised names are skipped: loot-tables.js is a map keyed 'Woods'/'Rare'/'Boss', and reporting catalogue keys as dead fields is noise (34 -> 29 candidates). NO GAMEPLAY CHANGED in this version - it is the map, not the digging. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.11_DEAD_FIELD_MAP.md.
// V0.20.10: ROADMAP ITEM 17 (prompts) - THE LABEL NOBODY READ. Item 17 requires 'interaction prompts must remain readable across input methods'. Closing it turned up the session's SIXTH dead field: `interactLabel` is authored on 4 objects in systems/world-system.js - the Camp Stash's 'Open Stash' and the waypoint's 'Attune Waypoint' - and grepping for any READ of it returned nothing at all. TWO different reasons it hid: (1) systems/chest-system.js refreshPanel HARDCODED `E: Open Stash` - the same words the object authored, so the field was invisible precisely because it AGREED with the literal sitting next to it; a stash authoring any other label would have been ignored. (2) systems/waypoint-system.js has NO HUD PANEL AT ALL, so its 'Attune Waypoint' had nowhere it could ever be displayed - nothing in the game has ever told a player that a waypoint does anything. THE FIX: a nearby-interaction prompt panel in the examine system (worldExaminePanel, in the existing externalSystemsHud, refreshed from updateExternalSystems where the other per-frame panels already refresh) that names what E will do - read from the object's OWN interactLabel - and what I will look at; plus chest-system's prompt now reads `stash.interactLabel || 'Open Stash'`. PROVEN DATA-DRIVEN, not assumed: mutating a stash's authored label at runtime to 'Rummage The Quartermaster's Hoard' changed the prompt to match, which is the difference between reading a field and printing a string that happens to look like it. VERIFIED with a LIVING player: an isolated path torch shows the look prompt ONLY; beside the stash the authored E label shows; the well reads; nothing nearby hides the panel; escapeHtml guards names that come from world data. NOTE a long detour chasing a 'stale prompt' that turned out to be correct behaviour - the test character had DIED mid-run (I teleported it to +40,+40 into the wilderness in an earlier step), and refreshExaminePanel correctly hides for a dead player, so the markup I kept reading was simply the last frame before death. The instrumentation that found it printed `playerAlive: false`; three rounds of reasoning about detached DOM nodes and stale references had found nothing, because there was nothing to find. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.10_INTERACTION_PROMPTS.md.
// V0.20.9: ROADMAP ITEM 17 (World Interaction and Environmental Feedback) - PRESS I AND LOOK AT SOMETHING. Item 17's list - inspect supply crates, use water sources, sit on benches, use training dummies, inspect tents, examine landmarks - describes objects V0.20.8 had just placed in Dead Lantern Camp, every one of which was scenery you walked past. NEW systems/world-examine-system.js (DR.WorldExamineSystem; wired into _script_order.json, the HTML script tags before game.js, and an install(Game) call - plus a per-instance installWorldExamineSystem() at boot beside installDebugTools, which is the pattern this codebase already uses). 22 camp object types examine, keyed by the type the renderer already draws, each with multiple authored lines. ITEM 17 RULES, met deliberately: 'not every interaction needs a reward' - none of these give one, they are text, a ring and a quiet cue; 'repeated interactions should avoid excessive message spam' - a mash cooldown swallows a held key, and a genuine second look advances to the NEXT line rather than repeating the first; 'interactions should provide animation, sound, text, or visual feedback' - all but the first. THE KEY IS THE STORY. The first version bound E and deferred explicitly, asking every other system's own finder (npc/chest/stash/quest/waypoint/station/resource/event/entrance - all nine verified to exist before being called) whether it had a target, and staying silent if any did. Then it was MEASURED: standing at a lone path torch with the nearest NPC 2.83 tiles away, E was STILL claimed - findNearbyNpc reaches ~3.25 tiles and this camp holds 27 NPCs, so an NPC is in range nearly everywhere and examine would have been SILENT IN THE EXACT PLACE ITS OBJECTS LIVE. A feature that looks finished and never fires is precisely the pattern this whole session has been deleting - and reasoning about the design had not caught it; measuring it did. So examining moved to its OWN key (examine: 'i', added to defaultKeyBindings; i was free and bags are on b), where it is always available and can never take a press from talking, looting, gathering or crafting - which is Item 17's 'world interactions must not interfere with combat targeting or movement' met by construction rather than by arbitration. The whole interactKeyIsClaimed() deferral was then DELETED rather than left in place, since keeping a function that no longer decides anything would be new dead code. That draft had also called this.findLootableCorpseNear?.(4.5) - a method that exists NOWHERE, so the optional-call would have evaluated to undefined forever: a guard that never guards. Caught and removed; corpse looting needs no check anyway, its handler (game.js ~984) is registered on the CAPTURE phase and already runs before every bubble listener. ALSO CUT: the `flower` entry. It was written for the camp's Medicinal Flowers ('planted deliberately in rows', 'someone weeds these') but the table is keyed by object TYPE, and the Dark Woods is full of wild flowers nobody planted - every one of them would have claimed a gardener. True of one object and false of hundreds is the same failure as a cone that draws a circle. VERIFIED in-world: all 22 camp types examine (0 silent); the torch-with-NPC-nearby case that killed the E design now fires; E STILL opens the NPC window beside Sister Liora; examining works beside her too; a wild flower is now silent. NOTE the 'empty woods' test that appeared to fail was MY assumption - the spot had a flower in it - and chasing that false failure is what exposed the flower line lying about the whole forest. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.9_WORLD_EXAMINE.md.
// V0.20.8: ROADMAP ITEM 2 (Dead Lantern Camp overhaul) - TWO MEN IN ONE PAIR OF BOOTS. THE BUG Item 2 NAMES TWICE ('prevent NPCs from spawning or standing on top of one another', 'no overlapping NPC coordinates'): systems/world-system.js ensureStartingCampRevamp created Quartermaster Brann at (campX + 6, campY) - the EXACT tile systems/npc-system.js:242 had already placed npc_camp_merchant on. Two vendors occupying one square. Found by auditing every camp NPC pair for identical coordinates rather than by looking at the camp. Brann is the newer arrival (added BY the revamp, onto a merchant that was already there), so Brann moves - to campX+7, campY+2, at the head of his own supply line, which satisfies the same rule's other half ('vendors and service NPCs should be positioned near objects relevant to their role'). BOTH branches that set his position were updated - the create branch AND the Object.assign branch that re-asserts position on an already-saved camp - because fixing only the first would leave every existing save with Brann still inside the merchant. THE CAMP ITSELF: the revamp placed 16 objects (5 tents, fire, cookingSpit, 2 logSeats, ONE bedroll, 4 lanternPosts, flowers, stash). Item 2's environmental targets ask for crates and barrels, weapon racks, storage piles, training areas, tables and benches, medical supplies, food and water - and the camp had ZERO of them. Recon explains why: a previous pass deliberately SHRANK the camp to a 'compact outpost', and its removeCampObjectTypes set still strips largeCampTent/campStall/crate/weaponRack/supplyStack/herbalistTable/forge on sight. ADDED 26 placements, EVERY type audited against render/object-renderer.js's own `case` list first, so nothing placed is an object the renderer cannot draw (placing an invisible prop would be creating the very dead data this session keeps deleting): quartermaster's supply line (supplyStack/crate/barrel/sackPile/campStall), training area by Marshal Corven (sparringDummy/weaponRack/brokenWeapon), herbalistTable + medical crate beside Sister Liora - which PAYS OFF V0.18.68's explicit deferral, since that version removed the Herbalist Table from camp and deferred re-placing it to Item 2 - studyTable + candles by the arcane trainers, well + grain sacks + water barrel + crate by the Camp Cook, 2 more bedrolls + a campLeanTo, 2 more tents (kept INSIDE the camp ellipse so they stand on camp ground rather than forest floor), 2 path torches, a banner, rope and a crate as clutter. NOT ADDED: hitching/animal areas - the renderer has no such type and the spec says 'where appropriate'; inventing one would mean new art, not placement. VERIFIED BY MEASUREMENT: NPC exact-overlaps 1 -> 0 (Brann 7,2 vs merchant 6,0); ZERO objects placed on an NPC tile; all 18 requested types confirmed actually placed (typesRequestedButAbsent empty - a type that silently failed to place would be invisible); only tents/lean-tos block, so paths stay open; and a flood fill from the campfire across walkable tiles reaches ALL 27 camp NPCs and all four camp exits, which is Item 2's 'maintain clear walking paths between tents, NPCs, quest areas, and exits' proven rather than asserted. Screenshotted in-world: the camp reads as inhabited. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.8_DEAD_LANTERN_CAMP.md.
// V0.20.7: ROADMAP ITEM 5 (final buildable piece) - ASK ME WHAT I WANT. The spec's layout list requires 'clear visual distinction between spoken dialogue and objective summaries', and the window had NO objective summary at all to distinguish: openNpcWindow rendered dialogueText(npc) - a single spoken line - and an action button reading 'Accept: Light the Way'. You agreed to a quest without ever being told what it asked of you, while its authored task labels (38 across 26 quests) sat unread in the data at the exact moment the decision was made. THE BUILD: objectiveSummaryHtml(npc) renders a briefing panel from those authored labels, and the two halves are now different OBJECTS rather than one blob of text - speech is a QUOTE (italic, warm, behind a speaker's rule), the briefing is a LIST (upright, its own frame, monospace counts, uppercase heading). That IS the distinction the spec asks for: one reads as a person talking, the other as a job. DETAILS THAT MATTER: an OFFERED quest shows the required count only, NOT '0/5' - a zero against work you have not started reads as failure rather than as an ask; an ACCEPTED quest switches to live n/required with a tick on finished objectives, and the heading changes 'What this asks of you' -> 'Underway' -> 'Ready to report' off the pick mode. The summary reads the SAME game.questSystem.chooseQuestFromSource pick that questButtonText uses, so the briefing and the button can never disagree about which quest is on the table. An NPC with no quest, or a quest with no tasks, renders NOTHING - an empty briefing frame is worse than none. ALSO: the subtitle was printing the raw data key as the NPC's title ('quest_giver', 'fisher_provisioner'); the spec asks for 'NPC title or role', so it is humanised for display only ('Quest Giver') with the underlying value untouched and mercenary_master's existing special case preserved. VERIFIED by driving the real openNpcWindow: an offered quest lists its objectives with NO progress counts; the same NPC after accepting shows '2/8' and 'Underway'; an NPC without a quest renders an empty string (no frame); speech computes italic + left rule while the briefing computes upright + its own border, and they are separate elements so they cannot overlap; all 10 distinct roles humanise with no underscores reaching the player. Screenshotted the finished window - portrait, name, role, italic speech, framed briefing - and it reads as intended. NOTE a corrupted colour literal ('#c9b<CJK>98') was typed into the first draft and caught before it shipped. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. ITEM 5 is now COMPLETE except for two things that need CONTENT, not code: alternate expressions (no NPC authors one) and multi-NPC conversations (no such scene exists). See docs/V0.20.7_DIALOGUE_VS_OBJECTIVES.md.
// V0.20.6: ROADMAP ITEM 5 (NPC dialogue interface) - THIRTY-THREE FACES NOBODY HAD SEEN. Item 5's core requirement is 'display a face portrait of the NPC currently speaking'. THE FIND: every one of the game's 33 NPCs already authors `portrait: { family, color, glyph }` in data/npcs.js - 33/33, zero missing - and `grep -rn '\.portrait\b'` across the entire codebase returned NOTHING. Somebody designed a portrait for every character in this game and not one of them was ever put on screen. Same dead-data pattern as coneDegrees (V0.19.6), the east/west poses (V0.19.9) and the slam style (V0.20.0), except this one was an entire authored FEATURE, not a field. The dialogue window already existed (ensureNpcWindow: name, role/faction/level, body text, quest/vendor/trainer actions) - the portrait is the piece it never had. THE BUILD: drawNpcPortrait(canvas, npc) renders FROM the authored descriptor - the 14 authored families (villager/scout/hermit/merchant/cook/trainer/warden/surveyor/healer/officer/smith/fisher/alchemist/spirit) map to a silhouette (hood, helm, brim, toque, cap, bare, wisp) plus a collar (cloth/leather/robe/apron/mail/wisp); the authored colour tints every layer; the authored glyph is the corner role badge. PORTRAIT_FALLBACK covers an unknown family AND an NPC with no portrait at all - the spec's required 'fallback portrait for minor NPCs'. Procedural rather than artwork DELIBERATELY: every NPC, mob and prop in this game is already drawn from code, so a bust drawn the same way matches the established visual style by construction and satisfies 'no stretched, cropped, or low-resolution portraits' at any UI scale for free. The dream spirits are drawn as a wisp with no bust - giving them shoulders would be a lie about what they are. LAYOUT: the canvas is a flex child of the existing .windowHeader beside the name/role block, NOT an overlay - the spec requires it be part of the window layout, and as siblings sharing a row the text and portrait cannot overlap (verified: position computes to `static`, and it lives inside .windowHeader). Speaker changes repaint it in openNpcWindow, which is the single entry point for showing an NPC, so 'update the portrait immediately when the active speaker changes' holds without a watcher. VERIFIED by driving the REAL openNpcWindow for every NPC and hashing the canvas pixels: all 33 draw (0 blank), 32 DISTINCT - and the single identical pair was investigated rather than accepted: Cavern Spirit Healer and Spirit Healer have BYTE-IDENTICAL authored portrait data (spirit/#d8f6ff/✦), and the renderer was proven to vary with colour (recolouring one changes its hash), so the duplicate is authored, not a renderer collapsing data. Unknown family and missing-portrait fallbacks both draw. A first pass had headwear at base-25 and the hoods/helms read as HAIR; raised to base-70 against a base+42 face - and the change was verified by SAMPLING PIXELS (hood = 89,129,63 = exactly base-70) after comparing two screenshots by eye wrongly suggested nothing had changed. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. Test DOM (contact sheet) removed. Item 5 REMAINDER: alternate expressions (no data), multi-NPC conversations (no such scene exists), and clearer separation of spoken dialogue vs objective summaries. See docs/V0.20.6_NPC_PORTRAITS.md.
// V0.20.5: ROADMAP ITEM 15 (tracking) - WHAT AM I ACTUALLY DOING. The HUD quest panel showed a single aggregate progress bar summed across EVERY active quest, plus a nearby-source prompt, and never named one objective - so the spec's 'show tracked objectives clearly' had nothing behind it at all. THE TRACKED-QUEST LIMIT is state.selectedQuestId: exactly one, already enforced by that field being single-valued and already driven by the journal's Select button - the spec asks to 'define a tracked-quest limit', and the honest answer was that the game already had one and never used it for anything. NOW: renderTrackedObjectives() (called from refreshPanel, which 16 call sites already invoke on every progress change, so 'update progress immediately' needed no new plumbing) names the tracked quest and each objective with live n/required, ticks a completed objective, and prompts 'No quest tracked - press L to select one' when nothing is selected. THE REAL FIND: task.nightOnly (3/38 objectives) has gated progress since V0.17.87 - advanceObjective SKIPS a nightOnly task by day - and NOTHING displayed it. A player could stand in the right place doing exactly the right thing and watch the counter not move. Those objectives now carry a moon glyph and 'waits for dark' until night falls. Escort state comes from this.escort.actor (runtime, not data) and shows the escorted actor's HP. DELIBERATELY NOT BUILT: the spec's 'distinguish optional and required objectives' - NO task carries an optional flag anywhere in the data (`required` is a COUNT of how many, not a required/optional marker), so the label would read 'Required' on all 38 objectives forever: a word that never varies is not information. Timed conditions were ALREADY handled and left alone - quest.deadlineAt drives an existing countdown in refreshPanel (V0.17.85); the audit's first pass wrongly called timed 'NO DATA' by checking TASK fields only, which reading the panel code corrected. VERIFIED against the real HUD: nothing-tracked prompts to select; tracking names quest + objective + progress; progress updates immediately (0/5 -> 1/5); a nightOnly objective says 'waits for dark' BY DAY and stops saying it AT NIGHT (isNight stubbed both ways); escort shows with 43/90 HP. NOTE the escort line LOOKED concatenated with the objective above it in the test output - that was innerText collapsing line breaks on an element that is not rendered (the HUD is hidden at the title screen), not a layout bug; the DOM is three separate display:block divs, confirmed directly. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.5_QUEST_TRACKING.md.
// V0.20.4: ROADMAP ITEM 15 (quest journal) - THE JOURNAL READS WHAT WAS WRITTEN. Audited all 26 quests against the spec's journal fields BEFORE building anything, and the finding was the session's recurring one: the data was already authored and simply not displayed. (a) COMPLETED HISTORY existed only as a COUNT - renderQuestLog put `Completed ${n}` in the summary line and rendered active quests only; state.completed stores just a key, so the fix reads the authored descriptor back out of DR.QUEST_BY_ID. Completed entries render as a compact history row deliberately: they have no live task progress and no claimable rewards, so reusing the active card would have shown empty meters and dead buttons. (b) AUTHORED FIELDS NEVER SHOWN - minLevel (26/26), giver (26/26) and repeatable (26/26) were all authored; the card's meta line carried only folder and turn-in. They now read from the DESCRIPTOR rather than the active-state copy, so they cannot go blank if that copy drops a field. (folder already carried "Region / Subregion", which is the spec's region labelling, and offerText/inProgressText already provided narrative context - both were already displayed and were left alone.) (c) SEARCH / FILTER / SORT - search matches name, giver and place; filter is Active/Completed/Repeatable/All; sort is level/name/place. View state (logSearch/logFilter/logSort) is deliberately NOT part of quest `state`: that round-trips through every character save, and a search box is a view preference, not progress. DELIBERATELY NOT BUILT, because the data does not exist: the spec's MAIN vs SIDE category split (no quest carries any main/side field - folder is region-based), a QUEST LEVEL distinct from minLevel, and REPEATABLE RESET TIMING. Shipping those tabs would mean inventing data or rendering a control with nothing behind it - the same dead-data anti-pattern this session has spent its time removing, just created rather than inherited. They need authoring first. VERIFIED against the real renderer with real descriptors: active view shows place/level/giver/turn-in; completed view lists actual finished quests (2/2 by name); repeatable filter isolates correctly; search finds by name AND by giver ('Road Warden Cael' -> 2 matches, all his) AND by place; no-match says so honestly; sorts by level, name and place all correct. NOTE the first place-search and place-sort tests were VACUOUS - the fixture took the first 5 quests, which all share one folder, so the search found 0 (correctly) and `.every()` on the empty array returned true. Re-tested with a fixture spanning all 6 distinct folders: place search matched 1 of 6 and excluded the rest; place sort ordered 6 distinct regions. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.4_QUEST_JOURNAL.md.
// V0.20.3: THE METHOD THAT ATE ITS TWIN - a live render crash, found while verifying V0.20.2 and confirmed PRE-EXISTING (render/object-renderer.js was byte-identical to the shipped Blackroot V0.20.1.zip backup, untouched by this session). THE BUG: object-renderer.js defined drawOrbWeb TWICE - an options-form `drawOrbWeb(cx, cy, opts = {})` at line 608 and a positional `drawOrbWeb(cx, cy, r, silkP, alpha, rnd, ky = 0.88)` at line 2269. JavaScript accepts a duplicate method name SILENTLY and the LAST definition wins, so the entire options-form implementation was unreachable dead code, and its three callers (drawWebbedBush, the web-strung tree, and the anchored prop) were really hitting the positional one: they passed an options OBJECT where `r` was expected, `rnd` arrived undefined, and `rnd()` threw "rnd is not a function" EVERY FRAME. Webbed bushes and web-strung trees had not been drawing AT ALL - drawObject's per-object try/catch swallowed each throw as a 'render fault in world-object' and moved on, so the game looked fine and the console scrolled. THE SECOND, SILENT VICTIM: drawCaveStairs was ALSO defined twice - a labelled `drawCaveStairs(s, obj, label = 'DOWN')` at 572 (used by the caveStairsDown/caveStairsUp shape cases) and V0.18.61's unlabelled silk-web cave-mouth version at 1498. The later one won, so EVERY cave staircase rendered the silk-web steps and lost its DOWN/UP label - the exact opposite of what V0.18.61's own comment promised ("other dungeons keep the old stylised steps"). That comment is also what made the fix unambiguous rather than a guess: the intent is written down. THE FIX: name each method for what it actually draws - drawAnchoredOrbWeb (ties a web to explicit branch-tip `anchors`, which the positional one cannot do) and drawNaturalCaveStairs (the Silk Web Cavern's rough stone cave mouth) - and repoint only their own callers. The two working positional drawOrbWeb callers are untouched, so there is zero regression risk on the paths that were fine. NEW tools/check-duplicate-methods.js, wired into validate.sh: this class is invisible to node --check AND to reading the file, because the dead code still looks finished; nothing else in the toolchain looks for it. It found both bugs, reports ZERO false positives across 193 files, and is negative-tested (re-introducing the drawCaveStairs collision makes it exit 1 and name both line numbers; restoring exits 0). VERIFIED: drawWebbedBush - the exact function in the crash stack - now runs to completion (54 canvas ops, previously a throw); all six affected paths draw without throwing, including drawCaveStairs with 'DOWN' and with 'UP' and the untouched positional drawOrbWeb; method arities confirm the right definitions are now reachable (drawCaveStairs length 1 = the labelled form, drawAnchoredOrbWeb length 2, drawOrbWeb length 6 = positional); and a console.error interceptor on a fresh page counted ZERO render faults across many frames, where the same page previously threw every frame. NOTE the console tool returns a stale buffer across reloads - the old line numbers (2273/4298) in those messages predate the edits, which is how the staleness was spotted rather than trusted. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2. See docs/V0.20.3_DUPLICATE_METHOD_SHADOWING.md.
// V0.20.2: REPORTED BUG - creating a new character on an account took the first character's gear and items (screenshot: a level-1 Fighter at Gear Score 50 wearing a Rare Silkfang Dagger, a Set Piece Webbed Queen Earring and a Warden Lantern Amulet). ROOT CAUSE - A CHARACTER'S BELONGINGS DO NOT LIVE ON THE PLAYER OBJECT. entities/player.js has no inventory at all: this.inventory, this.equipment, this.bags, this.bank, this.classStartingGearGranted and the quest/crafting/resource-gathering system states ALL hang off the GAME. game.js start() - which its own comment calls the single owner of world entry - does `this.player = new Player(className, appearance)` and leaves every one of them exactly where it was. The LOAD path got away with it purely by accident of ordering: save-system.js:1789-1790 calls start() and then applyCharacterState(), which overwrites inventory/equipment/bags/bank/quests/professions with the saved character's. The CREATE path (ui-system.js:2747, the Enter Realm button) calls start() and has NOTHING to overwrite them with, so character 2 simply kept character 1's things. Note resetRuntimeSessionForCharacterSwap() is NOT this and never was: it clears actors, party, targets and zone - the SESSION - and deliberately says nothing about what a character OWNS; the create path does not call it either, but calling it would not have fixed this. SECOND ORDER: because classStartingGearGranted also survived, grantClassStartingGear() early-returned and the new character was DENIED ITS OWN STARTER KIT on top of wearing someone else's - so the bug both gave and took away. THE LEAK WAS WIDER THAN REPORTED - verified by reproduction, not assumed: a new character also inherited the BANK, COMPLETED QUESTS, PROFESSION LEVELS and the EXPLORED FOG MAP. THE FIX: one owner - Game.prototype.resetCharacterOwnedState() in systems/save-system.js, placed directly above applyCharacterState() as its deliberate MIRROR (whatever that restores per character, this clears - a field added there and not here becomes the next leak), called from start() before the new Player is built. It resets inventory/equipment/bags/bank/classStartingGearGranted, calls each system's own importState(null) - the same entry point applyCharacterState uses with saved data, so a reset cannot drift from a load - and clears fog + re-arms _fogLoaded so the new character reads its OWN dream-realms.fog.v1:<characterId> key. VERIFIED: bug REPRODUCED first (a fresh CHAR-2 held CHAR-1's Silkfang Dagger, CHAR-1's equipped weapon and CHAR-1's bag loot), then 0 leaks across all 7 categories with the new character correctly receiving its own Fighter starter kit (Rustcleaver Training Blade, Split-Leather Bruiser Vest, ...); and the LOAD path re-verified END TO END through the real serializeCharacterState/applyCharacterState round trip - save a level-12 CharA with gear/bank/quest/profession, create a clean level-1 CharB, load CharA back: name, level 12, dagger, amulet, bank, quest completion and profession level ALL restored. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2. NOTE - a SEPARATE, PRE-EXISTING render crash was found while verifying this and is NOT fixed here (see V0.20.3): render/object-renderer.js defines drawOrbWeb TWICE (line 608 options-form, line 2269 positional-form); the later definition silently wins, so the three options-form callers pass an object where a number is expected and throw 'rnd is not a function' every frame. Confirmed pre-existing by diffing object-renderer.js against the shipped V0.20.1 backup - byte-identical, untouched by this session. See docs/V0.20.2_CHARACTER_STATE_ISOLATION.md.
// V0.20.1: ROADMAP ITEM 6 - TEN SWINGS, TEN SILHOUETTES. V0.20.0 fixed the VFX styles the game ASKED for (slam/crush/cast, all passed and never drawn). This fixes the ones it never thought to ask for. systems/spell-system.js:1016 hardcoded `id === 'titan_chop' || id === 'perfect_masterstroke' ? 'slam' : 'slash'`, so EIGHT other single-target fighter melee spells fell through to the same generic sweep: Crushing Blow (applies Crushed Armor), Reckless Strike (self-debuffs the caster), Heavy Riposte (a COUNTER off a dodge/parry), Armor Splitter (applies Split Guard), Bonebreaker (a snap that slows), Final Swing (an EXECUTE, gated below 30% HP), Shatter Guard (breaks a shield) - all pixel-identical to level-1 Heavy Swing. IMPORTANTLY this was NOT dead data and no validator could have caught it: nothing was claiming otherwise, no field was inert, nothing was malformed. It was a design gap, and it needed reading the spells and deciding what each should look like - the long-tail work flagged at the end of V0.20.0. THE FIX IS DATA-DRIVEN, the same shape as coneDegrees: a per-spell `vfxStyle` authored in data/spells.js beside the damage and the cone, and the resolver reads `spell.vfxStyle || 'slash'` instead of naming two spell ids. Six new silhouettes, each chosen to communicate what the spell DOES rather than to look different for its own sake: split (vertical rend, the halves parting - armour being opened), thrust (a straight counter-stab with a tip flash - a riposte is not a swing), wild (two crossing off-balance arcs - it debuffs YOU, it should not look controlled), execute (decisive downward arc + crossing glint - a decision, not another hit), shatter (shards bursting from the block point, no sweep at all), break (a hard zigzag crack). Crushing Blow reuses 'crush' (V0.20.0's blunt pound) - semantically exact, no new code. Heavy Swing authors NOTHING and stays the baseline sweep: it IS the plain swing, and giving it a bespoke look would be decoration, not communication. TWO CHECKS, EACH AT THE LAYER WHERE IT IS KNOWABLE: (1) authored vfxStyle values are DATA, so validateSpellShapes() rejects any style the renderer cannot draw, checked against DR.SLASH_STYLES - declared in render/effects-renderer.js BESIDE the branches and requested by data/spells.js, two INDEPENDENT sources, so unlike the validateVfxStyles() I wrote and deleted in V0.20.0 this one can actually fail; (2) tools/check-vfx-styles.js now also asserts DR.SLASH_STYLES matches the real `e.style === '...'` branches in BOTH directions, so the registry cannot silently become the next piece of dead data. That checker's style extraction was ALSO too broad and had to be scoped: it scanned the whole renderer and flagged 'arrow' as a stale registry entry, but 'arrow' belongs to drawHighQualityBoltEffect and has nothing to do with spawnSlash - it now reads only the `e.type === 'slash'` block. VERIFIED: all 11 styles proven to draw DISTINCT, non-empty paths via a recording ctx on the real drawEffect (0 identical pairs, 0 empty); registry drift negative-tested in BOTH directions by real exit code (an undrawn registry entry -> exit 1; a drawn-but-unlisted style -> exit 1; restored -> 0 - the first attempt at this test read head's exit code through a pipe rather than node's and falsely reported 0); runtime validator negative-tested (a bogus vfxStyle IS flagged, then restores clean); and the spell compiler confirmed to carry vfxStyle through. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.1_FIGHTER_MELEE_SILHOUETTES.md.
// V0.20.0: ROADMAP ITEM 6 - THE CAPSTONE THAT LOOKED LIKE LEVEL ONE (fighter VFX audit). Auditing the Fighter's 20 spells found the same dead-data pattern one layer down: in the VFX STYLE strings. systems/spell-system.js:1016 passes `id === 'titan_chop' || id === 'perfect_masterstroke' ? 'slam' : 'slash'` - and NOTHING in the codebase had ever branched on 'slam'. Both renderers implemented only 'claw'; every other style fell to the same else-arm and drew an identical horizontal arc. So the fighter's two heaviest hits - including PERFECT MASTERSTROKE, the level-20 CAPSTONE - were pixel-identical to level-1 Heavy Swing, and sounded identical too (the sfx line was likewise `style === 'claw' ? 'attack_claw' : 'attack_slash'`). Checking for it turned up TWO MORE dead styles: 'crush' (entities/enemy.js:315, heavy enemy attacks) and 'cast' (entities/pet.js:351 non-undead pets, entities/bot-player.js:546 ranged bots) - so CASTERS WERE SWINGING AN INVISIBLE SWORD. Fixing only 'slam' would have been the half-fix the golden rules forbid; the root cause is that spawnSlash did not render every style it was asked for, so all three are implemented, each a genuinely distinct silhouette: slam = heavy near-vertical stroke driven down + a ground shock once it lands; crush = blunt pound + radial debris, no blade; cast = glyph ring + rising motes, no blade. Slam's audio reuses attack_slash at rate ~0.58 (pitched well down = a heavier weapon landing) rather than inventing a sample that does not exist in sound-effects/. NEW tools/check-vfx-styles.js, wired into validate.sh. WHY A STATIC CHECK AND NOT A SUITE SECTION: this class CANNOT be a runtime data validator - the styles are string literals in CODE, not data, and the renderer's else-arm means an unimplemented style still draws SOMETHING (just the wrong thing), so nothing throws and no data is malformed. I first wrote it as a runtime validateVfxStyles() and DELETED it: its 'requested' list was hardcoded to mirror its 'implemented' list, making it a tautology that could never fail - exactly the dead validation this session has spent its time removing. The grep version was also wrong: it raised a FALSE POSITIVE ('undead_minion' - a petType inside a ternary CONDITION, not a style) and MISSED a real one ('cast', that same ternary's value), so the checker now balances parens to extract the 4th argument, reads only the VALUE side of a top-level ternary, and reports non-literal arguments honestly instead of guessing. VERIFIED: checker negative-tested (breaking the 'crush' branch makes it exit 1 and name entities/enemy.js:315; restoring exits 0); and all five styles proven to draw DISTINCT paths by handing the real drawEffect a recording ctx and diffing the traced canvas ops - previously slam/crush/cast all emitted the identical `arc(53,28,23,-0.9,0.7) | stroke()` as slash. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.20.0_FIGHTER_VFX_STYLES.md.
// V0.19.9: THE POSE NOBODY COULD REACH - sweeping V0.19.7's facing bug through the render layer. THE FIND: render/entity-renderer.js standingDirectionProfile read `const fy = Math.sign(e.facingY || 1)`, which makes fy === 0 IMPOSSIBLE - facingY is legitimately 0 when an entity faces due EAST or WEST, and `0 || 1` is 1. The function's own key selector has an explicit `fy === 0` branch (`: (fx < 0 ? 'west' : 'east')`), so that branch was UNREACHABLE and the authored 'east' and 'west' profiles it selects - sideProfile true, torsoTurn +/-1, headTurnX +/-7, visibleEyeCount 1 - were DEAD CODE that could never render. Every entity facing straight east or west was drawn as a southeast/southwest THREE-QUARTER DIAGONAL (sideProfile false, 2 eyes) instead of a clean side profile. This is the same `||` defect as V0.19.7 but with a bigger blast radius: it did not merely mis-aim a value, it made an entire authored feature unreachable. WHY THE FIX IS RIGHT (checked, not assumed): entityFacingView() does the camera maths properly - and notably uses `??`, not `||`, so it handles facingY === 0 correctly - and at the default yaw the iso projection resolves ALL FOUR cardinals to mode 'side'. That is exactly why lines ~1904-1913 override north/south into side profiles when the camera says 'side'. East/west already had side profiles AUTHORED (sideProfile: true), so the override deliberately excludes them (`profile.sideProfile === false` in its condition): all four cardinals were meant to end up as side profiles, and east/west simply never got there. A MISSING facing must still default to south, so the fix defaults only a NON-FINITE value (`Number.isFinite(rawFy) ? rawFy : 1`) - zero is a real value. ALSO: systems/fishing-system.js setPlayerFishingPose's untargeted cast used `(p.facingX || 1)` / `(p.facingY || 0)`, aiming 45 degrees off when facing north/south - and the very next line feeds that target into setFacingFromDelta, so the player physically TURNED to the wrong heading; it now uses actorFacingVector. FOUR further sites matching the same pattern were investigated and DELIBERATELY LEFT ALONE, because they are not bugs: humanoid-animation-system.js:385 and fishing-system.js:289-290 default to 0, which is the value being defaulted; and silk-web-spider / dark-woods-mob procedural-model facingProfile() use `facingX || 1` but only ever test `fx < 0 ? -1 : 1`, where 0 and 1 give the SAME result. Pattern-matching the idiom would have churned three files for zero behavioural gain - the memory note listing five 'unfixed' render sites was itself over-broad and has been corrected. VERIFIED: 8/8 direction cases (east and west now reach their authored side profiles with sideProfile true / 1 eye; all four diagonals and north/south unchanged), and a missing facing still defaults to south. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.19.9_RENDER_FACING_SWEEP.md.
// V0.19.8: ROADMAP ITEM 6 - CLEAVE DRAWS ITS SWING (the VISUAL half of the cone work). THE VIOLATION: Item 6's own first example is "a cone attack must visibly use the real cone dimensions". V0.19.6/V0.19.7 made the cone TRUE in targeting, but the picture was still wrong in the opposite direction - the fighter branch ended in `this.spawnRing?.(p.x, p.y, color, id === 'cleave' ? 16 : 22)`, so Cleave tested a 100-degree wedge IN FRONT and drew a full 360 circle AROUND the player. And spawnRing's radius is SCREEN PIXELS (a hardcoded 16) with no relation to the spell's real 2.05-tile reach, so that ring never showed true dimensions even as a circle. THE FIX: new `spellCone` effect type (spawnSpellConeVfx in systems/effects-system.js + drawSpellConeEffect in render/effects-renderer.js). Three deliberate design points, each verified rather than assumed: (a) its `radius` is WORLD units, unlike ring/spark - the renderer samples the arc in WORLD space and projects each point through vfxScreen, the same transform the world uses, instead of approximating with a canvas ellipse (an ellipse's parametric angle is NOT the world angle under an iso projection, so an arc drawn that way would not line up with the cone that kills); (b) it is deliberately NOT in render-backend-system's sprite-cache `eligible` set - that cache keys on type:color:style:radius:progress with NO facing, so a baked cone would point the wrong way for every direction but one; this is the same trap as the spider modelScale cache bug, and sidestepping it is why a new type was added rather than extending 'ring'. Verified the main loop (game.js ~4152) falls through to this.drawEffect when the webgl queue rejects a renderable, so a non-eligible type still draws. (c) the sweep uses 1-(1-p)^3 and lands EXACTLY on the real radius, never overshooting - the ring's easeOutBack overshoots past 1, which would paint the swing landing further out than it actually hits. Checked the pool is safe for custom fields: recycleEffectEntry deletes every key except __pooled before pooling, so a recycled entry cannot carry a stale coneDegrees into a plain ring. Berserker's Roar widens the drawn cone exactly as it widens the real one (radius already carries the bonus at the call site: 2.05 -> 2.65, angle unchanged). Groundbreaker and whirlwind_cleave declare no cone and ARE omnidirectional - they keep the ring, which is the honest picture for a ground slam and a spin. VERIFIED by driving the REAL renderer with a recording ctx and an identity projection, reading the world geometry back out: wedge centred on the actor, arc spans exactly 40-140 degrees (100 degrees centred on a due-NORTH facing - the axis case V0.19.7 fixed), outer edge exactly 2.05; reach over 7 frames grows 0.92 -> 2.05 monotonically with ZERO overshoot; end-to-end through resolveFighterRevampSpell, cleave spawns CONE (2.05/100) while groundbreaker and whirlwind_cleave still spawn RING(22). Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.19.8_CLEAVE_CONE_VFX.md.
// V0.19.7: ROADMAP ITEM 6 - FACING NORTH. Chasing V0.19.6's cone into the VFX turned up THREE things, one of them a one-line bug repeated across the whole spellbook. (1) THE FACING BUG: `Number(p.facingX || 1)` is not a way to read a facing vector. facingX is legitimately 0 when an actor faces due north or south (setFacingFromDelta normalises dx/len), and `0 || 1` is 1 - so the idiom silently rewrote a north-facing actor's facing to (1,1) and swung it 45 degrees off-axis. It came from the original `inFront` closure and had been copied to six sites: shipping CLEAVE has mis-aimed for any fighter facing straight up or down since it was written; blink and illusory_step TELEPORTED 45 degrees off-course; disengage_shot and evasive_step dodged diagonally; and isRogueBehindTarget used the mirror-image defaults (`target.facingX || 0, target.facingY || 1`), so a target facing due EAST (facingY === 0) was read as facing 45 degrees - rotating the entire BACKSTAB arc and landing shadowstep BESIDE such a target instead of behind it. All six now use one shared Game.prototype.actorFacingVector(actor), which defaults only a genuinely absent/non-finite component, falls back to facingAngle when both are missing, and treats the zero vector as directionless. `||` cannot supply a numeric default where zero is a valid value. (2) FAN OF KNIVES 108, NOT 180 - AN HONEST CORRECTION OF V0.19.6: I picked 180 before finding the VFX. spawnAssassinFanVfx (systems/effects-system.js) has drawn a Math.PI * 0.6 = 108-degree fan since V0.18.29, and the call site passed no spread - so V0.19.6 shipped a hit arc 72 degrees WIDER than the drawn one, closing one visual/behaviour mismatch by opening another. 108 is now the single source of truth: it is the authored width players have actually been watching, and the resolver derives the VFX spread FROM spell.coneDegrees. (3) ONE DIRECTION: the resolver centred the cone on p.facing but aimed the VFX at the FIRST ENEMY FOUND (atan2(aimY, aimX)) - up to half a cone apart. Unlike the fighter's resolver, whose hostileTarget() faces the target before swinging, this handler never set facing at all. It now faces the selected target first (when one is in range), and that single facing drives BOTH the hit test and the visual; the VFX reach also comes from the same radius the test uses (it drew to range 3.0 while killing to radius 3.2). Fan of Knives is the ONLY assassin kind:'aoe' spell (verified - the other 14 belong to classes that do not route through this resolver), so the change is contained to it. ALSO: both fan_of_knives (range 3 -> 3.2) and cleave (range 1.85 -> 2.05) advertised a TOOLTIP range shorter than the radius they actually hit at - neither resolver gates on range, so this is display-only truthfulness, caught by a new cone-range-under-radius check. VERIFIED: the 45-degree bug was found BY a test, not by reading - an end-to-end run of the real resolver drew the fan at 45 degrees when told to target due north, and hit both a north and an east enemy; now 4/4 aim cases pass, actorFacingVector 9/9 (incl. north, south, zero-vector, facingAngle-only, null actor), isRogueBehindTarget 7/7 against axis-facing targets, spellShapeContains 15/15. All four validateSpellShapes checks NEGATIVE-tested against DR.SPELL_BY_ID (the first attempt mutated COMPILED_SPELL_BY_ID - the wrong object - and falsely reported the check dead). Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.19.7_FACING_AND_CONE_ALIGNMENT.md.
// V0.19.6: ROADMAP ITEM 6 (spell visuals/behaviour must match intent) - THE CONE THAT WASN'T. THE VIOLATION: the roadmap's own first example is "a cone attack must visibly use the real cone dimensions". spell_assassin_fan_of_knives declares itself a cone THREE times - name ("Fan of Knives"), category ("AoE Ranged / Cone") and description ("Throw multiple blades in a short cone") - and hit a full 360 circle, including enemies standing BEHIND the player. THE ROOT CAUSE was structural, not a typo: the angle test was a local `inFront` closure defined INSIDE Game.prototype.resolveFighterRevampSpell, and its one call site hardwired the angle to `id === 'cleave' ? coneDegrees : 360`. Two consequences: (a) coneDegrees was an INERT field for all 279 other spells (only cleave declared it - a 1/280 field that looked plumbed and was not), and (b) no other class's resolver could even REACH the test - the generic `kind === 'aoe'` handler in resolveAssassinRevampSpell was a pure radius check with no notion of facing. This is the same dead-data pattern as the attribute aliases (V0.18.93), poisonResist (V0.18.96) and the silver/gold money paths (V0.18.99): a field the data author reasonably believed was doing something. THE FIX (root cause, in the owning module): `inFront` is lifted to ONE shared Game.prototype.spellShapeContains(enemy, radius, coneDegrees, actor) so a single implementation serves every class rather than each resolver growing its own copy; the fighter filter is now data-driven (`Number(spell.coneDegrees) > 0 ? ... : 360`); and the generic aoe handler honours a declared cone, engaging ONLY when coneDegrees is present so every existing aoe spell is untouched. BALANCE (the one intentional behaviour change): fan_of_knives now declares coneDegrees 180 - a forward fan, since "short" in its description qualifies the REACH (radius 3.2), not the arc. It still hits everything in front; only targets at the assassin's back are now spared. This is a modest nerf, and deliberate: the design intent was unambiguous (all three of name, category and description say cone), so implementing it is honouring the stated design rather than guessing at it - unlike the economy scale (V0.18.99), which had two valid readings and was escalated instead. ALSO FIXED a floating-point artifact inherited from the original math: Math.cos(Math.PI/2) is 6.12e-17, not 0, so `dot >= cos(halfAngle)` EXCLUDED an enemy at exactly 90 degrees from a 180-degree cone - a target standing straight out to your side skipped on a rounding error. Harmless at cleave's 100 degrees; exactly on the boundary for a half-plane. Now carries a 1e-9 epsilon. NEW validateSpellShapes() suite section (280 spells) holds the line so this cannot silently return: flags cone-without-dimensions, area-without-radius, dot-without-tickrate and no-cast-animation. VERIFIED, not assumed: a scope check caught that spellShapeContains's predecessor `inFront` was NOT in scope at the assassin call site (node --check cannot see this - it would have been a ReferenceError the first time anyone cast Fan of Knives); the validator was NEGATIVE-tested by stripping coneDegrees and confirming it CATCHES the bug (it does) rather than trusting a first-run pass - the same false-pass trap hit in V0.19.4; cleave/groundbreaker/whirlwind_cleave proven identical angle-for-angle (100/360/360 before and after); 15/15 synthetic geometry cases pass including both 90-degree boundaries; and the spell compiler was checked to carry coneDegrees through (it does - cleave's 100 survives compilation), since the ITEM compiler is known to drop custom fields. Suite PASS: statPipeline 15/15, items 396/396, 0 data/economy/dialogue/spellShape issues, warnings still 2, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.19.6_SPELL_SHAPES.md.
// V0.19.5: ROADMAP ITEM 1 - post-completion (state 8) completed for every REACHABLE quest, and the "5 missing beforeOfferText" investigated and found CORRECT. THE KEY FINDING - the two apparent gaps were not gaps, and filling them would have created DEAD DATA (the exact anti-pattern this session has been removing): (a) beforeOfferText is resolved inside an NPC dialogue function (systems/npc-system.js: npc.dialogueVariants -> npc.dialogueText -> npc.dialogueId -> quest.beforeOfferText), so it can ONLY display when the player talks to a real NPC. All 5 quests lacking it have NO NPC giver - quest_follow_the_blood and quest_lookouts_last_watch are hidden/autoOffer with giver null, quest_ruriks_bargain and quest_fall_of_rurik are given by "Rurik the Fallen" who is a MOB, and quest_fourth_member autoOffers at a POI. Verified: of the 21 quests with a real NPC giver, 21/21 already have beforeOfferText - the state is COMPLETE, and the 5 were correctly omitted. (b) a completed REPEATABLE never reaches the post-completion branch: it is re-offerable, so the picker returns mode 'accept' rather than falling through to the post-completion line (systems/quest-system.js pick modes: complete/accept/progress/locked, then the fallthrough). So postCompletionText only ever displays for a NON-REPEATABLE quest reachable through a real NPC. AUTHORED: postCompletionText for the 7 remaining non-repeatable NPC-given quests - quest_guides_warning (Cael: the lesson was standing still, and you have held a line without him since), quest_hunter_never_returned (Corven: Aldric's kit carried in, his sister coming from the coast, "I would rather tell her he ran than tell her he never woke"), quest_old_tusk (the pit filled in, "his bow for the beast that took him"), quest_blood_on_the_road (Cael still turning over why men dig in on a road they could walk away down), quest_lumen (the lumen still answers you and has decided something it has not told Selene), quest_what_the_gap_lets_in (the quiet means it has finished coming through and is out here now), and quest_the_long_root - the roadmap's named REGIONAL CONCLUSION (the seal still holds, the trees have stopped walking, and the road under the roots has not gone anywhere). RESULT (verified in-browser against reachability, not raw counts): beforeOfferText reachable 21 / authored 21 / missing 0; postCompletionText reachable 14 / authored 14 / missing 0 (15 authored in total - quest_fourth_member's is reachable via its turnIn, Iren, rather than its giver). Reporting these as "21/26" and "15/26" would have been misleading; the honest metric is 100% of what can actually display. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; suite PASS with 0 dialogue issues, warnings still 2. See docs/V0.19.5_POST_COMPLETION_COVERAGE.md.
// V0.19.4: ROADMAP ITEM 1 - DIALOGUE STATE 7 (LOCKED) + the branch half of STATE 6 (Rurik fork). THE VIOLATION: systems/quest-system.js unavailableQuestReason() returns bare system strings, and the caller SPEAKS them as the NPC (`${source.name}: ${unavailableQuestReason(...)}`). So all 8 condition-gated quests answered the player with "Requirements not yet met." in their giver's voice - most damningly Road Warden Cael, whose patrol you may have just murdered to join Rurik, replying to you with a developer string. That is exactly what state 7 forbids ("provides contextual hints without exposing internal prerequisite flags"). THE FIX: new authored `lockedText` field, preferred by unavailableQuestReason ONLY in the requiredConditions branch (`return quest.lockedText || 'Requirements not yet met.'`). The prerequisite ("Complete X first.") and level ("Requires level N.") branches are deliberately LEFT ALONE - they carry genuinely useful information, and blanketing them with lockedText would lose it (verified: Thalen still correctly says "Complete Offerings first."). STATE 6 FOR FREE: the Rurik fork's two gated dailies ARE each side's distinct response to the choice - quest_bandit_bounties (Cael, needs rurik_dead) and quest_fence_work (the Fence, needs rurik_allied) - so authoring their lockedText delivers the roadmap's "distinct responses for each selected outcome" through the game's existing gating rather than a new mechanic. AUTHORED: lockedText for all 8 condition-gated quests (Cael's bounties, Fence Work, The Bargain, The Order of Stones, The Fourth Expedition Member's permanent loss, Anti-Venom Supply's cold vats, The Long Root, Follow the Blood). ALSO state 6's other half - both fork quests now COMMUNICATE CONSEQUENCES before you commit (Rurik names the three wardens and that there is no road back; the bounty names the fence who will never deal with you again, and that "the wardens pay for a broken band, Rurik pays for a kept one"), and both had their inProgressText rewritten from raw objective restatement ("Kill Rurik the Fallen at the ruin.") into character - state 3 requires in-progress dialogue "remain in character rather than repeating raw objective text". validateQuestDialogue now also scans lockedText (7 spoken fields). VERIFIED: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; suite PASS with 0 dialogue issues and warnings still 2; with a level-12 stub (so the CONDITION gate is what fails, not the level gate - the first test was a false pass) all 8 gated quests speak in character and ZERO say "Requirements not yet met."; the two fork refusals read as intended. See docs/V0.19.4_BRANCH_AND_LOCKED_DIALOGUE.md.
// V0.19.3: VALIDATOR ACCURACY - quest giver/turnIn false positives removed; the 2 REAL warnings triaged, not papered over. THE PROBLEM: core/registry.js validated quest giver/turnIn with checkRefByName('npc', ...) - the NPC table ONLY - so 5 of the 7 descriptor warnings were FALSE ALARMS about content that works: (a) "Rurik the Fallen" is a MOB (mob_bandit_leader), named by quest_fall_of_rurik (a bounty - its task is literally {type:'kill', target:'Rurik the Fallen'}) and quest_ruriks_bargain; BOTH autoComplete, and the data's own note says "Rurik is not a turn-in NPC" - x4 warnings; (b) quest_fourth_member's giver "The Survivor" is nobody in the NPC table because the quest autoOffers at foundAtPoi and turns in to Iren; its escort task self-describes the actor - x1 warning. A validator that cries wolf is worse than none, so the CHECK was fixed rather than the data. THE FIX: new checkQuestPersonName(quest, field) accepts a giver/turnIn display name that resolves to an npc, a MOB or a BOSS, and treats the reference as OPTIONAL when the quest cannot have that NPC (giver: autoOffer/foundAtPoi; turnIn: autoComplete). CRITICALLY it is not merely weakened: verified that injecting a bogus giver ("Nobody McNotreal") is STILL caught. RESULT: descriptor warnings 7 -> 2, and both survivors are REAL, investigated, and deliberately NOT auto-fixed because each is unfinished content needing a design call: (1) event "quest_hook" -> questHook questId "quest_darkwood_first_steps", which exists only in systems/bot-player-system.js's separate BOT quest catalog and an editor default draft, never in DR.QUEST_BY_ID - so the event silently does nothing; the only real level-1 starter is quest_light_the_way, which already has Road Warden Cael as its giver, so repointing the hook could double-offer it. (2) dungeon_glooms_crypt has a valid zoneId ('dark_woods') but dangling caveZoneId 'blackroot_catacombs' / entranceZoneId 'blackroot_catacombs_f4' - that cave does not exist in DR.CAVE_BY_ID (only mossfang_cave + silk_web_cavern), and data/default-zones.js lists it beside ashroot_hollow/crystal_grotto/forgotten_mine as PLANNED cave zones. Building it is content work, not a reference fix. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; suite PASS; warnings 7 -> 2 with both remaining ones real. See docs/V0.19.3_VALIDATOR_ACCURACY.md.
// V0.19.2: ROADMAP ITEM 1 - DIALOGUE STATES 5 (FAILURE) + 8 (POST-COMPLETION) modelled, wired and authored. THE GAPS: (state 8) an NPC you had already helped replayed their turn-in completedText FOREVER - three call sites (systems/npc-system.js:1245, systems/event-system.js:615, systems/quest-system.js:1192) all rendered completedText for post-completion re-talk, so NPCs never acknowledged the changed world the roadmap asks for; (state 5) the ONLY failable quest in the game (quest_fourth_member - the escort, the sole quest carrying onFail) had NO authored failure dialogue: systems/quest-system.js hardcoded `${e.task.name} is dead. She does not come back.` in the escort-death branch, gendered pronoun and all. NEW FIELDS + WIRING (fallbacks keep every existing quest working): `postCompletionText` is now preferred at all three post-completion sites, falling back to completedText; `failureText` is now preferred in the escort permanent-failure branch, falling back to the old generic line. AUTHORED: failureText for quest_fourth_member naming the permanent consequence (no Quartermaster, Iren's last name unaccounted for) - state 5 is now 100% covered, because that quest is the game's only failable one (verified: every quest with onFail has failureText); postCompletionText for 8 quests reflecting changed regional conditions rather than repeating the thank-you (Cael's carter following the lanterns in, Liora's coins turning face-up, the bandits pulled off the north road, the stone ring gone quiet, Iren burying the five at the treeline, the Quartermaster counting antivenom). BUG FOUND BY THIS PASS: quest_fourth_member's spoken inProgressText contained RAW MAP COORDINATES - 'Escort the survivor safely back to the camp (100,100)' - developer terminology in an NPC's mouth that V0.19.1's word-list validator missed. Rewritten in the survivor's voice, and validateQuestDialogue gained a COORDS pattern (\(\s*-?\d{1,4}\s*,\s*-?\d{1,4}\s*\)) plus the two new spoken fields, so it now scans 6 fields. VERIFIED: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; suite PASS with 0 dialogue issues; the validator provably catches an injected '(100,100)' on the right quest/field and restores clean; cloneQuestForRuntime uses a full cloneJson so onFail (and the new fields) survive into runtime state - checked, not assumed. STATE COVERAGE NOW: offer 26/26, in-progress 26/26, completion 26/26, prerequisite 21/26, failure 1/1 failable, post-completion 8/26. Still unmodelled: objective summary as a first-class field (task labels serve it) and branch dialogue (state 6). See docs/V0.19.2_DIALOGUE_STATES.md.
// V0.19.1: ROADMAP ITEM 1 (QUEST DIALOGUE) BEGINS - UI terminology scrubbed from spoken dialogue + a validator to keep it out. THE RULE (roadmap Item 1): "No fourth-wall language, developer terminology, UI terminology, or character-breaking objective summaries inside spoken dialogue"; the OBJECTIVE SUMMARY is a separate, unambiguous journal record that may state conditions plainly. THE VIOLATION: 7 of 26 quests ended their spoken inProgressText with control instructions - quest_light_the_way "...Press E at each dark post.", quest_well_remembers, quest_pilgrims_road, quest_cut_supply_lines, quest_order_of_stones, quest_cut_them_down, quest_offerings ("...press E at the shrine with each in your bag."). THE FIX (data/quests.js): all 7 rewritten as in-character speech in each giver's established voice (Cael blunt/practical, Sister Liora gentle, Iren raw about her people, Selene mystical with a warning, Elder Thalen ritual), each still reminding the player what remains - per the roadmap's state-3 requirement - with zero UI terminology. SAFE TO REMOVE THE HINTS: the game already teaches the interact verb in SYSTEM text where it belongs - game.js:1571 start-up tip ("Press E near NPCs/chests/events/dungeon entrances, F near water, G near resources, and C near crafting stations") and quest-system.js:123/1348/1392 ("Press E near a quest source") - so no player is stranded, including in the onboarding quest whose note says it teaches the interact verb. OBJECTIVE SUMMARY: quest_order_of_stones' task label carried the least information of the set, so the puzzle restriction moved there rather than being lost with the dialogue rewrite ("Wake the stones in the right order" -> "Wake the 8 stones sunwise from the north stone"). NEW VALIDATOR: Game.prototype.validateQuestDialogue() (systems/inventory-system.js) scans the four SPOKEN fields (offerText/inProgressText/completedText/beforeOfferText) of every quest for banned UI/fourth-wall/developer terminology (press X, click, hotkey, hud, ui, menu, button, F-keys, esc, respawn, hp bar, xp, debug, placeholder, todo); task labels are deliberately NOT scanned (they are the journal record). Wired into runValidationSuite as a HARD-FAIL `questDialogue` section; boot log gains 'N dialogue issue(s)'. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; dialogue issues 7 -> 0 across 26 quests; the validator PROVABLY catches a regression (re-injecting "press E" is caught on the right quest/field, then restores clean); suite PASS. NOTE/CORRECTION: the 7 registry descriptor warnings are NOT Item 1 dialogue bugs as previously assumed - 5 are FALSE POSITIVES (giver/turnIn is validated against NPC names only, but "Rurik the Fallen" is a MOB - mob_bandit_leader - on two autoComplete bounty/branch quests whose own note says "Rurik is not a turn-in NPC", and quest_fourth_member autoOffers at a POI and turns in to Iren so needs no NPC giver); 1 is REAL (an event references the nonexistent quest id "quest_darkwood_first_steps"); 1 needs a look (dungeon_glooms_crypt references zone "blackroot_catacombs" while its zoneId is dark_woods). Left for a follow-up. See docs/V0.19.1_QUEST_DIALOGUE_PASS.md.
// V0.19.0: ROADMAP ITEM 23 - DEVELOPER DEBUG AND CONTENT INSPECTION TOOLS (completes the foundation track). NEW systems/debug-tools-system.js (DR.DebugToolsSystem, installed from game.js alongside the other systems; Game.prototype.installDebugTools() is called once at boot and attaches game.debug). SAFETY (all roadmap requirements met and verified): development-only - debug mode is OFF by default and every command refuses with a warning until explicitly enabled (DarkWoodsGame.debug.on(), or ?debug=1, or DR.CONFIG.DEBUG), so a normal player build cannot reach the tools by accident; debug state is VISIBLY INDICATED by a fixed DEBUG badge that appears on on() and is removed on off(); every action is LOGGED to both the console and the in-game log via a single run() funnel that also gates and try/catches each command; commands go through AUTHORITATIVE systems (grantEditorItem, applyStatusEffect/removeStatusEffect, resourceGatheringSystem.skill(), setWorldTime, setWeather, runValidationSuite/auditEconomy/getPlayerStatBreakdown) rather than mutating unrelated state; and unknown ids are rejected rather than creating impossible states. COMMANDS: on/off/enabled/help; items - grantItem, removeItem, money(silver); character - applyBuff, removeBuff, setSkill, statBreakdown; world - setTime, setWeather; inspection - lootTable, lootTables, item; validation - validate, economy, selfTest. NOTE on setSkill: resourceGatheringSystem.skill(name) silently falls back to 'Gathering' for an unknown name, so the debug command validates the name against state.skills FIRST rather than setting the wrong skill. Tools whose systems do not exist yet are deliberately NOT stubbed - mounts/taming (Item 7), spell-VFX trigger (Item 6) and NPC schedules (Item 16) land with their systems. Wiring: systems/debug-tools-system.js added to _script_order.json and the HTML script tags (before game.js). Verified in-browser: attached with enabled=false by default; a command while disabled returns false and no badge exists; after on() the badge appears and commands run; lootTable resolves 46 tables with item names + chances; item() reports the compiled instance and sell-back in real currency (60C 26S 0G 0P); validate() and economy() both return ok; unknown item id and unknown loot table are rejected; off() removes the badge and re-gates. node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.19.0_DEBUG_TOOLS.md.
// V0.18.99: ROADMAP ITEM 11 - FULL CURRENCY REWORK (user directive: "everything in the game should use the current currency not just gold"; user confirmed the ladder: 100 copper = 1 silver, 100 silver = 1 gold, 100 gold = 1 platinum - which the constants already matched). ROOT CAUSE of the V0.18.98 finding: the authored money values (item sellValue, quest rewards, chest gold, training and mercenary costs) are on a SILVER scale, but every money path spent/credited them through addGold/spendGold (x10,000) instead of silver (x100) - a 100x overcharge that made a basic hood cost ~950 level-8 kills and left 395/396 items with a 20,000x-100,000x buy:sell spread. THE SCALE WAS EVIDENCED, NOT GUESSED: reading the values as gold gives 948-16,552 kills per item (absurd); as copper gives 0.1-1.7 kills (free); as SILVER gives 9-165 kills (a sensible ladder) - and silver is the only reading that also makes quest rewards (12-140), training (25-85) and the deliberate rare-gold-coin mob drop (+10000 copper at 2-9% on elites+) all coherent. THE REWORK - COPPER is now the internal unit everywhere and formatCopper is the display everywhere: new Game.prototype.spendCopper / addSilver / spendSilver / silverToCopper helpers (inventory-system.js; spendGold now delegates to spendCopper). itemSellValue returns COPPER (x COPPER_PER_SILVER applied at the one formula site) - which automatically makes every existing copper consumer right: vendorSellInventoryIndex's addCopper, the item tooltip's formatCopper, the bags-full overflow (V0.18.98) and auditEconomy. event-system.js itemPrice returns COPPER (silver x2 x100); the buy affordability check compares copper directly (was `price * 10000`), payment uses spendCopper, and the price/purchase log render via formatCopper (was `${price}g`); chest table gold credits addSilver. quest-system.js quest rewards credit addSilver. npc-system.js class training pays copper AND fixes a latent bug where the affordability check read the legacy player.gold field while the spend went through spendGold/coinCopper - the two could disagree. mercenary-system.js contracts pay copper. auditEconomy compares copper vs copper. RESULT (verified in-browser): out-of-scale items 395 -> 0; buy:sell spread now a healthy 3x-6x catalogue-wide; Homespun Hood buy 22S / sell 3S 84C (~9 L8 kills), Iron Helm 1G 52S (~66 kills), Hollowsteel Greathelm 3G 84S (~166 kills); mob drop 2S 32C; quest 50S; training 25S; a boss gold coin = 1G. Money flow end-to-end: addSilver(50) -> 5000c, spendCopper(25S) -> 2500c left, overspend rejected with no negative balance. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; suite PASS (economy 0 issues, 0 ladder inversions, 0 arbitrage, stat-pipeline 15/15, items 396/396). NOTE: formatCopper's established "0C 22S 0G 0P" format is left as-is (pre-existing display used by tooltips); tightening it is an optional UI follow-up. See docs/V0.18.99_CURRENCY_REWORK.md.
// V0.18.98: ROADMAP ITEM 11 - GOLD-FAUCET FIX + economy-audit UNIT FIX (my own V0.18.97 bug), and the real finding it exposed. THE CURRENCY MODEL (COPPER_PER_GOLD=10000; 100 copper = 1 silver, 10,000 = 1 gold, 1,000,000 = 1 platinum): the money paths do NOT share a unit. BUY: event-system.js itemPrice = sellValue x 2, spent via spendGold() => GOLD (= sellValue x 20,000 copper). VENDOR SELL: inventory-system.js vendorSellInventoryIndex credits addCopper(itemSellValue(item)) => COPPER. BUG 1 (FIXED) - GOLD FAUCET: Game.prototype.addItem's bags-full overflow credited addGold(item.value) - the item's FULL value, in GOLD, bypassing the sell formula entirely. For item_head_iron_helm that paid 760,000 copper vs 42 copper for a deliberate vendor sale (~18,000x; 26,000-36,000x across sampled items). Overflowing your bags was therefore the single most profitable action in the game, and selling gear was strictly worse. addItem now credits addCopper(this.itemSellValue(item)) and logs via formatCopper - exactly matching vendorSellInventoryIndex. Verified: overflow now pays 42 copper == vendor 42 copper. BUG 2 (FIXED) - MY OWN AUDIT WAS WRONG: V0.18.97's auditEconomy compared the buy price (GOLD) against the sell-back (COPPER) as raw numbers and reported a reassuring 'tightest spread 2.0x'. That was meaningless. auditEconomy now normalises BOTH sides to copper before comparing, and adds a SANE_SPREAD (20x) check. THE FINDING (advisory, needs a design decision - deliberately NOT auto-fixed): 395 of 396 items exceed the sane spread, ratios 20,000x (item_torn_boot) to 100,000x (item_cave_blindfish); selling a blue helm returns 104 copper while buying it costs 3,840,000 copper, and at ~232 copper per level-8 kill that is ~16,552 kills to afford one. Item sellValues and mob currency drops are on a copper scale; shop prices are charged on a gold scale - a ~10,000x mismatch. Still TRUE and unchanged: 0 arbitrage (buying always costs more than selling back) and a perfectly monotonic value ladder (junk 1 / common 5 / uncommon 52 / rare 150 / epic 260 / legendary 600). Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; suite PASS (economy hard-checks green; the spread is reported as advisory). See docs/V0.18.98_GOLD_FAUCET_AND_UNIT_FIX.md.
// V0.18.97: ROADMAP ITEM 11 (ECONOMY) BEGINS - economy audit: arbitrage safety + value-ladder coherence. NEW: Game.prototype.auditEconomy() (systems/inventory-system.js, next to itemSellValue/validateItemData) is a read-only audit of the item economy. THE TWO ECONOMY FORMULAS (now documented): BUY = sellValue x 2 (systems/event-system.js itemPrice); SELL-BACK = sellValue x rarityMult x (1 + (level-1) x 0.08) x 0.35 (Game.prototype.itemSellValue). CHECK 1 - ARBITRAGE SAFETY (hard-fail): for every item, buy price must exceed sell-back, else players could farm gold by buying and re-selling. Result: 0 arbitrage across 396 items; the TIGHTEST spread in the whole catalogue is still 2.0x (item_torn_boot, buy 2 / sell-back 1), so there is healthy headroom. (The buy:sell-back ratio is ~5.7x at level 1 and only closes as levelMult grows - it would need level ~59 to invert, far beyond the level 1-10 range.) CHECK 2 - VALUE LADDER (advisory): median sellValue must ascend by rarity tier so "rare items feel valuable" (roadmap Item 11). Rarity keys are CANONICALISED first because the game treats yellow/gold/orange as one Legendary tier (raw keys made gold@260 look equal to purple@260; canonicalised, legendary is n=4 median 600). Result: a perfectly monotonic ladder with 0 inversions - junk 1 (n=3), common 5 (n=164), uncommon 52 (n=122), rare 150 (n=82), epic 260 (n=20), legendary 600 (n=4). CHECK 3 - ZERO-VALUE items (hard-fail) that should be sellable; quest items are exempt (item_glooms_crypt_key legitimately has no value - it is a key, not tradeable, and both formulas floor to 1 which would otherwise read as false arbitrage). Result: 0. Wired into runValidationSuite as an `economy` section (arbitrage + zero-value hard-fail; ladder inversions advisory); boot log gains 'N economy issue(s)'. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; suite PASS with economy 0 issues / 0 ladder notes, stat-pipeline 15/15, items sourced 396/396, 0 data issues. See docs/V0.18.97_ECONOMY_AUDIT.md.
// V0.18.96: IMPLEMENT poisonResist (was a whitelisted dead stat; follow-up from V0.18.93 data-integrity check). The silk-cavern venom items (item_venom_stained_boots pR3, item_old_venomsacs_gland pR4, item_silk_web_antivenom_charm pR6, + a pR8 trinket) and the Antivenom potion buff (pR20) all carried poisonResist, but it was in NO stat pipeline and nothing read it -> a dead stat. IMPLEMENTED (chosen over retiring it: poison resistance is thematically core to the venom zone). core/stats.js: 'poisonResist' added to STAT_KEYS; a poisonResist entry in STAT_RULES (a NICHE resistance so it stacks more generously and caps higher than magicResist - cap 0.75, denominatorBase 24, denominatorPerLevel 3.0, never fully negates poison); computePlayerDerived now derives poisonResistRating + poisonResistReduction (same additive-rating -> diminishing-return shape as magicResist, opt-in via the stat, 0/inert otherwise); new poisonResistReductionFor(entity) helper mirrors magicResistReductionFor; both exported on DR.StatSystem. systems/inventory-system.js recalculatePlayerStats assigns player.poisonResistRating/Reduction from derived. systems/status-effect-system.js DoT tick: poison/venom DoT ticks (isPoisonLikeEffect) now reduce their damage by the victim's poisonResistReductionFor before dealing it. systems/inventory-system.js validateItemData: poisonResist removed from the tolerated-unimplemented whitelist (it is now a real STAT_KEY). Regression guard added to runStatPipelineSelfTest (#14): a poisonResist item yields a positive, capped reduction. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; poisonResist is a STAT_KEY; no gear -> 0 reduction (inert); 3 venom pieces -> rating 17 / 20.6% reduction (capped); a 100-dmg poison DoT -> 79; poisonResistReductionFor matches; boot validation suite PASS with stat-pipeline 15/15, items sourced 396/396, 0 data issues, 0 compiler errors. See docs/V0.18.96_POISON_RESIST.md.
// V0.18.95: ROADMAP ITEM 22 CLOSE-OUT - final regression scenarios + release process codified. runStatPipelineSelfTest (systems/inventory-system.js) grows 12->14: (#12) LEVEL GROWTH - a higher character level yields higher derived stats (L15 maxHp 329 > L5 263), confirming level is a live stat source; (#13) CURRENT-HP RATIO PRESERVATION - equipping a +maxHp item while at ~50% HP keeps the player at ~50% of the new higher max (ratio 0.49, max 263->295), not a free heal or a stale value - proving recalculatePlayerStats' hpRatio preservation on gear changes. Suite stat-pipeline now 14/14. RELEASE PROCESS CODIFIED (Item 22 "validation runs as part of every release"): NEW validate.sh runs the CLI-automatable checks (node --check on all JS, JSON.parse on all JSON, and version consistency across config/HTML/VERSION/PATCH_NOTES/README) and prints RESULT: PASS/FAIL; NEW RELEASE_CHECKLIST.md documents the full per-version process including the in-browser boot validation suite (DarkWoodsGame.runValidationSuite must be PASS) and which checks block a release vs are advisory. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; validate.sh prints RESULT: PASS; the boot validation suite is PASS with stat-pipeline 14/14 (items sourced 396/396, 0 data issues, 0 compiler errors, 7 advisory warnings). This closes the initial Item 22 pass: the suite covers content validation, item data integrity, and stat-pipeline regression across equip/unequip/re-recalc/set-bonuses/save-load/death-respawn/level-growth/hp-ratio/aggregation/attribute-aliases, with both a CLI script and an in-browser entry point. See docs/V0.18.95_RELEASE_PROCESS.md.
// V0.18.94: ROADMAP ITEM 22 - REGRESSION SUITE EXPANSION (death/respawn + aggregation + alias guard). runStatPipelineSelfTest (systems/inventory-system.js) grows from 8 to 12 checks, all on the isolated scratch player: (#9) ATTRIBUTE-ALIAS REGRESSION GUARD - an item written with a display-name attribute ('intellect') must still raise intelligence (locks in the V0.18.93 dead-stat fix so it can never silently regress; passes 8->12); (#10) additive aggregation - two stat items in different slots stack (321>295); (#11a/b) DEATH/RESPAWN - runs the game's REAL respawn stat path Game.prototype.restoreActorAfterRespawn(scratchPlayer) (which only mutates the passed actor, so it is safe on the scratch player) and asserts it does NOT duplicate stat modifiers (295==295) AND restores full HP (295/295) - the roadmap's 'death and respawn cannot duplicate modifiers'. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; the boot validation suite is PASS with stat-pipeline 12/12 (items sourced 396/396, 0 data issues, 0 compiler errors, 7 advisory warnings), and the scratch game state is restored after the run. See docs/V0.18.94_REGRESSION_SUITE_EXPANSION.md.
// V0.18.93: ROADMAP ITEM 22 (DATA INTEGRITY) - new item-stat-key validator + root fix for a widespread DEAD-STAT bug it surfaced. NEW CHECK: Game.prototype.validateItemData() (systems/inventory-system.js) scans every DR.ITEM_BY_ID entry's stats for keys not in the valid set, and validates armour-set integrity (pieceIds resolve, bonus.stats keys valid). Wired into runValidationSuite as a HARD-FAIL section (an unknown stat key is a real bug); boot log gains 'N data issue(s)'. THE BUG IT FOUND: the game's DISPLAY vocabulary names the attributes Intellect/Agility/Spirit (systems/inventory-system.js:1459-1460), and item/data authors wrote stats under those names - `intellect` (45 uses), `agility`, `spirit` - but core/stats.js mergeAttributes only read the canonical keys intelligence/dexterity/wisdom, and NOTHING read intellect/agility/spirit as values. So every such bonus was a SILENT DEAD STAT across a lot of caster gear (incl. Wispflame Focus and all V0.18.75-88 caster pieces) and the silk-cavern venom set. ROOT FIX (surgical, one place): core/stats.js gains ATTRIBUTE_ALIASES { str/dex/agility/sta/int/intellect/wis/spirit -> canonical } and mergeAttributes folds any alias spelling into its attribute, so these bonuses finally apply. Exposed as DR.ATTRIBUTE_ALIASES; validateItemData accepts STAT_KEYS + those aliases + legit non-combat fields (bag 'slots') + one tolerated-unimplemented stat ('poisonResist' - intended silk-cavern resistance, not yet wired into combat; whitelisted so a real typo still stands out, flagged as a follow-up task). BALANCE NOTE: this restores intended functionality, so affected caster/silk gear gets its Intellect/Agility/Spirit back (a buff to previously-dead stats). Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; equipping an intellect item raises intelligence 39->43, an agility item raises dexterity 38->40, a spirit item raises wisdom 37->39 (all previously 0 change); validateItemData reports 0 issues; validation suite PASS (stat-pipeline 8/8, items 396/396, 0 data issues, 0 compiler errors). See docs/V0.18.93_DATA_INTEGRITY_DEADSTAT.md.
// V0.18.92: ROADMAP ITEM 22 - CONSOLIDATED VALIDATION SUITE + save/load regression check + stale-obtainability fix. NEW: Game.prototype.runValidationSuite() (systems/inventory-system.js, after runStatPipelineSelfTest) aggregates the registry validation (descriptor references, compiler errors, item obtainability) and the stat-pipeline regression self-test into ONE report { ok, summary, sections } and decides one overall pass/fail. HARD failures = compiler errors or a failed self-test; descriptor WARNINGS stay ADVISORY (the game continues; the 7 pre-existing quest-giver-name warnings belong to the Item 1 quest-data pass). INVOKED once at boot (game.js, after bindEvents) replacing the standalone stat-self-test log with one consolidated line: '[Dream Realms] validation suite: PASS - stat-pipeline 8/8, items sourced 396/396, 0 compiler error(s), 7 descriptor warning(s).' (console.info on pass, console.warn + sections on fail); advisory-only, bare try/catch so it never blocks the loop. NEW regression check (self-test #8): SAVE/LOAD SAFETY - round-tripping a scratch player's equipment through JSON (as a save does) must reproduce identical stats, never duplicate modifiers (roadmap: 'save/load cannot duplicate modifiers'); passes 295==295. VALIDATION-QUALITY FIX: the boot-time runBootValidation in data/default-zones.js fires BEFORE all source data (loot tables / shop lists / crafting outputs) is registered, so its cached obtainability was premature (reported 340/396 = 56 false-unsourced). The suite re-runs runBootValidation FRESH (it runs late, after full init) so the number is accurate (396/396, 0 unsourced) AND the corrected report is re-cached for anything else reading DR.Registry.getReport(). Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; boots with 0 console errors; suite runs at boot -> PASS with stat-pipeline 8/8 (now incl. save/load), items sourced 396/396, compiler errors 0; DR.Registry.getReport().obtainability is 396/396 after the suite runs. This advances Item 22 (automated validation & regression): one release-time report is now the single entry point (DarkWoodsGame.runValidationSuite()). See docs/V0.18.92_VALIDATION_SUITE.md.
// V0.18.91: ROADMAP ITEM 14/22 - STAT-PIPELINE REGRESSION SELF-CHECK (first automated gameplay-regression guard). NEW: Game.prototype.runStatPipelineSelfTest() (systems/inventory-system.js, after getPlayerStatBreakdown) runs an ISOLATED self-test of the stat pipeline on a SCRATCH player + equipment, saving/restoring the real this.player/this.equipment in a finally block and wrapping everything in try/catch, so it can never disturb or break the game or a save. It asserts the roadmap's pipeline invariants: (1) recalc is idempotent - calling recalculatePlayerStats twice on the same inputs never changes the result (proves no temporary bonus is written into base stats, because computePlayerDerived always reads baseX); (2) equipping a stat item increases the stat; (3) that contribution is not double-counted on re-recalc; (4) unequipping removes it exactly; (5) a full armour set is detected; (6) its set stat bonus flows through the pipeline (isolated by toggling bonus.stats on the same equipment); (7) the set bonus drops when a piece is removed. Returns { ok, total, failed, checks } and stashes it on game._statPipelineSelfTest. INVOKED once at boot (game.js, after bindEvents) advisory-only: logs '[Dream Realms] stat pipeline self-test: N/N checks passed.' (console.info) or a console.warn listing the failed checks - mirrors the registry obtainability-audit boot log; a bare try/catch guarantees it never blocks the loop. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; boots with 0 console errors; the self-test runs at boot and passes 7/7 (idempotent 263==263, equip 295>263, no double-count 295==295, unequip 263==263, full-set detected, set aura 371>361, set drops on removal), and game state (this.player) is restored afterwards. This completes the stat-pipeline audit (Item 14: order documented V0.18.89, set bonuses first-class V0.18.89, inspectable V0.18.90, regression-guarded this) and opens Item 22 (automated validation/regression). See docs/V0.18.91_STAT_PIPELINE_SELFTEST.md.
// V0.18.90: ROADMAP ITEM 14 (STAT PIPELINE) - the pipeline is now INSPECTABLE (the roadmap's Stat Breakdown UI requirement). NEW: Game.prototype.getPlayerStatBreakdown() (systems/inventory-system.js, right after recalculatePlayerStats) returns the per-source RAW stat contributions from the SAME sources in the SAME order the aggregator uses - trainer bonuses, talent ranks, equipment stats/armour, and full-set bonuses - plus the derived final values for reference. It recomputes nothing and mutates nothing (read-only), so the breakdown is always faithful to what combat uses. UI (systems/ui-system.js character sheet): the Damage/HP/Mana/Armor/Speed stat cards now carry a title tooltip built from that breakdown (bdTitle) - e.g. 'HP breakdown - base class + level scaling, then: Equipment +98 - Set Bonus +10. Final 367.' - honestly separating base/level derived scaling from the summed per-source contributions rather than pretending the final is a plain sum (computePlayerDerived applies base + level + a scalar). statCardMarkup gained an optional 4th title element; entries without it are unchanged. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; getPlayerStatBreakdown on a full-Wanderer-set stub correctly buckets equipment (rarity-scaled item stats, e.g. hp 98) vs set aura (hp 10 / speed 0.03) vs empty trainer/talents, and reports the derived finals. Reuses the V0.18.89 pipeline; no gameplay/combat math changed. See docs/V0.18.90_STAT_BREAKDOWN.md.
// V0.18.89: ROADMAP ITEM 14 (STAT PIPELINE) BEGINS - armour SET BONUSES are now a first-class stat source in the one authoritative recalculation. AUDIT FINDING: the player stat pipeline is already centralized - Game.prototype.recalculatePlayerStats (systems/inventory-system.js) aggregates trainer bonuses + talent stat ranks + equipment stats/armour into a single `totals`, then DR.StatSystem.computePlayerDerived(className, level, baseStats, totals, raceStatMods) produces every final/derived value (maxHp/mana, attack, defense, speed, armorReduction, magicResistReduction, crit/cdr/damage multipliers, regen). But of the roadmap's listed stat sources, SET BONUSES had no stage - my V0.18.88 Wanderer set only did XP/meditation (non-stat) via live-checked hooks. FIX (surgical, in the owning aggregator): after the equipment loop, recalculatePlayerStats now iterates DR.ARMOR_SETS and, for each fully-equipped set (hasFullArmorSet), adds set.bonus.stats to the SAME `totals` that feeds computePlayerDerived. Because recalculatePlayerStats re-runs on every equip/unequip (inventory-system.js:302/407/460), a set stat bonus is added exactly once and removed immediately when a piece comes off - never written into base stats (satisfies the roadmap's 'added once / removed when conditions fail / not written into base' rules). The Wanderer set gains bonus.stats {speed:0.03, hp:10} to exercise/showcase the new stage; its xpPercent/meditationSpeedPercent stay at their own hooks (awardPlayerXp / meditationTickRate) since they are not stats. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; toggling the aura on the SAME full-set equipment changes final maxHp by exactly +10 and speed by exactly +0.03 (aura flows through the real pipeline); removing one piece drops the whole set contribution. The authoritative calculation order is documented in docs/V0.18.89_STAT_PIPELINE.md.
// V0.18.88: ROADMAP ITEM 4 D (CAPSTONE) - the rare DARK WOODS WANDERER SET, the game's first true armour set with a full-set bonus. DATA (data/items.js): 4 blue level-8 leather pieces (item_wanderer_hood/garb/leggings/boots, slots head/chest/legs/feet, allClasses) with strong solo stats; plus DR.ARMOR_SETS.dark_woods_wanderer = { pieceIds, bonus:{ xpPercent:0.03, meditationSpeedPercent:0.15 }, bonusText }. SET DETECTION is by item id (the compiler carries only a fixed field set, so a custom setId would be dropped; runtime instances hold the source id in itemId/sourceItemId, id is a numeric instance id - the helper checks itemId||sourceItemId||id). CODE HOOKS (both single-point, no separate tick loop): (1) game.js equippedArmorSetCount()/hasFullArmorSet() read the player's this.equipment map; meditationTickRate() shortens the existing meditation tick interval by meditationSpeedPercent for the PLAYER when the full set is worn (15s -> 12.75s); (2) systems/combat-system.js awardPlayerXp() - the one canonical XP award path - adds xpPercent to its multiplier when the full set is worn (applies uniformly to every XP source), and logs '(Wanderer Set: +3%)'; (3) systems/ui-system.js character-sheet Set Bonuses box is now dynamic - shows each set the player has >=1 piece of, X/total, and whether the full-set bonus is active (was a hardcoded 'No active set bonuses.'). SOURCES: all 4 drop from the tougher Dark Woods loot tables (data/loot-tables.js - named rares [hood/garb], ashroot [leggings], common chest [boots]) at low rare-set chances; audit-guarded. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; full set -> equippedArmorSetCount 4, hasFullArmorSet true, meditationTickRate 15->12.75, awardPlayerXp(1000) -> 1030 with the set / 1000 without / 1000 with only 3 pieces (full-set gated); audit 0 unsourced (396 items now). With V0.18.79's save migration the set reaches existing saves. This COMPLETES Roadmap Item 4 (itemization): every equip slot now has a full pool. See docs/V0.18.88_WANDERER_SET.md.
