// V0.18.74: LOOT AUDIT TRIAGE - every item now obtainable + audit sees vendor/quest-grant sources (Roadmap Item 12 follow-up to V0.18.71). The V0.18.71 obtainability audit flagged 10 items with no data-level source (2 starter bags, 5 gathering tools/rods, 3 quest-script-given items). Triage: (1) systems/event-system.js - the vendor stock lists are lifted out of shopItemIds() into a shared const SHOP_ITEM_LISTS exposed as DR.SHOP_ITEM_LISTS (single source of truth; shopItemIds now just reads it), and the camp general store (shop_camp_basic_goods) now also stocks the basic gathering tools a new character needs - item_crude_pickaxe, item_worn_fishing_rod, item_basic_fishing_rod, item_herbalist_knife, item_worn_hatchet - and the starter bags item_linen_pouch + item_travelers_pack (pickaxe also at the blacksmith, herbalist knife also at the herbalist). (2) core/registry.js auditItemObtainability now also cross-references DR.SHOP_ITEM_LISTS (vendor:<shop>) and quest-script grants via DR.INTERACT_POINTS / DR.DISCOVERY_POINTS grantItem (quest-grant:<poi>). RESULT: 262/262 items sourced, 0 unsourced - every item in the game has a reachable, recognized source (verified live: pickaxe -> vendor camp+blacksmith, linen pouch -> vendor camp, hunters journal -> quest-grant poi_hunter_journal, tarnished coin -> quest-grant poi_well_coin; remaining list empty). node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors. Foundation quality for the itemization expansion (Item 4). See docs/V0.18.74_LOOT_AUDIT_TRIAGE.md.
// V0.18.73: CRAFTING WINDOW REDESIGN + CENTER-ON-OPEN for all button windows (user: "Crafting UI is still ugly it needs a lot of work, i want a way cleaner UI, also any windows the player opens by pressing a button should always open in the middle of their screen only"). (1) CRAFTING REDESIGN (systems/crafting-system.js): a one-time scoped stylesheet (#dr-crafting-styles) replaces the old inline-styled boxes. The window is a rounded gradient panel with a sticky draggable header (title + station subtitle); recipes render as CARDS - a coloured item-icon tile (from the output item's icon family/glyph/colour), the result name, the effect/stats line, colour-coded MATERIAL CHIPS per ingredient (green .ok when you have enough, red .miss when short, each showing have/need), a meta line (skill/level/time, red when not craftable with the reason), and a clear gradient Craft button (greyed when disabled). Category tabs are now proper pills with an active gradient state + per-category counts. (2) CENTER-ON-OPEN (systems/ui-system.js installMovableUiWindows): prepareWindow now attaches a per-window style MutationObserver that RE-CENTERS a .gameWindow whenever it transitions hidden->visible (via game.centerUiWindow), overriding any previously dragged/stored position - so every button-opened window opens in the middle of the screen. Dragging while open still works (the observer only fires on the open transition; re-entrancy guarded by a uiCentering flag). Opt-outs: the world map overlay and the profession/skills PAIR (which keeps its own side-by-side centering), plus any panel with data-no-auto-center. Verified in-browser: the crafting window renders the new cards/icons/chips/tabs (styles injected; 4 buff-potion cards, 8 material chips colour-split by ok/miss, 4 craft buttons, 7 tabs); and a hidden->shown .gameWindow moved to (0,0) snaps to the screen centre. node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.73_CRAFTING_REDESIGN.md.
// V0.18.72: CRAFTING WINDOW CATEGORY TABS (user request: "we need buttons for each category, Food, potions, Armor, Weapons etc. You click the button and then it shows the recipes for that category"). systems/crafting-system.js refreshWindow now renders a category TAB BAR at the top of the crafting window: an "All" tab plus one button per category the current station actually makes (Armor / Weapons / Cooked Meat / Cooked Fish / Meals / Health Potions / Mana Potions / Buff Potions / Materials / Other), each showing its recipe count, and clicking a tab filters the list to just that category (the V0.18.70 headers now only show inside the "All" view). New runtime.selectedCraftCategory holds the choice and persists across re-renders and crafts; it defaults to the first real category so the window opens already filtered rather than as one long scroll. Category clicks are handled in the ensureWindow click listener (button[data-craft-cat] -> set selectedCraftCategory + refreshWindow) alongside the existing craft-button handler. Verified via the live window with a mock campfire station: tabs render [All, Armor, Cooked Fish, Meals, Health Potions, Mana Potions, Buff Potions], the window opens on Armor (8 recipes), clicking Buff Potions shows exactly the 4 buff potions, Armor shows 8. node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.72_CRAFTING_TABS.md.
// V0.18.71: ROADMAP ITEM 12 - LOOT / ITEM-OBTAINABILITY AUDIT (foundation for the itemization expansion) + fixed one gap it found. NEW core/registry.js auditItemObtainability() (exposed on DR.Registry, and its summary folded into runBootValidation's report + a boot console.info): cross-references EVERY acquisition source that names items - loot tables incl. boss/miniboss/chest/dungeon-reward tables + their rarePool/guaranteedPool (by itemId), crafting recipe outputs (itemId), quest fixed + player-choice rewards (rewards.items/.choiceItems by id), gathering/fishing resource-node drops (by item NAME -> resolved to id), the fishing catch tables, and class starting gear (item_starter_ id convention) - and reports items in DR.ITEM_BY_ID with NO reachable source (the roadmap "no item exists only as an unused data record" check). To make it accurate: systems/fishing-system.js now exposes its fish catch tables as DR.FISH_TABLES (read-only) so fishing is a recognized source. RESULT on current content: 252/262 items sourced, 10 flagged (2 vendor bags, 3 gathering tools + 2 rods, 3 quest-script-given items - all obtainable via vendor/quest-script/starting mechanisms the data-level audit does not resolve). The audit also found ONE genuine orphan - item_cooked_forest_stew, a green food with NO recipe - now FIXED: data/crafting.js recipe_cooked_forest_stew (campfire, gloomleaf x2 + gloomcap mushroom) and the item is upgraded to a proper food (useEffect hp/mana + a 'Warm Meal' food buff + cooldown). Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; the audit resolves all new content (potions/armor/foods) to their real sources, fish resolve to fish:<zone>, the stew resolves to its new recipe, and the boot report carries obtainability {total:262, sourced:252, unsourced:10}. Vendor stock (tag-based) is a known uncaptured source, noted in the audit. See docs/V0.18.71_OBTAINABILITY_AUDIT.md.
// V0.18.70: ROADMAP ITEM 3 E - CRAFTING PANEL POLISH + a root-cause effectCategory compile fix. (1) systems/crafting-system.js refreshWindow now GROUPS recipes by category with headers (Armor / Weapons / Cooked Meat / Cooked Fish / Meals / Health Potions / Mana Potions / Buff Potions / Materials / Other) and shows each recipe's RESULT effect: new helpers recipeOutputDraft / recipeCategory / recipeEffectText classify the output item and format it - armour shows "Armor +N · +stats", consumables show "Restores N HP/MP · Buff: Name (Ns) · Cooldown Ns". (2) ROOT CAUSE found while classifying: the item compiler (systems/item-compiler-system.js) was DROPPING the top-level effectCategory (and armorType) when compiling a draft to a runtime item, so at runtime item.effectCategory was undefined - which meant the V0.18.66/68 consumable cooldown routing (item.effectCategory -> DR.effectPolicy.cooldownGroupFor -> shared group) never resolved (potions were getting per-item cooldowns, not the intended shared potion cooldown) and the crafting panel could not distinguish a potion from a meal. FIX: compileOne now carries effectCategory + armorType onto the compiled item, and createRuntimeItemInstance copies effectCategory onto consumable instances + armorType onto equipment instances. Now verified: a Minor Healing Draught use keys the cooldown to the shared "potion_heal" group and a Minor Mana Draught to "potion_mana" (independent shared cooldowns), instances carry effectCategory/armorType, and the panel groups correctly (Armor 8, Cooked Fish 6, Meals 3, Health Potions 1, Mana Potions 1, Buff Potions 4 at the campfire) with correct effect text. node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.70_CRAFTING_PANEL.md.
// V0.18.69: ROADMAP ITEM 3 A - the WILDPELT starter armor SET. A complete craftable Dark Woods leather set, one piece for every armour slot INCLUDING the belt (the roadmap's explicit callout): head (Wildpelt Hood), shoulders (Mantle), chest (Vest), legs (Leggings), hands (Gloves), feet (Boots), cape (Cloak), belt (Belt) - 8 pieces. ADDED: (1) data/items.js - 8 armor pieces (type armor, armorType 'leather', slot per piece, low starter stats: armor 1-4, small defense/hp/speed; white rarity; level 1-2; allClasses; full name/description/icon/sellValue). Total set ~15 armor / ~9 defense / ~34 hp - a meaningful first upgrade for a naked new character. (2) data/crafting.js - 8 recipes (profession tailoring = leatherwork, stationId station_campfire so they are craftable NOW at the campfire hub, since the Loom/Herbalist Table are not placed) that turn Dark Woods animal materials (item_wolf_pelt Gloom Wolf Pelt, item_briar_hide Briar Hide, item_briar_tusk Briar Tusk, item_bone_dust Bone Dust) + item_gloomleaf binding into the pieces. Gives all those gathered pelts/hides a use. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; all 8 pieces compile as kind 'equipment' with the correct slot/armor/stats (all 8 armour slots covered head/shoulders/chest/legs/hands/feet/cape/belt); a runtime Wildpelt Vest equips into the chest slot (armor 4, +2 defense/+8 hp); all 8 recipes reference only valid item ids (0 bad refs) at station_campfire; registry resolves every new item and adds 0 new boot warnings. NOTE: armorType 'leather' is draft metadata (the item compiler does not carry it onto the runtime instance yet) - it is forward-looking for the armor-proficiency skills (Roadmap Item 8). See docs/V0.18.69_WILDPELT_ARMOR.md.
// V0.18.68: ROADMAP ITEM 3 D - HERBAL POTIONS (first batch), built on the V0.18.67 consumable-buff plumbing. Recon found: the campfire (a world object type 'fire') maps to station_campfire so cooking is functional, but the Herbalist Table is removed from the camp by ensureStartingCampRevamp and never re-placed, so a dedicated alchemy station is not usable yet. Item 3's premise is that CAMPFIRES become the functional early-game crafting hub for cooking AND alchemy, so these potions are brewed at the campfire (no world-placement work, craftable now). ADDED: (1) data/items.js - six functional potions: item_minor_healing_draught (useEffect.hp 45, effectCategory potion_heal), item_minor_mana_draught (mana 35, potion_mana), item_regeneration_tonic (hp 10 + a potion_buff HoT periodicHealing 6/3s/30s), item_clarity_tonic (mana regen HoT), item_bramblehide_elixir (potion_buff +4 defense/+3 armor 180s), item_antivenom_draught (potion_buff +20 poisonResist 180s); each with per-item cooldownMs. Instant heal/mana route their cooldown to a shared potion group (potion_heal/potion_mana); the buff potions apply a categorized potion_buff, so the effect policy keeps only one potion buff active at a time (verified: Bramblehide replaces Regeneration). (2) data/crafting.js - six campfire recipes (profession cooking, stationId station_campfire) using gathered Dark Woods herbs (gloomleaf, wispbloom, lantern_moss, thornberry, blackroot, gloomcap_mushroom, webcap_fungus) -> the potions. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; all six potions compile with correct useEffect/effectCategory/cooldown; recipes reference only valid item ids (0 bad refs), registry resolves all new items, and the registry boot report adds 0 new warnings (7 pre-existing quest/dungeon warnings are unrelated). A live mock-use test: Minor Healing Draught healed hp 40->85 + set a cooldown; Regeneration Tonic applied a potion_buff HoT; Bramblehide Elixir then replaced it (one potion buff cap). NOTE: a dedicated alchemy station/profession + placing the Herbalist Table in camp is deferred (ties into the Dead Lantern Camp overhaul, Roadmap Item 2). See docs/V0.18.68_HERBAL_POTIONS.md.
// V0.18.67: ROADMAP ITEM 3 begins - FOOD BUFFS ACTUALLY APPLY (built on the V0.18.65/66 effect-policy foundation). ROOT CAUSE: cooked-food items in data/items.js already declared useEffect.buff (Grilled Minnow -> "Well Fed" +1 defense 120s; Cooked Eel Skewer -> "Eel Vitality" +8 hp 180s), but the consumable-use path (systems/item-compiler-system.js Game.prototype.useInventoryItem) only ever applied useEffect.hp / .mana / .castsSpellId - it never applied useEffect.buff, so every food buff was dead data. FIX: (1) useInventoryItem now applies useEffect.buff as a status effect via this.applyStatusEffect (with a stable per-item buff id, the buff's own effectCategory, name/duration/mods/color), counts it toward "did anything happen", and includes it in the no-usable-effect guard. Because the buff carries effectCategory:'food', the central effect policy (V0.18.66) governs it: food is maxConcurrent 1 / replaceStronger, so eating a second food REPLACES the first food buff instead of stacking. (2) data/items.js: the two existing buff-foods get effectCategory:'food' on their buff + a per-item cooldownMs (10s / 12s) so a food heal+buff cannot be spammed (Item 3 requires an item cooldown). Cooldown key defaults to the itemId (per-item), so different foods do not share one timer. Verified end-to-end on a mock player: eating Grilled Minnow healed hp 50->68 + mana 20->28, applied "Well Fed" (effectCategory food, +1 defense), set a cooldown on item_grilled_minnow; eating Cooked Eel Skewer next replaced it so only "Eel Vitality" remained (1 food buff cap). node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors. This is the plumbing every future food & potion (the 20+ foods, fish recipes, herbal potions) plugs into by declaring useEffect.buff + effectCategory. See docs/V0.18.67_FOOD_BUFFS.md.
// V0.18.66: ROADMAP FOUNDATION - Effect Policy slice 2 (wire the policy into the live paths). Slice 1 (V0.18.65) added core/effect-policy.js but only the Bard song cap read from it. This slice makes the policy the SINGLE AUTOMATIC enforcement point: (1) systems/status-effect-system.js DR.StatusEffects.applyToEntity now, for a NEW effect, resolves DR.effectPolicy.categoryOf(normalized) and calls enforceConcurrency - dropping the oldest of that category to make room, or denying the incoming when overflow=rejectNew. Uncategorized effects (categoryOf -> null) are untouched, so all existing effects behave exactly as before (verified: 3 generic buffs all kept; bard major songs still cap at 5 through this path with no explicit call). (2) normalizeEffect now carries effectCategory through normalization (it previously stripped it, so only majorSong survived) - so a categorized food/potion effect stays recognizable after it is stored (verified: two 'food' effects -> only the newer kept at cap 1; 'food' and 'potion_buff' are independent categories and coexist). (3) systems/item-compiler-system.js consumable-use resolves the cooldown key as item.cooldownGroup || effectPolicy.cooldownGroupFor(item.effectCategory) || item.itemId, so a categorized consumable shares its category cooldown (copies/stacks cannot bypass it); inert today (no item sets effectCategory) and an explicit item.cooldownGroup still wins. Net: the effect/consumable systems now enforce the policy automatically, ready for food/potions (Roadmap Item 3) to just declare effectCategory. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.66_EFFECT_POLICY_WIRED.md.
// V0.18.65: ROADMAP FOUNDATION - Effect Policy (slice 1 of Roadmap Item 13: Buff/Debuff/Cooldown/Stacking Rules). Recon first confirmed the data-driven content architecture (Roadmap Item 9) is largely already present - core/registry.js is a read-only descriptor/reference-validation layer over the data-owned DR.*_BY_ID catalogs with a boot-time consistency report + descriptor version, core/ids.js canonicalizes IDs, and item/spell cooldownGroup + player.itemCooldowns (save-persisted) already exist. The genuine gap was Item 13: there was NO central authoritative policy for effect categories / concurrency limits / stacking / cooldown groups, which is why the Bard song cap was hard-coded (V0.18.63's MAX_ACTIVE_MAJOR_SONGS=5). NEW core/effect-policy.js (DR.effectPolicy) is that authoritative, data-driven policy: a CATEGORIES table keyed by category -> {scope target|sourceAndTarget, maxConcurrent, overflow dropOldest|rejectNew, stackMode, cooldownGroup, dispelType}, plus a query API (ruleFor/limitFor/cooldownGroupFor/categoryOf/enforceConcurrency) and a non-fatal boot validate() in the same spirit as registry.js. It OWNS the policy catalog only - it applies no effects and stores no per-actor state (the status-effect/spell/item systems remain the owners). Wired in: systems/spell-system.js applyBardMajorSongLimit now reads the 'major_song' cap from the policy (enforceConcurrency) instead of the hard-coded 5 - behaviour-preserving (verified: 6th song drops the oldest to keep 5; a second bard's songs are independent per source+target scope). Food/potion/consumable categories (+ cooldown groups) are pre-defined in the policy now as forward-looking DATA so the campfire cooking & alchemy work (Roadmap Item 3) consumes an existing policy instead of hard-coding fresh caps; wiring the rest of the effect systems through the policy is a later slice. Loaded in the HTML core group (after core/ids.js). Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; policy validate() reports 0 issues; the song-cap reroute matches the old behaviour in a live test. See docs/V0.18.65_EFFECT_POLICY_FOUNDATION.md.
// V0.18.64: TORCH LIGHT - light sources now project real light through the cave darkness (the torch "isn't emitting any light"). Root cause: drawTorch's warm glow is painted INSIDE the world pass, but the silk-cavern darkness (renderSilkCavernAtmosphere) is a full-screen overlay drawn AFTER the world, so it covered the torch's little glow and the torch read as unlit. FIX: (1) drawTorch (render/object-renderer.js) now registers each visible torch as a light source in game._silkFrameLights (its unzoomed screen pos + colour); game.js render() resets that list each frame before the world draw. (2) renderSilkCavernAtmosphere darkens the cave a bit more (tint 0.4->0.52, vignette 0.55->0.66 so it reads pitch-black away from light) and then adds a LIGHT PASS after the darkening: each torch projects a warm, gently flickering pool (additive 'lighter' radial gradient - bright amber core to orange falloff), projected from unzoomed screen space through the live camera zoom so the pools track pan/zoom; the player also gets a much dimmer warm light so your party isn't standing in pitch black with no torch nearby. Net effect: a dark, enclosed cave with torches punching warm pools of light out of the black. Gated to the silk cavern (where the darkness overlay lives). Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a captured render over a mock cave floor confirms bright warm torch pools (centre luminance ~161, warm r>g>b) against dark surroundings (~28-41) with a subtle player light (~86). See docs/V0.18.64_TORCH_LIGHT.md.
// V0.18.63: wall CUT-AWAY (walls still covered the party) + bard 5-song cap. (1) WALLS OVER ACTORS: V0.18.62's depth-sort tweak wasn't enough - tall cave walls (elev ~5 = ~140px) still drew over the player/mercs/pets/bots because those actors were genuinely at lower depth than the wall in front of them (correct iso occlusion, but the user wants their party visible). New render/terrain-renderer.js computeCaveWallCutaways() scans the friendly party each frame (projection-based, so it works at every camera yaw) and marks the cave-wall tiles whose tall body would draw OVER a friendly (wall in front + within its ~140px screen reach + horizontal overlap); drawCaveWallDepthOccluder now early-returns for those tiles, so it SKIPS the occluder redraw and the wall stays painted only by the base terrain pass (BEHIND the actors) - the party is fully visible in front of the wall instead of being covered by its corner/face. Wired into game.js render() as this._caveWallCutaways before the world draw loop. Enemies are NOT cut away (they stay hidden behind walls). (2) BARD SONGS: systems/spell-system.js applyBardMajorSongLimit raised the max concurrent major songs from 2 to 5 (MAX_ACTIVE_MAJOR_SONGS) so a bard can keep 5 songs active at once. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a before/after showcase confirms party members previously hidden behind a wall are now visible; a rotation sweep (yaw 0/45/90/135/180/270) confirms the cut-away tracks the camera-front walls at every angle and leaves behind/far walls alone; 12 bard spells carry majorSong so the 5-cap applies. See docs/V0.18.63_WALL_CUTAWAY_BARD_SONGS.md.
// V0.18.62: silk depth/occlusion fixes (last of the user's list: "webs should not render over the top of the walls also the wall corners shouldnt render over the top of players, mobs, pets etc"). (1) WEBS OVER WALL TOPS: render/terrain-renderer.js drawSilkCavernWallWebs now CLIPS every web on a wall to that face's quad (a per-face ctx.clip to ta,tb,bb,ba). The silk sheet, drape strands, cross-weave, binding threads, corner orb webs and the variety-a "curtain" (which used to hang ~32px past the face bottom) can no longer spill ABOVE the top edge onto the wall/ledge top or BELOW onto the ledge/floor in front - in the user's tiered cave the drapes were caking every wall/ledge TOP; now silk stays strictly on the vertical faces. (2) WALL CORNERS OVER ENTITIES: (a) terrain-renderer caveWallOcclusionDepth dropped the old "+ 0.38" forward bias - it pushed the wall's depth-sort anchor ~0.38 units PAST its own frontmost top corner, so a cave wall reached out and drew its corner/face over players/mercs/pets/mobs standing at or just in front of its front face; the bare front-corner anchor still covers everything genuinely behind the wall by a huge margin. (b) game.js render drawOrder now ranks caveOccluder (1.9) BELOW entity (2, was 2.35 ABOVE it) so on an exact depth tie the ACTOR wins and draws on top - walls/corners no longer paint over an actor hugging the wall's front face (depth still dominates: an actor genuinely behind stays occluded; occluder still ranks above objects/terrain so it keeps covering props/ground behind the wall). Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a captured showcase confirms the wall webs stay on the face (wall top + floor in front clean); a faithful depth-sort test confirms behind-actors stay hidden while front/hugging/tie actors now win. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see the web-clip (occlusion is immediate). See docs/V0.18.62_DEPTH_WEB_FIXES.md.
// V0.18.61: silk visuals (part 2 of the user's list). (1) GROUND WEB REDESIGN + 30s VANISH: render/object-renderer.js drawWebHazard (the "Thick Webbing" ground traps the user reads as spider shots) is rebuilt as a real ORB WEB splat - an iso-squashed radial-spoke + capture-spiral + silk-bead web on the ground (tears + rising puffs on break, a countdown ring when triggered) instead of concentric-ellipse ripples; and systems/dungeon-system.js updateSilkWebControlObjects now stamps a vanishAt (now+30000) on each web and removes it (row[x]=null) ~30s after it appears if it hasn't been triggered/broken. (2) EGG PILES: new drawEggPile (object type eggPile) - a silk-nest mound of varied-size spider eggs, some hatched (a torn husk + dark hole + a hatchling), draped in webbing with 1-2 guard spiders crawling on it; large + small sizes, royal (pink) on floor 3, position-seeded for variety; placeSilkCeilingWebsAndJunk scatters large ones in brood/egg rooms + open caverns and small ones elsewhere. (3) NATURAL CAVE STAIRS: drawDungeonStairs now routes the silk cavern to a new drawCaveStairs - rough hewn stone treads + shadowed risers (irregular, position-jittered) descending into a dark radial-gradient cave mouth, flanked by rock shoulders and draped cobwebs, replacing the old flat parallelogram steps + "DOWN" label. Still queued: the wall depth-occluder drawing over entities and webs drawing over wall tops. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a captured showcase confirms the orb-web hazard, the varied large/small/royal egg piles, and the natural cave stairs. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.61_WEBS_EGGS_STAIRS.md.
// V0.18.60: fixes + polish (part 1 of the user's larger list). (1) DARKNESS OVERLAY GLITCH: game.renderSilkCavernAtmosphere (render/object-renderer.js) sized its full-screen tint/vignette/fog with canvas.width/height (DEVICE pixels), which mismatched the dpr-scaled ctx transform, so when zoomed the darkness only covered part of the screen. Now sized with window.innerWidth/innerHeight (CSS pixels), exactly like drawVignette - full coverage at any zoom. (2) TORCH: drawTorch is ~40% smaller (wrapped in translate(s)+scale(0.62)) and the flame animation is smoother/gentler - a lower-amplitude 3-sine flicker at a slower rate, softer sway + spark speed. (3) TITLE CARD: entering/descending the Silk Web Cavern (loadDungeonFloor sets game.dungeonTitleCard) now pops a big centered "Silk Web Caverns" title (serif, glow, rule) that scales in and fades out ~2s later - drawn in renderSilkCavernAtmosphere. (4) BUG: click-to-move ignored ROOT (keyboard movement already respected it). setClickMoveTarget now rejects + logs "You are rooted." when rooted, and updateClickToWalk stops an in-progress click-move the moment root is applied. Still queued from the request: spider-web-shot redesign + 30s expiry, better/varied egg piles, natural cave stairs, and the wall-over-entity / webs-over-wall depth fixes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; render tests confirm the smaller torch + the atmosphere darkening the full screen (corner 200->83, centre 123) + the title card, and the two click-move root guards are present. See docs/V0.18.60_FIXES_POLISH.md.
// V0.18.59: Silk Web Caverns - stalactite + size variety, and a dark/foggy "night" (user request). (1) STALAGMITE VARIETY: render/object-renderer.js drawCaveStalagmite rebuilt around a shared tapered-spike helper that works UP or DOWN, so it now supports 5 size tiers (xs/small/medium/large/xl - width+height tables) for both GROUND stalagmites and hanging ceiling STALACTITES (obj.hang -> anchored ~200px above the tile, pointing down), plus the floor-to-ceiling 'column'. systems/dungeon-system.js placeSilkCeilingWebsAndJunk scatters all five ground sizes + columns AND a fringe of hanging stalactites (xs/small/medium/large) in every room, and the tunnel pass drops both ground stalagmites and hanging stalactites along the corridors. (2) NIGHT + GROUND FOG: new game.renderSilkCavernAtmosphere(ctx) (render/object-renderer.js), called from game.js right before drawVignette - only in the silk_web_cavern it lays a cool dark tint (rgba(8,6,16,0.4)) + a radial vignette (to rgba(3,2,9,0.55)) over the whole view so the cave reads as night/enclosed, then draws a slight layer of pale fog (8 soft wisps, screen blend) slowly drifting across the lower/mid screen. No gameplay changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a captured showcase confirms the graduated ground stalagmite sizes (xs..xl), the hanging stalactites (xs..large) + the webbed column, and a pixel test confirms the atmosphere darkens the view in the cavern (200->85) and is a no-op elsewhere. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see the stalactites (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.59_STALACTITES_NIGHT_FOG.md.
// V0.18.58: a real TORCH + way more stalagmites (user request from a screenshot). (1) TORCH: render/object-renderer.js drawTorch was a brown line topped by a solid yellow triangle (via fillPoly) that read as an upward ARROW/cursor, not a torch. Rebuilt as an actual torch: a tapered wooden handle with a grain-shadow, a dark pitch-soaked wrapped head with 3 binding bands + charred embers, a soft warm radial glow, a 3-layer flickering FLAME (outer orange #ff5f18 / mid amber #ffb43c / inner bright #ffe9a8, teardrop beziers that sway with a 2-sine flicker), and rising sparks; drawn with a contact shadow. (2) STALAGMITES: placeSilkCeilingWebsAndJunk (systems/dungeon-system.js) now scatters WAY more caveStalagmite - small big?6:3 (was big?2:1), large big?3:1 in EVERY room (was big-only x1), floor-to-ceiling column big?4:2 in every room (was big-only x1), some silk-draped; and the tunnel pass now also drops stalagmites (incl. columns) along the corridors on their own lattice. drawCaveStalagmite gained a tile-position seed fallback so the many new stalagmites vary instead of all sharing seed=1. No gameplay changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a captured showcase confirms the torch reads as a torch (handle + wrapped head + layered flame + glow) and the stalagmite small/large/column/webbed variants render + vary. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see the stalagmites (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.58_TORCH_MORE_STALAGMITES.md.
// V0.18.57: Silk Web Caverns - way more + thicker floor-to-ceiling webs, plus a MASSIVE "everything" web lair (user request). (1) MORE + THICKER COLUMNS: placeSilkCeilingWebsAndJunk columnCount raised ~30% (minimal 4->5, big 9->12, pocket 3->4, else 6->8) and the tunnel-column pass is denser (lattice %8 -> %6); the thick bias is raised so ~half the columns are thick (c%2 with a lower room-size gate), and render/object-renderer.js drawCeilingWebColumn thick spread 2.7 -> 3.2 so thick columns are SUPER-thick (~3.5 tiles wide). (2) GREAT WEB LAIR: new drawGiantWebLair (object type giantWebLair) - a massive ~300px-tall floor-to-ceiling web with a huge silk sheet, sagging scaffold + capture threads, MANY embedded orb webs, 3 web nests, ~24 egg sacs, 6 bone clusters, 5 cocooned bodies, 3 webbed stalagmite columns (via drawCaveStalagmite) inside it, ~26 animated crawling tiny spiders, and a big matriarch spider with glowing eyes in the centre. placeSilkCeilingWebsAndJunk places ONE per floor in the biggest non-safe/non-boss/non-treasure room. No gameplay changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a captured showcase confirms the super-thick columns + the massive lair (nests + spiders + bones + eggs + stalagmites + cocoons + matriarch); the lair routes through the in-game object dispatch. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.57_MORE_WEBS_GREAT_LAIR.md.
// V0.18.56: Silk Web Caverns - the hanging web columns (and piles/nests) are now RANDOMLY MIXED (user: "all those need to have varieties, they can have any of those things, 1 thing, 2 things, mixed... randomly make them all mixed"). Two parts, render/object-renderer.js. (1) INDEPENDENT FEATURE ROLLS: drawCeilingWebColumn no longer gives every thick column the same full set. Each of the 5 extras now rolls independently (egg sacs >0.42, web nest >0.62, base bones >0.5, a cocooned body >0.5, crawling spiders >0.25), regardless of size, so a column can carry none, one, two, or all of them in any mix. Sizes scale to the column (small columns get lighter versions). (2) DISTINCT SEEDS (bug fix that made the variety actually visible): columns/piles/nests are placed WITHOUT a _propSeed, so their `st = obj._propSeed || 1` collapsed to 1 -> every instance shared one random sequence and looked identical. drawCeilingWebColumn, drawWebbedBonePile, drawWebJunkPile and drawGiantSpiderNest now fall back to a tile-position seed (floor(obj.x)*374761 + floor(obj.y)*668265 + k) when _propSeed is absent, so each instance is unique. The tunnel-column placement (systems/dungeon-system.js) now stamps x,y on its objects so those get position seeds too. No gameplay changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a captured showcase of 8 unseeded columns at different tile positions shows 8 DIFFERENT feature mixes. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.56_COLUMN_VARIETY.md.
// V0.18.55: Silk Web Caverns cleanup + richer hanging web columns (user request from a screenshot). (1) REMOVED the ugly geometric webs: the 'webCurtain' (a rectangular net grid), 'heavyWebCurtain' and 'silkStrands' (sparse hanging curtains/fans) are now rejected centrally in placeSilkObject (systems/dungeon-system.js) so none of their ~13 placement sites emit them; their draw functions remain for any other zone. (2) FLOOR SPIDER SPEED: updateSilkCritters movement speed 1.15 -> 0.5 tiles/s (they were scurrying too fast); the walk-gait phase scales with speed so the legs step slower to match. (3) MORE + RICHER COLUMNS: placeSilkCeilingWebsAndJunk columnCount raised (minimal 3->4, big 6->9, pocket 2->3, else 4->6); render/object-renderer.js drawCeilingWebColumn now adds tiny spiders crawling UP+DOWN the column (animated, facing their travel), a BODY cocooned in the silk (new drawWebCocoon - a silk-wrapped bundle with wrap bands + a dark face-gap, on thick always / medium sometimes), bones at the base extended to medium columns, on top of the existing egg sacs and web nest. drawWebJunkPile and drawWebbedBonePile also get tiny spiders crawling over them. No gameplay changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a captured showcase confirms the columns carry cocoon + crawling spiders + bones + eggs and the piles have crawlers, and the placeSilkObject filter drops the removed types. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.55_WEB_CLEANUP_RICH_COLUMNS.md.
// V0.18.54: Silk Web Caverns - the tiny spiders CRAWL like spiders now (user: "the tiny spiders just spin around in circles on the walls instead of crawling", "the spiders on the floor slide around instead of crawling"). ROOT CAUSE: drawTinySpider (render/object-renderer.js) drew a STATIC pose, so any translation looked like sliding; and the wall spiders were rotated by a continuous time term (spinning) on a sinusoidal loop path. FIXES: (1) drawTinySpider gains a walkPhase param -> a stepping alternating-tetrapod LEG GAIT (each of the 8 legs swings fore/aft + lifts, out of phase) plus a slight body bob; walkPhase 0 = a natural static pose so non-animated callers are unchanged. (2) FLOOR crawlers: dungeonSystem.updateSilkCritters advances a per-critter c.walk phase ONLY while it actually moves, and renderSilkCritters passes it - so the legs step as it crawls and hold still when idle (no more sliding); it already faced its velocity. (3) WALL spiders (render/terrain-renderer.js): rewritten to WALK back and forth across the web (a ping-pong triangle-wave sweep), FACING their direction of travel (derived from the web ta->tb across-angle, flipped at the turn) with the stepping gait - no more spinning in place. (4) NEST spiders: pass a walkPhase so their legs step while they orbit. No gameplay changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a captured showcase confirms the legs step through the gait cycle and the spiders orient to their heading. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.54_SPIDER_CRAWL_GAIT.md.
// V0.18.53: Silk Web Caverns - CRASH FIX (stepping on ground spiders) + more webs/spiders (user report). (1) CRASH FIX: squishing a floor critter threw "CanvasRenderingContext2D.ellipse: Negative radius" and faulted the whole render. ROOT CAUSE: dungeonSystem.updateSilkCritters stamps c.deadAt with nowMs() = Date.now() (a ~1.7e12 epoch value), but game.renderSilkCritters (render/object-renderer.js) computed the splat fade k against performance.now() (ms since load, small); performance.now() - Date.now() is hugely negative -> k negative -> (0.7 + k*0.5) negative -> a NEGATIVE ellipse radius on the squish splat. Fixed by using Date.now() in renderSilkCritters to match, plus a defensive Math.max(0, ...) clamp on k. (2) MORE GROUND SPIDERS: spawnSilkCritters cap raised (F1 26->50, F2 30->56, F3 34->62) so there are more to step on. (3) WEBS EVERYWHERE: placeSilkCeilingWebsAndJunk now places floor-to-ceiling web columns in EVERY room - the safe-entry + treasure rooms get a lighter set (webs only, no gore) instead of being skipped - AND a new tunnel pass drops columns along the corridors (walkable CAVE_FLOOR tiles outside every room, on a sparse lattice), so no passage is bare. No other gameplay changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a render test that reproduces the exact squish path (dead critter, deadAt = Date.now()) no longer throws. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.53_SQUISH_CRASH_FIX_MORE_WEBS.md.
// V0.18.52: Silk Web Caverns - the web COLUMNS rebuilt to look like real spider webs + faster crawlers (user: "these webs need to be revamped to look like real spider webs or just removed", "spiders move too slow"). (1) COLUMNS (render/object-renderer.js drawCeilingWebColumn): the woven-NET node grid (which still read as a rectangular fishing net however much it was jittered) is REMOVED entirely and replaced with a vertical STACK of real ORB WEBS (thick 3 / medium 2 / small 1) - each a proper orb (radial spokes + a dense capture spiral + frame ring via drawOrbWeb) - hung on an organic scaffold: a few sagging spine strands running floor -> each orb hub -> ceiling, plus jittered guy-lines from each orb frame out to the edges. drawOrbWeb's spiral now scales with radius (bigger orbs get ~4.6 turns + finer steps) so the big column orbs stay dense. The translucent silk sheet, ceiling fan, floor pool, egg sacs, web nest and base bones are kept. (2) CRAWLER SPEED: the animated wall spiders (render/terrain-renderer.js) and nest spiders (drawGiantSpiderNest) had their time multipliers raised ~3-4x so they visibly crawl. No layout/config/gameplay changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a captured showcase confirms the columns now read as stacked orb webs (no net grid), and a two-sample pixel test confirms the faster crawl still animates. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.52_ORB_WEB_COLUMNS.md.
// V0.18.51: Silk Web Caverns - cleanup + living spiders (user request from screenshots). (1) REMOVED two props the user flagged: the 'pitShadow' (a large flat black radial-gradient circle that sat on the floor and read as a weird hole - its placement in placeSilkStructuredObjectives' signature_bridge role is deleted) and the 'stalactiteCluster' (4 tan/yellow downward triangles hung from the ceiling in web_choke/gate/bridge rooms - its add() is deleted). Both draw functions remain (used elsewhere); only the silk-cavern placement is removed. (2) ANIMATED the decorative tiny spiders so they slowly crawl instead of sitting frozen: render/object-renderer.js drawGiantSpiderNest's on-nest spiders now orbit the nest at per-spider slow speeds/directions with slight radial breathing and face their motion; render/terrain-renderer.js drawSilkCavernWallWebs variety (c) wall spiders now drift across + up/down the web face and slowly turn. Both passes run every frame (the nest is an object draw; the wall webs are drawn in the per-frame depth-occluder pass), so the performance.now()-driven motion animates live. No layout/config/gameplay changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; two-sample pixel-diff tests confirm both the nest spiders and the wall spiders move over time. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.51_CLEANUP_LIVING_SPIDERS.md.
// V0.18.50: Silk Web Caverns - the floor webs + web columns read as ORGANIC silk instead of a geometric mesh (you sent a screenshot showing the webs still looked triangulated / grid-like). Two render tweaks, no new systems. (1) FLOOR (render/terrain-renderer.js drawSilkWebCavernSurfaceDetails): the bright silk junction beads (which read as the dotted vertices of a mesh) are cut way down - sparse + dim at anchor knots, and the orb web's ring of junction dots is dropped for just a soft centre bead; the orb's straight radial spokes are dimmed/thinned and the curved capture spiral is made denser (~3 turns) + brighter so the soft coil, not the star-spokes, is what reads. (2) COLUMNS (render/object-renderer.js drawCeilingWebColumn): the net node grid jitter is raised (x 0.16->0.44 of width, y 7->13) so the cells are IRREGULAR (a spun web) rather than a rectangular fishing-net grid, and the embedded orb-web count is raised (thick 2->3, medium 1->2, small 0->1) with the node beads made sparse+dim, so the orb webs dominate. No layout/config/gameplay/other-file changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; a captured contiguous-floor + columns showcase confirms the softer, more organic look. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.50_ORGANIC_WEBS.md.
// V0.18.49: Silk Web Caverns "spiders live here" pass PART 2 (completes the request). (1) WALL-WEB VARIETIES - render/terrain-renderer.js drawSilkCavernWallWebs now picks a per-wall-tile variety (hash2D seed 9190) on top of the base silk sheeting: (a) a heavy web curtain that stretches DOWN below the wall face to the floor in front of it, (b) a web hung with clustered egg sacs, or (c) a web with 1-3 tiny spiders crawling on it (via this.drawTinySpider) - so the walls read differently tile-to-tile instead of a uniform drape. (2) FREE-ROAMING AMBIENT SPIDERS - a new lightweight, purely-cosmetic critter system (NOT enemies: no AI/HP/combat/threat, not in game.enemies/entities). spawnSilkCritters (systems/dungeon-system.js, called from generateSilkWebCavernFloor) seeds ~26-34 crawlers on walkable floor tiles into game.silkCritters; dungeonSystem.updateSilkCritters(dt) (wired into the dungeon update loop) wanders them on the floor (random walk, bounces off walls) and SQUISHES any that a friendly actor [player, merc, pet, ...botPlayers] steps on (within 0.42 tiles) - the squished one dies with a brief splat then is culled; game.renderSilkCritters (render/object-renderer.js, called from game.js right after renderSilkWebFloorOverlay so party members walk visibly OVER them) draws each live crawler via drawTinySpider and dead ones as a fading splat. Critters are cleared on leaving the cavern and regenerated each floor entry. No layout/config/enemy changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; render smoke tests + a captured showcase confirm the wall varieties + crawlers/splat, and unit tests confirm squish-on-step and floor-bounded wander. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.49_WALL_WEBS_AMBIENT_SPIDERS.md.
// V0.18.48: Silk Web Caverns "spiders live here" pass (PART 1 of the request; wall-web varieties + free-roaming squishable ambient spiders come next). (1) TINY EGG/BABY SPIDERS - ROOT CAUSE: the spider sprite cache (render/entity-renderer.js) keyed by a coarse xs/s/m/xl bucket and BAKED modelScale into one shared bitmap per bucket, so a 0.32 hatchling and a 0.5 skitterer both landed in 'xs' and the first cached size won - i.e. shrinking a baby's modelScale did NOTHING. The cache now keys by QUANTIZED modelScale (0.1 steps) so each size gets its own baked bitmap; egg hatchlings (makeBabySpider) dropped 0.46->0.32 and the filler baby/little variants 0.46/0.66 -> 0.34/0.5, so babies actually render tiny. (2) FLOOR WEBS (render/terrain-renderer.js drawSilkWebCavernSurfaceDetails) - the rigid corner-to-corner truss (which tiled into a geometric triangle grid) was replaced with an IRREGULAR woven cobweb: threads run between jittered INTERIOR anchors (not shared tile corners) and sag like draped silk, and the woven orb web now appears on more tiles - so the floor reads as organic spider silk, not a geodesic mesh. (3) CAVE DRESSING (render/object-renderer.js + placeSilkCeilingWebsAndJunk) - new drawCaveRocks (little rocks, some webbed), drawCaveStalagmite (size small/large/column = floor-to-ceiling, obj.webbed drapes silk), scattered so the caverns feel like a real cave. (4) GIANT SPIDER NESTS - new drawGiantSpiderNest (a big domed silk mass, a dark mouth with a big spider + glowing eyes lurking inside, egg sacs, and tiny spiders crawling all over it via new drawTinySpider) placed in the big caverns + brood/nest rooms. New object types caveRocks/caveStalagmite/giantSpiderNest in the object dispatch. No layout/config/gameplay changes beyond the spider scale tweaks. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; render smoke tests + captured showcases confirm tiny spiders, woven floor webs, stalagmites/rocks, and the giant nests. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.48_SPIDERS_LIVE_HERE.md.
// V0.18.47: Silk Web Caverns - the floor-to-ceiling web COLUMNS now actually look like spider webs (user: they "still do not look like spider webs, it looks too stringy like white lines, theres no web design to it at all"). render/object-renderer.js drawCeilingWebColumn was a bundle of near-parallel vertical strands (hence "stringy"); it is REBUILT as a proper woven NET - a jittered node grid connected by vertical radial threads + horizontal capture threads (with catenary sag) + a diagonal weave, forming irregular web cells - with ONE-TO-TWO embedded ORB WEBS (new reusable drawOrbWeb: radial spokes tied by a real capture spiral + frame ring + centre bead = the unmistakable spider-web shape), bright silk junction beads at the nodes, a ceiling anchor fan, and a translucent silk sheet behind it (thick/medium). The V0.18.46 nest (drawWebNest), egg sacs and base bones are kept on the thick columns; sizes still thick/medium/small. Threads are batched into per-family paths for perf. No layout/config/other-render changes. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; render smoke tests pass + a captured showcase confirmed the columns now read as webs (net cells + orb webs), not strings. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.47_SILK_WEB_COLUMNS.md.
// V0.18.46: Silk Web Caverns WEB VISUAL OVERHAUL (4 new environmental items; the V0.18.45 hazard/bugfix items ship unchanged). (1) WEB VISUAL OVERHAUL - render/terrain-renderer.js drawSilkWebCavernSurfaceDetails: the per-tile floor orb-web is now a real WOVEN orb (iso-squashed radial spokes tied together by a genuine capture spiral instead of concentric rings, with bright silk junction beads) and the front lattice is thicker/denser + beaded; render/object-renderer.js drawCeilingWebColumn adds a diagonal cross-weave + junction beads so the floor-to-ceiling columns read as woven, not parallel threads. (2) CEILING WEB NESTS - new drawWebNest (concentric woven rings + radial spokes + a dark funnel mouth + clustered egg sacs) bulges partway up every thick column (and occasionally medium ones), adding depth + an active-infestation focal point. (3) WEBBED BONE PILES - new drawWebbedBonePile ('large' | 'small') built from new recognizable bone primitives (drawBoneSkull = cranium + eye sockets + jaw + teeth; drawBoneFemur = bowed shaft with knobbed epiphyses; drawBoneRibs = spine + curved ribs; composed by drawBonesCluster) heavily wrapped in webbing; the old drawWebJunkPile's squiggle-bones were replaced with the same primitives. (4) WEB COLUMNS & MIXED CLUTTER - placeSilkCeilingWebsAndJunk (systems/dungeon-system.js) scatters webbedBonePile objects across every non-safe room (large in the big caverns, small everywhere) and the thick columns tangle a webbed bone cluster at their base, so caverns + tunnels feel overwhelmingly infested. New object type 'webbedBonePile' added to the object-renderer dispatch. No layout/config changes; existing systems preserved. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; 14/14 isolated render smoke tests pass + a captured showcase render confirmed the look. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.46_SILK_WEB_VISUAL_OVERHAUL.md.
// V0.18.45: Silk Web Caverns "Bug Fixes & Updates" pass (5-item request). (1) WEB DENSITY & VARIETY - placeSilkCeilingWebsAndJunk now scatters MORE floor-to-ceiling web columns per room of VARIED sizes; render/object-renderer.js drawCeilingWebColumn honours obj.webSize ('thick' = an extremely dense ~3-tile-wide silk curtain on a filled sheet with extra egg sacs; 'small' = a thin wisp; 'medium' = the original), so caverns read as truly infested. (2) EGG-SPAWNED BABY SPIDERS - placeSilkNestEggs tags ~half the eggs as babyEgg ("Twitching Spider Egg" / "Twitching Royal Egg"); smashSpiderEgg guarantees those hatch and spawnBabySpidersFromEgg now takes {aggressive} -> the babies get aggro + a target + a wider leash so they crawl out and immediately attack. (3) DESCENDING SPIDER MODEL (was invisible: bots attacked nothing) - ROOT CAUSE was that runtime-spawned enemies were pushed only to enemies/dungeonEnemies (the AI list) but NOT to game.entities (the render snapshot from setActiveEnemySet), so they were AI-active but never drawn. New registerRuntimeSilkEnemy(game, add) pushes to all three lists; applied to makeBabySpider (covers the ceiling dropper) and the boss summon_adds. (4) DESCENDING SPIDER FREQUENCY - silkDropTick reset raised to 60 + rand*75 (~1-2.25 min between drops, was ~13-29s) and the ambient dropper cap lowered to 2 (was 4), so drops stay impactful. (5) BOSS ENTRANCE SEAL OVERHAUL - startSilkBossRoomSeal now sweeps the FULL entrance cross-section wall-to-wall (every open tile across the throat, 4 tiles deep) with no fixed +-5 band, so there are no edge gaps to slip through; drawBossWebSeal is taller (floor-to-ceiling) and wider so neighbouring seal tiles overlap into one giant continuous web; and updateBossSeal now waits for playerFullyInsideSilkBossArena (player past the outer ring, ~68% margin) before sealing, so it only triggers once you have FULLY entered - no more sealing at the threshold then slipping back out. No layout/config changes; all existing systems preserved. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors. RE-ENTER / descend the Silk Web Cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.45_SILK_INFESTATION_HAZARDS.md.
// V0.18.44: Silk Web Caverns FLOORS 2 & 3 rebuilt to match the floor-plan reference (completes the layout rebuild started for Floor 1 in V0.18.43; user said "continue"). systems/dungeon-system.js SILK_WEB_FLOOR_CONFIG[2] and [3] rewritten as the plan's flow. FLOOR 2 (9 rooms): Deep Descent -> Echoing Cavern -> Webbed Alcove (mini-boss: The Cocoon Tender) -> Underground Pool (large cavern + water pool + safe camp) -> Nesting Grounds (mini-boss: Pale Spinner Yssra) -> Sealed Silk Gate -> Chasm Overlook (boss: Matron Velyra) -> descent; Collapsed Chasm Ledge dead end off the pool; both mini-bosses gate the boss. FLOOR 3 (8 rooms): Royal Web Descent -> Silk Cocoon Hall (mini-boss: Chitinmaw) -> The Great Nest (huge central cavern) -> Brood Nursery (mini-boss: Widow of the Loom) -> The Chitin Gauntlet (gate) -> Matriarch's Lair (boss: Queen Arakh'Zel, with a broodpool) -> exit thread; Silk-Choked Hollow dead end off the Great Nest. To match the plan's "2 mini-bosses" on Floor 3, F3 dropped from 3 mini-bosses to 2 (Chitinmaw + Widow of the Loom) and SILK_WEB_GATE_REQUIREMENTS[3] was updated to require just those two so the gauntlet gate still opens. Water pools carve into rooms tagged 'underground_pool' (F2 Underground Pool, F3 Matriarch's Lair broodpool). Existing boss ids / puzzle ids / valid mini-boss draft ids all preserved; every room is on a connected path. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; all THREE floors' room-ids + reachability validated programmatically (no orphaned refs; every room reachable from the entrance; bosses, descents and gates present). RE-ENTER / descend to walk the new Floors 2 & 3 (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.44_SILK_FLOOR23_LAYOUT.md.
// V0.18.43: Silk Web Caverns FLOOR 1 rebuilt to match the user's floor-plan reference (user chose "Floor 1 first, then 2 & 3" - so this ships Floor 1 for playtest before Floors 2 & 3 get the same treatment). systems/dungeon-system.js SILK_WEB_FLOOR_CONFIG[1] rewritten as the plan's left-to-right flow: Lantern-Safe Entry Alcove (entrance + safe camp) -> Webbed Tunnels -> Spider Cavern (large, underground pool) -> {Web Bridge Room, Egg Sacs Chamber} -> Sealed Web Gate -> Broodmother Arachnis Den (BOSS) -> Silk Descent Drop (stairs down); the Broodwarden Approach off the bridge holds the single mini-boss (Threadjaw Alpha), whose death opens the gate to the boss, and a Collapsed Silk Pocket hangs off the egg chamber as a dead end. Reachability is guaranteed by construction (verified: all 10 rooms reachable from the entrance, boss + descent reachable). Supporting changes so the plan renders right: carveSilkWebFishingPools is now tag-aware (pools carve in rooms tagged 'underground_pool' - so the F1 pool lands in Spider Cavern - with the old index-based placement as fallback for untagged floors), and the boss-room web seal (startSilkBossRoomSeal) now derives the sealed entrance from the boss room's non-treasure link neighbour instead of a hardcoded room id, so it works for the new layout. Narrow tunnels + pocket caverns from V0.18.41 apply. Floors 2 & 3 still use their existing layout pending playtest of Floor 1. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; F1 room-id + reachability validated programmatically. RE-ENTER the cavern (floors regenerate on entry) to walk the new Floor 1. See docs/V0.18.43_SILK_FLOOR1_LAYOUT.md.
// V0.18.42: Silk Web Cavern boss mechanics - entrance web-seal + attack telegraphs (user: "the first floor boss, upon entering the boss room, we need 3 spiders to walk to the entrance of the boss room and web up the entire entrance so the player can't leave until the boss is dead. This needs to be fully animated. We also need the boss + miniboss attacks to show up as indicators with red visual markings on the ground where it will strike"). (1) BOSS-ROOM WEB SEAL (systems/dungeon-system.js dungeonSystem.updateBossSeal + startSilkBossRoomSeal / placeSilkSealBarrier / unsealSilkBossRoom): when the FLOOR-1 boss first engages, 3 spiders (animated silkSealCrawler effects, dragging silk) scuttle from the boss to the room entrance over ~2.6s, then spin it shut - blocking 'bossWebSeal' barrier objects are placed across the entrance tiles (map.blocked = true + solid objects) that grow in over ~1.2s (render/object-renderer.js drawBossWebSeal, a floor-to-ceiling silk curtain with an orb web), trapping the player until the boss dies, at which point the seal tears apart and the tiles are restored. Defensive: the barrier only sits on the entrance chokepoint toward skirr_approach, and unseal only restores tiles that still hold OUR seal, so a regenerated floor can't be corrupted. (2) ATTACK TELEGRAPHS: the boss/miniboss damaging ground abilities (castSilkWebBossAbility) no longer hit instantly - they queue a delayed strike (queueSilkBossStrike / updateSilkBossStrikes, ~0.8-0.95s) and spawn a RED ground danger marker (render/effects-renderer.js drawBossGroundTelegraphEffect - a filling red ellipse + pulsing boundary ring + hazard ticks) showing exactly where the AoE lands; the strike then applies damage/poison/web in-radius with a bossStrikeHit flash. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; the telegraph/strike/crawler effects and the bossWebSeal draw all render without faults; updateBossSeal wired into the dungeon update. The full seal sequence + telegraph->strike need an in-dungeon boss fight to eyeball. See docs/V0.18.42_BOSS_SEAL_TELEGRAPHS.md.
// V0.18.41: Silk Web Cavern layout + population revamp (user: "revamp the layout - small narrow tunnels leading into small caverns, with more tunnels into large caverns/rooms; more spiders - baby, big, little, plus elites; floors need more webs; webs stretching from the floor up to the cave ceiling; big piles of webs with junk all webbed up - armor, weapons and bones"). (1) NARROW TUNNELS (systems/dungeon-system.js carveCorridor): now takes a radius - main corridors carve at radius 2 (~5-wide) instead of the old fixed ~7-wide hall, so the layout reads as tunnels. (2) POCKET CAVERNS (carveSilkPocketCaverns): branches small/medium dead-end caverns off the combat rooms via radius-1 (~3-wide) NARROW tunnels, only carving into dead rock (>80% wall footprint) so they can never break boss/gate/objective reachability; they are registered as rooms so they get webbed, dressed and populated. (3) MORE SPIDERS (makeSilkSpiderVariant + spawnSilkExtraSpiders): on top of the authored elite packs, each combat room + pocket now gets size-varied FILLER spiders - tiny babies (modelScale 0.46), little skitterers (0.66) and tanky big broodmothers (1.34) - capped per floor (40/48/54) and placement-limited. render/entity-renderer.js now buckets the spider sprite-cache key by size (xs/s/m/xl) so each size renders distinctly instead of inheriting the full-grown sprite. (4) FLOOR-TO-CEILING WEBS + JUNK PILES (placeSilkCeilingWebsAndJunk + render/object-renderer.js): new 'ceilingWebColumn' (a thick silk column of strands fanning floor-to-ceiling with rung threads + a clinging egg sac) and 'webJunkPile' (a web mound with a shield, a sword, ribs and a skull cocooned in silk), scattered through the rooms. Floors keep the V0.18.40 dense web overlay. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; new render objects draw without faults; sprite size-bucketing loaded. RE-ENTER the cavern (floors regenerate on entry) to see the new layout, spiders and webbing. See docs/V0.18.41_SILK_LAYOUT_POPULATION.md.
// V0.18.40: Silk Web Cavern floor webs FINALLY render + walls made heavier (user, again: "the floors still aren't covered in webs and the walls still look like shit. the dungeon still doesn't feel like a spider home"). ROOT CAUSE the V0.18.37/38 floor webbing never actually drew: the Silk Web Cavern floor is CHUNKED terrain (render/terrain-renderer.js isTerrainChunkGroundTile === true for CAVE_FLOOR), so drawTile runs those tiles in 'depth-underlay'/'occlusion-cap' mode and RETURNS before the per-tile surface-detail hook (drawSilkWebCavernSurfaceDetails at the bottom of drawTile) - so the dense floor mat added in V0.18.37/38 was dead code for the actual floor. Only the WALLS showed web (they render via the separate drawCaveWallDepthOccluder pass, which is not chunk-bypassed). FIX (1): new render/terrain-renderer.js renderSilkWebFloorOverlay(minX,maxX,minY,maxY) - a dedicated pass that iterates the visible silk CAVE_FLOOR tiles and draws the woven-silk mat directly over the (chunk-cached) terrain every frame; wired into game.js right after the terrain passes and before the entity/object pass (same slot as the V0.18.34 resource ground layer). Gated to currentZone==='dungeon' && silk_web_cavern. Verified in-browser: with a faked silk-cavern zone + a 5x5 silk floor it drew ~25229 web px. FIX (2): drawSilkCavernWallWebs made much heavier - a top-weighted gradient silk SHEET, 14 thick vertical drapes, a diagonal CROSS-WEAVE, 6 horizontal binding threads, dangling beads and orb webs in BOTH top corners (verified ~9383 px for 2 faces, was ~5773) so the walls read as caked in web, not lightly draped. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors. RE-ENTER the cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.40_SILK_FLOOR_WEBS_RENDER.md.
// V0.18.39: Silk Web Cavern ENTRANCE fix + overhaul (user: "once you walk into the entrance you should teleport inside. Right now you walk in and then you have to walk back before it triggers"; "the entire cave entrance needs a graphical overhaul it looks pretty generic, no webs, no mountain or hill attached to it, we want it to look real"). (1) TRIGGER (systems/cave-system.js checkZoneTransition): the cave object is PASSABLE, so walking into the mouth carried the player NORTH past the old front trigger band (an ellipse centred ey+3.05, radii 2.05/1.35 -> only covered py ey+1.7..4.4, i.e. BELOW the mouth) - so it only fired when they walked back out. The trigger now covers the whole mouth (centre ey+1.4, radii 2.5/2.7 -> py ey-1.3..4.1, px ex-2..3), including the opening at/above the origin, so walking IN teleports immediately. (2) ART (render/object-renderer.js drawCaveEntrance, gated on the silk cavern's variant==='web' so the other cave is untouched): the mouth is now seated in a real earthen HILL/mound (mossy earth + grassy crown highlight + exposed dirt bank + grass tufts, drawn behind the rock so the cave reads as dug into a hillside), and the opening is choked with WEBBING - a giant orb web (12 spokes + 5 rings) filling the mouth, 10 heavy drape curtains, 3 hanging egg-sac cocoons on silk lines, and corner webs - with the generic purple glow dimmed into a webbed hollow (leaves a sickly halo). Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; drawCaveEntrance runs without faults (isolated pixel probing is unreliable here due to object-renderer's captured ctx closure, but the art uses the identical fillPoly/P()/stroke primitives as the existing working entrance and is gated to the web variant). RE-ENTER/return to the surface to see the new entrance. See docs/V0.18.39_SILK_CAVERN_ENTRANCE.md.
// V0.18.38: Silk Web Cavern infested & dangerous overhaul (user: walls still look bad, "the entire floor should mostly be webs with tiny paths", baby spiders invisible, want egg-break + ceiling-drop spiders + breakable web-wrapped bodies with a skeleton falling out, "needs to feel scary and dangerous"). (1) FLOOR (render/terrain-renderer.js drawSilkWebCavernSurfaceDetails) rewritten to be MOSTLY webs: silk film base + a back web layer + a dense front lattice + orb-web hubs (webs-on-webs), with a coherent low-frequency mask carving thin winding dirt paths through it (~17% dirt). (2) WALLS (drawSilkCavernWallWebs) rewritten from a few thin strands into thick layered curtains: a translucent web sheet over each face + 10 dense drape strands falling most of the way down + horizontal binding threads + dangling beads + a corner orb (verified ~5773 px for 2 faces, was ~735). (3) BABY SPIDERS now render as TINY hatchlings (modelScale 0.46 -> ~64x40 px vs 139x87 full-size), given a distinct 'spider:<role>:baby' sprite-cache key (render/entity-renderer.js) so they don't inherit the full-grown skitterer sprite; egg hatches spawn a small swarm. (4) EGG BREAK animation: new silkEggBurst VFX (flying shell shards under gravity + bursting silk puff). (5) CEILING SPIDERS: updateSilkWebHazards drops a small spider on a silk line (silkDrop VFX) near the player on a randomised interval while exploring (capped at 4). (6) WEB-WRAPPED BODIES: new breakable 'webWrappedBody' object (upright silk-cocooned victim); walking into it splits it open (silkSkeletonFall VFX - a skeleton tumbles out and collapses on the floor) leaving a 'brokenWrappedBody', sometimes drops loot. New VFX draws live in render/effects-renderer.js; new object draws in render/object-renderer.js; all placed per-run with consumed-key persistence. All deterministic per tile so nothing shimmers. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; every new render/effect path measured drawing in-browser. RE-ENTER the cavern to see it (floors regenerate on entry). See docs/V0.18.38_SILK_CAVERN_INFESTED.md.
// V0.18.37: Silk Web Cavern actually looks webbed now (user: "nothing is covered in webs at all... i want webs everywhere like they belong there"). The V0.18.35 update only scattered a handful of web PROPS; the floor/wall SURFACES stayed bare. Root cause: the per-tile silk floor overlay (render/terrain-renderer.js drawSilkWebCavernSurfaceDetails) drew just 2-3 hairline strands at alpha 0.20 on ~56% of tiles, and only ROOM tiles were flagged silkWebCavern (corridors got nothing; walls never got webs at all). FIX: (1) drawSilkWebCavernSurfaceDetails rewritten into a dense woven-silk mat on EVERY silk floor tile - a faint silk film so no bare floor shows, a lattice of strands strung between the tile's four diamond corners (shared with neighbours, so the web is continuous across the whole floor), and an orb-web hub (rings + spokes + dew) on ~45% of tiles; royal/venom/cocoon tint variants preserved. Verified in-browser: ~9051 web px over a 3x3 tile patch (near-full coverage) vs a few faint threads before. (2) new drawSilkCavernWallWebs draws silk drapes hanging down the cavern's exposed wall faces (gated on a new tile.silkWebWall flag). (3) systems/dungeon-system.js generateSilkWebCavernFloor now flags EVERY walkable floor tile silkWebCavern (rooms AND corridors) and every wall bordering the floor silkWebWall, so the whole cavern - not just room interiors - is webbed. Deterministic per tile (hash2D) so nothing shimmers while the camera pans. Verified: node --check clean; JSON clean; 0 console errors; both new render paths draw without faults. See docs/V0.18.37_SILK_CAVERN_WEB_COVERAGE.md.
// V0.18.36: Three reported bug fixes (user report w/ screenshots). (1) ROTLING ROOTS AT WAIST (still): the rotling snare's root-entangle VFX (render/effects-renderer.js drawRotlingRootEntangleEffect) anchors to the target's foot anchor, but for HUMANOIDS (players/bots/mercs/NPCs drawn via render/humanoid-base-renderer.js) that anchor (_rootVfxFootAnchor = visualFoot.y + 5) sits ~39px ABOVE the real feet: the rig's `ground` anchor is authored at the body origin (y+0) while the legs actually draw the boots at foot.y ~= +38..44 (MEASURED: origin 200 -> boots 244). So the roots wrapped the hips/waist, not the feet. ROOT-CAUSE FIX: humanoid-base-renderer.js now publishes the TRUE rendered foot line in _lastGroundAnchor.groundY (= y + max(near/far leg foot.y)); effects-renderer.js prefers _lastGroundAnchor.groundY when present, so the snare wraps the feet. Mobs have no _lastGroundAnchor and keep using _rootVfxFootAnchor (already at their feet). _lastGroundAnchor had no other consumers, so this is isolated to the root VFX. Verified in-browser: anchor moved from 39px-above-feet to 6px-from-boots across fighter/bard/cleric. (2) LIVE BOAR NAMED "CORPSE BAG": when several corpses merge into a grouped loot bag, mergeCorpseLootIntoBag renames the bag corpse to "Corpse Bag (N)". Enemy.respawn() (entities/enemy.js) only reset combat state, so a self-respawning overworld mob (boars etc.) came back ALIVE still named "Corpse Bag (N)" with a threat bar. FIX: respawn() now restores this.name from this.baseType.name and clears all corpse/loot-bag state (corpseLoot, isLootCorpse, corpseLooted, corpseLootInteractPending, corpseVisualExpired, corpseLootSummary, groupLootMergedInto, blocksMovement) and drops itself from game.lootableCorpses. (3) NPC RENDERS OVER PLAYER: all entities queued at depthFast(...) + 0.95, so a companion/merc/NPC sharing the player's tile won depth ties (array order) and painted over the player. FIX (game.js): the player gets a small +0.05 depth nudge so it wins same-tile/hair's-breadth ties, while an actor clearly in front (> ~0.1 tile) still occludes it ("unless the player is behind them"). Verified: node --check clean on all changed files; JSON clean; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.36_ENTITY_RENDER_BUGFIXES.md.
// V0.18.35: Web Silk Cavern update - "spiders live here and people die here". (1) WEB DENSITY / ATMOSPHERE: new placeSilkInfestationDressing pass (systems/dungeon-system.js) scatters far more floor + wall + hanging webs (caveWeb/silkStrands/webCurtain) plus web-wrapped remains, bone middens and cocooned-prey racks (webBones/boneMidden/preyCocoonRack - all passable, visual-only high-fidelity dressing) across every room on every floor, so the caverns read as thoroughly infested and lethal. (2) SPIDER EGGS: new smashable 'spiderEgg' clutch object (render/object-renderer.js drawSpiderEgg + drawSpiderEggBurst; placed by placeSilkNestEggs). Walking into one smashes it: ~45% it hatches 2-3 baby spiders (Spiderlings = weak non-elite Webling Skitterers spawned via createSilkDungeonEnemy and pushed to dungeonEnemies+enemies), otherwise it spills loot (rollEditorLootTable 'loot_silk_web_cavern'). (3) VENOM EGGS: new 'venomEgg' hazard (drawVenomEgg + drawVenomEggBurst) - small, dead, green-tinted eggs full of venom; walking over OR smashing one applies venomEggPoisonEffect (id 'venom_egg_poison', added to the environmental-poison allow-list so it survives the friendly-poison scrubber) and bursts it. Both eggs reuse the proven venom-sack proximity/consumed-key machinery (updateSilkWebHazards player-proximity tick) so they persist per run and do not respawn once broken; both are passable (walk-over) and place only on empty floor tiles (never clobber gates/anchors/stairs). Verified: node --check clean on all changed files; JSON clean; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.35_WEB_SILK_CAVERN_UPDATE.md.
// V0.18.34: Three rendering bug fixes (user report w/ screenshots). (1) ROTLING ROOTS AT WAIST: the rotling snare's root-entangle VFX (render/effects-renderer.js drawRotlingRootEntangleEffect) is anchored to the target's foot/ground anchor, but its "wrapping tendrils" were grown so tall (topY = groundY - up to ~23, plus motes at groundY-13) that they climbed to the hip/waist and no longer read as ground roots; lowered the tendril heights (topY ~= groundY-5..12, midY ~= groundY-1..6.5) and the mote band (groundY-6) so the snare hugs the ankles/ground. (2) RESOURCES DRAWN ON TOP OF ACTORS: resource nodes (herbs/ore/roots incl. silkroot) rendered via renderExternalSystems AFTER the depth-sorted world pass, so they painted on top of players/bots/mobs/pets (and a root/silkroot node on the player's tile looked like roots at the waist). ROOT CAUSE FIX: renamed the resource system's render() to renderGroundLayer() (so renderExternalSystems no longer draws it as a post-world overlay) and game.js now calls this.resourceGatheringSystem.renderGroundLayer(ctx) at the layeredMapEditor.renderUnderEntities hook - i.e. after terrain, BEFORE the entity/object pass - so resource props are a proper ground layer beneath the actors (same worldToScreen coord space + zoom transform, so positions are unchanged). (3) UGLY WEBBED CORPSE: render/object-renderer.js drawSilkCocoon rebuilt - the old flat ellipse with horizontal ribs is replaced by a wrapped-body cocoon: a tapered vertical pod (fattest at the body), a faint head/torso/hips silhouette showing through, two families of criss-crossing woven silk strands (clipped to the pod), tapered binding wraps that cinch the silk, frayed silk wisps at the top, and loose web anchor threads tying it to its surroundings; deterministic per obj position so it does not shimmer. Verified: node --check clean on all changed files; 0 console errors; renderGroundLayer wired once, old render() no longer referenced. See docs/V0.18.34_RENDER_BUGFIXES.md.
// V0.18.33: Portal always returns to camp (follow-up to V0.18.32; user: "portal is still glitched its supposed to return you to camp, not a random location"). ROOT CAUSE (systems/portal-system.js tryCastPortalSpell): the portal was a two-way swap keyed on isPortalCampArea, which counts anywhere within CAMP_RADIUS=22 TILES of camp centre as "at camp". Casting within that huge radius took the atCamp branch -> destination = runtime.lastWildernessLocation (a stale anchor from a previous excursion) instead of camp = the "random location". FIX: removed the atCamp destination swap - a cast portal now ALWAYS leads to camp (destination = ensurePortalCampArrivalSafe(), label "Portal to Camp", destinationZone overworld); the return portal that opens at camp still brings you back to exactly where you cast (originTravel). Verified: casting NEAR camp (atCamp=true) with a stale wilderness anchor at (250,300) now sets destination = camp arrival (101.5,104.5), not the stale spot; originTravel preserved for the return; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.33_PORTAL_ALWAYS_CAMP.md.
// V0.18.32: Walk-through portals (user: pressing T instantly teleported instead of requiring you to walk through the portal). ROOT CAUSE (systems/portal-system.js): the T-portal walk-through machinery already existed (tryCastPortalSpell only OPENS a link; updatePortalRuntime triggers useActivePortal on proximity; useActivePortal does origin->camp->return->collapse) - but findPortalSpawnPoint spawned the portal ON the player (first try step = PORTAL_SPAWN_FORWARD=0, all tries <= 0.95 tile, inside PORTAL_TRIGGER_RADIUS=0.96), so after the 0.42s spawn grace the stationary player was already in the trigger zone and it fired immediately (felt instant). The return portal had the same bug (spawned at capturePortalLocation(player.x,player.y) = the camp arrival spot). FIX: PORTAL_TRIGGER_RADIUS 0.96->1.1; new PORTAL_SPAWN_DISTANCE=2.5; new findPortalPlacement(ax,ay,dirX,dirY) finds a walkable spot ~2.5 tiles out (preferring facing, fanning to other angles/distances, always >= triggerRadius+0.6 from the anchor); findPortalSpawnPoint + the return-portal spawn both use it. Now pressing T opens a portal ~2.5 tiles in front; you WALK INTO it to travel to camp; a return portal opens 2.5 tiles from your camp arrival (so you can shop/restock, not bounce back); walking through it returns you to your original cast spot and the link collapses (one round trip). Verified: findPortalPlacement returns points exactly 2.5 tiles from the caster in every direction (east/north/diag/no-facing), all beyond the trigger radius; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.32_WALK_THROUGH_PORTALS.md.
// V0.18.31: CLERIC spell-animation revamp (3rd class of the per-class pass; see [[spell-vfx-revamp-progress]]). The whole Cleric kit ran on generic VFX (resolveClericRevampSpell: heal/cleanse/buff/groupBuff/aoeHeal -> spawnRing, holy damage -> spawnBolt, revive -> nothing) and had NO bespoke draw functions at all. BUILT a holy VFX set from scratch: (a) render/effects-renderer.js - drawClericBlessEffect(e) [one fn, by e.style: heal bloom / hot sustain / aoeheal radiant ripple w/ per-ally glows / ward golden dome+facets / cleanse upward flush shedding dark specks / nova radiant repel (Turn Undead) / revive rising light column] + drawClericSmiteEffect(e) [a pillar of light slams onto the target then blooms; styles smite/judgment/exorcise], plus drawHolyCross + drawSunburst motif helpers; all use screen-composite for additive holy light. (b) systems/effects-system.js - spawnClericVfxEffect(type,payload) + spawnClericSpellEffect(spell,source,target,opts) dispatching every clericSpellId via a CLERIC_VFX config (fx type + style + theme colors: green heals/regen, gold wards, blue/white cleanse, white exorcise, gold-white revive/nova). (c) systems/spell-system.js - resolveClericRevampSpell now calls spawnClericSpellEffect at each branch (heal/cleanse/buff/groupBuff shields w/ allies/aoeHeal w/ allies/revive-on-success/holy-damage) and the generic spawnBolt/spawnRing are DELETED. Verified: all 8 bless + 3 smite render variants run 0-throw + balanced transform; every clericSpellId dispatches to the correct themed effect (minor_heal->heal, smite->smite, renewing_prayer->hot, turn_undead->nova, divine_light->aoeheal, judgment_light->judgment, exorcise_evil->exorcise, radiant_revival->revive, etc.); 0 generic bolt/ring left in the resolver; 0 console errors. NOTE the Cleric heal branch shares code shape with the Druid resolver (disambiguate edits by woundedThresholdPct/log text when Druid's turn comes). See docs/V0.18.31_CLERIC_SPELL_VFX_REVAMP.md.
// V0.18.30: BARD spell-animation revamp (2nd class of the per-class pass; see [[spell-vfx-revamp-progress]]). The ENTIRE Bard kit ran on generic spawnBolt/spawnRing (resolveBardRevampSpell): bolt/debuff->spawnBolt, aoeDebuff/buff/groupBuff->spawnRing. There was already a rich Bard VFX toolkit (drawBardSongWaveEffect + ally buff-flashes, drawBardSonicCutEffect crescent blade, drawBardLullabyEffect, drawBardDiscordantNoteEffect, drawBardRefrainEffect, note glyphs) BUT it was ORPHANED dead code: the dispatcher spawnBardSpellEffect keyed off STALE spell names (warhymn/soniccut/valorchorus/discordantnote/refrain) that match no current spell (only 'lullaby' matched), and it was never called anyway because spell-system.js:3323 dispatches to resolveBardRevampSpell and returns before the triggerBardSpellEffect calls at ~3446+. REVAMP: (a) render/effects-renderer.js - drawBardSongWaveEffect + drawBardSonicCutEffect now theme by e.color/e.color2 (were hardcoded gold) so each song reads by role. (b) systems/effects-system.js - rewrote spawnBardSpellEffect to dispatch by options.spell.bardSpellId via a BARD_VFX config (fx + theme color + grand flag) covering all 20 spells: songs->song wave [green heal / blue mana / red war / cyan rhythm / teal harmony / etc], major songs->grand 'valorChorus' wave, self-buffs [echoing_verse/songweave]->compact 'verse' self-shimmer, sonic damage [quick_note/dissonant_chord/mournful_note/final_refrain]->themed sonic crescent blade, lullaby->drowsy purple waves, dirge_of_weakness->discordant corona; gathers allies via bardAlliesForSpell for the ally buff-flashes. (c) systems/spell-system.js resolveBardRevampSpell now calls spawnBardSpellEffect at each branch and the generic spawnBolt/spawnRing are DELETED. Verified: all 5 bard renderers run 0-throw + balanced transform; spawnBardSpellEffect dispatches every bardSpellId to the correct themed effect type/color; 0 generic bolt/ring left in the resolver; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.30_BARD_SPELL_VFX_REVAMP.md.
// V0.18.29: ASSASSIN spell-animation revamp (first class of a planned per-class pass; user: "get rid of all the generic spell animations and add actual depth so they behave as the spells they are"). Only Throwing Knife/Light Crossbow/Poison Dart/Marked/Tripwire had bespoke VFX; EVERY other Assassin damage spell fell back to a generic spawnBolt, and all AoE/traps/self-buffs used a generic spawnRing (resolveAssassinRevampSpell + applyAssassinTrap in systems/spell-system.js). REVAMP: (a) render/effects-renderer.js - data-driven ASSASSIN_PROJECTILE_KINDS / ASSASSIN_IMPACT_KINDS tables give each weapon its own silhouette: knife/blade tumble end-over-end, crossbow light bolt, heavyBolt (piercing) heavy w/ speed-streak + punch-through shards, venomBolt green w/ venom motes, executionBolt crimson w/ lethal glint + execute sigil, poisonDart green. New drawAssassinSelfBuffEffect (styles reload/silentstep/shadowfuse/venomcoat/ambush) + drawAssassinTrapFieldEffect (Death Box mechanical kill-zone). (b) systems/effects-system.js - projectile/impact spawners keyed per-kind (speed+tint); new spawnAssassinSelfBuffVfx, spawnAssassinTrapFieldVfx, spawnAssassinFanVfx (cone of blades), spawnAssassinBurstVfx (N staggered bolts); added a reusable effect `delay` field (updateEffects holds delayed effects; drawEffect skips them) so bursts stagger. (c) systems/spell-system.js resolver now maps each spell to its weapon (ASSASSIN_PROJECTILE_KIND), fires aim for crossbows, burst for Repeater (5 bolts), bounce for Ricochet (2nd blade), cone for Fan of Knives, trap-field for Death Box, wire-deploy for all traps (poison_snare green + pulse, springblade steel + blade), and per-style self-buff flourishes - and the generic spawnBolt/spawnRing fallbacks are DELETED. Verified: 7 projectile + 7 impact kinds, 5 self-buff styles, trap-field all render with 0 throws + balanced canvas transform; fan spawns 5 blades, burst spawns 5 staggered (delay 0->0.4), self-buff/trap-field spawn their own types; 0 generic bolt/ring left in the Assassin paths; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.29_ASSASSIN_SPELL_VFX_REVAMP.md.
// V0.18.28: (1) K REGRESSION FIX + (2) cape z-order generalized to all class models. (1) V0.18.27's window merge left TWO K handlers alive: game.js:1027 (central 'skills' action -> toggleSkillsPanel) AND profession-system.js's own duplicate keydown listener. Before V0.18.27 both fired independently (the original "one at a time" desync); after the merge both routed to the same profession.toggle(), so one K press toggled it TWICE = net zero (K appeared to do nothing). FIX: removed the profession-system duplicate keydown listener; the central game.js binding (toggleSkillsPanel -> delegates to toggleProfessionPanel) is now the single K handler. Verified K opens/closes the one window cleanly. (2) The V0.18.26 Bard cape fix (drape over back gear when facing away) was Bard-only; the same gear-through-cape issue hit EVERY caped class. ROOT CAUSE is general: the humanoid base renderer draws the cape (the `backCape` hook, or a default cloth cape) EARLY in drawBackLayers, before the torso/belt gear - correct for front/side, but when back-facing the cape is on the near side and must drape OVER the gear. FIX (render/humanoid-base-renderer.js): extracted drawBackCapeLayer(); drawBackLayers now draws the cape there only when NOT backVisible (back props still stay behind it), and the main sequence draws the cape LATE (after hooks.front, over belt/instrument/weapon) when backVisible - one fix covering all classes (Paladin shortCape, Ranger/Assassin splitCloak, Wizard/Enchanter/Necromancer mantles, Warden, Cleric, Bard, Druid leaf-mantle, camp NPCs, and the default cape). Reverted the now-redundant V0.18.26 Bard-specific hack so the base renderer is the single mechanism. Verified: all 12 class profiles + bard + druid render with 0 throws front AND back facing; bard central-back stays cape-dominant (41.7% cape vs 24% leather, matches the old Bard-only result); front/side unchanged; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.28_CAPES_ALL_CLASSES_AND_K_FIX.md.
// V0.18.27: Merge Professions + Skills into ONE window (user: "combine both these menus together... pressing K should only show 1 window with both professions and skills, then pressing K again should close"). Two near-duplicate windows both keyed off K (professions = 6 activities; skills = same 6 + Meditating; both read resourceGatheringSystem+craftingSystem skills). Only profession-system bound K; its toggle() opened BOTH windows as a side-by-side "paired view" but had NO else-branch to close the skills window, so they desynced ("one at a time"). FIX: single window. (a) systems/profession-system.js collectRows now appends a Meditating row (pulled from game.collectSkillRows() so the meditation XP curve stays owned by skills-system); window retitled "Professions & Skills" (7 rows); toggle() now just shows/hides the one #professionWindow and force-hides the retired standalone skills panel (game.skillsOpen=false) - no more opening a 2nd window or layoutProfessionsAndSkillsWindows pairing. (b) systems/skills-system.js toggle() delegates to game.toggleProfessionPanel (so the menu Skills button + gamepad shortcut open the same unified window, never a 2nd one); renderSkillsPanel also refreshes the professions window. (c) systems/ui-system.js periodic refresh points at professionSystem.update() instead of the dead skillsOpen flag. Verified: open via K OR the Skills button => exactly ONE window ("Professions & Skills", 7 rows incl Meditating, skills panel hidden); K again fully closes it; repeat toggles clean; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.27_UNIFIED_PROFESSIONS_SKILLS.md.
// V0.18.26: Bard cape z-order fix (user, viewing a Bard from behind: "none of these items should show through your cape"). When facing AWAY, back-worn gear - belt pouches, sash, instrument, weapons - was rendering ON TOP of the cape. ROOT CAUSE: the Bard's cape is drawn by the `backCape` layer hook, which the humanoid base renderer invokes EARLY (drawBackLayers, ~L1122, before the torso), while the Bard's `chest` hook (drawBelt/drawBeltGear/drawSash) and `front` hook (instrument) run LATE (after the torso). For front/side facings that's correct (cape behind body, gear on the front); but when back-facing the cape is on the near side and must drape OVER that back gear, so drawing it early left every belt item painted on top of it. FIX (render/bard-procedural-model.js): the cape now draws conditionally by facing - `backCape` draws it only when NOT rig.dir.backVisible (front/side, behind the body as before); when backVisible it's drawn at the END of the `front` hook instead, after the belt gear / instrument / weapon, so it drapes over them. (Held paperdoll weapons already flip to the back pass when back-facing, so they're covered too.) Left the Druid's backCape (a leaf-mantle underlayer, different semantics) and the class-identity backCape (a back-body silhouette, NOT a cape) untouched - a blanket base-renderer change would misfire on those. Verified: back-facing Bard renders with 0 throws; central-back band is now cape-dominant (was gear-on-top); 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.26_BARD_CAPE_ZORDER.md.
// V0.18.25: Spider-web shape STABILITY fix (follow-up to V0.18.24; user: "the spider webs look really good but they move / change shape as you walk around"). ROOT CAUSE: the V0.18.24 drawOrbWeb callers seeded the web's procedural randomisation (spoke jitter, hub offset, dew) on the SCREEN point - drawCaveWeb used `seed: s.x*7.1 + s.y*13.3`, webbedBush/webbed-tree similar - and s = worldToScreen(...) changes every frame as the camera pans, so the seed (and thus the whole random shape) re-rolled continuously while walking. FIX (render/object-renderer.js): drawObject now stamps a stable per-object seed from the WORLD tile once - `if (obj && obj._propSeed == null) obj._propSeed = floor(x)*73856 + floor(y)*19349` (set before any dispatch, so every prop path gets it) - and the three web callers now pass `seed: obj._propSeed` instead of the screen-derived value. The web geometry is relative to its centre (which still tracks the camera correctly); only the RANDOM seed is now world-fixed, so each web keeps one shape forever. Verified: obj._propSeed = 47*73856+136*19349 = 6102696 for tile (47,136) and is stable across redraws; the SAME web drawn at two different screen positions is now PIXEL-IDENTICAL (0 differing pixels; was reshaping before); 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.25_STABLE_SPIDER_WEBS.md.
// V0.18.24: Spider-web visual revamp (user: "the spider webs look like complete garbage - revamp them so they actually look like a spider web + look attached to whatever they're stuck to"). The webs were hand-rolled as perfect concentric ELLIPSES + evenly-spaced spokes = a flat radar/target look, with no attachment to their surface. ROOT-CAUSE FIX (render/object-renderer.js): new reusable drawOrbWeb(cx, cy, opts) primitive builds a believable orb web - off-centre hub, irregular radial spokes (jittered angle+length), a bowed outer frame, and a spiral CAPTURE thread whose segments SAG toward the hub (that concave sag between spokes is what reads as a web vs. concentric circles); plus optional `anchors` (surface points) that get support/bridge threads tying the web to whatever it hangs on, a silky two-pass sheen, hub, and dew. Deterministic per seed so static webs don't shimmer. Rewired the three shown webs through it: drawCaveWeb (the big ground/"radar" web -> orb web + 5 ground anchor strands + a silk-wrapped egg sac on obj.color), drawWebbedBush (small orb slung across the bush, anchored to sprig tips), and the drawDeadTree obj.webbed overlay (orb strung in the crown, anchored to branch tips). ALSO fixed a V0.18.21 scale-regex bug: overworldObjectScale matched 'caveWeb' on 'cave' (and web props on 'gate'/'rack') and was enlarging webs 2.2x like structures; added an early `if (/web|silk|cocoon|spider/) return 1` and narrowed 'cave'->'caveentrance|cavemouth' so webs stay decal-sized. Verified: all web draws render with 0 throws + balanced canvas transform; overworldObjectScale('caveWeb')=1 (was 2.2); 0 console errors on boot; visual preview rendered from the exact code. See docs/V0.18.24_SPIDER_WEB_REVAMP.md.
// V0.18.23: Bard/Druid fishing-line rod-tip anchor fix. The fishing line detached from the pole (hung from mid-body, not the rod tip) for BARD and DRUID players. ROOT CAUSE: those two classes render their rod via their own drawFishingRod (render/bard-procedural-model.js, render/druid-procedural-model.js), which compute the rod tip with the exact same formula as the shared drawClassFishingRig (class-identity-procedural-model.js) but were MISSING the one line that records source.fishingRodTipLocal = { x: tip.x, y: tip.y }. entity-renderer.js (~L1105) only publishes the live screen-space fishing-line anchor (fishingRodTipScreen = visualFoot + fishingRodTipLocal*scale) when fishingRodTipLocal is set; with it unset for bard/druid, the anchor was never published and the fishing system fell back to a world-space guess near the body => detached line. The V0.17.68 rod-tip fix added the recording to drawClassFishingRig (Fighter/Rogue/Cleric/etc.) but not to the bard/druid custom rods. FIX: added the identical recording line to both custom drawFishingRod functions. Verified: drove both models with a synthetic fishing actor - each now records fishingRodTipLocal = {x:126,y:-109} (model space, up-and-out at the visible pole tip) with 0 throws; 0 console errors on boot. NOTE: unrelated to V0.18.21/22 (object scale + ground wash) - a pre-existing bug surfaced by the user fishing on a bard. See docs/V0.18.23_BARD_DRUID_FISHING_LINE_FIX.md.
// V0.18.22: Seamless ground depth-wash (follow-up to V0.18.21's ground fix). V0.18.21 replaced the overlapping-circle depth wash with a flat per-tile fillRect - but terrain bakes in a square GRID space that's later drawn to isometric screen space, so each flat tile became a hard-edged diamond and the smoothly-varying per-tile depthFactor now stepped visibly at every tile boundary = a diamond checkerboard on the ground (user screenshot). ROOT-CAUSE FIX (render/terrain-renderer.js): the depth-darkening wash is now precomputed once per chunk into a low-res buffer (1px per tile, rgba(5,8,7, depthFactor*0.22)) and drawn back per elevation layer with imageSmoothingEnabled=true (bilinear) + source-atop, so the exact same intensity is interpolated into a SEAMLESS gradient across tile AND chunk boundaries - no diamond grid, no overlap rings. A 1-tile sample border makes adjacent chunks line up (depthFactor is a pure world-position function). Verified: replicated the exact op sequence against a depthFactor ramp - runs with 0 throws and the upscaled scanline steps by at most 1/255 between adjacent pixels (a flat per-tile fill jumped ~6/255 in one pixel at each tile edge = the visible grid), with per-tile intensity preserved. 0 console errors on boot. See docs/V0.18.22_SEAMLESS_GROUND_WASH.md.
// V0.18.21: World-object scale + ground-wash fix (two screenshot-driven requests). (1) OBJECTS TOO SMALL: the generic prop draws (render/object-renderer.js drawTent/drawWell/etc.) are authored at a small FIXED footprint (tent apex only ~70px, well ~52px) versus a ~90px character, and startingCampObjectScale was only ever applied to the special largecamptent/vendorstall early-returns - so plain tents/wells/buildings rendered toy-sized (smaller than the player). ROOT-CAUSE FIX: new overworldObjectScale(obj) returns a per-type real-world multiplier (built structures tent/well/hut/house/shop/etc. 2.2x, mid furnishings/stations 1.5x, small ground clutter 1.12x, natural foliage 1x, default 1.25x); drawObject now applies it as a transform ABOUT the object's foot (translate s, scale, translate -s) so props grow upward from the ground, not off their tile. To keep ctx.save/restore balanced through the switch's per-case returns, the shadow+dispatch switch was extracted verbatim into a new drawObjectShape(obj, s) helper (drawObject scales, calls it, then restores). Verified live: all 14 sampled types render with 0 throws and the canvas transform returns to identity (no leak between props); tent/well now clearly larger than the character. (2) OVERLAPPING GROUND CIRCLES: the Dark Woods depth-darkening wash (render/terrain-renderer.js ~L574) painted a per-tile filled circle of radius 0.62*tile, so adjacent tiles' circles overlapped into a fish-scale/ring pattern on the ground. FIX: replaced the per-tile ellipse with a per-tile fillRect covering the tile (same depthFactor gating + 0.22 alpha + #050807), so depth areas darken uniformly with no circles. See docs/V0.18.21_OBJECT_SCALE_GROUND_WASH.md.
// V0.18.20: Full-game bug/error review - found + fixed ONE real bug, rest clean. BUG: during combat, casting spells produced repeated render faults every frame - 'addColorStop ... rgba(NaN,11,236,...) could not be parsed as a color' from render/effects-renderer.js drawSoftGlow<-drawImpactBloom<-drawCombatImpactEffect. ROOT CAUSE: hexToRgb (effects-renderer.js:30) parsed channels with bare parseInt(hex.slice(),16) + NO NaN guard, so a malformed effect colour yielded {r:NaN,...} and rgba() emitted 'rgba(NaN,...)' which CanvasGradient.addColorStop rejects, throwing on every draw (caught by the render-fault wrapper -> console spam + skipped effect + wasted CPU; INVISIBLE to window.onerror since the wrapper swallows it - only console.error showed it). FIX: NaN-safe parser - each channel `const n=parseInt(v,16); return Number.isFinite(n)?clamp(0,255,n):255` - a colour parser must never emit NaN; fixes every rgba/hexToRgb caller. Verified: rgba('#zz0bec',.5)->rgba(255,11,236,.5) (was NaN); reproduced combat scenario (Wizard, all 20 spells cast repeatedly in melee) = 0 new render faults (was continuous); broad sweep Cleric/Necro/Bard/Druid all-spells+panels = 0 new console errors. REVIEW ELSE ALL CLEAN: 0 syntax errors (134 files); boot+all panels+combat+death+cave enter/exit+6s soak = 0 errors + no entity/effect leaks; talent data 14 classes/42 specs 0 issues; save/load round-trip clean incl adventurerPopulation. Non-bug note: [SpriteSheetSystem] procedural-fallback warns once/class/load (deduped, expected - game uses procedural models). See docs/V0.18.20_EFFECTS_COLOR_CRASH_FIX.md.
// V0.18.19: Talent tree - remove tier labels + bigger icons (systems/talent-system.js), user request. (1) REMOVED the T1/T2/... + gate-number column (.talTierGate) on the left of every tier row (render dropped gateHtml + the grid gate column; .talTier now single-column padding 2/0; removed .talTierGate CSS) - gate requirement still shows in the node hover tooltip, locked tiers still greyed. (2) BIGGER/WIDER icons so they fill each tree + read easier: talTileIcon 48->60px (cap 52->66), tile 62->70, talTierTiles gap 16->30, talTileName font 10->11px. Route re-measured to new icon centres: rung width (n-1)*100, rung top 24->30 (60px icon centre); the JS 'route spine' auto-adapts. (3) KEPT IN WINDOW despite taller content: reclaimed vertical (tier padding, name line-height 1.0) + panel max-height calc(100vh-40px) top:28. Verified at 963x669: whole tree (3 specs x 5 tiers, 60px icons) fits with NO scroll + fully on-screen (top28/bottom650/left13/right950), uniform names, tier labels gone, spine+rungs aligned, 0 console errors. NOTE: talent panel is a draggable gameWindow whose DRAGGED position is saved+restored (ui-system applyUiWindowStoredPosition); a stale saved pos can push it off-screen (per-user drag state, not the code default which is centred top:28). See docs/V0.18.19_TALENT_TREE_BIGGER_ICONS.md.
// V0.18.18: Talent tree UI cleanup (systems/talent-system.js) - "make everything fit + look clean" follow-up to V0.18.17. ROOT CAUSE of "text doesn't fit": at ~963x669 the 5-tier panel was ~91px too tall (max-height reserved 96px + top:70px → only ~573px usable) so it SCROLLED and clipped the bottom tier, and it overran the LEFT edge (pinned right:120px while ~940px wide). FIXES: (1) FITS VERTICALLY - compacted per-tier footprint (talTier padding 10/6→4/2, talTileIcon 50→48 / cap 54→52, talTile gap 4→3, talTileName reserve 24→21px + line-height 1.05, tighter talColHead/talColBar/talTier grid gate col 34→30) + panel max-height calc(100vh-60px), top 44px → whole tree (5 tiers × 3 specs) fits with 0px cut off at 963x669. (2) FITS HORIZONTALLY - panel centred + viewport-clamped: right: max(13px, calc(50vw - 470px)) so it always lands fully on-screen. (3) ALIGNED GRID - node names get uniform reserved min-height (flex-centred) so 1-line vs 2-line names no longer stagger rows; tiers line up across all 3 columns. (4) CLEANER ROUTE - replaced the per-tier connector stubs (floated + overlapped name text) with ONE continuous 'route spine' per column, JS-positioned through every tier's node centre (from getBoundingClientRect of first/last .talTileIcon), .talSpine (dim) + .talSpineFill (glows spec colour top→last-reached tier), plus horizontal .talTierRung sibling connectors (width (n-1)*78 = icon-center to icon-center). Verified in-browser at 963x669: panel fits both ways (left13/right950, bottom619), no scroll/clip; spine spans first→last node centre + auto-adapts; uniform 21px names; 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.18_TALENT_TREE_CLEANUP.md.
// V0.18.17: Talent tree UI revamp (systems/talent-system.js) from user-supplied spec background art. (1) BACKGROUNDS: the user's 14 '<Class> Spec Backgrounds.png' each hold 3 spec panels side-by-side; cut into 42 per-spec PNGs at assets/talents/<specId>.png (the panel already auto-discovers that path - no wiring). Cutter tools/cut-spec-backgrounds.py (gutter-detected split near thirds, ~480px wide); spec ids/order from data/talents.js DR.TALENT_TREES[class].specs[].id (left/mid/right -> spec 0/1/2). (2) LOCK ICONS REMOVED: dropped the 🔒 on locked tiles + tier gates and the unused .talTileLock CSS; locked tiers stay indicated by the existing greyed/desaturated .talLocked styling (user preferred). (3) ROUTE LINES: nodes are tier-gated (T1→T5 ladder) so added connectors behind the tiles - vertical .talTierLink up to the tier above + horizontal .talTierRung joining sibling nodes (width (nodeCount-1)*78px = exactly icon-center to icon-center), dim when locked, glow in spec colour once the tier is reached; tiles z-index above the lines. Verified in-browser: 3 cols load bg images, 0 lock icons, 12 links + 6 rungs (4 active after spending points), rung geometry exact (center at icon-center height, spans 411→489px w78), all 42 PNGs serve, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.17_TALENT_TREE_REVAMP.md + assets/talents/README.md.
// V0.18.16: Adventurer Population - PHASE 9 (tuning & scale) - FINAL PHASE, ARC COMPLETE. Real time scale = secondsPerGameDay 14400 = 4 real hours/in-game-day (1 in-game hr = 10 real min). PERF VERIFIED: full adventurer update stack (world events + daily schedule + abstract sim + promote/demote), all forced to expensive path, = 0.015ms/call (2000 iters/30ms) ~0.09% of a frame, flat (only ~12 records + <=1 event ever touched; throttled + hour-gated in real play). BALANCE (checked at real pacing via a 12-in-game-day/48-real-hour real-time-paced campaign sim): progression/economy/death all bounded + believable - 4 world adventurers→L20, Arlen→Renowned, each 2 mercs, gold soft-capped 1.3k-2.4k, 9 deaths distributed by role (DPS died most, tank/healer least), all recovered. TUNED: world-event post-event gap 20-48→6-16 in-game hrs (first 6-24→3-8) so the world has an active happening ~54% of the time (was too sparse ~1 start/6 real hrs). Everything else (SIM/ECON/DEATH/REP_TIERS/EVENT_RESPONSE_CHANCE/promoteR-demoteR/travel speed/pop size 12) confirmed sensible + left as tunable constants. The persistent Adventurer Bot AI System (spec Blackroot_Adventurer_Bot_AI_System.txt) is COMPLETE: Phases 1 registry, 2 promote/demote bridge, 3 daily scheduler, 4 abstract sim, 5 economy/mercs, 6 death/recovery, 7 reputation/recurring-characters, 8 world-happenings/social, 9 tuning. Population = a dozen recurring adventurers by user choice; two-tier arch scales to hundreds at flat frame cost if ever wanted. See docs/V0.18.16_ADVENTURER_POPULATION_PHASE9.md + docs/PLAN_ADVENTURER_BOT_AI.md + memory adventurer-population-progress.
// V0.18.15: Adventurer Population - PHASE 8 (world happenings & social). systems/adventurer-population-system.js: no dedicated world-boss/caravan system existed to hook, so this adds a lightweight ABSTRACT event: ONE happening at a time, spaced on the in-game clock. WORLD_EVENTS = caravan (levelMin1, reach0.5, gold×2.2), beast (levelMin6, reach0.85, rep×1.8 + danger hpRate-0.05), call_to_arms (levelMin4, reach0.15, rep×1.4); derived EVENT_ACTIVITIES (event_<type> sim rates); EVENT_RESPONSE_CHANCE 0.55. updateAdventurerWorldEvents(dt) (hooked in the frame update BEFORE updateAdventurerDailySchedule) starts/ends the single active event on the in-game clock (announces both startMsg + 'The <name> has passed'), placed at a walkable point via findBotSpawnPoint, next event scheduled 20-48h later. rollAdventurerDailyActivities adds an event-RESPONSE branch (after recovering check): eligible non-squad records (level>=levelMin) with EVENT_RESPONSE_CHANCE drop their plans → activityId='event_'+type, travelTarget=event loc, state='responding', pay supplies, added to event.respondents; dest loop skips 'responding'; sim resolves event activities via EVENT_ACTIVITIES (rewards + beast death rolls). Social: a campfire log when >=3 non-squad records spend the day in town. adventurerWorldEventInfo() for inspection. Verified in-browser: caravan started+announced; an eligible adventurer responded + travelled to the event loc + tracked as respondent (level gate ok); gained gold+rep at the site; event ended with 'has passed' log; 0 console errors. NEXT = Phase 9 tuning & scale (FINAL). See docs/V0.18.15_ADVENTURER_POPULATION_PHASE8.md + memory adventurer-population-progress.
// V0.18.14: Adventurer Population - PHASE 7 (reputation & recurring characters). systems/adventurer-population-system.js: the reputation accumulating since Phase 4 now surfaces. REP_TIERS (Unproven0/Known20/Respected40/Renowned75/Famed150/Legendary300) + standingFor(rep); NOTABLE_RANK=3 (Renowned); EPITHETS per class + earnedTitleFor(rec) (deterministic id-hash pick). New record fields standing/standingRank(persisted, edge-detect)/titleEarned; normalizeRecord hoists repVal + sets initial tier. updateAdventurerStanding(rec): recompute tier, and on a rank INCREASE into Renowned+ earn a class epithet if untitled (seed titles Arlen 'the Hunter'/Mira 'the Kind'/Sable 'the Grey' preserved) + post a one-time 'Word spreads of X — now <tier>' chat line (rank persisted so no re-announce after reload). Called from the abstract sim whenever a dormant adventurer's rep ticks up. /who shows 'Rep N [Standing]'; new adventurerRenownList(limit) returns top names+standing. Verified in-browser: seed standings correct (Arlen41→Respected, Bram34→Known, Orin16→Unproven); untitled Fighter Doran→Renowned earned 'the Bulwark' + titleEarned + both log lines; titled Arlen→Renowned kept 'the Hunter' (no new title); re-call at same rank no re-announce; /who renders 'Rep 90 [Renowned]'; renownList surfaces recurring names; 0 console errors. NEXT = Phase 8 social & dynamic-event reactions. See docs/V0.18.14_ADVENTURER_POPULATION_PHASE7.md + memory adventurer-population-progress.
// V0.18.13: Adventurer Population - PHASE 6 (death & recovery loop). systems/adventurer-population-system.js: DORMANT adventurers can now fall. DEATH tuning block (hpThreshold 0.15, chancePerHourBase 0.05 × danger(|hpRate|/0.06), recoveryHours 8, reviveHp 0.3, xpPenaltyFrac 0.4, goldPenaltyFrac 0.25, healerMitigation 0.4). New record fields deaths (lifetime), reviveAtHour, hasHealerSupport (recomputed each dawn = self healer role / cleric merc / party healer). updateAdventurerAbstractSim: (1) recovering records revive when hoursNow>=reviveAtHour (state→in_town, hp→1); (2) HP loss is healer-mitigated (rate×0.4 when supported, rest recovery unaffected); (3) DEATH ROLL only when !inTown && !traveling && hpPct<=0.15 - on death: deaths++, xp -= xpForLevel*0.4, gold ×0.75, hpPct→0.3, state→recovering, reviveAtHour=now+8h, moved to camp/spirit healer. rollAdventurerDailyActivities keeps 'recovering' records at the healer (no activity/party/travel/spend) and computes hasHealerSupport after merc hiring. Materialized adventurers keep the existing live-bot death/respawn; abstract loop is dormant-only. /who marks fallen with †N. Verified in-browser: forced death cycle (death→recovering→revive full HP), xp+gold penalty (isolated small-step), stays at healer through dawn; healer mitigation 19→8 deaths/60 trials; 40-day continuous sim = 21 deaths across the 4 world adventurers, NO permanent death (all recover), emergent pattern (squishy DPS Arlen died 12×, self-heal Cleric Mira 3×, tank Doran 2×); 0 console errors. Rates in DEATH/SIM tunable (Phase 9); forced-arrival test maximizes exposure so real rates lower. NEXT = Phase 7 reputation & recurring characters. See docs/V0.18.13_ADVENTURER_POPULATION_PHASE6.md + memory adventurer-population-progress.
// V0.18.12: Adventurer Population - PHASE 5 (economy & mercenaries). systems/adventurer-population-system.js: adventurers now participate in the economy. MERCENARIES are ABSTRACT record data (record.mercs [{roleKey,hiredDay}], cap 2, migration-safe) keyed to the REAL DR.MERC_ROLES (data/mercs.js: guardian/cleric/adept/scout costs 25-35) so numbers match the player. ECON tuning block (poorThreshold 20, maxMercs 2, mercUpkeepFrac 0.3, repairFrac 0.02, sellGearPerLevel 5, soloHireGoldMin 120); helpers roleCategory(rec: tank/healer/dps from rec.role), MERC_FOR_CATEGORY, mercHireCost/mercUpkeep. rollAdventurerDailyActivities now: (1) POVERTY BIAS - a record below poorThreshold gathers instead of paying to adventure ("poor bots gather"); (2) after party formation, MERC HIRING - a party missing tank/healer has its richest affordable member hire a merc of that role, a wealthy (>=120g) lone solo_adventure hires a bodyguard of the complementary role; (3) DAILY SPEND per non-squad record - pay merc upkeep (ceil(cost*0.3)/merc/day; UNPAYABLE MERCS LEAVE via pop until affordable), then supplies (12+lvl*2, non-town), then repair (floor(gearScore*0.02)), all bounded >=0. Abstract sim adds SELL-GEAR gold on level-up (sellGearPerLevel*level, soft-capped). /who now shows gold + "+N merc(s)"; new adventurerEconomySummary() for tuning. Verified in-browser (30-day sim, manual-driven): mercs hired (up to 5) + leave when upkeep unpayable (roster->0 by day 30), role keys valid; broke adventurer never adventured across 20 days; avg gold equilibrium ~100-150 (no runaway to 5000, no collapse); 0 console errors. NOTE: squad records mirror their live bot's level (so /who can show a squad member at the bot's actual level, e.g. Lv 1). NEXT = Phase 6 death & progression loops. See docs/V0.18.12_ADVENTURER_POPULATION_PHASE5.md + memory adventurer-population-progress.
// V0.18.11: Adventurer Population - PHASE 4 (abstract simulation tier). systems/adventurer-population-system.js: DORMANT distant records (non-squad, non-materialized) now progress off-screen on the in-game clock. Each ACTIVITIES entry gained sim rates xpMult/goldMult/repMult/hpRate; new SIM tuning block (xpBase 55, goldBase 9, repBase 0.15 per in-game hour, travelFactor 0.3, goldSoftCap 5000, gearFindPerHour 0.4) + xpForAdventurerLevel(level)=80+level*45. updateAdventurerAbstractSim(dt) - called in the frame update between updateAdventurerDailySchedule and updateAdventurerMaterialization - advances by the in-game-HOUR delta (getWorldTimeInfo (day-1)*24+min/60, clamped 6h vs paused-tab/day-skip) and per dormant record applies: XP→level-ups (cap 20, gearScore floor-bumps on level), gold (soft-capped), reputation from non-travel deeds, hp +/- (rest recovers, adventuring costs, clamped 0.1..1.0), gear creep; gains ×0.3 while still traveling. MATERIALIZED + SQUAD records are skipped (they progress via their live bot). Supply-cost SPEND added at dawn in rollAdventurerDailyActivities (non-town activities pay 12+level*2 gold, bounded ≥0). /who floors the now-fractional reputation. Verified in-browser (manual-driven over 48 in-game hours): large-group raider Doran L9→15, gold 145→663, gear 108→182, rep 30→38, hp 0.9→0.1(clamped); resting Sable hp 0.4→1.0; level cap + hp bounds respected; a squad + a materialized record untouched by the sim; 0 console errors. Rates are generous for test visibility - real play varies activity daily and only sims dormant records → gradual; all SIM constants are tunables (Phase 9). NEXT = Phase 5 economy & mercenaries. See docs/V0.18.11_ADVENTURER_POPULATION_PHASE4.md + memory adventurer-population-progress.
// V0.18.10: Adventurer Population - PHASE 3 (daily activity scheduler). systems/adventurer-population-system.js: every in-game dawn each adventurer rolls a primary activity from the spec distribution (ACTIVITIES: rest 15% / craft 10% / gather 15% / solo 20% / small-group 25% / large-group 15%), world (non-squad) adventurers who roll a group activity form parties (small 3-4 / large 5-6, PARTY_SIZE) that share ONE destination, and each picks a travel destination scaled by activity reach + level (pickAdventurerDestination: in-town activities stay at camp; adventuring ones go deeper for higher levels, via findBotSpawnPoint). NEW record fields activityId/groupId/travelTarget (+ activity/activityLabel/state). rollAdventurerDailyActivities() rolls+parties+destinations (squad records get an activity for display but no party/travel - they stay with the player). updateAdventurerDailySchedule(dt) - called before updateAdventurerMaterialization in the frame update - detects the worldTime.day rollover (getWorldTimeInfo) and re-rolls, else walks DORMANT distant records toward travelTarget at 5 tiles/s (materialized/squad excluded - live bot AI owns their movement); on promote the bot behaviorGoal comes from the activity. Verified in-browser (driven manually - preview rAF pauses when backgrounded): all 12 get valid activities w/ expected variety; across 8 days every party shares one destination + squad never in a party; a dormant record (Doran) walks 70->44 tiles toward target + arrives; day rollover re-rolls (lastDawnDay advances); 0 console errors. NEXT = Phase 4 abstract sim (XP/level/gold/gear progression for distant records on the budgeted world-clock tick). See docs/V0.18.10_ADVENTURER_POPULATION_PHASE3.md + memory adventurer-population-progress.
// V0.18.9: Adventurer Population - PHASE 2 (promote/demote bridge, the two-tier core). systems/adventurer-population-system.js: non-squad records now MATERIALIZE into full BotPlayer entities when the player is near their overworld anchor and DEMOTE back to data when the player leaves; the 8 squad records BIND to the existing BOT_START_PROFILES bots (always materialized, never doubled). NEW: record.location {x,y,zone,traveling} (added to normalizeRecord; runtime materialized/botId now reset to false/null on load - never trusted from a save); ensureAdventurerWorldPositions (deterministic golden-angle scatter of distant records to walkable overworld anchors via findBotSpawnPoint); promoteAdventurerRecord (spawnBotPlayer from the record, tags bot.adventurerRecordId + worldAdventurer); syncAdventurerRecordFromBot (writes position/hp/activity back on demote; level/gold mirrored only for squad bots so distant records keep record authority for the future abstract sim); updateAdventurerMaterialization(dt) - throttled 0.5s, called after updateBotPlayerSystem in the frame update, promoteR 26 / demoteR 34 tiles (gap = hysteresis vs thrash), same-zone gated. /who marks materialized adventurers with ●. Verified in-browser: 4 distant records placed + 8 squad bound; Arlen/Mira auto-promote near spawn; moving onto Doran's anchor promotes him; moving far demotes (botCount 16->14); repeated passes keep 1 entity (no double-spawn); squad bots never removed by the bridge; 0 console errors. Perf: only ~12 records scanned every 0.5s, only near ones ever become entities -> flat frame cost as population grows. NEXT = Phase 3 daily activity scheduler. See docs/V0.18.9_ADVENTURER_POPULATION_PHASE2.md + memory adventurer-population-progress.
// V0.18.8: Adventurer Population - PHASE 1 of the persistent "living world of adventurers" build (spec Blackroot_Adventurer_Bot_AI_System.txt; plan docs/PLAN_ADVENTURER_BOT_AI.md; user chose FULL ARC phase-by-phase + a dozen recurring adventurers). New systems/adventurer-population-system.js = a persistent DATA layer only (additive, NO bot spawn/AI/behavior change yet, NO simulation yet - those are Phase 2 promote/demote + Phase 4 abstract sim). Two-tier design: every adventurer is a lightweight RECORD; only nearby ones become full BotPlayer entities (Phase 2). Phase 1 delivers: AdventurerRecord model (id/name/race/class/role/personality/level/xp/gold/reputation/title/homeTown/gearScore/activity/state/materialized/squadBot, schema-versioned + migration-safe), a curated cast of 12 (SEED_ADVENTURERS: first 8 mirror BOT_START_PROFILES squad bots Bram/Talia/Riven/Luma/Elowen/Orin/Fenn/Varek so Phase 2 can fold them together; +4 new distant records Arlen the Hunter/Ranger, Mira the Kind/Cleric, Doran/Fighter, Sable the Grey/Wizard), initAdventurerPopulation (seeded in start() after ensureBotPlayers), serialize/restoreAdventurerPopulation persisted in save under runtime.adventurerPopulation (next to botPlayers), and a new /who chat command listing the roster by reputation. Registered in _script_order.json + HTML after bot-player-system.js, installed via AdventurerPopulationSystem.install(Game). Verified in-browser: 12 records on entry, fields correct (Arlen Lv9/Rep41/gear108), serialize->12 + restore round-trip reverts mutations, /who prints 12-line ranked roster, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.8_ADVENTURER_POPULATION_PHASE1.md + memory adventurer-population-progress.
// V0.18.7: New music - three real recorded tracks applied to their contexts (systems/audio-system.js). FILES (music/): dark_woods_loop.wav REPLACED with the new Dark Woods track; silk_web_cavern_loop.wav NEW; menu_theme_loop.wav NEW. WIRING: MUSIC_MANIFEST +silk_web_cavern +menu_theme; audioSceneForCurrentState now returns the dedicated 'silk_web_cavern' theme when currentZone is cave/dungeon AND dungeonSystem.state.active.dungeonId==='silk_web_cavern' (other caves keep cave_ambience); new Game.prototype.playMenuMusic loops menu_theme on the logo splash / character screens - triggered from unlockAudioSystem on the first user gesture when !this.started, and refused once started (updateAudioSystem crossfades to the zone scene on world entry); playMusic's async-load retry guard generalized so the menu theme (not a zone track) starts once its buffer decodes. Verified in-browser (served over http): all 3 wavs 200/valid RIFF-WAVE; silk-web dungeon scene->silk_web_cavern, other caves->cave_ambience; menu (pre-start) unlock -> menu_theme decoded + playing; start() hands off menu_theme -> town_lantern; playMenuMusic()==false after start; 0 console errors. file:// standalone still falls back to procedural WebAudio (existing behavior). See docs/V0.18.7_MUSIC.md.
// V0.18.6: High-Poly Spider Webs - graphical upgrade pass for the Silk Web Cavern environment bake mesh (assets/models/highpoly/silk_web_cavern_environment_highpoly_quadmesh_v0.18.6.obj + .json). OFFLINE bake/reference asset - NO runtime code loads these OBJs (verified), so zero pathing/collision/gameplay impact. The v0.15.05 generator was missing, so this adds a reproducible one: tools/generate-silk-web-highpoly.js. APPROACH = up-res in place: the 6 structural groups (floor_{1,2,3}_structural_floor_quads/_wall_faces = 96% of the mesh) are copied BYTE-IDENTICAL (independently verified: all 6 groups + the full 622,224-vert original block preserved as an exact prefix; per-floor floor-plane bboxes identical) so room centers/dimensions/corridor links/coverage/boss-arena bounds are provably unchanged; every web-feature group (anchor cables, hanging-silk curtains, egg sacs, bone/debris strands, gouge rings, shed exoskeletons, egg clutches) is regenerated as real high-poly geometry anchored to its EXISTING bbox/endpoints; venom-pool-lip groups pass through; new brief detail (mummiform prey cocoons with victim-form + torn feeding variants, teardrop egg sacs + spiderlings + hatch holes, twisted rope anchor cables with fan-splay/adhesive beads, sagging debris-laden felt-center curtains with ragged tears + dew-bead fringe, three-clawed Broodwarden gouge tears + repair patch, dusty crevice-fill mats + web balls, bound foreign objects: coin/vial/arrow/page) is added only within existing coverage. Quads on all primary surfaces (cables/sheets/sacs/cocoons), triangles only on fine threads, 0 n-gons. Deterministic (seeded per feature). OUTPUT (verified): 887,310 verts (622,224 orig + 265,086 new), 281,782 quads + 98,824 tris + 0 n-gons, indices all in range, 23MB->36MB; DENSITY knob at top of the script for a denser bake. This is bake SOURCE geometry - it is not visible in the Canvas2D game until normal maps are baked + applied. See docs/V0.18.6_SILK_WEB_HIGHPOLY.md.
// V0.18.5: Meditation-system review cleanup - safe fixes only, no mechanics/balance/core changes (the tick model, L1-20 chart, regen math, bonuses and state machine are all untouched). (1) DEAD CODE removed: game.js Game.prototype.meditationRestoreAmount (defined, never called) and the meditationSafetyOk helper (systems/meditation-system.js function + DR.MeditationHelpers export + Game.prototype wrapper - defined and exposed but never invoked; bots/mercs gate their own meditation safety via meditationDesireScore + combat checks). Removing meditationRestoreAmount also closes the only non-tick caller of calculateMeditationRegen, so its progress side-effects (environment-visit tracking, shared_dream/duet achievement hooks) can now only fire on a real 15s tick. (2) UX GUARD: game.js startMeditation now returns a single 'You are already fully rested.' line when the PLAYER (unforced) tries to meditate at full HP+resource, instead of the old jarring 'begin settling...' immediately followed by 'Meditation complete.' (updateMeditationForEntity completes instantly at full). Scoped to entity===this.player && !options.force, so bots/mercs - which pre-check need and never start at full - are untouched. DELIBERATELY LEFT (would change behavior/core, flagged for owner decision): the player's passive mana regen stacking with meditation ticks (combat-system.js regen - likely intended baseline), the intentionally-broad actorIsMeditating predicate (narrowing a shared predicate risks regressions for a non-triggered latent freeze case), the V0.17.21 player-XP revert safeguard, and the hpPerSec/resourcePerSec chart field naming (rename would alter the calculateMeditationRegen result contract with real reader-breakage risk for a cosmetic gain; the existing explanatory comment stays). Verified in-browser: both methods undefined, full-rest press blocked with one message, meditating while hurt still starts + calculateMeditationRegen returns hp/resource + a tick restores HP, 0 console errors. See docs/V0.18.5_MEDITATION_REVIEW_CLEANUP.md.
// V0.18.4: FIX - "animations only play fully in Debug mode." ROOT CAUSE: in normal play every character model is drawn from the runtime sprite cache (systems/runtime-sprite-cache-system.js), which bakes each procedural model into a BOUNDED flip-book of quantized frames - idle is only spriteCacheIdleBuckets:2 frames sampled spriteCacheIdleFrameMs:250 apart (so ~frozen), moving 6 frames, actions 8. The debug overlay sets actor.debugFacing, and render/entity-renderer.js drawCachedModelOrFallback gates the cache with `!debugFacing`, so opening Debug drew every model LIVE at 60fps - hence the symptom. FIX: the cache is a legitimate perf net for the DISTANT crowd (hundreds of mobs on a 360x360 map), so keep it there but render the things the eye actually tracks LIVE. New EntityRenderer.shouldRenderModelLive(actor) returns true for the player (always) and any entity within CONFIG.PERFORMANCE.spriteCacheLiveRadius (=18) tiles of the player; drawCachedModelOrFallback now also bypasses the cache when that's true (`!debugFacing && !shouldRenderModelLive(actor)`). 18 sits just inside nearAiRadius:20 so every live-rendered entity is also in the near-AI band (full AI + full animation, consistent). Verified in-browser: shouldRenderModelLive(player)=true, entity 8 tiles away=true, 40 tiles away=false; after real frames the player + near enemies are NOT _runtimeSpriteCached while the cache stays active (4184 hits/62 entries) on the mid/far on-screen crowd; 0 console errors. Motion smoothness is the user's visual sign-off. See docs/V0.18.4_ANIMATION_FIDELITY_FIX.md.
// V0.18.3: four world/UI fixes from user screenshots. (1) MOB DISTRIBUTION (systems/mob-spawn-system.js) - camp is at (100,100) on a 360x360 map (activeMapSize 360; the HUD's "200x200" is a stale CONFIG.MAP_SIZE label), so the SE half was near-empty: mobs thinned with distance. darkWoodsTieredEncounters now covers the whole content radius (dist cap 205->300), ramps `progress` over the full distance (was saturating at dist 106), and raises acceptance 0.12+0.26*progress -> 0.17+0.41*progress (far reaches denser). Added 13 well-spaced far-reach camps to DARK_WOODS_MOB_CAMPS (east/south/deep-corner, deeper=tougher families). DARK_WOODS_POPULATION_VERSION 5->6 re-seeds over saves. Verified: total 345->414 enemies, mobs beyond dist 120 went 109->203, 79 camp-tagged mobs now spread across the map. (2) WORLD MAP FOG (render/minimap-renderer.js buildFogOverlay) - unexplored alpha 236->255 so the world map is truly BLACK until discovered (was faintly showing terrain); compositeFogMinimap draws at globalAlpha 0.92 so the minimap keeps its softer look. Verified: overlay unexplored alpha=255, rgb~[3,5,4]. (3) MAP UI OVERLAP (systems/ui-system.js toggleMap + HTML CSS) - opening the map now sets body.worldMapOpen and CSS hides all gameplay chrome (#hud/#hotbar/#minimapWrap/#menuDock/#mercPanel/#partyHud/#externalSystemsHud/.unifiedCompanionHud) so nothing draws over the map; cleared on close. Verified: those elements compute display:none while open, class removed on close. (4) MOB SWIM VISUAL - enemies swim now (V0.17.97) but rendered walking on top of water. swimming-system.updateAuxiliarySwimStates now also applies applySwimmingRenderState to nearby (<=44 tiles) enemies (full swim state: swimming/swimSubmerge/swimAnim/swimState); entity-renderer.drawEntity wraps the procedural enemy model in a waterline clip (hides the submerged lower body) + drawMobSwimSurface draws an animated water ellipse behind and a bright rim in front, so mobs look partly submerged. Verified: a mob in water gets swimState 'swimming'/submerge 0.52/isEntitySwimming true and render() runs with 0 errors (exact look is user sign-off - preview tab was backgrounded so no screenshot). See docs/V0.18.3_WORLD_FIXES.md.
// V0.18.2: AI overhaul part IV - the remaining stubbed boss ability kinds + a bot-AI audit. PART 1 (entities/enemy.js executeDataAbility): the V0.18.0 executor left summon/charge/blink/lunge/retreat/cocoon_prison as no-ops; now implemented. summon_adds/phase_adds -> new Enemy.summonMobAdds spawns `summonCount` temporary combat adds around the caster via game.spawnQuestWaveEnemy, resolving what to summon from ab.summonMob / baseType.summonMob else Enemy.resolveSummonAddId (picks a family-appropriate weak non-elite from DR.MOB_DRAFT_BY_ID: spiders for spider bosses -> mob_thorn_widow, else weakest -> mob_rotling). charge/lunge -> dash `advance` tiles toward target then strike (+ small AoE/status for lunge). blink -> teleport to just short of the target, strike + Flicker slow. retreat -> burst away while facing. cocoon_prison -> hard root (moveSpeedMultiplier -1) + light AoE damage. All damage still = getEnemyAutoAttackRawDamage x damageScale (+ damageBonus) so it stays balanced, and every kind is gated by the existing range/cooldown logic in tryDataAbility. Verified in-browser: summon spawned 3 adds (resolved mob_rotling), charge at proper range dealt 44 dmg + closed distance, blink teleported near + 38 dmg + Flicker, cocoon_prison rooted the player, retreat backed the mob away; a mixed 4-caster exotic-ability fight ran 0 errors and abilities are attack-gated (no per-frame cost). The Egg-Heart (summon-only miniboss) now actually does something. PART 2 (bot skill-use AI): AUDITED, NOT CHANGED - it was already comprehensive. All 14 classes have tuned BOT_CLASS_AI_PROFILES (role, preferredRange, heal/emergency thresholds, ordered spellPriority); chooseBotClassSpell/botSpellMatchesPriority already do emergency-heal (<35%)/heal(<70%)/revive/cure/CC/mana/pet-heal/pet-buff/summon/defensive/group-buff selection with mana+cooldown+LoS gating; bots already KITE (bot combat positioning repositions ranged bots when d < preferredRange-1.25 and closes melee bots). Verified: no orphaned spells (every class spell's kind is castable), Cleric heals injured allies + casters bolt in live combat, and the game's own auditClassBotAiStability() returns ok:true (14 classes, no missing profiles/spellbooks/cooldowns). Changing tuned, working AI for its own sake would only risk regressions, so it was left as-is. Optional future: DPS-bot self-preservation (they facetank at low HP with no healer, but respawn exists). See docs/V0.18.2_AI_BOSS_ABILITIES_BOT_AUDIT.md.
// V0.18.1: Fix - the in-game Patch Notes panels were FROZEN at V0.17.25. ROOT CAUSE: the panels only ever rendered a hand-embedded copy of the notes inside the HTML (the `.patchNotesEntries` sections); refreshPatchNotesPanels just cloned that embedded copy between the splash + menu panels, and NOTHING read PATCH_NOTES.md - so every release since V0.17.25 updated PATCH_NOTES.md (per the golden rules) but the embedded copy was never re-synced (a classic dual-source drift; the container even carries data-patch-notes-source="PATCH_NOTES.md", the intended-but-never-built source). FIX (systems/ui-system.js): (1) renderPatchNotesMarkdown(md) parses PATCH_NOTES.md (## = entry title/<h4>, ### = sub-header/<h5>, - = bullet, 2-space-indented - = nested bullet, **bold**/`code`/*em* inline) into the exact patchNoteEntry markup; (2) ensurePatchNotesFromSource() fetches PATCH_NOTES.md once (only over http[s]; file:// can't fetch) and stamps it into every .patchNotesEntries container, so on a served build the panel is ALWAYS the live PATCH_NOTES.md; refreshPatchNotesPanels now calls it. (3) For file:// (and to avoid a stale flash before the fetch lands) the embedded fallback is regenerated from PATCH_NOTES.md by a new reusable release script tools/sync-patch-notes.py (same parser) - run it after every PATCH_NOTES.md edit. Verified in-browser: panel was 'V0.17.25 - Rotling Root...', now 'V0.18.0 - Smarter AI III...' at the top; 240 entries + 158 sub-headers render (screenshot), embedded + fetched are identical, bold markdown renders, 0 errors. RELEASE PROCESS UPDATE: after editing PATCH_NOTES.md, run `python3 tools/sync-patch-notes.py` (regenerates the embedded fallback in the current HTML) - the runtime fetch covers served builds automatically. See docs/V0.18.1_PATCH_NOTES_SOURCE_FIX.md.
// V0.18.0: AI overhaul part III - mobs use their DATA ability kits + minor rollover marking the AI/perf overhaul complete. ROOT ISSUE: minibosses/bosses (and some mobs) carry object-format `abilities` [{id,name,kind,damageScale,radius,cooldown,summonCount,status,...}] in data/enemies.js + data/npcs.js, but NOTHING consumed them - only the bespoke tryAshrootHorrorAbility + the 3 hardcoded family checks (spider venom / wolf rend / root snare) ran, so bosses never used their designed kits (dead data). FIX: (1) Enemy.tryDataAbility (entities/enemy.js) - hooked into tryTacticalAbility (after the ashroot check, before family fallbacks); picks an off-cooldown, in-range object-format ability and runs Enemy.executeDataAbility by `kind`, tracking PER-ABILITY cooldowns on the instance (_abilityCd). Damage uses the mob's normal auto-attack damage (getEnemyAutoAttackRawDamage) x ability.damageScale so it stays balanced. Kinds implemented: aoe/venom_rain/silk_lines (AoE at target), cleave (AoE around self), poison_cloud (AoE + venom DoT), snare (root in radius), debuff (status + optional slow via moveSpeedMultiplier), shield (self damageTakenMultiplier -0.5), buff/frenzy (self moveSpeed + faster swing), boss_heal/heal (self +12% max HP). Exotic movement kinds (summon_adds/phase_adds/charge/blink/lunge/retreat/cocoon_prison) are gracefully skipped (return false -> next ability / fallback) - future work. (2) New game-side primitives (systems/combat-system.js): enemyAoeDamage(x,y,radius,amount,source,color,options) - the mirror of the player's aoeDamage, hitting player+merc+pet+bots(+bot pets) instead of enemies, with an optional per-target status; enemyAoeStatus wraps it for status-only (snare/debuff). Verified in-browser: a test mob given aoe/poison_cloud/snare/shield fired them - AoE dealt 44 dmg to the player, poison applied a venom_bite DoT, shield applied mob_shield to the caster; per-ability cooldowns set; 0 console errors; performanceSettings memo still stable (aiUpdateBand ~0.001 ms/call) and steady-state update ~11 ms (the V0.18 perf work holds - the executor only runs on attack, never per-frame idle). Camp render unchanged (screenshot). NOTE ON VERSION: rolled V0.17.99 -> V0.18.0 (not .100) to mark the completed arc: nameplate cache (V0.17.96), swimming+pathfinding (V0.17.97), the performanceSettings allocation-storm fix / ~10x AI loop (V0.17.98), ranged casters + target priority (V0.17.99), data ability kits (V0.18.0). Remaining optional polish: summon/charge/blink/etc. ability kinds; bot skill-use AI. See docs/V0.18.0_AI_DATA_ABILITIES.md.
// V0.17.99: AI overhaul part II - smarter combat (ranged casters + target priority). ROOT ISSUES: (a) every enemy was hardcoded range:1.35 (melee) in the Enemy constructor, so "ranged casters" (Grave Wisp/Duskwisp, aiProfile 'ranged_caster', floating spirits) walked up and MELEED - the dumbest possible behavior; the aiProfile tag and the rich weighted `abilities` data were ignored by combat. (b) target selection was basically nearest-actor. FIXES (entities/enemy.js + systems/combat-system.js): (1) RANGED CASTER AI - the constructor now detects ranged mobs from data tags (aiProfile/animationProfile/rendererId matching /ranged|floatingcaster/) and gives them range 6.5 + isRangedAttacker; new Enemy.performRangedAttack (spawns a travelling bolt via game.spawnBolt and deals the SAME damage as the melee auto via getEnemyAutoAttackRawDamage - balance-neutral, just delivered from distance) and Enemy.kiteFromTarget (backs away inside leash while still facing/firing). The combat block gained a kite branch (target within rangedKiteRange 3.2 -> retreat + fire) and the attack branch is now ranged-aware (fire only with line of sight, else reposition); melee mobs are byte-for-byte unchanged. 72/350 mobs in the test zone are now proper ranged casters. (2) SMARTER TARGET PRIORITY - pickEnemyTarget's actorScore now favors WOUNDED targets (score -= (1-hpFrac)*1.1, i.e. finish near-dead targets) and SQUISHIER targets (score += maxHp/700 capped 0.9, i.e. casters/healers over tanks); distance still dominates and the threat table still takes precedence (taunts unaffected), so this mainly sharpens opening target acquisition. Verified in-browser: ranged mob classification correct (Duskwisp range 6.5 vs Ashroot Horror 1.35), performRangedAttack fires from 5 tiles dealing damage + spawning a bolt + setting cooldown, kiting backs a too-close caster from 2.0->3.2 tiles (label 'kiting'), a mixed 6-mob aggro runs with 0 console errors and update still ~5 ms (V0.17.98 perf intact). Ranged encounters are now harder to simply walk away from (same per-hit damage, but the mobs actually use their range) - intended. NOTE: broader use of the weighted per-mob `abilities` data (AoE/summon/shield kinds) is future polish; melee ability variety still runs through the existing tryTacticalAbility family checks. This completes the requested AI arc: pathfinding + swimming (V0.17.97), AI perf (V0.17.98), combat/skill (V0.17.99). See docs/V0.17.99_AI_RANGED_COMBAT.md.
// V0.17.98: Performance - the big one. Profiling the enemy-AI update loop (~90 ms, the dominant frame cost) attributed ~85% to ONE function: Enemy.aiUpdateBand (a trivial distance/band check) at ~0.19 ms/call x ~460 calls = 88 ms/frame. ROOT CAUSE: aiUpdateBand calls game.performanceSettings() TWICE per call (~920x/frame), and performanceSettings was NOT memoized - performanceVerifier.effectiveBaseSettings does `Object.assign({}, ...)` (a fresh object EVERY call), which also breaks adaptivePerformance.effectiveSettings's identity-keyed cache so IT re-allocates too. Result: ~2500 object allocations/frame from AI banding alone (plus every render/UI caller), i.e. a GC/alloc storm masquerading as "AI cost". FIX (game.js performanceSettings): memoize - rebuild only when preset / lowSpecMode / adaptive level / adaptive-enabled actually change (4 scalar comparisons on the hit path), else return the cached object (the result is read-only for all ~47 call-sites; the QA-telemetry `perf.x=` writes are on game.perfStats, a different object). This is engine-wide, not just AI. MEASURED in-browser (software sandbox, 345 mobs): Enemy.aiUpdateBand 88 -> 0.18 ms, Enemy.update 106 -> 1.35 ms, update 82 -> 17 ms, render ~23-48 -> ~5 ms (render also calls performanceSettings for cull pads/DPR/effect gating), frame ~114 -> ~24 ms (~4.7x, ~8 -> ~40 FPS here; larger on real GPU+CPU). Verified: memo returns a stable object, invalidates correctly on adaptive level change (renderScale 1/0.85/0.72 for levels 2/1/0), the V0.17.95 render-resolution slider still works, dpr/mode correct, 0 console errors. The remaining ~17 ms update is legitimate AI work (patrol/target-pick/pathfinding), dt-amplified at low FPS and smaller at 60. See docs/V0.17.98_PERFORMANCE_SETTINGS_MEMO.md.
// V0.17.97: AI overhaul part I - movement (swimming + pathfinding). Root causes found: (a) NON-players were hard-blocked from every water tile (systems/collision-system.js tryMove `if (enteringWater && !movingPlayer) return false` + isWalkable water branch returned false for anyone not `kind==='player'`), so enemies/mercs/pets/bots could never cross water and A* never routed through it; (b) enemies used ONLY local steering (entity moveToward) and never called the existing A* (findPath), so a tree/rock/water-edge between them and their target left them stuck. FIXES: (1) SWIMMING for all actors - new Game.actorCanSwim(entity) (true for player/enemy/merc/pet/bot/remote; opt out per-actor with cannotSwim=true / canSwim=false; player still honors playerCanSwim===false). tryMove now admits any swimmer to water and sets `entity.swimming` for everyone (the player's flag is still refined per-frame by swimmingSystem); isWalkable's water branch returns actorCanSwim(entity). Because ALL movement + pathfinding (findPath -> pathTileBlocked -> isWalkable) funnels through these, mobs, mercs, pets and bots now cross rivers/lakes and follow the player across water, and A* routes through water for swimmers but not for cannotSwim actors. (2) ENEMY PATHFINDING - new Game.moveEnemyToward(enemy, tx, ty, dt, stopRange): if the straight line is clear it steers directly (cheap, unchanged); if blocked it A*-routes around the obstacle with a per-enemy cached, throttled path (repath ~0.5 s, maxNodes 520, allowPartialPath) so cost stays bounded even with many chasers. entity/enemy.js chase and home-return now call it instead of raw moveToward; handlePathingFailure remains the last-resort. Verified in-browser: actorCanSwim correct per kind; a water tile is walkable for enemy/merc/pet/player, blocked for cannotSwim; an enemy physically enters water (swimming flag set) and A* finds a 2-step route ACROSS water (crossesWater true) while a non-swimmer gets none; 5 enemies swimming + 1 actively A*-routing in live play with 0 console errors; camp render unchanged (screenshot). NOTE: this is AI part I (movement). Combat/skill-use smarts and the enemy-AI PERFORMANCE pass (the ~90 ms update loop) are the next phases. See docs/V0.17.97_AI_SWIMMING_PATHFINDING.md.
// V0.17.96: Performance - nameplate render cache (the single biggest draw cost) + a GPU-check tool. Draw-phase profiling on real GPU hardware (AMD RX 7900 XT, hardware-accelerated canvas2d confirmed via the new checker) showed the in-world render (~48 ms/frame) was NOT software/GPU-vs-headless (an earlier wrong assumption) - it was drawEntity at ~1.43 ms/entity, and within that drawNameplate at ~2.1 ms PER PLATE (~24 ms/frame for ~12 plates = over half of render). Canvas2d TEXT drawing (fillText/measureText) plus shadowBlur, a per-frame gradient, and 5 rounded-rect frame strokes are CPU-bound and were redrawn from scratch every frame for every visible entity, uncached - which is why a strong GPU still chugs. FIX (render/entity-renderer.js drawNameplate): cache each fully-drawn plate to a per-entity offscreen canvas keyed by everything that changes its pixels (name, level, action text, kind, elite/class emblem, quest flag, width, and bucketed HP / threat% + primary / spider-web / meditation progress); blit the cached image while the key is unchanged, and only re-run the (UNCHANGED) drawing when it changes. Because `ctx` is the global window.ctx, the existing draw code renders into the offscreen buffer unmodified via a translate + retarget (wrapped in try/finally so the real canvas is always restored) - so the plate is pixel-identical, no feature/graphic removed. Result: per-plate cost 2.1 ms -> 0.68 ms in this (draw-call-bound) sandbox and render ~48 -> ~23 ms median; on real GPU+CPU the win is larger (cache-hit blits are ~0.1 ms). Verified in-browser: nameplates render identically (screenshot A/B), 0 errors, high cache-hit rate on idle plates, dynamic plates (HP/threat/meditation) re-render on change with no staleness. Also added `Blackroot GPU Check.html` - a one-click, plain-English diagnostic (WebGL GPU name + software-vs-hardware, a canvas speed test, display/DPR, and fix steps) so players can confirm their browser is GPU-accelerating the canvas. NOTE: the next remaining bottleneck is the enemy-AI update loop (pathfinding), not render. See docs/V0.17.96_NAMEPLATE_RENDER_CACHE.md.
// V0.17.95: Performance pass - a real boot bug + render-resolution scaling. Full profiling review of the running game (menu + in-world Fighter, 338 mobs). FINDINGS: the render pipeline is already well-optimized (screen-cull drops ~347/355 entities so ~8-16 draw; renderables use reused pools = no per-frame GC; runtime sprite cache ~88% hit / 0 re-bakes/frame; no per-frame shadowBlur/filter/getImageData in the canvas2d path) and enemy AI is distance-banded with wall-clock budgeting (bounded work per real-second, so ~6-7 ms/frame at 60 FPS). (1) BUG FIXED (systems/performance-stable-release-lock-system.js): an infinite-recursion stack-overflow storm on EVERY boot. PerformanceStableReleaseLockSystem's constructor ran side effects (applyReleaseDefaults -> setHybridDefaultRolloutPolicy -> renderSettingsPanel) whose settings-snapshot chain re-entered ensurePerformanceStableReleaseLockSystem() before the singleton was stored, so it rebuilt the system forever until the stack blew; worse, the overflow happened before the defaultsApplied='1' guard was written, so it re-fired on every page load (hundreds of thrown/caught 'Invalid regular expression /[|,]+/g: Stack overflow' exceptions). Root-cause fix: ensure() now stores the singleton BEFORE running the deferred init, so the re-entrant call reuses the instance. Verified: forcing the exact path now constructs cleanly with 0 errors. (2) RENDER-RESOLUTION SCALING (adaptive cap + user slider) for fill-rate-bound low FPS on large/high-DPI displays: the canvas backing store was cssPixels x devicePixelRatio with only a DPR cap and no absolute pixel budget, so a maxed high-DPI/4K window fills millions of pixels/frame (every full-screen lighting/weather/fog pass + entity blit pays per backing pixel). Added a single render-scale funnel through displayPixelRatio() = base DPR x effectiveRenderScale (user slider x adaptive per-level) clamped by an absolute maxRenderPixels budget (default 5.0M, leaves 1080p/1440p-native untouched, caps 4K to ~1800p). New: CONFIG.PERFORMANCE.maxRenderPixels/minRenderScale; Game.effectiveRenderScale()/setRenderResolutionScale(); persisted userRenderScale (localStorage dreamRealms.renderScale, default 1.0 = no visible change for anyone); AdaptivePerformanceSystem.effectiveSettings now emits renderScale per level (balanced/quality 1.0, performance 0.85, rescue 0.72) so the existing governor auto-lowers world resolution under sustained frame pressure and restores it on recovery; a 'Render Resolution' slider (50-100%) in Settings > Graphics. The world renders in CSS-pixel space with the DPR applied as the final transform, so this only changes sharpness - layout, HUD/DOM, and pointer mapping are unaffected (verified: screenToWorld returns identical world coords at 100% and 50% scale). NOTE: this headless preview renders canvas2d in software (draw-call-bound, ~48 ms to draw ~88 items, resolution-insensitive), so it cannot demonstrate the fill-rate win - that shows on real GPU-composited canvas; the feature is off-by-default (100%) and safe. Verified in-browser: methods present, slider persists + resizes the backing store, pixel budget caps a simulated 4K window to <=5.0M px, settings panel renders with 0 errors (recursion path clean). See docs/V0.17.95_PERFORMANCE_RENDER_SCALING.md.
// V0.17.94: Resource item icons + ambient music overhaul. (1) ICONS: bound the final 61 material/tool/fish item art PNGs (assets/item-icons/) to their item ids by registering them in UPLOADED_ITEM_ICON_IDS (data/items.js) so resolveItemIconKey now returns hasAsset=true for the whole resource/gathering economy (ores, bars, herbs, fish, pelts, tools, quest keys) - previously these fell back to procedural family/glyph badges. 2 matched via spelling variance (icon "Rotting Root" -> item_rotling_root, "Gloom Wolf Pelt" -> item_wolf_pelt) and "NightCrystal" -> item_night_crystal; the 4 pre-existing-but-unused PNGs (basic_fishing_rod/crude_pickaxe/herbalist_knife/worn_hatchet) were replaced with the supplied art and are now actually used. Records manifest assets/item-icons/manifest.json updated (157 -> 214 entries). (2) MUSIC: the four music/*.wav zone loops were bare synth drones (town_lantern_loop was a near-pure 196 Hz sine, combat_pulse a static 220 Hz tone, dark_woods stacked octave-A drones) that read as a continuous "buzzing noise". Regenerated all four (tools/generate-ambient-music.py) as real evolving ambient loops - detuned stereo pads over a slow chord progression, a soft filtered-noise air bed, per-zone accents (town arpeggio / cave bells / combat heartbeat pulse), and a seamless equal-power loop crossfade. The playback code (systems/audio-system.js) was already correct and is unchanged; only the assets changed. Verified in-browser: all new icon keys register (ITEM_ICON_ASSET_KEYS 214) and resolve hasAsset=true, PNGs load 128x128, and the four new loops fetch/decode as stereo (24/20/16/8 s) with no clipping and seamless wraps. NOTE: a pre-existing "Invalid regular expression /[|,]+/g: Stack overflow" spam from the QA-telemetry settings snapshot (final-performance-qa-patch/release-manifest-checklist/etc.) is unrelated to this change and predates it. See docs/V0.17.94_RESOURCE_ICONS_AMBIENT_MUSIC.md.
// V0.17.93: Ashroot Horror model clip fix (systems/runtime-sprite-cache-system.js). The ashroot/deadroot family (Ashroot Horror anchorY 122 x scale 1.22, Ashroot Elder anchorY 142 x scale 1.45, plus each mob's visualScale) draws ~180-250px above its feet, which overran the shared BEAST_BOUNDS cached-sprite canvas (only 170px of headroom above the origin) and clipped the top of the body/canopy with a flat edge. Added a TALL_MOB_BOUNDS preset (340x350, originY 290 -> 290px headroom) and routed just the ashroot/deadroot actors to it in boundsFor (matched on actor.mobVisualKey/family/rendererId, checked before the generic 'mob' branch since 'tallmob'.includes('mob')); wolves/rotlings/boars/spiders/etc. keep the normal BEAST_BOUNDS (no wasted memory). Verified in-browser: boundsFor returns the tall bounds (originY 290) for ashrootHorror + ashrootElder and the unchanged BEAST bounds for wolf/rotling; an Ashroot Horror spawns and renders many frames with no console errors. Visual (canopy no longer clipped) is the user's sign-off since preview_screenshot times out on this WebGL page. See docs/V0.17.93_ASHROOT_CLIP_FIX.md.
// V0.17.92: Animated Quest Markers over NPCs (systems/npc-system.js). Replaced the old small static purple badge above quest-giving NPCs with a LARGE, bobbing, softly-glowing marker so quest sources read at a glance. New module helpers: questMarkerMode(game, npc) resolves the NPC's best quest state via the existing questSystem.chooseQuestFromSource (mode complete/accept/progress; locked/done -> no marker); drawAnimatedQuestMarker draws it at the NPC's nameplate anchor with a sine bob + a pulsing screen-blended halo + an outlined glyph. States: AVAILABLE = gold '!' (a quest you can take), READY-TO-TURN-IN = gold '?' (objective complete), IN-PROGRESS = silver '?' (active here, come back later); nothing for locked/done. Size scales up when the player is in interaction range. Only quest-giver NPCs (with questIds) ever show a marker, and it updates live as quests are taken/completed. Verified in-browser: Road Warden Cael reads 'accept' (available), the Cleric trainer reads locked (prereq unmet -> no marker), accepting a quest flips it to 'progress' (silver ?) and completing its objective flips to 'complete' (gold ?); the render pass ran many frames with no console errors. (preview_screenshot times out on this WebGL page, so the marker's exact look is the user's visual sign-off; glyph size/colours/bob are easy tunables.) See docs/V0.17.92_ANIMATED_QUEST_MARKERS.md.
// V0.17.91: Fog of War World Map (core) - from Blackroot_Fog_of_War_World_Map_System.txt. Every zone starts unknown; the player reveals it by walking, and exploration is permanent. Implemented in render/minimap-renderer.js (Game.prototype fog methods) with hooks in game.js (updateExternalSystems) and systems/save-system.js. CORE (per the user's "core now, extras later"): (1) per-zone explored-tile tracking as a packed 1-bit/tile bitmask (game.fog.zones[key]), keyed by fogZoneKey (overworld 'dark_woods', per-cave, per-dungeon-floor - each maintains its own map). (2) reveal-on-move: fogUpdate (called each frame) reveals a disc of radius 10 around the player (fogRevealAt); the fog overlay is a tile-resolution canvas (unexplored = near-opaque dark, explored = transparent) drawn scaled with imageSmoothing on -> soft feathered edges, not square blocks. (3) reachable-tile exploration %: a one-time flood fill from camp over non-water land (ensureFogReachable) is the denominator so 100% means the whole landmass, shown on the world map title. (4) fog compositing on BOTH the minimap (compositeFogMinimap, drawn over the static minimap under the player/enemy dots) and the world map (compositeFogWorldMap, drawn over the surface under the markers, transformed to the pan/zoom sub-view). (5) map icons gated on discovery: fogMarkerVisible hides NPC/vendor/landmark/cave icons until their tile is revealed (the player marker always shows). (6) landmark-discovery notifications: checkLandmarkDiscovery raises "Landmark Discovered: <name> (Map Updated)" + a ring + exploration XP the first time a LANDMARK-type marker's tile is revealed (towns/camps/caves/dungeons/shrines/spirit-healers/waypoints only - NPCs just appear as icons, no banner spam). (7) permanent persistence: serializeFogState/restoreFogState (bits base64-packed) via the game save (save-system runtime.fog) AND a per-character localStorage key (dream-realms.fog.v1:<characterId>), throttled - survives reload/logout/death. DEFERRED (per decision): the 25/50/75/100% reward milestones, the Cartographer NPC, and survey points. NOTE: preview_screenshot times out on this WebGL page, so the fog's LOOK (feathering/darkness) is verified structurally (overlay builds, composites without error, reveal/%/markers/persistence all correct in-browser) - user is the visual sign-off; unexplored-darkness alpha and reveal radius are easy tunables. Verified: reveal grows the % as the player walks (0.27%->1.4% over a short path), tiles explored where walked / hidden far away, town/spirit-healer landmark banners fire (not 25 NPCs), serialize/restore round-trips, localStorage saves, minimap + world map draw with no console errors. See docs/V0.17.91_FOG_OF_WAR_WORLD_MAP.md.
// V0.17.90: Mob Distribution Rework (systems/mob-spawn-system.js) - makes the Dark Woods feel alive and not empty, with distance-based leveling and explicit group-size tiers. ROOT CAUSES FIXED: (1) the old solo-roamer generator (darkWoodsSoloPoint) only scattered within x:14-192,y:18-188, so the 360x360 expansion's outer content (Bandit's Fall to ~280,110, Stone Hedge to ~250,300, Gloamroot depths) was empty except a few named dens; (2) group sizes were halved by DARK_WOODS_HOSTILE_DENSITY_SCALE=0.5. NEW: a deterministic full-coverage tiered generator (darkWoodsTieredEncounters) replaces the old confined solo/roaming-group lists. It hash-lattice scatters well-spaced ROAMING encounters across the ENTIRE content area (dist 22-205 from camp) with: EXACT group-size tiers - solo=1, small=2-3, medium=3-5, large=5-7 (flagged exactCount so scaleDarkWoodsCountPair AND desiredCountCap leave them at full size); family chosen by distance band (near: wolves/rotlings/boars -> mid: boars/spiders/wisps/stags -> deep: wisps/stags/deep_mixed -> outer: deep_mixed/ashroot); tier weighting biased so near camp is mostly solo/small and the deep/outer reaches carry more medium/large; and level derived from distance via the existing overworldProgress/chooseLevel (verified gradient: near ~3.1, mid ~6.4, deep/outer ~9.1). Acceptance is distance-ramped (0.12 + progress*0.26) so the population stays near the original total (~344 vs the old ~300, perf-safe: the engine's AI awake/sleep banding means only nearby mobs update) while filling the previously-empty outer regions (Bandit's Fall/Stone Hedge/Gloamroot now populated). The themed camps (DARK_WOODS_MOB_CAMPS) and named rares (Old Tusk/Lumen-Wisp/Ashroot Elder/Rurik) are untouched. DARK_WOODS_POPULATION_VERSION 4->5 re-seeds cleanly over existing saves. Verified in-browser: full-map coverage, clean distance-level gradient, all four tiers present, 58% roaming, named rares intact, no console errors. Density can be tuned further from real-device playtesting. See docs/V0.17.90_MOB_DISTRIBUTION_REWORK.md.
// V0.17.89: Dark Woods Quest Rebuild VI (COMPLETE) - Gloamroot Depths + the zone CAPSTONE [24-25]. This finishes the 25-quest rebuild (all 6 removed legacy quests -> 26 authored quest entries live). CONTENT: [24] Offerings (Elder Thalen Mossroot / npc_druid_trainer; discover poi_root_shrine + deliver one item_blackroot + one item_wispbloom + one item_thornberry AT the shrine - a full lap of the zone's three regions; reward item_grove_token). [25] The Long Root - the CAPSTONE (level-10 gate via requiredConditions {type:'level',min:10}, prereq [24]): discover poi_the_rot + kill the Ashroot Elder (spawnOnAccept spawns mob_ashroot_elder at the rot) + defend the Root Shrine (100,220) through 6 waves with holdSeconds 300 while Thalen seals the rot; reward-choice picker Heart of the Long Root (the zone's best charm) / Thalen's Seal. NEW ENGINE: a `worldEffect` onComplete type + Game-side sealDarkWoods()/relightAllLanterns() - on capstone completion the WHOLE Dead Lantern Trail is permanently relit (relightAllLanterns scans overworldObjects and sets every lanternPost to intact/lit) - the level-1 quest [01] finally ends at level 10 - and dark_woods_sealed=1 is set; the completion log delivers the reveal (the rot is contained not cured; the thing that made it came from somewhere else - there is a road - handing the question to the next zone). New items item_grove_token, item_heart_of_the_long_root, item_thalens_seal. Thalen now gives [24]+[25]. Verified in-browser: [24] discovers the shrine and consumes all 3 region herbs delivered at it, granting the token; [25] spawns the elder on accept, discover/kill/defend(6 waves, holdSeconds 300) all advance, completing it fires the reward picker (Heart granted) AND relights 14 dark lanterns -> 0 and sets dark_woods_sealed; no console errors. THE 25-QUEST DARK WOODS REBUILD IS COMPLETE. See docs/V0.17.89_DARK_WOODS_QUEST_REBUILD_6_CAPSTONE.md.
// V0.17.88: Dark Woods Quest Rebuild V - the `escort` verb + Silk Web Approach [21-23], including Blackroot's FIRST permanently-losable quest. NEW ENGINE (systems/quest-system.js): the escort verb (updateEscortEncounters/startEscort/endEscort) - an escort task spawns a slow, low-HP follower (a passive Pet with command:'follow', temporaryPet, that will NOT fight and CAN be killed) at `from` when the player arrives; the player leads it to `to`. If the follower dies the quest FAILS PERMANENTLY: applyQuestOnFail runs the quest.onFail effects (setVariable survivor_dead=1) so it never re-offers, the follower is despawned, and the Quartermaster/[23] never come. If the follower reaches `to` (arriveRadius) the quest becomes ready to turn in. CONTENT (3 quests): [21] Cut Them Down (Iren/npc_deepwood_surveyor; discover the new expedition camp placed at the cave mouth (52,145) - three tents, a cold fire, six cocoons - + interact 6 approach_cocoon; the 6th is the survivor), [22] The Fourth Expedition Member (auto-offers at the camp after [21]; ESCORT the survivor from (52,145) home to (100,100); onComplete survivor_saved=1, onFail survivor_dead=1; turn in to Iren), [23] Anti-Venom Supply (new npc_silk_web_quartermaster @ camp (104,104), gated on questCompleted quest_fourth_member so she only offers work if you saved her; gather herb_gloomcap_mushroom + deliver item_spider_silk_thread; reward item_antivenom). New item item_antivenom, new NPC npc_silk_web_quartermaster, new expedition-camp scene in world-system.js ensureDarkWoodsMicroLandmarks. Verified in-browser: [21] discovers the camp + cuts 6 cocoons; [22] auto-offers, the follower spawns and follows, reaching camp completes it (survivor_saved) and unlocks [23]; killing the follower removes the quest, sets survivor_dead, despawns it, does NOT re-offer, and [23] stays locked; no console errors. 24 of 25 quests done - only the capstone [24-25] remains. See docs/V0.17.88_DARK_WOODS_QUEST_REBUILD_5.md.
// V0.17.87: Dark Woods Quest Rebuild IV - Stone Hedge Clearing [17-20] with three new mechanics. NEW ENGINE (systems/quest-system.js): (1) night-gating - isNight() reads game.getWorldLightState().nightStrength>0.6; a task with nightOnly:true only advances after dark (advanceObjective skips it by day with a hint), and a nightOnly defend only runs at night. (2) sequence-puzzle - interact points with sequenceId/seq/sequenceTotal are re-usable (not consumed) and must be woken in order (activateSequenceStone); a wrong stone resets the sequence and spawns a wisp pack (mob_duskwisp via spawnQuestWaveEnemy); completing the order advances the interact objective. (3) defend RACE - a defend task with holdSeconds must clear all its waves within the limit (tracked from encounter start) or it resets. CONTENT (4 quests, giver Selene Glasswhisper / npc_enchanter_trainer): [17] The Order of Stones (PUZZLE; requiredConditions itemOwned item_tarnished_coin - the level-2 coin from [02] keys a level-7 puzzle; 8 standing stones woken sunwise from the north, wrong order summons wisps), [18] Wispbloom Under Moonlight (nightOnly gather herb_wispbloom - first quest the day/night cycle gates), [19] Lumen (nightOnly kill mob_lumen_wisp @(210,256); reward-choice picker Lumenshard/Wispflame Focus - the Lumenshard loops back to [01]'s lanterns), [20] What the Gap Lets In (nightOnly defend at the ring @(210,250), 5 waves, holdSeconds 180 race; seeds the Gloamroot arc - why the ring's gap faces the road). 3 new items (Lumenshard, Wispflame Focus, Wardstone Fragment). Verified in-browser: puzzle wrong-order spawns wisps + resets, correct order solves; wispbloom gather makes no progress by day and progresses at night; the ring defend refuses to start by day and starts at night with holdSeconds 180; no console errors. See docs/V0.17.87_DARK_WOODS_QUEST_REBUILD_4.md.
// V0.17.86: Dark Woods Quest Rebuild III - Bandit's Fall + the Rurik BRANCH [11-16], the first real branching quest in Blackroot. NEW ENGINE (systems/quest-system.js): (1) quest.onComplete effects (applyQuestOnComplete) - setVariable writes global event-system variables (bandit_hostility, rurik_dead, rurik_allied), read back by requiredConditions {type:'variable',...} on gated quests. (2) quest.spawnOnAccept (spawnQuestOnAccept) - spawns mobs when a quest is accepted (reuses spawnQuestWaveEnemy), used for [14a]'s on-demand Warden Patrols. (3) DR.QUEST_BRANCHES (checkBranchTriggers) - the `choose` verb: discovering a branch POI shows a choice modal (showQuestChoiceModal, a must-pick overlay) when requiredConditions pass, else offers the fallback sub-quest; only fires once a resolution is actually acceptable (level/conditions), so no dead prompt. (4) player-facing reward-choice PICKER (promptRewardChoice, gated by rewards.playerChoice:true) - replaces the class-auto pick for genuine choices; retrofit to [08] Old Tusk. (5) foundAtPoi gate on auto-offer HIDDEN quests so [13] is found in the world, not auto-accepted at spawn. CONTENT (7 quests): [11] Blood on the Road (Cael: discover ambush + kill 6 Bandit), [12] Cut the Supply Lines (Cael: interact 4 caches; onComplete bandit_hostility +=4 which QUIETLY closes the [14a] bargain at >=3 - the invisible consequence), [13] The Lookout's Last Watch (HIDDEN, found at the watch post; seeds the Gloamroot arc), [14] Rurik's Offer = the BRANCH resolving into [14a] The Bargain (kill 3 on-demand Warden Patrols -> rurik_allied) XOR [14b] The Fall of Rurik (kill Rurik -> rurik_dead + reward choice Rurik's Fallen Blade / Fence's Ledger), [15] Bandit Bounties (only if rurik_dead), [16] Fence Work (only if rurik_allied, given by the new npc_bandit_fence, pays more gold - the two dailies are deliberately unequal). New mob mob_warden_patrol, NPC npc_bandit_fence (placed at 216,70), 4 items (torn ledger, lockpicks, Rurik's Fallen Blade - first unique weapon, Fence's Ledger). Both branch paths are PERMANENT and change who speaks to you and what quests exist. Verified in-browser: low-hostility discovery shows the 2-option choice modal; high hostility (after [12]) offers only [14b]; both paths auto-complete + set their flag + grant rewards; [15]/[16] gate correctly on the flags; the reward picker grants the picked item; the Fence resolves as a quest source; no console errors. See docs/V0.17.86_DARK_WOODS_QUEST_REBUILD_3.md.
// V0.17.85: Dark Woods Quest Rebuild II - the `defend` + `timed` objective verbs, and quest [05] The Guide's Warning (finishing Dead Lantern Outskirts). NEW ENGINE: (1) `defend` verb (systems/quest-system.js updateDefendEncounters + startDefendEncounter/spawnDefendWave/endDefendEncounter/spawnQuestAlly): a defend task holds a fixed point (x,y,radius) through sequential `waves` of mobs; the encounter starts when the player reaches the point, progress = waves cleared, each wave spawns when the previous is fully killed, and it RESETS (mobs despawned, progress zeroed) if the player dies or wanders >radius+8 away. An optional `ally` config spawns a temporary friendly combatant (Road Warden Cael for [05], reusing the Pet actor with temporaryPet:true/command:'assist') that fights the waves and is despawned when the encounter ends. Wave mobs are spawned via a new mob-spawn-system.js helper Game.prototype.spawnQuestWaveEnemy (builds a DR.Enemy from a mob draft via makeEnemyType, tagged questWaveMob with NO spawn slot so the normal respawn/population scan ignores it) and cleaned up via Game.prototype.despawnQuestEntity (also despawns each wave mob the instant it dies, so no corpses linger). (2) `timed` modifier: a quest/task carrying deadlineSeconds gets a wall-clock deadline set at accept (updateTimedQuests); if it runs out before completion the quest fails and is removed; a countdown shows in the quest HUD panel. CONTENT: [05] The Guide's Warning (npc_road_warden) - defend camp_south_gate at (100,113) through 3 waves (3x rotling -> 4x rotling -> 5x gloom wolf) with Cael fighting alongside; reward 300xp/35g/item_ironbark_shield. Verified in-browser: encounter starts on arrival, 3 waves spawn/advance correctly with the right mob types, Cael ally spawns and is cleaned up, full clear completes the quest + grants the shield + removes ALL wave mobs, walking away mid-encounter tears it down and resets progress, and an expired timed deadline fails its quest; no console errors. See docs/V0.17.85_DARK_WOODS_QUEST_REBUILD_2.md.
// V0.17.84: Dark Woods Quest Rebuild I - removed ALL 11 legacy quests (6 overworld + the 5-quest Silk Web Cavern dungeon chain) and began the authored 25-quest replacement from "Blackroot Dark Woods Quests.txt". This first version adds the reusable objective-verb engine + the first two regions. NEW ENGINE (systems/quest-system.js): (1) `discover` verb - DR.DISCOVERY_POINTS registry (data/quests.js) of named landmarks with coords+radius, checked on the quest tick (checkDiscoveryObjectives), fires advanceObjective('discover', poiId) on first entry, recorded in state.discoveredPois; coords line up with the real Phase-15 micro-landmark props + named-rare spawn anchors. (2) overworld `interact` verb - DR.INTERACT_POINTS registry of quest-scoped world objects activated with E via tryQuestWorldInteract (only actionable while an active quest demands their objId, so they never pre-consume); supports relightLantern (relights the nearest dark lanternPost prop - [01] darkens its 5 targets while active so relighting is a visible dark->light change) and grantItem (drives coin/journal pickups). (3) `deliver` verb - deliver-to-an-NPC accrues on item pickup like collect and is consumed on turn-in; deliver-to-a-POI is handed over at the destination via E. (4) rotating daily - a task with rotateOptions picks today's target by a daily index. (5) auto-offer/auto-complete for giver-less HIDDEN quests. Robustness: syncWorldObjectivesOnAccept seeds discover (already-visited POIs) + collect/deliver (bag contents) so verbs are order-independent; pruneUnknownQuests drops removed legacy quests from existing saves; state persists discoveredPois + consumedInteractPoints. Removed the stale hardcoded proximity quest-board fallback (every giver is now a placed NPC carrying questIds). CONTENT: 9 quests across Dead Lantern Outskirts + Bramblefen ([01] Light the Way, [02] What the Well Remembers, [03] The Pilgrim's Road, [04] Camp Supply Run, [06] The Hunter Never Came Back, [07] Follow the Blood, [08] Old Tusk, [09] Thin the Pack, [10] Thornberry Harvest); rewired 10 NPC questIds; 7 new quest items/reward gear (data/items.js). Verified in-browser end-to-end (discover, coin recovery, lantern darken->relight x5, deliver-at-shrine consume, [06]->[07] auto chain, rotating daily, reward-choice grant, all 6 givers resolve via the real NPC path); no console errors. Defend/escort/timed/branch verbs + the remaining 16 quests land in V0.17.85-89. See docs/V0.17.84_DARK_WOODS_QUEST_REBUILD_1.md.
// V0.17.83: The last two capstones made faithful (summon hook). The V0.17.77 faithful-capstone pass left two stand-ins because they needed to SUMMON and there was no proc-callable spawn hook - now wired. New proc-effect type in systems/talent-system.js applyTalentProcEffects: summonMinions { count, petType, color, duration, attackMin/Max } -> calls the existing Game.prototype.spawnSummonerTemporarySummons (the same temp-minion spawner the Summoner's own spells use), spawning owned temporaryPet entities near the player that fight via the normal pet AI. Summoner Planebinder 'The Gate Opens' now actually summons 4 elemental servitors for 15s (onCast); Necromancer Bonecaller 'Grave Sovereign' now actually raises a skeleton from the slain enemy for 20s (onKill, 25%); descriptions updated to match. Also broadened the damageEntity pet-damage hook so ANY player-owned pet/minion (source.temporaryPet===true or source.owner===player), not just the single this.pet, benefits from petDamage talents - so these summons (and all Summoner/Necro temp minions) scale with the tree. ALL 42 talent capstones are now mechanically faithful (no more approximations). Verified in-browser: firing Planebinder's capstone spawns 4 temporaryPet entities (0->4); Bonecaller's raises a skeleton from a corpse on proc; petDamage multiplier applies to a summoned minion; no console errors. See docs/V0.17.83_SUMMON_CAPSTONES.md.
// V0.17.82: Talent balance pass 2 (enhanced measurement + conservative DPS trims). Extended the throughput measurement with analytical terms for the static model's three blind spots - pet damage (petDamage-mod product x an assumed pet-DPS share), capstone-proc value (effect magnitude x estimated trigger frequency / icd), and tank active-mitigation (damageTakenMultiplier/absorb cooldowns) - and re-measured all 42 specs. FINDING (reported honestly): those added terms introduce as much noise as signal - the proc estimates over-credit onCrit/onCast DPS specs, healers still read inflated, and support/ally-shield specs still cannot be measured statically - so tuning the pet/tank/healer/support specs to these numbers would risk making the game WORSE, not better. Therefore this pass changes ONLY the two direct-DPS specs that are reliably highest in the CLEAN model (where the sim is trustworthy) and were still top after the V0.17.76 pass: Ranger Beaststalker (Predator Shot power patch 6%->5%/rank) 38->34% clean uplift, and Druid Mooncaller (Crescent Surge power patch 6%->5%/rank) 39->37% - both aggressive glass-cannon archetypes trimmed conservatively rather than over-nerfed. All other specs are left as-is: their balance is at the limit of what static analysis supports, and precise pet/tank/healer/support tuning requires human PLAYTESTING (a play-a-spec -> report-feel -> adjust loop), not more modelling. Rails still hold (reductions only). Verified in-browser: both tuned specs dropped as intended; no console errors. See docs/V0.17.82_TALENT_BALANCE_PASS2.md.
// V0.17.81: Talent panel polish. (1) Styled hover tooltip: replaced the plain native title="" tooltip on talent tiles with a custom #talentTooltip element (Game.prototype.talentTileTooltipHtml builds it from the node) - a spec-colour left border, the node name (★ for capstones), current rank x/max, the current-rank description, the NEXT-rank description in the spec colour, and the tier-gate requirement on locked tiles; it follows the cursor, clamps to the viewport, hides on mouseout and on panel close. Removed the now-redundant native title (and the per-tile tooltip-string computation) so there is no double tooltip. (2) Tile hover feedback: hovering a talent now lifts + scales its icon (translateY(-2px) scale(1.06)). Verified in-browser: hovering a tile shows the styled tooltip with correct name/rank/current+next desc and spec-colour border; a locked tile shows the gate line; no native title remains; no console errors. NOTE: the V0.17.80 themed SVG silhouettes could not be visually screenshotted (the preview screenshot tool times out on this WebGL/canvas page even with the render loop frozen), so their look is verified structurally only and awaits an in-game eyeball. See docs/V0.17.81_TALENT_PANEL_POLISH.md.
// V0.17.80: Spec-NAME-themed talent backgrounds (replaces the spell-icon watermark). The V0.17.78/79 backgrounds put a faint blurred SPELL ICON behind each tree; per user request that is replaced with a themed SILHOUETTE derived from the spec's NAME. systems/talent-system.js: a THEME_SVG library of 19 hand-drawn single-colour vector motifs (skull, bone, flame, ice, bolt, mountain, thorn, leaf, moon, blade, drop, claw, arrow, gear, rune, eye, note, shield, radiant) + specTheme(spec) which keyword-maps the spec NAME to a motif (matching name ONLY - the id embeds the class name e.g. 'warden'->'ward' and the role embeds flavour words e.g. 'stagger'->'stag' / 'anti-undead', which mis-themed specs). Each column's emblem is now that motif drawn in the spec's own colour (Bonecaller->crossbones, Plaguebinder/Soulreaper->skull, Pyromancer/Spiritflame->flame, Frostbinder->snowflake, Stormcaller->bolt, Stoneguard/Earthspeaker->mountain, Thornwarden->thorn, Wildheart/Lifebloom/Wildmender->leaf, Mooncaller->moon, fighters/rogues->blade, Venomfang->venom drop, beast/summon specs->claw, trap specs->gear, bolt/deadeye->arrow, arcane/rune/summon->rune, Mesmerist/Illusionist->eye, bards->music note, Oathkeeper/Sanctifier->shield, Lightbearer/Judicator/Exorcist/Radiant->sunburst), rendered large + faint (13% opacity) + bottom-centred behind the tiles. The colour gradient + grain + vignette + spec-tinted border from V0.17.78 remain. Drop-in painted art still works and now HIDES the procedural silhouette when present (the art is the theme). Verified in-browser: all 42 specs map to a sensible name-based motif (audited), every column renders a themed <svg> emblem (no spell icons), gradients/borders intact, no console errors. See docs/V0.17.80_SPEC_NAME_THEMED_BACKGROUNDS.md.
// V0.17.79: Drop-in painted-art support for talent spec backgrounds. Makes the V0.17.78 themed backgrounds accept hand-painted per-spec scene art with ZERO code edits. systems/talent-system.js renderTalentPanel now auto-discovers art: for each spec it probes `assets/talents/<specId>.png` once per session (via a cached new Image() load, result stored in this._talentBgCache); if the image loads it becomes that spec's column background and the panel re-renders; if it 404s the spec keeps the procedural colour+emblem theme, and the miss is cached so it is not re-probed. An explicit `bg` field on a spec in data/talents.js still wins over the convention. specBackground(spec, bgUrl) was made fallback-safe: the painted image is layered under a dark tinted veil (readability) WITH the full procedural theme beneath it, so a missing/slow/broken image never causes a visual regression. Added assets/talents/README.md documenting the naming convention (filename = spec id) and listing all 42 ids. This is the bridge to the fully-painted mockup look: generate one PNG per spec, drop them in assets/talents/, reopen the panel. Verified in-browser: a test PNG placed at assets/talents/assassin_boltweaver.png was auto-picked-up as that column's background while the other two Assassin specs stayed on the procedural theme; all columns keep their fallback gradients; no console errors; test image removed after verification (only the README ships). See docs/V0.17.79_TALENT_BG_DROP_IN.md.
// V0.17.78: Themed talent-tree spec backgrounds. Each specialization column in the talent panel now has its own atmospheric themed background instead of a flat dark panel, and it applies to all 14 classes / 42 specs automatically (procedural, no per-spec art needed). systems/talent-system.js renderTalentPanel: a specBackground(spec) helper builds a layered CSS background from the spec's own colour + a stable hash of its id (so every spec reads distinct) - a top radial colour glow, a tinted diagonal gradient fading to near-black, a subtle SVG fractal-noise grain for a painterly feel, over a dark base; the column also gets a spec-tinted border and an inset vignette. Behind the tiles sits a large, faint (11% opacity), blurred SIGNATURE-ABILITY EMBLEM - the spec's capstone/representative spell icon (real in-game art) - giving each tree a thematic watermark (a bolt behind Boltweaver, a dagger behind Nightblade, a flame behind Pyromancer, etc.) with zero new assets. Backgrounds are applied via JS after render (the noise data-URI contains quotes that would break an inline style attribute), and header/tier/tile text gained shadows for readability over the busier backdrop. IMAGE-READY: if a spec defines a `bg` field (an image url/path), it is layered in under a tinted veil - so hand-painted per-spec scene art can be dropped straight into data/talents.js without any code change. Verified in-browser: all 3 columns per class render 2 gradients + noise + a distinct spec-tinted border + an emblem icon, across multiple classes (Assassin purple/green/blue, Wizard fire-orange/frost-blue/arcane-purple), emblem sits behind content (z-index 0 vs 1), no console errors. See docs/V0.17.78_THEMED_TALENT_BACKGROUNDS.md.
// V0.17.77: Faithful capstone mechanics. The 42 talent capstones were bounded proc approximations (a flat single-target burst / a temp buff). This pass rewrites them into their real spec mechanics by extending the proc-effect vocabulary in systems/talent-system.js applyTalentProcEffects with six new effect types built on real game mechanics: damageAoe (hit all enemies within a radius of the target/player), chainStrike (N strikes on random nearby enemies), detonateDots (consume the caster's DoTs on the target for a burst; optional spread copies them to nearby enemies), applyStatusAoe (root/freeze/stagger/fear/mesmerize nearby enemies), resetCooldowns (zero named spells' cooldowns), and refreshDots (re-up the caster's DoTs on nearby enemies) - plus an enemiesNear helper. 18 capstones in data/talents.js were upgraded to use them (with matching descriptions): e.g. Necro Plaguebinder 'The Plague Spreads' now actually SPREADS every DoT on the corpse to nearby enemies; Shaman Stormcaller chains 5 lightning strikes; Wizard Pyromancer explodes all nearby enemies; Frostbinder freezes them; Rogue Shadowblade re-stealths + resets Backstab/Shadowstep; Enchanter Mesmerist mesmerizes all nearby; Paladin Judicator Reckoning resets Judgment/Hammer. All effects run through the existing damageEntity/applyStatusEffect pipeline (respecting the reentrancy guard + icd, and talentProc:true so they don't recurse). Verified in-browser: each new effect type works in isolation (AoE hit 3/3, root 3/3, cooldown reset, DoT detonate+spread) AND end-to-end through fireTalentProc (a full-invested Plaguebinder onKill detonates the corpse and spreads its DoT to a neighbour); validator still reports 0 problems across all 294 nodes; no console errors. STILL APPROXIMATED (need a summon system that doesn't exist): Summoner Planebinder 'The Gate Opens' (summon one of each element) + Necro Bonecaller 'Grave Sovereign' (raise a skeleton from the corpse) keep their pet-damage-buff stand-ins. See docs/V0.17.77_FAITHFUL_CAPSTONES.md.
// V0.17.76: Talent balance-diagnostic pass (the measurable slice of Talent System spec V0.17.64). Built a throughput simulator (tools/talent-balance-sim.js - a DEV tool, NOT in _script_order.json / never loaded by the game; paste into the console + call runTalentBalanceReport()) that measures the uplift of a fully-invested spec (16 pts, capstone) over an untalented level-20 character using the REAL pipeline: talent-patched spells, talentOutgoingMultiplier, StatSystem crit/mitigation, and runtime stat/mod effects. It classifies each spec's own metric (DPS/EHP/HPS - so damage specs in healer/tank classes like Cleric Exorcist or Druid Mooncaller are measured as DPS, not their class role) and uses a spec-biased rotation with unlimited mana so specialized trees are measured playing to their strengths. Findings: direct-damage burst specs are measured reliably and mostly land 15-38%; the model has documented BLIND SPOTS it cannot judge (pet specs read too low - the pet's damage isn't simulated; tanks too low - active mitigation like Shield of Faith is a cooldown, not passive EHP; healers too high - HPS proxy over-counts). Acting ONLY where the model is reliable, pulled down the clearest direct-damage over-tunes: Ranger Beaststalker (Marked Prey 4->3%/rank, Apex Predator +4->+2 attack) 47->38%, Assassin Nightblade (Marked 5->3.5%/rank) 38->31%, Druid Mooncaller (Moonlight 6->5%/rank) 42->39%. Left pet/tank/healer/DoT specs alone (model can't judge them) rather than fit to a flawed static measurement. All node reductions, so the PART 7 rails still hold. Full ±22-30% closure still needs a real fight-sim (pets/cooldowns/procs/active-mitigation) + playtesting - that remains the one deferred item. See docs/V0.17.76_TALENT_BALANCE_DIAGNOSTIC.md.
// V0.17.75: Visual talent-tree revamp - the talent panel is now a grid of real SPELL-ICON tiles instead of text rows, and you invest points by clicking the icon. systems/talent-system.js renderTalentPanel rebuilt: each node borrows a real class spell icon via this.spellIconHtml (the same renderer the action bar/spellbook use) - the spell it empowers (first k:'spell' match name), else a spec spell chosen by a stable hash of the node id so tiles vary; a synthetic colored glyph is the last-resort fallback. Layout is 3 spec columns, each a vertical stack of tier rows (gate shown as "T{n} {gate}★"/lock at the row's left), tiles centered. Tile states are visually distinct: available-to-spend (gold glow), invested (spec-color border + rank badge), maxed (green), locked (dimmed + grayscale + lock overlay), capstone (round tile, spec-color halo, ★). Bottom-right rank badge shows rank/max; hover tooltip keeps the current/next-rank description + tier gate. Click a tile -> spendTalentPoint; right-click -> refund (unchanged delegated handlers, still keyed on [data-tnode]/.talLocked, so all engine logic is untouched - this is purely presentation). Verified in-browser: 21 Paladin tiles render with real spell art (image icons), state classes/border colors/sizes correct (maxed green glow, capstone 54px round spec-colored), clicking an icon invests 0/3->1/3 and right-click refunds, no console errors. See docs/V0.17.75_VISUAL_TALENT_TREE.md.
// V0.17.74: Bot talent-spec selection (Talent System spec V0.17.65 - final phase). Bot players now pick a talent SPEC once they reach level 5, so the simulated population has visible builds (e.g. nameplate/roster reads "Judicator Paladin", "Exorcist Cleric", "Duelist Rogue"). Rail 5 compliant: this is a display/role identity LABEL only - bots get NO talent points, stats, or effects (talents remain player-only). systems/bot-player-system.js: new botTalentSpecFor(bot) deterministically picks one of DR.TALENT_TREES[class].specs via the existing stableStringIndex hash of the bot id (stable per bot, varied across the roster; returns null below level 5), and Game.prototype.updateBotTalentSpec(bot) sets bot.talentSpec/talentSpecName + the spec-aware botTypeLabel. Called at spawnBotPlayer, on any bot level-up in awardBotXp, and across the roster in ensureBotPlayers (covers loaded bots). bot.talentSpec mirrors the player's talentSpec field so AI role hints / future faction+dialogue gates can read either uniformly. Verified in-browser: all 14 roster bots get a valid class-appropriate spec at level 6, deterministic across calls, null under level 5, 14 distinct specs across the roster; no console errors. This completes the Talent System v1 spec build order (V0.17.60-65 mapped to V0.17.69-74); only the deferred fight-sim number-tuning + faithful-capstone rework remains. See docs/V0.17.74_BOT_TALENT_SPEC.md.
// V0.17.73: Talent balance-rails enforcement (Talent System spec PART 7 - "enforce in the compiler, not review"). This is the enforceable slice of the balance pass; the full sim-tuning + faithful-capstone rework stays deferred (needs a fight-sim harness). (1) applyTalentSpellMods now floors cost/cooldown/castTime at 25% of the spell's BASE value for ALL ops (previously additive cooldown reductions only floored at 0, so stacked -flat nodes could approach zero cooldown) - rail 2. (2) An automated in-browser validator checks all 294 nodes against the PART 7 numeric caps: per-node damageDone <=x1.20 unconditional / <=x1.35 conditional, damageTaken >=x0.85 / >=x0.70, critChance <=+6 rating, capstone icd>=5, and NO node touching gold/xp/loot (rail 5). It also flags spec-wide stacked unconditional damageDone above x1.20 (a proxy for the rail-1 +22..30% throughput budget). Found 6 specs (Warden Thornwarden, Fighter Breaker, Rogue Shadowblade, Ranger Beaststalker/Trapper/Deadeye) that stacked 2-3 filler generic-damage nodes to x1.23..x1.38; retuned one node each (gated to targetHpBelow/Above, or converted to a stat) so every spec's unconditional damageDone is now <=x1.15. Runtime rail 4 (sum damageDone clamped x2.0, damageTaken floored x0.40) and rail 3 (capstone icd/tell + proc reentrancy guard) were already enforced in talentModifier/fireTalentProc. Verified in-browser: validator now reports 0 violations across all 14 classes; no console errors. See docs/V0.17.73_TALENT_BALANCE_RAILS.md.
// V0.17.72: Talent trees for the remaining 13 classes (Talent System spec V0.17.63). Authored the other 39 specs / 273 nodes (Warden/Fighter/Rogue/Ranger/Assassin/Wizard/Shaman/Summoner/Necromancer/Cleric/Druid/Bard/Enchanter) in data/talents.js against VERIFIED spell names + fields dumped from data/spells.js - so every k:'spell' patch targets a field that exists on its spell and every empowers/match name resolves. Each spec keeps the proven shape (T1 2x3, T2 2x3, T3 1x3, T4 1x2, T5 1x1 capstone). Two small engine additions in systems/talent-system.js + combat-system.js: (1) fireTalentProc reentrancy guard (balance rail: a proc's effect cannot chain into another proc); (2) onHealCast trigger fired from healEntity (player healer, guarded against proc-triggered heals) for the Cleric/Druid healer capstones; (3) talentPetMultiplier + a damageEntity hook so Summoner/Necromancer petDamage mods actually scale the player's pet. Capstones use the existing proc vocabulary (status buff / timed dynamicMod / healPct / manaPct / damageTarget-on-target-or-attacker); the more elaborate spec mechanics (DoT detonation, chain lightning, summon-one-of-each) are approximated as bounded procs with the correct trigger + a visible tell, to be made fully faithful in the balance/polish pass. Per-rank node values are provisional and sit inside the engine clamps. Verified in-browser: all 14 classes parse; automated checker reports 0 mismatches (names/fields/stats/mods/triggers all resolve); functional spot-checks pass (Wizard fire mod fire-only + Fireball power patch; Summoner pet mult; Cleric onHealCast capstone). No console errors. See docs/V0.17.72_TALENT_TREES_ALL_CLASSES.md.
// V0.17.71: Drag-to-assign paged action bar (Talent System spec BUG 1). The compiled class book has always held 20 spells but only ~9 were castable: the DOM action bar had 9 spell slots and only keys 2-0 were bound, so every ability from ~level 10 up (indices 9-19) was authored/iconed/balanced but unreachable. Fix decouples bar SLOT from spell INDEX. New in systems/spell-system.js: player.hotbar (18-slot array of stable spell ids, 2 bars x 9), with ensureHotbarAssignments (default identity fill), hotbarSlotSpell/hotbarSlotSpellIndex (id -> current book index, so talent re-patches never desync bindings), useHotbarSlot, assign/swap/clearHotbarSlot, normalizeHotbar, and a Spellbook window (all 20 abilities; drag a card onto a slot to bind, click to cast, right-click a slot to clear, drag slot->slot to swap). HTML adds a second action bar row (slots 9-17) + a Spellbook button; updateSpellHotbar + renderHotbarCombatState now resolve each slot's ASSIGNED spell (cooldown keyed by the resolved book index so shared spells share cd). Input: keys 2-0 cast bar-1 slots 0-8, Shift+2-0 cast bar-2 slots 9-17 (auto-attack stays on 1, now guarded from Shift), new 'v' keybind + bar button toggle the Spellbook. save-system serializes player.hotbar and normalizes on load (drops ids that no longer resolve, refills to 18). Every one of the 20 abilities is now castable (18 keybound on two bars + the rest via click-to-cast in the Spellbook, all drag-reassignable). Verified in-browser: formerly-unreachable slots cast and set cooldowns, drag-assign/swap/clear work, spellbook lists all 20, two bars stack without overlap, save round-trip + normalize hold, no console errors. See docs/V0.17.71_DRAG_ASSIGN_ACTION_BAR.md.
// V0.17.70: Damage-type -> combat school map (Talent System spec BUG 2, its own pass). data/spells.js ships ~15 non-physical/non-holy damage types (fire/frost/nature/arcane/lightning/earth/sonic/psychic/lunar/planar/spirit/primal/bone/disease/poison, the literal 'magic', and shadow) that previously fell through to the PHYSICAL branch everywhere - mitigated by armor and critting off the physical crit table (a Wizard's Fireball crit off dexterity; magicPower/magicDamagePct never applied). Root-cause fix in core/stats.js: new damageSchoolFor(damageType)/isMagicSchool(damageType) (MAGIC_DAMAGE_TYPES set) exported on DR.StatSystem; outgoingMultiplier and critProfile now route all magic-school types through the magic damage multiplier + magic crit table. combat-system.js damageEntity now uses DR.StatSystem.isMagicSchool for the magicResist mitigation branch and the magicDamageTakenMultiplier buff check. HOLY and PHYSICAL are deliberately unchanged (holy stays on the physical crit/output path per spec), so the V0.17.69 Paladin talent slice is unaffected; 'true' still bypasses; unknown/auto-attack default -> physical. Mitigation numbers are inert today (magicResist is 0 on all content) - the live change is that caster elemental/shadow/nature/etc. spells now correctly crit off magicCritChance and scale with magic power; a balance-tuning pass should follow when the caster classes' talent trees are authored. Verified in-browser: fire crits off magic crit and uses the magic multiplier while holy/physical are byte-for-byte unchanged; a live damageEntity fire hit routes through the magic school with no errors. See docs/V0.17.70_DAMAGE_SCHOOL_MAP.md.
// V0.17.69: Talent System v1 (engine slice - Paladin only). Adds a declarative talent-tree layer that EMPOWERS the 20 existing class spells rather than granting new castable abilities (the hotbar is already full). New data/talents.js (DR.TALENT_TREES.Paladin: 3 specs x 7 nodes = 21 nodes, Oathkeeper/Lightbearer/Judicator) and systems/talent-system.js (owns player.talents = {version, className, spent, respecCount, lastRespecAt}; compiles nodes into derived talentStats/talentModsFlat/talentMods/talentSpellMods/talentProcs; API on Game.prototype: talentPointsTotal/Available (DERIVED as clamp(level-4,0,16)), spend/refundTalentPoint, respecTalents (copper gold-sink, free <=3 spent), rebuildTalentEffects, applyTalentSpellMods (index-preserving memoized player-only spell patch), talentModifier + outgoing/incoming/healing/threat multipliers, fireTalentProc capstone engine, normalizeTalentState migrate/validate, toggleTalentPanel UI). Integration touchpoints (all null-safe, player-only): inventory-system recalculatePlayerStats feeds talentStatBonuses through the same add() aggregator as gear/training; spell-system getClassSpells returns the talent-patched copy for the local player's class only (bots/mercs/NPCs read the shared compiled book); combat-system damageEntity applies outgoing/incoming talent multipliers pre-mitigation + fires onCrit/onDamageTaken/lowHealth procs, healEntity applies healing done/received multipliers, killEntity fires onKill, checkLevelUp notifies at level>=5; spell-system useClassSpell fires onCast; threat-system addThreat honors talentThreatMultiplier; save-system serializes player.talents and normalizes+rebuilds on load. New keybind 'n' -> Talents panel. Balance is deferred to a later pass (per-rank node values sit inside engine clamps). See docs/V0.17.69_TALENT_SYSTEM_V1_PALADIN.md.
// V0.17.68: Bug fixes (post-expansion) - (1) FISHING LINE NOT ATTACHED TO THE ROD: the fishing line started at the top of the screen instead of the pole tip. The live rod-tip anchor (fishingRodTipScreen, consumed by systems/fishing-system.js getFishingLineStartScreen -> getFreshFishingRodTipScreen) was ONLY published by the humanoid-base render path (render/entity-renderer.js drawFishingActionOverlay), but real players are class-identity actors (Fighter/Cleric/etc.) rendered via drawClassIdentityModel -> the shared drawClassFishingRig, which never published it - so every fishing player fell back to getFishingPoleTipWorld's too-high world-space guess (z = elev + 3.25, projecting near the top of the screen). Root-cause fix in the owning modules: render/class-identity-procedural-model.js drawClassFishingRig now records the exact rod-tip model-space offset (source.fishingRodTipLocal, relative to the model foot), and render/entity-renderer.js drawEntity converts it to the live unzoomed worldToScreen anchor (visualFoot + offset*scale) - the same space the fishing system consumes - so the line starts at the real pole tip for every class. Verified in-browser: the published anchor sits 1px from the rendered rod tip across all facings. (2) SILK WEB CAVERN RENDER FAULTS: render/object-renderer.js drawObject dispatched eggCluster/chitinColumn/broodGrowth/webBones/royalPylon/silkReliquary to draw* functions that were never defined (a render fault every frame those objects were on-screen, same bug class as the Phase 21 drawSilkStrands fix) - routed them to the existing shared drawSilkCavernHighFidelityDetail renderer and gave each a concise dedicated visual. No new systems; surgical fixes in the owning render modules. See docs/V0.17.68_FISHING_LINE_ROD_TIP_AND_SILK_OBJECT_RENDERER_FIXES.md.
// V0.17.67: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 28 - Final Documentation + Patch Notes - THE FINAL PHASE, completing the 28-phase Dark Woods 360x360 Zone Expansion + Resource Identity master plan (delivered V0.17.40 -> V0.17.67). Documentation only, no functional game-code changes: added the comprehensive expansion summary (docs/V0.17.67_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE28_FINAL_SUMMARY.md) and the consolidated PATCH_NOTES.md entry with the plan's exact required must-mention checklist (360x360; exactly 2 caves; Silk Web Cavern the only dungeon cave; Hidden Tree Cave secret cave; Bandit's Fall; Stone Hedge Ruins; centred waypoint; animated waypoint aura; wisps; Dark Woods herbs/fish; Silk Web-only herbs/fish; resource level/EXP/respawn rules; zone identity via dead lanterns/props/terrain/overlays/ambient life). The expansion is COMPLETE. See docs/V0.17.67_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE28_FINAL_SUMMARY.md.
// V0.17.66: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 27 - Performance + Culling - audited the per-frame work of the expanded zone and applied one targeted optimization; no duplicate render loops or per-frame random generation were introduced by the expansion (all Math.random in the resource/fishing paths is harvest-time/per-catch/spawn-time, never per-frame render; atmosphere/fog/ambient use deterministic seededNoise; resource-node render culls >34 tiles and iterates only the ~18 overworld + few dungeon nodes; waypoint VFX reuse the effects pipeline; terrain uses cached chunk baking). Optimization: getWorldLightState() (a pure function of minuteOfDay/zone/weather, all stable within a frame) is called ~17x per frame PLUS once per on-screen lantern (Phase 17) / wisp / the waypoint aura, with no caching - now memoized per frame via a frame token bumped once per frame in updateWorldClock (which runs in update() before render()), so it recomputes exactly once per frame and every other caller reuses the result. No stale light (time/weather still advance each frame; frozen correctly when paused), no new loop/timer, cache keyed on token+zone. Verified in-browser: within a frame all getWorldLightState calls return the identical cached object (1 recompute); bumping the token recomputes; light values remain correct and advance across frames. See docs/V0.17.66_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE27_PERFORMANCE_CULLING.md.
// V0.17.65: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 26 - Collision + Readability Cleanup - AUDIT ONLY, no functional game-code changes (version/docs only, like Phases 7 and 18). Ran a real reachability sweep to confirm everything added in Phases 2-25 is reachable and non-blocking, and found NO issues to fix (the careful isWalkable-verified placement in Phases 20-25 already avoided collision problems). Verified in-browser: OVERWORLD - flood-fill from spawn reaches 113,621 tiles; all 18 herb nodes are on walkable AND reachable tiles; waypoint centre (210,250), Silk Web entrance (52,139), Hidden Tree Cave (76,74), Bandit's Fall, and spawn are all reachable; all 6 sampled map-edge tiles are blocked. DUNGEON (all 3 Silk Web floors) - every dungeon herb node reachable; every carved fishing pool has reachable walkable shore tiles (fishable); zero water tiles in any boss arena; floors stay well-connected (11-13k reachable tiles each) so the Phase 23 water pools did not disconnect any room/corridor. No accidental blockers, no interactables under collision, no unreachable nodes/pools/waypoint. See docs/V0.17.65_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE26_COLLISION_READABILITY.md.
// V0.17.64: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 25 - Resource UI Messaging + Feedback - aligned the resource messaging to the master plan and added EXP-gain feedback, reusing the existing status/panel/log surfaces (no HUD redesign). Most feedback already existed from Phases 19-24 (gather/catch success, first-discovery/rare bonus notes, level-up log, xp bars). Changes: (1) the hard level-gate message is now the plan's exact phrasing "<node>: Requires <Skill> Level X" (was "<node> requires <Skill> X"); (2) the nearby-resource panel now shows "<node> · Requires <Skill> Level X" when the player is under the required level (uncollectible reads clearly) instead of the gather prompt; (3) gather success feedback now includes the total profession EXP gained ("+N Gathering EXP") alongside the existing first-discovery/rare bonus breakdown; (4) fishing catch feedback now includes the total Fishing EXP gained. Fishing has no per-fish node-gate message (fish-anywhere: under-level fish simply don't bite, there is no node to gate) - documented, not faked. See docs/V0.17.64_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE25_RESOURCE_UI_MESSAGING.md.
// V0.17.63: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 24 - Resource Persistence + Anti-Farming - verified the existing anti-farm persistence and added the plan's respawn-range randomization. The core anti-farm was ALREADY in place (no duplicate save system needed, per golden rules): gathering depletion uses absolute wall-clock respawnAt timestamps keyed by zoneKey:x,y:type, persisted in BOTH localStorage (dream-realms.resource-runtime.v2) and the game save (resourceRuntime via world-serializer/save-system), and node positions are deterministic (overworld deterministic map scan; Silk Web fixed-room herb/pool placement) so a depleted node's key is stable across re-entries - the timer never resets on leave/re-enter/reload/off-screen. Verified end-to-end in-browser: harvest -> depletedNodes has future respawnAt -> serializeState/importState round-trip (simulated reload) keeps it depleted -> re-seeding (ensure* idempotent) does not reset it -> zone/floor transitions preserve it. NEW this phase: added respawnSecondsMin/Max to all 8 herb defs (data/resources.js, exact master-plan ranges 60-90/90-150/180-240/300-420/600-900 overworld, 180-240/300-480/720-1200 Silk Web) and made completeHarvest roll a randomized respawn within that range (randInt) instead of a fixed interval - randomized respawns are less predictable/farmable; falls back to single respawnSeconds if no range. Fishing is fish-anywhere (no depletable nodes) so the plan's fish respawn timers do not apply - the per-cast timer is the throttle; documented, no duplicate system added. See docs/V0.17.63_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE24_RESOURCE_PERSISTENCE.md.
// V0.17.62: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 23 - Silk Web Cavern Cave Fish - added the 3 dungeon-only cave fish (item_blind_silk_minnow L4/28xp/9c, item_venomgill_eel L6/44xp/20c, item_broodpool_angler L8/75xp/55c + rareNodeXpBonus:30 + deepWaterOnly). The hardest fishing phase: the Silk Web dungeon had ZERO water tiles (its 'pools' were visualOnly dressing objects) AND fishing actively disables itself in dungeons. Solved by (a) carving real small TILE.WATER pools (with waterDepth) into the deterministic Silk Web floor rooms - new carveSilkWebFishingPools() in dungeon-system.js, called in generateSilkWebCavernFloor before reachability/enemy placement; only converts existing carved CAVE_FLOOR so pools never punch through walls/corridors; shallow pools on floors 1-2, a deep pool (waterDepth>=9) on floor 3 for the deep-water-only Broodpool Angler - and (b) making fishing-system.js dungeon-aware: its own zoneKey() now returns 'silk_web_cavern' for that dungeon, activeMap/activeObjects resolve game.dungeonMap/dungeonObjects, added FISH_TABLES.silk_web_cavern (3 fish + junk, level-gated), and render() now draws the fishing line inside the Silk Web dungeon (other dungeons still excluded; ambient swimming fish stay overworld/cave only). The Phase 22 eligibleFish level-gate + deep-water gate and the Phase 19 first-discovery(+30/+75)/rare(+30) wiring work for free. Zone-exclusive (silk fish only resolve in the Silk Web dungeon). See docs/V0.17.62_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE23_SILK_WEB_CAVE_FISH.md.
// V0.17.61: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 22 - Dark Woods Overworld Fish - added the 5 Dark Woods-only overworld fish to systems/fishing-system.js FISH_TABLES.dark_woods (item_duskmud_minnow L1/10xp, item_lanternfin L2/14xp, item_brambleback_pike L4/24xp, item_ghostscale_trout L5/34xp, item_gloamroot_catfish L7/55xp+rareNodeXpBonus:20+deepWaterOnly) plus 5 matching material items in data/items.js (sellValue = plan vendor 2/4/8/15/35). Fishing is a fish-anywhere FISH_TABLES architecture (not placed nodes) so zone-exclusivity is automatic (zoneFishTable only returns dark_woods for the overworld; fishing is disabled in caves-as-dungeons). ADDED THE PER-FISH LEVEL GATE the Phase 18 audit found missing: new eligibleFish(table, fishingLevel, deepWater) filters the weighted pick to fish whose levelRequired <= the authoritative resource-gathering Fishing level (single-source since Phase 19), and gates deepWaterOnly fish (Gloamroot Catfish) to deep-water casts (reusing the existing spot.rare=waterDepth>=9 hook) so the rare fish stays in deeper water; falls back to level-1 non-deep fish so every cast has a pool. First-discovery (+15/30/50 by levelRequired tier) and rare-fish bonus (+20) already work via the Phase 19 resolveCatch wiring - just populated the fields. Existing generic fish (Small Pondfish etc.) keep level-1 behavior (no levelRequired). See docs/V0.17.61_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE22_OVERWORLD_FISH.md.
// V0.17.60: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 21 - Silk Web Cavern Herbs - added the 3 dungeon-only herbs (herb_webcap_fungus L4/28xp/9c, herb_widows_veil L6/44xp/18c, herb_queens_silkroot L8/75xp/50c + rareNodeXpBonus:30) as node defs in data/resources.js + material items in data/items.js, reusing the exact same schema as the Phase 20 overworld herbs. The hard part (per the Phase 18 audit): Silk Web Cavern is a 3-floor DUNGEON (currentZone==='dungeon'), which the overworld gathering system did not reach. Solved by making the EXISTING gathering system dungeon-aware rather than building a parallel system - the gathering update/render/G-key already run in every zone (updateExternalSystems/renderExternalSystems are not zone-gated), they just resolved the wrong grid. Changed resource-gathering-system.js zoneKey() so a dungeon returns a floor-specific key ('silk_web_cavern:F<n>'); this also fixes a latent bug where overworld nodes could resolve inside a dungeon. New Game.prototype.ensureSilkWebCavernHerbs (world-system.js) seeds the herbs into editorResources['silk_web_cavern:F<n>'] placed relative to the deterministic SILK_WEB_FLOOR_CONFIG rooms (ring-scan for a walkable cave-floor tile with no dungeon object), idempotent per (type,room) so re-entering a floor never duplicates and keeps the wall-clock respawn/depletion keys stable. Webcap on floors 1-2 (entrance/mid), Widow's Veil deeper (floors 2-3), Queen's Silkroot only in the final deep chamber of floor 3 (boss room). Called from loadDungeonFloor. Everything else (level gate, respawn, first-discovery +50/+75, rare +30, cast bar, node rendering) is reused from Phases 19-20 for free. See docs/V0.17.60_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE21_SILK_WEB_HERBS.md.
// V0.17.59: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 20 - Dark Woods Overworld Herbs - added the 5 Dark Woods-only overworld herbs, reusing the existing resource-node + item systems (no new resource system). Added 5 node defs to data/resources.js DR.RESOURCE_TYPES (herb_lantern_moss L1/10xp, herb_thornberry L2/14xp, herb_gloomcap_mushroom L4/24xp, herb_wispbloom L5/34xp, herb_blackroot L7/55xp with rareNodeXpBonus:20) using the existing schema (levelRequired/xpReward/respawnSeconds[midpoint of plan range]/drops[].min-max=yield, tool 'Hands' so no tool gate, no lootTableId so completeHarvest yields the herb via direct drops) plus declarative allowedZone/allowedRegion/allowedBiome scope metadata. Added 5 matching material items to data/items.js (item_*, sellValue = plan vendor value 2/3/7/14/32c, icon family 'herb'). Placement: new Game.prototype.ensureDarkWoodsOverworldHerbs (systems/world-system.js) is a DETERMINISTIC terrain scan - the overworld is fully deterministic (generateMap uses only seededNoise, no Math.random) so it picks identical terrain-valid coords every run - that seeds nodes into editorResources.dark_woods within the correct Phase-3 region (getDarkWoodsRegionAt): Lantern Moss in Dead Lantern Outskirts (near town), Thornberry in Bramblefen, Gloomcap in the mid/deep forest rings, Wispbloom around Stone Hedge (>=9 tiles off the waypoint centre), rare Blackroot only in Gloamroot Depths >=116 tiles from town. Each candidate is validated with isWalkable + a natural-ground tile whitelist (grass/forest/dirt/underbrush), spaced apart, hash-ordered for deterministic scatter. Idempotent (skips a herb type if any node of it already exists). Called from the generateMap sequence (new games, after collision/terrain is finalized) AND from rebuildWorldRuntimeAfterWorldLoad (after a saved editorResources is applied, so pre-Phase-20 saves get the herbs too). Zone-exclusivity is automatic (nodes live only in the dark_woods grid; cave/dungeon grids are separate). Low-level gathering gate + first-discovery/rare-node bonuses are handled by the Phase 19 mechanics. See docs/V0.17.59_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE20_OVERWORLD_HERBS.md.
// V0.17.58: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 19 - Profession EXP Tables + Resource Rules - aligned Gathering/Fishing level 1-10 progression to the master-plan table and added the core resource-rule mechanics, reusing the existing owning systems (no duplicate profession/failure system). (1) EXP TABLE: replaced resource-gathering-system.js's power curve (max(50,100*level^1.45)) with the plan's exact per-level table PROFESSION_XP_TABLE=[100,150,225,325,475,675,950,1300,1750]; cumulative totals to reach L2..L10 now match the plan exactly (100/250/475/800/1275/1950/2900/4200/5950), verified in Node. Beyond L9 it continues at the final finite step (1750) rather than a hard cap, so all four EXP-display consumers (resource panel, professions panel, skills panel, fishing panel) keep rendering finite values and future higher-tier content is not blocked. Exposed the curve + first-discovery helper once as DR.Professions so fishing-system.js reuses the exact same math instead of duplicating it. (2) DUAL FISHING LEVEL FIXED: fishing-system.js previously tracked Fishing level in BOTH its own state (curve max(65,80*level^1.32)) and the resource-gathering Fishing skill (different curve) - they diverged. The resource-gathering 'Fishing' skill is now the single source of truth: fishing gainXp grants there (authoritative leveling + level-up log) and mirrors the level/xp back into its own state for the panel + catch-chance; refreshPanel re-syncs each frame. (3) FIRST-TIME DISCOVERY BONUS: +15/30/50/75 by resource level tier, granted once per resource id/fish species via a new persisted state.discovered map (shared by gathering + fishing). (4) RARE-NODE BONUS: data-driven via an optional node/def/fish rareNodeXpBonus field (0 today; Phases 20-23 will set +20/+30 for Blackroot/Queen's Silkroot/Gloamroot Catfish/Broodpool Angler). Hard level-gate messaging and soft-failure already existed and match the plan's primary rule, so they were left untouched. See docs/V0.17.58_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE19_PROFESSION_EXP_TABLES.md.
// V0.17.57: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 18 - Resource System Audit - read-only audit (no functional game-code changes; version/docs only) mapping the ownership of every resource/gathering/fishing/profession/vendor/persistence system before the resource-content phases 19-23. Key findings: (a) herbs/ore are coordinate-placed nodes in game.editorResources[zoneKey] defined in DR.RESOURCE_TYPES (data/resources.js) and run by systems/resource-gathering-system.js (which also owns the Gathering/Mining/Fishing skill state + EXP curve max(50,100*level^1.45)); profession-system.js is UI-only. (b) Fishing (systems/fishing-system.js) is a SEPARATE fish-anywhere-near-water architecture using hardcoded FISH_TABLES keyed by zone, with NO per-fish level gate and NO depletion/respawn, and it double-tracks Fishing XP in both its own state (curve max(65,80*level^1.32)) and the resource-gathering Fishing skill (divergence risk). (c) The plan's proposed schema field names (professionXp/firstDiscoveryXp/respawnSecondsMin-Max/yieldMin-Max/allowedZone-Region-Biome/nodeVisual/questTags) exist in 0 files - the existing schema already covers the same concepts under levelRequired/xpReward/respawnSeconds/drops[].min-max/lootTableId, and item vendor price is sellValue in data/items.js - so 19-23 must reuse, not invent a parallel registry. (d) Region->resource spawn hooks already exist dormant since Phase 3 (data/default-zones.js region identity.resourceIds: dead_lantern_outskirts->herb_lantern_moss, bramblefen_thicket->herb_thornberry, stone_hedge_clearing->herb_wispbloom, gloamroot_depths->herb_blackroot). (e) Persistence is already complete: depletedNodes use absolute wall-clock respawnAt timestamps persisted in localStorage + save (world-serializer resourceRuntime + per-zone editorResources; save-system fishing/professions/resourceGathering), so reload/zone-change farming is already prevented for gathering. (f) BIGGEST RISK: Silk Web Cavern is a 3-floor DUNGEON (currentZone==='dungeon'), and fishing disables itself in dungeons while gathering's zoneKey() only knows dark_woods/cave - so Phases 21 & 23 (Silk Web herbs/fish) need a dungeon-owned resource/fishing path, not the overworld systems. No duplicate systems created. See docs/V0.17.57_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE18_RESOURCE_SYSTEM_AUDIT.md.
// V0.17.56: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 17 - Atmosphere / Time-of-Day Identity - strengthened the haunted-forest mood by hooking the existing world-light state (systems/time-cycle-system.js getWorldLightState -> nightStrength/phaseKey, already weather-merged) into the systems that were already drawing live each frame, with NO new weather framework, clock, or render loop. Six items: (1) MORNING FOG IN LOW AREAS - reweighted atmosphere-system.js's existing deterministic fog-pocket seeding so dawn/morning raises fog density biased toward low-elevation valley tiles (elev 0-1 pool most, tapering by elev ~2); night fog is untouched. (2) FIREFLIES AT NIGHT - already satisfied by the pre-existing fireflyBoost=light.fireflyBoost gating (confirmed in Phase 16 audit), left as-is. (3) STRONGER WAYPOINT GLOW AT NIGHT - effects-renderer.js drawWaypointAuraEffect now scales its aura/ring/mote/ground-glow alphas and aura radius by a nightBoost derived from nightStrength (capped so it never blows out). (4) DEEPER SHADOWS UNDER ANCIENT TREES - object-renderer.js drawTree gives obj.ancient trees a wider soft outer shade + darker inner core, static identity, drawn in the already-scaled context. (5) WISPS MORE VISIBLE AT NIGHT - because mob bodies are sprite-cached (entity-renderer drawCachedModelOrFallback), added a live uncached screen-blend halo behind wisp-family mobs in entity-renderer.js drawDarkWoodsMobVisualModel, scaled by nightStrength, camera-culled for free. (6) FAINT LANTERN GLOW ALONG ROADS - object-renderer.js drawLanternPost adds a faint warm (or wisp-green) road-marker halo behind lit lanterns that strengthens at night; broken/fallen lanterns stay dark. All effects subtle and gated so they vanish by day. See docs/V0.17.56_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE17_ATMOSPHERE_TIME_OF_DAY.md.
// V0.17.55: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 16 - Creature Territory Signposting + Ambient Life - audited first and found two major pieces of infrastructure this phase needed already existed: Phase 3's DR.DEFAULT_WORLD.zones.dark_woods.regions.identity.signpostProps field (grepped the whole codebase - confirmed it was 100% dormant metadata, never read anywhere since V0.17.42), and systems/atmosphere-system.js, a pre-existing lightweight camera-culled ambient-creature/fog/firefly renderer already covering firefly/butterfly/moth/beetle/lizard. Wired up signpostProps as new Game.prototype.ensureDarkWoodsTerritorySignposts (reuses brokenWeapon+arrow/magicResidue/webbedBush/eggCluster/rootCluster for 5 of 6 named signs, only clawMarks needed a new prop; dead_lantern_outskirts's lanternPost entry is skipped since the Phase 4 Dead Lantern Trail already fully owns that region's signage). Extended atmosphere-system.js's existing ambientCreatureKind/renderAmbientCreature with 5 new kinds (crow, squirrel, deer, frog, bat) using the same stateless per-frame noise-jitter style as the existing ones - deer's "flee" behavior is a stateless per-frame offset away from the player's current position rather than persistent flee AI, a deliberate scope decision to stay within this layer's existing no-collision/no-state architecture. Found and fixed a real, previously-unnoticed bug while auditing atmosphere-system.js: it clamped its render bounds to the shared cave/dungeon DR.CONFIG.MAP_SIZE (200) instead of activeMapSize(), so fog/fireflies/ambient creatures silently failed to render for any player position with x or y >= ~200 - more than half of the Phase 2 360x360 resize - since V0.17.41; confirmed the severity by a standalone Node simulation before fixing. See docs/V0.17.55_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE16_SIGNPOSTING_AMBIENT_LIFE.md.
// V0.17.54: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 15 - Micro-Landmarks + Environmental Storytelling - added 4 authored micro-landmarks (Abandoned Hunter Camp, Old Forest Well, Collapsed Watch Post, Root Shrine) and 4 authored story scenes (Bandit Ambush Remains, Failed Spider Hunt, Lost Pilgrim Shrine, Old Road Collapse) as new Game.prototype.ensureDarkWoodsMicroLandmarks, called once from the same boot sequence as the other landmark builders. Coordinates were verified by a standalone Node distance sweep against every one of the zone's ~70 existing mob spawn anchors and prior landmarks rather than eyeballed, after the sweep caught two initial picks landing almost exactly on top of existing spawn anchors. Reused existing props wherever a fit already existed (fire+new obj.dead flag for cold firepits, bedroll+color for a torn look, brokenCart, crate, silkCocoon corpse, caveWeb, well+new obj.mossy flag, standingStone as a small solitary marker, rootArch/hangingRoots/rootCluster, magicResidue in place of a second animated aura); added 6 new small scene-only props (hunterTrap, coinPouch, candleCluster, tornCloak, bloodTrail, archerPlatform) and bow/arrow kinds on the existing drawBrokenWeapon for the handful of things nothing else covered. See docs/V0.17.54_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE15_MICRO_LANDMARKS.md.
// V0.17.53: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 14 - Trees, Bushes, Terrain Props - audited render/object-renderer.js and systems/world-system.js first, found most of the plan's named tree/bush variety already existed incidentally (deadTree with variant/webbed, tree's mossy flag and 9-shape/tall/broad/sparse variety, thornBush/webbedBush) so scoped to genuine gaps: added an obj.ancient flag to drawTree (larger scale + gnarled trunk knot), obj.scale to drawDeadTree (thin/gaunt size variety), obj.kind (dead/berry/flowering/mossy) and obj.scale to drawBrush for bush variety reusing one clump geometry instead of 5 new functions, an obj.mossy overlay on drawRock, an obj.natural palette flag on drawAshStump for a non-burnt forest stump, and three new ground props - drawFallenLog/drawRootCluster (non-blocking) and drawRootBarrier (blocking, per the plan's "only large props block movement" rule). Wired all of it into the existing sparse forest dressing pass in placeWorldLandmarks using a second independent noise channel plus Phase 13's darkWoodsDepthFactor so variety (ancient/dead/mossy trees, berry/flowering vs dead/mossy bushes, rare deep-woods root barriers) scales with region depth rather than being uniform across the whole zone. See docs/V0.17.53_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE14_TREES_BUSHES_PROPS.md.
// V0.17.52: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 13 - Terrain Tile Detail + Overlays - audited render/terrain-renderer.js first and found the specific 28-item grass/dirt/overlay wishlist mostly did not exist as named variants (only a generic 6-name stone/dirt/grass variant system and per-tile-type detail functions existed); scoped this phase to a concrete, high-value slice: added Game.prototype.darkWoodsDepthFactor (reuses Phase 3 region levels, 0 at spawn ramping to 1 in level 9-10 regions), threaded it into a new depth-darkening wash baked once per cached terrain chunk tile and into getTileVisualVariant's moss chance, fixed a real gap where FOREST_FLOOR fell to a generic undetailed ellipse in the cached bake path instead of proper ground detail, and implemented drawTerrainScatterDetails (previously a dangling, never-defined optional-chain call/silent no-op) to add depth-scaled shadow flecks and a terrain-level magical-residue shimmer confined to the Stone Hedge Ruins region. See docs/V0.17.52_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE13_TERRAIN_OVERLAYS.md.
// V0.17.51: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 12 - Animated Waypoint Aura - added the pulsing glow, ground glow, radial light expansion, rotating rune ring, and rising motes to the Stone Hedge Waypoint, reusing the existing effects-system.js/effects-renderer.js VFX pipeline entirely (new 'waypointAura' effect type + drawWaypointAuraEffect, modeled directly on the existing bardMeditationAura pattern) - no new render loop, no new interval/animation timer; the aura is ensured/refreshed from the waypoint system's existing update(dt), which the pre-existing updateExternalSystems(dt) loop already calls every frame. Effect is camera-culled for free by the existing generic effect-culling pass. Verified the ensure-effect lifecycle (create once, never duplicate, recreate if dropped) by simulation. See docs/V0.17.51_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE12_WAYPOINT_AURA.md.
// V0.17.50: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 11 - Wisps + Waypoint Integration - built the game's first waypoint system from scratch (new systems/waypoint-system.js; player.unlockedWaypoints was pre-existing dormant save-schema scaffolding with no owning system until now) and placed the actual waypoint object in the Phase 10 stone ring's clear center (210,250), static/non-animated per this phase's scope (Phase 12 owns the aura animation). Added wisps around the ring: an outer-ring Duskwisp camp and an inner-ring named Lumen-Wisp anchor, both reusing existing mob/spawn data - no new wisp mob types were invented. Scope deliberately excludes a fast-travel menu (only one waypoint exists so far). See docs/V0.17.50_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE11_WISPS_WAYPOINT.md.
// V0.17.49: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 10 - Stone Hedge Ruins Static Landmark - built a partial standing-stone ring (center 210,250, in the stone_hedge_clearing region box) with a deliberately distinct grey-blue mossy-megalith palette from the Phase 9 bandit ruins: 8 standing stones (partial ring, gap precisely oriented toward the Phase 4 road's approach angle, verified), inner rune stones with a pulsing glow, drifting magic-residue motes, and a couple of fallen/broken slabs. Center kept clear (nearest prop is 5 tiles out) and ready for Phase 11's waypoint and wisps - no waypoint object or wisps placed yet. Added 4 new props (standingStone, runeStone, brokenSlab, magicResidue). See docs/V0.17.49_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE10_STONE_HEDGE_RUINS.md.
// V0.17.48: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 9 - Old Ruins / Bandit Area - built the Bandit's Fall landmark (outer broken wall ring with a south entry gap, central ruined structure, flanking rubble/LOS-break pockets, bandit camp clutter) in fresh Phase 2 territory (center 230,60) rather than the pre-existing dense old-territory ruin remnants, to avoid overlapping ~10 unrelated existing mob camps/anchors (nearest is 40+ tiles away, verified). Added the Bandit's Fall enemy family (5 MOB_DRAFTS: Scout/Thug/Archer/Lookout/named Leader "Rurik the Fallen", all reusing the already-fully-wired generic 'bandit' renderer) plus a mixed-role camp spawn and named-rare spawn. Added 6 new props (ruinArch, rubble, barrel, sackPile, ropeBundle, barricade) and mossy/vines/fallen variants on the existing ruinWall/ruinPillar. See docs/V0.17.48_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE9_BANDITS_FALL.md.
// V0.17.47: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 8 - Hidden Tree Cave Exterior + Interior - added a dense concealment ring (mossy tall trees, root arches, hanging vine-roots, brush, thick grass) around the Hidden Tree Cave entrance at 76,74. Added one hidden interior lore NPC (Hollow Root Hermit) at the cave's deterministic 'nest' room center - no quest chain, no named rare mob, no multi-floor logic. Fixed a real conflict: removed the 'underwater_cave_blind_pool' entrance (systems/swimming-system.js) that force-carved a live second-dungeon entrance (dungeon_blind_pool_depths) inside this exact cave, independent of and invisible to cave-system.js's generation - orphaning that dungeon (data intact, not deleted). Fixed stale "Mossfang Cave" text in quest_mossfang_warning and dialogue_mossfang_warning to say Hidden Tree Cave. See docs/V0.17.47_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE8_HIDDEN_TREE_CAVE.md.
// V0.17.46: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 7 - Silk Web Cavern Dungeon Interior - audit only, no functional changes. Confirmed the 3-floor Silk Web Cavern dungeon (systems/dungeon-system.js generateSilkWebCavernFloor) is already fully implemented and wired end-to-end: authored room graphs, spider-only encounters/minibosses/3 named bosses with real phase/ability logic, web-anchor gate puzzles, quest chain, boss-gated stairs/treasure, dungeon-specific exit. Documented 3 small pre-existing orphaned items (poisonDrip render case, legacy dungeon_silk_web_depths/boss_silk_mother draft) left in place, not deleted - see docs/V0.17.46_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE7_SILK_WEB_INTERIOR_AUDIT.md.
// V0.17.45: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 6 - Silk Web Cavern Exterior + Approach - scattered spider-territory dressing (webbed bushes, thorn bushes, webbed dead trees, bones, wrapped corpses via a repurposed silkCocoon, broken weapons, web strands) across the silk_web_approach region box, deterministically seeded and excluding a 10-tile clear radius around the actual cave entrance. Added drawThornBush/drawWebbedBush/drawBrokenWeapon to render/object-renderer.js and an optional webbed overlay on drawDeadTree. No interior dungeon content touched - see docs/V0.17.45_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE6_SILK_WEB_APPROACH.md.
// V0.17.44: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 5 - Cave Count Enforcement - Dark Woods now has exactly 2 caves. Removed the Ashroot Hollow, Crystal Grotto, and Forgotten Mine entrances/zone descriptors entirely, and removed Blackroot Catacombs (orphaning the endgame dungeon_glooms_crypt dungeon, which is left fully intact but currently unreachable - see phase report). Repurposed mossfang_cave (id kept for save-schema compatibility) into Hidden Tree Cave, lvl 4-8, small secret exploration cave. Silk Web Cavern is unchanged. No dungeon interior content built yet - see docs/V0.17.44_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE5_CAVE_COUNT.md.
// V0.17.43: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 4 - Main Paths + Dead Lantern Trail - extended the road network into the Phase 2 resize area with a maintained spur into Stone Hedge Clearing, a rougher side path into Gloamroot Depths, and an unmarked/lantern-free hidden trail; added a Dead Lantern Trail variant system to lanternPost (intact/broken/hanging/fallen/wisp/bandit/webbed) rendered in render/object-renderer.js, with Game.prototype.applyDeadLanternTrailVariants assigning a variant to every lantern by the Phase 3 region it falls in (verified in Node against all new lantern coordinates). No mobs/resources/props added - see docs/V0.17.43_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE4_PATHS_LANTERNS.md.
// V0.17.42: Dark Woods 360x360 Expansion Phase 3 - Named Regions + Level Bands - added DR.DEFAULT_WORLD.zones.dark_woods.regions (Dead Lantern Outskirts, Bramblefen Thicket, Bandit's Fall, Stone Hedge Clearing, Gloamroot Depths, Silk Web Approach) with level bands and identity/hook metadata, plus Game.prototype.getDarkWoodsRegionAt/getDarkWoodsRegionLevelRange lookups. Metadata only - no terrain, mob, or resource changes yet - see docs/V0.17.42_DARK_WOODS_360_EXPANSION_PHASE3_REGIONS.md.
